</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="CCSO Sites User">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#00FFFF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<CENTER><P><B><I><FONT COLOR="#400080"><FONT SIZE=+4><U>Limiters</U> <U>And</U>
<U>Divertors</U></FONT></FONT></I></B></P></CENTER>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">With two strikes against them
after the gas blanket and &quot;z&quot; wall failed, scientists finally
came up with an idea which is not only feasible, but also can be easily
implemented. They decided that if you can't beat 'em, join 'em. Rather
than trying to stop the sputtering from occurring, they would strategically
use devices known as limiters and divertors to keep impurities from the
plasma and out of the tokamak.</FONT> </FONT></B></P>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="L&d4.gif" HEIGHT=403 WIDTH=317></P></CENTER>

<P><B><I><U><FONT COLOR="#400080"><FONT SIZE=+2>Divertors</FONT></FONT></U></I></B></P>

<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>The main idea behind the divertor
is to use a powerful magnetic field to steer the ions into a divertor chamber.
In here, the ions collide with the divertor collector plate and actually
cause sputtering to occur. Two possible things can happen to the ions after
it hits the plate. It can so what a small portion of the ions do, and be
extracted from the system via a vacuum duct. Or, the ion might stay and
act as coolant for the divertor chamber. It can do this because after the
collision the ion's energy has decreased quite significantly and it has
only a fraction of electron volts remaining. This is actually acting like
the gas blanket by reducing other ion's energies below the binding energy
and sputtering threshold.</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Divertors have shown great promise
in tokamak testing. They have been able to significantly reduce the plasma
impurity concentration, as well as improving the tokamaks efficiency. It
is not know why the efficiency level is raised by divertors yet, but no
one is complaining about that. However, there is a downside to divertors.
The magnetic coil system necessary to steer the ions is expensive and quite
complicated. It would take a great effort of time and money to provide
the coils big enough for a full scale reactor.</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="L&d6.gif" HEIGHT=358 WIDTH=528></P></CENTER>

<P><B><I><U><FONT COLOR="#400080"><FONT SIZE=+2>Limiters</FONT></FONT></U></I></B></P>

<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Limiters are much simpler than
divertors, but do virtually the same thing. Limiters use a material surface
which comes in direct contact with the impurity ions on the outskirts of
the plasma. The limiter is hit by these ions on and sputter off neutrals
which can be collected and drawn out of a vacuum duct where they are removed
from the plasma chamber. One might question how much unnecessary impurities
would be created by this intentional sputtering, after all, in the divertor,
they were only sputtering ions which were known to be impurities. This
can be countered by a good vacuum and a sufficiently cooled area around
the limiter created by the lower energy impurities. Also, neutral beams
can be injected to reverse the natural inward flow of the neutrals and
the transport of impurities.</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="L&d3.gif" HEIGHT=565 WIDTH=492></P></CENTER>

<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+1>Limiters and divertors offer
the most promise in the hopes to clean up the plasma inside the tokamaks.
However, more engineering and devellop of these devices is necessary in
order to have a successful fusion reaction.</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="mailto:k-cofey@uiuc.edu">Ken Coffey</A></FONT></I></B></P>

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/~kenc">Return
to my page</A></FONT></I></B></P>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT></B>
</BODY>
