<CENTER><P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+4><U>Low</U> &quot;<U>Z</U>&quot; <U>Walls</U></FONT></I></B></P></CENTER>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Another logical solution would be to use walls that
have a low atomic number. As the graph shows, it quite possible to have
an impurity concentration of up to ten percent for walls with an extremely
low &quot;z.&quot; </FONT></B></P>

<CENTER><P><IMG SRC="Zwall.gif" HEIGHT=504 WIDTH=481></P></CENTER>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>This all seems nice and dandy, but in order for this
to work carbon or boron are about the only things one could make a reactor
out of. Since stainless steel and other metal alloys are the surface of
choice so we must keep searching for another possible solution.</FONT></B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><I>How's this? </I><A HREF="mailto:k-coffey@uiuc.edu">Ken
Coffey</A></FONT></B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/~kenc">Return<U>
to my page</U></A></FONT></B></P>

