<HEAD>

<TITLE> Wind Energy </TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../backgrnd/marble3.jpg" TEXT=#000000 LINK=#4B0082 VLINK=#FF0000>

<A NAME="top">

<!-- Beginning of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<CENTER>

<B>

<FONT COLOR=#4B0082>
<FONT SIZE=7>W</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>IND</FONT>  
<FONT SIZE=7>E</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>NERGY</FONT>
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4>

Lecture-Discussion #8

<BR>

Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems

<BR>

Professor David N. Ruzic

</FONT>

</B>

</CENTER>

<!-- End of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../breaks/marble.gif" WIDTH=580 HEIGHT=5 ALT="Horizontal Marble Divider">
</CENTER>
</P>

<BR>

<!-- Beginning of Introduction -->

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

<TR>

	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>he wind blows because the Sun shines and heats areas of the Earth unevenly.  When this phenomenon is coupled with the Earth's rotation,
prevailing wind directions are established.  Harnessing this wind energy &#151; actually a form of nuclear energy from fusion in the Sun &#151; has presented many engineering challenges.  Many of those problems are just now being resolved.  In the right location, wind power is a viable economic alternative to fossil fuels.  Of course, the wind is variable, and there may be a time span over which the wind does not blow.  Therefore, use of this energy source is reserved for a supplemental role only, until it is coupled with an
economic energy storage system.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<!-- End of Introduction -->

<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% NOSHADE>

<BR>

