<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="CCSO Sites User">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#0080FF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+4><U>How</U> <U>The</U> <U>Energy</U> <U>is</U> <U>Lost</U></FONT></I></B></P>

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+3><U>Line</U> <U>Radiation</U></FONT></I></B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>When the electron from in a partially ionized impurity
strikes a electron in the plasma the plasma electron becomes excited and
jumps to the next higher energy level. However, this is only for one small
instant and the electron returns to the ground state immediately after
that. Again, the net change in energy must be zero, so the loss of energy
must be accompanied by something else. That something is most often an
emission of a photon that has a defined frequency, <FONT FACE="Symbol">n</FONT>,
in accordance to the equation h<FONT FACE="Symbol">n</FONT> = E</FONT></B></P>

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+3><U>Recombination</U> <U>Radiation</U></FONT></I></B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>The free electrons created in the plasma have the ability
to recombine with the partially ionized impurity. When this happens, the
result is an ion in a ground state that is one less than original ground
state of that of the plasma electron. The energy loss by the plasma in
this event is approximately equal to the plasma electron thermal energy.</FONT></B></P>

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1>Any Comments? <A HREF="mailto:k-coffey@uiuc.edu">Ken
Coffey</A></FONT></I></B></P>

<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu">Return to
my page</A></FONT></I></B></P>

</BODY>
