<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Resource Availability</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Biomass</h1><br>
Lecture-Discussion # 11<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 From the energy flow discussion in the last lecture, only 133
Terawatts of the sun's energy goes into the biosphere.  Considering
that mankind only uses 10 Terawatts &quot;biomass&quot; has a
great potential.  As with most sources though, the fuel must be
avialable to us and in a form that is usable and economical. 
This lecture discussion and the nex two will cover all the direct
and converted uses of biomass fuels.  We will start with direct
use (firewood and solid wastes) and conversion to other solid
forms.
<P>
<h2><a href="overview.html">Overview of Use</a></h2>
<P>
<h2>Direct Combustion</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="fuelwood.html">Fuelwood</a>
<li><a href="crop.html">Crop Residue</a>
<li>Wet Refuse
<li><a href="dry.html">Dry Refuse</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Conversion to Solids</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="refuse.html">Refuse Derived Fuels</a>
</ul><P>
<h2><a href="links.html">Related Sites on the Web</a></h2><p>
<h2><a href="hw11.html">Today's Homework</a></h2>
<hr>
