<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="CCSO Sites User">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FF44FF" LINK="#0000EE" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#FF0000">

<CENTER><P><B><I><FONT SIZE=+4><U>Gas</U> <U>Blanket</U></FONT></I></B></P></CENTER>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>One hypothesis of how to create a cool wall surface
is to surround the plasma with a &quot;cool gas&quot; that would insulate
the wall from the plasma. This would virtually guarantee that the particle
fluxes experienced by the wall would be low enough to easily be under the
sputtering threshold. There is only one slight problem with this idea.
The minimum thickness of the &quot;gas blanket&quot; would be about one
meter. Any gas blanket that size would totally impractical.</FONT></B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><I>e-mail me with your thoughts </I><A HREF="mailto:k-coffey@uiuc.edu">Ken
Coffey</A></FONT></B></P>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/~kenc">Return
to my page</A></FONT></B></P>

