<ul><ul><H1>MY HIGH SCHOOL ACTIVITIES</H1></ul></ul><P>

<img src="Images/line_rainbow.gif"><p>

During my high school days, my years seemed divided into three basic sections.<p>

<ul>
<h2><img align=bottom src="Images/greenball.gif"> Band Season</h2><p>
	<ul>No, I don't play any instruments!  All four years, I was a
member of the majorette squad.  As part of the auxillary unit of the
band, we did all sorts of neat stuff like putting on the half-time
shows at football games, marching in parades (mainly Christmas
parades, but we also marched in the governor's inaugural parade one
year), competing in band festivals, and attending various camps.
Since our football team made it to the state championship game every
year that I was in high school, I got to see a fair amount of the
state of Virginia by traveling with the band to the football games.
Also the camps and competitions took as to places in Maryland, <a
href="http://www.neosoft.com/citylink/nc.html">North Carolina</a>, and
Virginia.</ul>
<p>


<h2><img align=bottom src="Images/greenball.gif"> A.C.E. Season</h2><p>
	<ul>ACE, the Academic Competition for Excellence is a quiz
bowl competition between schools in the southside Virginia area.  Each
school has four teams, a literature team, a math team, a science team,
and a history team.  Of course, I was a member of the science team.
My freshman year, I learned tons about the earth and planetary sciences.
  Then the next year, I concentrated on biology. 
My junior year I somehow managed to handle
both the chemistry and the physics fields.  By my senior year, I had
even learned a little anatomy.  The competitions were a blast!</ul>
<p>

<h2><img align=bottom src="Images/greenball.gif"> Summer Vacation</h2><p>
	<ul>During my summer vacation, I rarely managed to stay home
for any length of time.  I always went to band camp and <a
href="4-H.html">4-H Congress</a>.  One summer I went to the Virginia
Governor's School at <a href="http://www.wm.edu/">The College of
William and Mary</a>.  During this summer, I worked at a graduate
school of William and Mary, <a href="http://vims.edu/">VIMS</a>
(Virginia Institute of Marine Science).  I have always enjoyed
oceanography and this program let me work at the VIMS Aquarium where I
fed fish and swam with the shark.  Plus I met tons of interesting
people.</ul>

</ul>
</DOC>
