<html>

<head>
    <title>MAGNETIC CONFINEMENT FUSION</title>
</head>

<body background="screen.jpg">
   </address>
<center>
<h1>MAGNETIC CONFINEMENT FUSION</h1>
</center><br><br><br><br>
As we move into the 21st century, we are faced with an increasing
<a href="http://sunsite.unc.edu/lunarbin/worldpop">population.</a>
In addition to placing a greater stress on thte food producing 
centers, this increase also stresses an equally important sector, 
energy. As we continue to rely on energy to perform our tasks, heat 
our homes and light our cities, the demand for energy increases
greatly as shown here:<br><br><br><br>
<center>
<img  width=500 length=400 src="energy.gif"><br>
</center><br><br><br><br>
As you can see, we are greatly increasing the demand for energy. This 
would not be a problem if our supplies of energy was inexhaustible,
however, according to current
<A href="http://www.eia.doe.gov/oiaf/aeo95/homepage.html">projections
</a>, we only possess the reserves to last us a few decades at the 
current rates of consumption. So,what to do? Fortunately, visionary
researchers have worked on the problem for many years. They have come 
up with many
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201/students.html">solutions</a>
to provide for our energy demands. All of these solutions do have 
limitations. They typically do not provide a viable solution to all
our demands and they typically do not provide an inexhaustible 
source of energy. There is however one source that promises to be
inexhaustible and widely deployable, Magnetic Confinement Fusion!<br>
<br><br><br><br>
<center>
<img width=500 length=400 src="tokomakt2.gif"><br>
</center><br><br><br><br>
But what is Magnetic Confinement Fusion? What does it do for us? And 
how will it solve our problems? Read on and learn how.!<br>
<a href="index.html#whatfusion"><h3>What is Fusion and how does it 
work?</h3></a>
<a href="index.html#mcf"><h3>What is Magnetic Confinement Fusion?
</h3></a>
<a href="index.html#start"><h3>How do we start the reaction?</h3></a>
<a href="index.html#confine"><h3>How do we confine the reaction?
</h3></a>
<a href="index.html#fuel"><h3>What fuels do we use?</h3></a>
<a href="index.html#doing"><h3>What are we doing to develop this
technology?</h3></a>
<a href="index.html#conclusion"><h3>Conclusion</h3></a>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name=whatfusion>
<h4>First of all, what is 
<a href="http://FusionEd.gat.com/SlideShowFolder/SlideShowIntro.html>
fusion?</a></h4>
Simply put, fusion is the process by which two lighter nuclei fuse
 together to form a heavier nucleus. This is the same process that 
powers the stars. Although the process seems simple,fusion is a very 
difficult process to achieve and the only natural occuring fusion
takes place in the stars. There are several reasons for this. First of
all, there are three forces acting in nature. They are the Gravitational
, Electro-Magnetic, and Strong nuclear. When atoms are near to each other, 
the E-M forces repel the like charged shells of the atoms. And in 
order for the nuclei to fuse, the nuclei have to be brought close
enough together for the strong nuclear force to bind the nuclei 
together. The only way to achieve this is be using great ammounts of 
energy to force the nuclei together. The stars achieve this through
their immense gravitational force,gravity so great that we can't hope to
 achieve this on earth. But, there are ways to achieve this on earth. We
do this by utilizing very high temperatures, as high as 200 million degrees
celcius! Much hotter than the sun! At these high temperatures, the atoms
break down into a cloud of charged particles called a plasma. In this 
state, the nuclei are moving so fast that they overcome the E-M forces
and get close enough for the strong force to fuse the nuclei together. The
most successful fuel used for fusion is deuterium( an isotope of hydrogen with
1 neutron) and tritium( an isotope of hydrogen with 2 neutrons) and from
this reaction we get a helium atom plus a neutron and 17.6Mev of energy,
three times as much as fission! <br><br><br><br>
<center>
<img src="dtreacti.gif">
</center><br><br><br>
<a name=mcf>
<h4>Now, what is Magnetic Confinement Fusion?</h4> MCF, as it is known, is the
process by which the fusion reaction is confined and shaped by magnetic
 fields. Since the reaction is so volitile and chaotic, it takes great 
ammounts of force to do so. Due to the interaction of the E-m forces, the
charged plasma can be directly formed by magnetic fields. And, when a 
charged particle moves in a field, it moves in a spiral. A Russian scientist
discovered that if he passed a current through the plasma, and used a 
torus shaped confinement field, then the plasma would flow in a helical
pattern through the chamber. This design is so successful that it is the 
basic design by which all MCF reactors are built. In fact, the name for the
reactor class, Tokamak, comes from the Russian word for torus. The idea behind 
the operation of these reactors is as such: A gas such as deuterium-tritium
is pumped into an evacuated chamber such as this one:<br><br><br><br>
<center>
<img width=500 length=400 src="iterf.gif">
</center><br><br><br><br>
The reactor then heats the gas in pulses to achieve the fusion temperature
while using an immense magnetic field to confine the plasma. The plasma then 
reacts and gives off energy. Once the energy is released, the plasma cools 
down and another pulse reheats the plasma to the fusion temperature. Currently
the only method for creating the reaction is by pulsing power into the 
plasma, however, there is hope that soon we will have the reactions operating
effifiently enough to be in the self-heating condition called ignition.<br>
<br><br><br>
<br>
<a name=start>
<h4>Now, how exactly do we get this reaction going?</h4> Well, as was said before,
the fuel is heated until it is a plasma. It is then heated more until the 
reaction occurs. Now, the temperature for the D-T reaction that is used is 
approximately 200 million degrees celsius. That translates to about 15Kev
of heating energy needed. There are several ways to heat the reaction to
this temperature. First is called OHMIC HEATING. Ohmic heating is the
heating that occurs when a current flows through a medium. The current that
flows several million amperes, but it is not enough to heat the plasma all
the way. The second method to heat the plasma is called "Neutral Beam Heating"
. Neutral Beam Heating is the idea that fast moving particles carry a lot 
of energy with them. And if these particles are injected into the plasma,
they impart their excess energy into the plasma. And, if they are neutral
atoms such as helium-4, the cause no reaction. The typical potential needed to 
accelerate the particles is 140,000 Volts. This still is not enough. The third 
type of heating is called RF-HEATING. RF Heating is basically microwave 
heating. The energy of the e-m waves is directed into the plasma by antennae
arrays. The heat gained from this can be several MW of heating power. And 
the fourth method of heating the plasma is called SELF-HEATING. When the
D-T reaction occurs, the helium nucleus carries with it 3.5MeV of energy.
Self-Heating occurs when the excess helium nuclei heat the plasma enough to 
continue the reaction. This has not been achieved, but if it is, the energy
produced by the reaction would be much greater than the input. Now, the 
methods of heating aren't quite enough to sustain the reaction so it is 
common to use several methods at once.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name=confine>
<h4>Now, how do we confine this reaction?</h4> Well, as was mentioned earlier,
a plasma is a charged cloud and when a current flows, a magnetic field is 
generated. In the MCF reactors, the field resultant is called the poloidal
field. When the magnetic field if the torus, called the torroidal field, is 
combined with the poloidal field, the stable helical flow is achieved
and the plasma is stable and contained without the use of a container.
This method of confinement is called the "magnetic bottle". And here is the 
confinement:<br><br><br><br>
<center>
<img src="confinem.gif">
</center><br><br><br><br> 
<a name=fuel>
<h4>Now, what fuels do we use to run the reaction?</h4> While theoretically, almost
any nucleus can be used to create a fusion reaction. However, practically,
the only reactions we can hope of achieving are the lightest of the atoms.
The most common fuel proposed for running the reaction now is D-T. This is
 due to the relative ease of producing fusion this way. The D-T reaction only
 requires heating of slightly above 100 million Centigrade. There is one 
drawback, the neutron radiation causes problems for the structural integrity
of the reactor. The prefered reaction for experimentation is the D-D
reaction. In this reaction only half as many neutrons are released as in 
the D-D reaction. But, it is harder to achieve. The reaction scientists hope
to achieve is called aneutronic. This is when there are no neutrons produced
by the reaction. The most common aneutronic reactiion is the D-Helium3
reaction. This gives the structure of the reactor a longer life
and creates no radioactive material and it would be the easiest aneutronic
reaction to achieve. There are many other reaction envisioned for the 
Tokamaks, but we'll just deal with what's up and coming in the near future.
<br><br><br><br><center>
<img src="fusionfu.gif">
</center><br><br><br><br>
<a name=doing>
<h4>Now what is being done to develop this technology?</h4> Well, since 1985, there has
been a reactor on line at Princeton University. This reactor is called the 
Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor(TFTR). The reactor has achieved a record 10.7MW
of controlled fusion power. Although this reactor is no longer on line,there
are many being developed and
<a href="http://www-jt60.naka.jaeri.go.jp/">built</a>. The push for the 
future is to develop these reactors in international unions of scientists.
 Currently in Europe, there is the Joint European Tokamak(JET). And the 
project which the US and several other countries is the 
<a href="http://www.pppl.gov/oview/pages/iter.html">ITER</a>-International
Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor. This reactor is being designed to 
offer the increased efficiencies which come from increased size. The reactor
should be on the drawing board by 1998. Scientists propose the year 2050
for commercial reactors to come on line. Right about the time our oil 
reserves should be running out.<br><br><br>
<center>
<img src="advancem.gif">
</center>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<a name=conclusion>
Finally, as our reserves dwindle and the human race becomes increasingly
reliant upon energy intensive industry, we see the need to find new resources.
 As our technology improves, we develop more and more ways to solve our
problem. Now, Magnetic Confinement Fusion may not be the solution, but, it 
seems as it may be the right choice to develop for our future.<br>
<a href="http://neutrino.nuc.berkeley.edu">To See Other Sites Click Here</a><br>

<a href="mailto:r-ahern@students.uiuc.edu">Send Me Mail Please!</a><br>

</address>
</body>
