<HTML>
	<TITLE>HYDROPOWER</TITLE>
<body Background="http://donews.do.usbr.gov/graphics/yellow_r.gif">

<h1><B>HYDROPOWER</B></h1>
 <BODY>
<h2><b>INTRODUCTION</b></h2>
<img src="http://donews.do.usbr.gov/dams/Hoover.gif"> <p>
This site deals with hydropower and all of the ways that hydropower 
affects our energy consumption by giving us a 
cheaper alternative to conventional approaches to <TD><A 
HREF="http://www.nrel.gov/documents/energy/energy.html">energy</A><BR>.<P>
In fact, hydropower is the largest renewable energy source in the United 
States, generating about ten percent of our nation's electricity. This 
amounts to <i>500</i>  million barrels of oil. This shows that hydropower 
has made its contribution to supplying energy to our nation. There are 
many examples of working hydroelectric plants out <TD><A 
HREF="http://206.10.243.2/nsp/stafalls.htm">there</A><BR><p> 
<h3><b>ADVANTAGES</b></h3>
There are many advantages to this type of energy. One would be storage. 
This would primarily include resevoirs and lakes behind <td><A 
HREF="http://donews.do.usbr.gov/Denver/tsc/Concdams/Arch/ADpage.html">dams</A><br>. Also, hydropower allows for quick availiability. Turbine-generators are not turned off, requiring only 45 seconds. Even if the generators are not on, only 90 seconds are r

















































equired. And a major advantage comes from the fact that the fuel is free. 
Also, hydropower produces no air emissions at all and no liquid or solid 
wastes.<p>

<h4><b>DISADVANTAGES</b></h4>
Along with these advantages come many disadvantages. many of these 
disadvantages come from the <td><A 
HREF="http://www.envision.net/osites/environ/envrelat.html">environmental</A><BR> arena. Siltation and erosion cause major problems for dams as does the segmentation of the riverine ecosystem. What this segmentation does is stop the river from having a fr














































ee-flowing movement to it. And this causes adverse affects towards <td><A 
HREF="http://www.riverdale.k12.or.us/salmon.htm">salmon</A><br> and 
catadrommous fish. Fish ladders and minimum flows are used to reduce this 
adverse affect. Weeds seem to be a problem that causes harm more towards 
the dams by causing a loss of power since these weeds can grow inside the 
turbines and dams. The reservoir mentioned as an advantage before can 
also cause a serious problem. This problem is disease and the disease is 
schitosomiasis, which is caused by snails. The snail populaiton increases 
from the still water causing all of this. Another dangerous aspect when 
dealing with dams are dam failures and other accidents. One dam a year 
fails, on average. These failures usually cause the death of many 
villagers or townspeople beneath the dam.<p>
<img src="http://donews.do.usbr.gov/dams/MorrowPoint.gif">
<h5>HYDROPOWER(STORAGE)</h5>
Hydropower fits into two broad classes. The decision for which class a 
dam fits into is based on geography, economics, and environmental impact. 
The first class includes dams with a one-way flow out of reservoirs and 
out through turbine-generators. The second class includes pumped storage, 
which are specially designed waterwheels and act as pumps or turbines. 
These coupled generators also can run as motors. But natural dams 
dominate pumped when compared on a world scale. The reason being that 
pumped hydro do not serve other purposes. Some of these purposes include 
<td><A 
HREF="http://www.wiz.uni-kassel.de/kww/projekte/irrig/irrig_i.html">irrigation</A><BR>, recreation and also fish production.<p>
<img src="http://donews.do.usbr.gov/dams/BuffaloBill.gif">
<h6>COST OF HYDROPOWER</h6>
Most of the cost for hydropower comes from land use and the dam itself(or 
also the reservoir, for pumped storage). The cost also comes from other 
items whose cost does, in fact, not depend on the rate of filling or 
emptying of the system. The ratio( capital in storage system/capital in 
the generation system is higher for natural systems that for pumped 
storage. The only exception is when the pumped reservoir is exceptionally 
expensive.<P> 
<h7>CONCLUSION</h7>
Hydropower, along with:
<UL>
<L1> <TD><A 
HREF="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/nbia/index.html">BIOENERGY</A><BR>
<L1> <TD><A 
HREF="http://www.energy.ca.gov/energy/earthtext/geothermal.html">GEOTHERMAL</A><BR>
<L1> <BR><a 
href="http://www.yahoo.com/text/Science/Energy/Solar_Energy/">SOLAR</a><br>
<L1> <BR><A 
HREF="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/re-kiosk/wind/index.shtml>WIND</A><BR> 
</UL> <P>
make a good compliment to our energy consumption, but hydropower will 
never be the main source of energy. But the usefullness of hydropower 
will lead to a greater utilization of present dams and <TD><A 
HREF="http://kiri.ccs.carleton.ca/images/drilltunnel.html">hydropower 
facilities</A>. But there is not room for expansion since most large sites 
are either unavailable or taken. So, in conclusion, there is a future in 
hydropower but it is one where there will not be a great increase of 
large plants, but the current ones can greatly help supply our demand for 
power and energy. The benefits are vast for our communities through the 
use of large-scale hydropower.<P>
Large-scale hydropower is a large source of energy for this country, 
especially for the Pacific Northwest, where hydropower is an ideal source 
of energy. The reason being that the abundance of rivers allows the use 
of them for energy usage. Hydropower is becoming useful since the people 
in the Pacific Northwest spend, on average, less for the using the same 
amount of energy.<P>
While this can be a good example for the rest of the country, most 
large-scale hydropower sites are, unfortunately, for the most part taken, 
leaving few large sites that have been left alone. And of the large sites 
left, most, for one reason or another, cannot be used.<P>
But through research and current technology, are current sites can be 
made more efficient. With some of the methods mentioned below, hydropower 
can be more environmentally friendly in the future.
<UL>
<L2>Spilling water over the dams in order to avoid the turbines, thus 
increasing the number of juvenile salmon that pass through without going 
through the turbine by at least eighty-percent.
<L2>A barge system to transports these juveniles around the dams.
<L2>A system to guide these young salmon past the turbine intakes and in 
the bypass system
</UL>

The <TD><A HREF="http://donews.do.usbr.gov/power.resources/">USBR- Power 
Resources Office</A><BR> can be a helpful place to look if you would 
like information that has not been mentioned above. Also,  <TD><A 
HREF="http://140.90.236.70/public-affairs/pr95/mar95/bioopin2.html">NMFS 
Releases Two Biological Opinions Aimed At Protecting Pacific Northwest 
Salmon</A><BR> may be helpful.<P>
With an efficiency of 85-90%, it is obvious as to why this is such a 
useful source of energy. In 1987, 17% of the industrialized countries 
electricity was supplied by hydropower and 31% for developing countries.
Overall, large-scale hydropower is a source of energy that will continue 
to make its impact on this country well into the future.<P>

 <A 
HREF="mailto:buntic@students.uiuc.edu">here</A> is 
where to go if you have any comments or questions about this page.<P>
Also, if you really would like to find out more information 
about <TD><A 
HREF="http://128.219.152.164/ORNLReview/rev26-34/text/hydside2.html">hydropower</A><BR> in 
general or more about large-scale hydropower, contact:
<p> 
<strong>National Hydropower Association(NHA)</strong></a>
<address>
122 C Street, NW<br>
Fourth Floor<br>
Washington, DC 20001<br>
(202) 383-2530<br>
fax: (202 383-2531
</address>
