<!-- Beginning of Introduction -->

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

<TR>

	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>hose people who have some idea of geothermal energy often picture a geyser of hot water or steam, like Old Faithful, at the mention of this energy source.  While such recognition is important and a good start, applications of geothermal energy today include many other ingeneous methods for using the energy within the Earth.  Temperature differences between one spot on Earth and another spot can be used either to turn a heat engine, or to transfer that thermal energy where it can be appreciated &#151; such as your house in the winter if you live in the upper latitudes.  The key to using geothermal energy is that the two points of temperature difference must be in close proximity, and the different in temperature must be large in magnitude.  We will start by looking at the overall flow of energy into, around, and throughout the layers of our planet.  Then the two great potential reservoirs of stored energy &#151; the
land masses and the oceans &#151; will be considered.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

