<HEAD>

<TITLE> Energy Usage </TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../backgrnd/marble3.jpg" TEXT=#000000 LINK=#4B0082 VLINK=#FF0000>

<A NAME="top">

<!-- Beginning of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<CENTER>

<B>

<FONT COLOR=#4B0082>
<FONT SIZE=7>E</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>NERGY</FONT>  
<FONT SIZE=7>U</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>SAGE</FONT>
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4>

Lecture-Discussion #3

<BR>

Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems

<BR>

Professor David N. Ruzic

</FONT>

</B>

</CENTER>

<!-- End of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../breaks/marble.gif" WIDTH=580 HEIGHT=5 ALT="Horizontal Marble Divider">
</CENTER>
</P>

<BR>

<!-- Beginning of Introduction -->

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

<TR>

	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>K</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>nowing that "x" units of oil, coal, or natural gas is used each year allows us to make an estimate of how long these resources will be available at a certain price.  The numbers are often based on a standard or current level of technology.  For example, they do not tell us what advanced technology can do to ameliorate the effect of dimishing fossil fuels.  Where do we use oil, coal, natural gas, etc.?  For what purposes are these fuels typically used?  Before
we can look at the accomplishments of new technology and how these advancements fit into the overall picture of energy sources, we need to look at how energy is used in American society as well as throughout the world.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<!-- End of Introduction -->

