<HEAD>

<TITLE> Energy Cycles </TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../backgrnd/marble3.jpg" TEXT=#000000 LINK=#4B0082 VLINK=#FF0000>

<A NAME="top">

<!-- Beginning of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<CENTER>

<B>

<FONT COLOR=#4B0082>
<FONT SIZE=7>E</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>NERGY</FONT>  
<FONT SIZE=7>C</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>YCLES</FONT>
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4>

Lecture-Discussion #5

<BR>

Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems

<BR>

Professor David N. Ruzic

</FONT>

</B>

</CENTER>

<!-- End of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../breaks/marble.gif" WIDTH=580 HEIGHT=5 ALT="Horizontal Marble Divider">
</CENTER>
</P>

<BR>

<!-- Beginning of Introduction -->

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

<TR>

	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>B</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>esides the transportation sector, the other dominant area of consumption in which energy is "wasted" is the generation of electricity.  The primary way that electricity is produced involves boiling water.  This phase change, the transition from liquid water to the gaseous steam, introduces a new complication in normal diagrams of energy cycles.  Nevertheless, preparing a diagram of the cycle is still essential in order to ascertain how its efficiency can
be improved.  The same principle of maximizing useful work, or the area enclosed within the curve on a diagram,
can be applied in the presence of a phase change.  At the end of this lecture-discussion, we will show how to apply that concept to sample diagrams of real cycles, and we will discuss actual examples of this practice in electrical generation plant design.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<!-- End of Introduction -->

<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% NOSHADE>

<BR>

<!-- Beginning of Lecture Outline -->

