<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Fusion Energy</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Fusion Energy</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 25
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
  Since all the materials on earth were originally created
in stars through fusion, and since the sun, which powers virtually
all of the renewable energy options, runs on fusion, one could
say that we are using this energy source already.  The quest is
to use this source directly on earth in centralized power stations.
 Controlled fusion potentially has the most plentiful energy reserves
on the planet since 1 out of every 6500 water molecules is &quot;heavy
water&quot; ,  that is, it contains deuterium instead of hydrogen.
 This lecture-discussion will cover the basics of fusion physics
and engineering, as well as show some detail of actual machines.
<P>
<h2>Plasma Physics</h2>
<P>
<li><a href="plasmas.html">Plasmas</a>
<li><a href="our.html">Our Sun</a>
<li><a href="reactions.html">Reactions</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Fusion Energy</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="advantages.html">Advantages</a>
<li><a href="how.html">How Magnetic Fusion Works</a>
<li><a href="heating.html">Heating</a>
<li><a href="actual.html">Actual Machines</a>
</ul><P>
<h2><a href="links.html">Related Sites on the Web</a></h2>
<h2><a href="hw25.html">Today's Homework</a></h2>

