<HEAD>

<TITLE> Hydroelectric Energy, Waves, And Tides </TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../backgrnd/marble3.jpg" TEXT=#000000 LINK=#4B0082 VLINK=#FF0000>

<A NAME="top">

<!-- Beginning of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<CENTER>

<B>

<FONT COLOR=#4B0082>
<FONT SIZE=7>H</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>YDROELECTRIC</FONT>  
<FONT SIZE=7>E</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>NERGY,</FONT>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=7>W</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>AVES,</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=7>A</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>ND</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=7>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>IDES</FONT>

</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4>

Lecture-Discussion #9

<BR>

Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems

<BR>

Professor David N. Ruzic

</FONT>

</B>

</CENTER>

<!-- End of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../breaks/marble.gif" WIDTH=580 HEIGHT=5 ALT="Horizontal Marble Divider">
</CENTER>
</P>

<BR>

<!-- Beginning of Introduction -->

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

<TR>

	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>he use of water to generate power is a very old practice.  A flowing stream can make a paddle turn, but a waterfall can spin a blade fast enough
to generate electricity.  The real key in the magnitude of water-based power is the physical height difference achieved between source and sink &#151; the distance through which the water falls.  As in the case of wind, most water-based power also relates to fusion energy from the Sun.  Rivers flow downhill because the Sun evaporated water from some low spot on the planet, and the water later returned to the Earth as rain at a higher altitude.  The waves are a direct result of wind, which itself is
cause by uneven heating of the ground and oceans by the Sun.  Of the several types of hydropower, only the origin of the tides is not related to the Sun.  The gravitational pull of the moon is responsible for the tides, which vary in magnitude by location according to latitude and geography.  After the nuclear furnaces started at the center of our solar system, the planets were formed from the massive clouds of material remaining in orbit.  The moon, and its particular orbit, were created shortly thereafter.  The moon does not rotate &#151; a consequence of its solid interior and lack of bodies of water &#151; within its monthly orbit around the Earth.  Critical features of the Earth maintain our rotational pattern, despite the realization that the actual time span of one day has lengthened over billions of years.  When considered as a whole, the energy locked within Earth's water cycle and ocean waves is extremely large, but harnessing this energy has proved to be exceedingly difficult.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<!-- End of Introduction -->

<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% NOSHADE>

