<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nuclear Waste</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Nuclear Wastes</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 24
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 Of all the subject relating to nuclear power, wastes invokes
the greatest reaction from the public.  &quot;Where are we going
to put all that stuff?&quot;, and &quot;It will last forever!&quot;
are common comments.  This lecture-discussion will quantify the
magnitude, longevity and danger.  There are two categories of
wastes.  High-level wastes are the fission products left when
uranium splits.  Low-level wastes are protective clothing and
the left-over &quot;water-conditioner beads&quot;.   High-level
wastes can be reprocessed to reduce their volume considerably
and remove for re-use, the most long-lived wastes.  Unfortunately
that requires more handling and cost.  The ultimate fate of the
wastes is burial.  This lecture-discussion will cover the technology
of the disposal systems and many of the new concepts about to
be employed.
<P>
<h2>Radioactivity</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="uses.html">Uses</a>
<li><a href="amounts.html">Amounts</a>
<li><a href="fuel.html">Fuel Cycle</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>High-Level Wastes</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="oragin.html">Origin</a>
<li><a href="radioactivity.html">Radioactivity</a>
<li><a href="transportation.html">Transportation</a>
<li><a href="reprocessing.html">Reprocessing</a>
<li><a href="disposal.html">Disposal</a>
<P></ul>
<h2><a href="natural.html">Natural Reactor</a></h2>
<P>
<h2>Low-Level Wastes</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="oraginb.html">Origin and Radioactivity</a>
<li><a href="disposalb.html">Disposal</a>
<li><a href="decommissioning.html">Decommissioning</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Current Status</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="whats.html">What's Happening</a>
<li><a href="regulations.html">Regulations in Perspective</a>
</Ul><P>
