	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>N</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>ow that we know how much of each resource exists and who has it, we need to examine how much of each resource is used on a yearly basis.  Armed with such data, we can start making intelligent estimates of how long each resource will last.  These types of predictions are difficult to make, and the task of maintaining a high level of accuracy with such hypotheses certainly does not simplify the problem.  Indeed, it is beneficial and critical for governments and major corporations around the world to have as clear a picture of the current and future energy trends as possible.  The process of formulating predictions requires that many be taken into account.  This lecture-discussion will guide you through the raw numerical data regarding energy consumption and ultimately provide some answers to these complex questions.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

