<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nuclear Physics:  Fusion and Fission</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Nuclear Physics:  Fusion and Fission</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 20
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 The source of nuclear energy is the rearrangments of  protons
and neutrons into more stable nuclei.  Fusion is the combining
of light nuclei like H together into something heavier , like
He.  Fission is the breaking apart of large nuclei, like U, into
something smaller, like Kr and I.  Both produce more stable nuclei,
and both release very large amounts of energy in the process.
 This lecture-discussion looks at the principles behind nuclear
energy and at the energy resources available to be used in this
form.
<P>
<h2>Nuclear Energy</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="analogy.html">Analogy to chemistry</a>
<li><a href="binding.html">Binding Energy per Nucleon</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Fusion Energy</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="reactions.html">Reactions</a>
<li><a href="resources.html">Resources</a>
<li><a href="wastes.html">Wastes</a>
</ul><p>
<h2>Fission Energy</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="reactionsb.html">Reactions</a>
<li><a href="resourcesb.html">Resources</a>
<li><a href="wastesb.html">Wastes</a>
</ul><P>
<h2><a href="why.html">Why Chernobyl can't happen here</a></h2>
<P>
<h2><a href="links.html">Related Sites on the Web</a></h2>
<P>
<h2><a href="hw20.html">Today's Homework</a></h2>
