<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-57</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000765-B048-148</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/dforsyth/ 128.174.200.146 19970303041023 text/html 3449
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 04:07:26 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Last-modified: Sun, 27 Oct 1996 23:07:54 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 3266
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body background="images/marmor.gif">
<title>Hydrogen Fuel Cells</title>
<center><h1>Fuel Cells</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
	<font size="+1">A</font>s the world population continues to grow, 
total worldwide energy consumption will rise with it.  There is no 
disagreement over the fact that our current oil <a 
href="reserves.html">reserves</a> will be 
insufficient to carry us through the 21st century.  Although vast 
quantities of <a 
href="http://info.nrel.gov/documents/energy/ff-coal.html">coal</a>  
remain, its use is 
generally not viewed as an alternative since it produces much more 
<a href="pollution.html">pollution</a> than oil or gas.  In addition, it 
would be impractical to use for transportation.  Consequently we have 
few options:
<UL>
<LI>Improve the efficiency in using remaining reserves.
<LI>Find an alternative source of energy.
</UL>
<hr>
<center><h2>So where do fuel cells fit into this?</h2></center>
<br>
<br>
<font size="+2">The basics:</font>
<br>
<p>A fuel cell generates electricity and heat through an <a 
href="ecpic.html">electrochemical process</a>, much like a battery, in 
that an anode and a cathode, separated by an electrolyte, produce a 
direct current.  However, a 
fuel cell doesn't consume the electrodes to produce electricity.  
Instead, it converts hydrogen <a href="fuel.html">fuel</a>
directly into electricity very efficiently.  Efficiency is currently around 
40-50%, and is expected to top 60% as the technology advances.  If the 
by-product heat is utilized for 
cogeneration, total efficiency approaches 80%.  Fuel
cells also have the advantage of lower <a href="pollution.html">emissions</a>
over traditional fossil fuel applications.  A 
fuel cell releases 50% less carbon dioxide 
than a coal power plant of equal electrical output, and fuel cell 
emissions of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides are virtually nil.  

<br>
<br>



<font size="+2">Applications:</font>
<br>
<UL>
<LI><a href="trans.html">Transportation</a>
<LI><a href="util.html">Utilities</a>
</UL>
<br>
<br>
<font size="+2">The Contenders:</font>
<br>
<UL>
<LI><a href="spfc.html">Solid Polymer Fuel Cell</a>
<LI><a href="afc.html">Alkaline Fuel Cell</a>
<LI><a href="pafc.html">Phosphoric Acid Fuel Cell</a>
<LI><a href="sofc.html">Solid Oxide Fuel Cell</a>
<LI><a href="mcfc.html">Molten Carbonate Fuel Cell</a>
</UL>
<br>
<hr>
<center><h2>Conclusions:</h2></center>
<br>
<br>
<p>With efficiencies between 40-60% and virtually no emissions, fuel cells 
have the potential to be one of the most promising means to meet the 
country's growing energy needs. Even though fuel cells are not yet
economically competitive with fossil fuels,
fuel cells have the advantage of being 
inherently modular.  This will allow for the development of central mass 
production and a system to transport components to a site.  
Low oil prices have offered little incentive for intensive investment in 
advancing the technology, however current levels of development are 
sufficient to utilize fuel cells on a limited basis.  As petroleum 
supplies dwindle and prices rise, fuel cells are guaranteed to receive 
serious consideration.
<br> 
<br> 
<hr> 
Questions or comments? Page by <a  
href="mailto:dforsyth@uiuc.edu">dforsyth@uiuc.edu</a>







