Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 851
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body>
<title>Fuel Cell Operation</title>
<center><h1>How does a fuel cell work?</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
<center><img src="images/fc_5-2.gif"></center>
<br>
A fuel cell can operate on a wide variety of fuels.  The only limitation 
is the ability of the fuel to be <a
href="http://www.anl.gov/OPA/frontiers96/hreform.html">reformed</a>.  The 
hydrogen liberated from the fuel is oxidized at the anode and then released 
into the electrolyte.  The electrolyte must allow the hydride ions to 
pass freely through to be reduced at the cathode.  This reaction 
theoretically produces about 1 V per cell.  When the two electrodes are 
connected, electrical current flows across the connection.
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><a href="index.html">Back<img src="images/left.gif"></a></center>
<br>
<br>
<a href="mailto:dforsyth@uiuc.edu">dforsyth@uiuc.edu</a>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-61</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B022-241</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/dforsyth/fuel.html 128.174.200.146 19970303034547 text/html 2136
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 03:42:49 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Last-modified: Sun, 27 Oct 1996 22:53:22 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 1953
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body>
<title>Fuel Sources</title>
<center><h1>Possible Fuels</h1></center>
<br>
Fuel cells can operate on a variety of fuels, provided that the source 
fuel is sufficiently <a 
href="http://www.anl.gov/OPA/frontiers96/hreform.html">reformed</a>.  The 
process usually involves heating the fuel to 
decompose it into simpler compounds.  Catalytic reactions are also used 
to further break down the fuel and separate the hydrogen.  Pure hydrogen 
is the only fuel that would not need to be processed.
<br>
<br>
In order for a fuel to be effective, it must have a simple chemical 
structure and be highly reactive.  Possible fuels include:
<UL>
<LI>Hydrogen - As stated above, hydrogen does not need to be reformed, 
plus it is highly reactive in its natural state.  In order to carry a 
sufficient amount of gas, the hydrogen must be stored 
in pressurized tanks, which presents additional problems in handling and 
safety.
</UL>
<br>
These are considered compromise fuels; they have relatively high 
reactivity, simple chemical structures, and are a liquid at room 
temperature and thus easier to transport and store.
<UL>
<LI>Hydrazine - This fuel is close to hydrogen in reactivity, but is very 
expensive to produce.
<LI>Ammonia - Ammonia is the next best choice in terms of reactivity, 
plus it is very cheaply produced.
<LI>Methanol - Considered another likely alternative.  Methanol can be 
stilled from renewable sources and is fairly easily reformed.
</UL>
<br>
Hydrocarbons are easily transported with current equipment.  However, 
they have low reactivity and complex chemical structures.  Methane is the 
mosy likely hydrocarbon to be used; it is the simplest of the alkanes and 
can be reformed using current technology.  Even coal can be used if 
gassified and then reformed. 
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><a href="index.html">Back<img src="images/left.gif"></a></center>
<br>
<br>
<a href="mailto:dforsyth@uiuc.edu">dforsyth@uiuc.edu</a>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-62</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B022-252</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/dforsyth/trans.html 128.174.200.146 19970303034555 text/html 2127
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 03:42:56 GMT
