Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 1944
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body>
<title>Transportation</title>
<center><h1>Fuel Cell Vehicles</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>The transportation sector is most vulnerable to an interruption of 
petroleum supplies.  Oil is also the fossil fuel shortest in supply.  
Thus fuel cell powered cars stand to greatly extend the life of this 
precious resource.  As of 1994, the US transportation sector used 23.42 
Quads of petroleum per year.  This is 75% of the total usage.  Should the 
US be able to convert all of the vehicles on the road to 
<a href="http://www.astc.org/inquirer/hydrocar.html">fuel cell powered 
vehicles</a>, we could eliminate a need for foreign oil entirely.  <br>
<p>Currently, a Canadian company, Ballard Power Systems, has developed a 
fuel cell powered bus which is in use in Vancouver.  The city of Chicago 
will soon be testing these buses as well.  The buses are powered by 
275 HP <a href="spfc.html">Solid Polymer Fuel Cells</a> which operate on 
pure hydrogen. 
<br>
<br>
<center><img src="images/spfc.jpg">
<br>
<i>Two men working on one of the fuel cells.  The bus can be seen in the 
back with the hydrogen storage tanks on the top.</i></center>
<br>
<br>
<p>It is unlikely that hydrogen will be used as a fuel source for 
automobiles.  The tank would be very heavy, and there are hazards 
involved in dealing with a pressurized, flammable gas.  Methanol or 
ammonia are the most likely <a href="fuel.html">fuels</a>.  The difficulty 
in using these is that they must be converted into hydrogen and CO2.  
However, researchers at the <a href="http://www.anl.gov">Argonne National 
Laboratory</a> have developed a device that is small enough to fit next 
to a 50 kW fuel cell under the hood of a compact car.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><a href="index.html">Home<img src="images/left.gif"></a><a 
href="util.html"><img src="images/down.gif">Utilities</a></center>
<br>
<br>
<a href="mailto:dforsyth@uiuc.edu">dforsyth@uiuc.edu</a>
</DOC>
