</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body>
<title>SPFC</title>
<center><h1>Solid Polymer Fuel Cell</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>Solid polymer fuel cells (SPFC) show great promise for transportation 
use.  The cell operates at relatively low temperatures (~100 C) with a 
high power density.  This means that the size of the cell is relatively 
small for the power output.  SPFCs can also vary output quickly 
which is a necessary trait for use in automobiles.  The electrolyte (a 
"proton exchange membrane") still needs further development.  As it 
stands, it is sensitive to moisture depletion and freezing, which would 
limit its use in colder climates.  In addition, since the cell is a 
"cold" operation cell, platinum catalysts are necessary and are very 
expensive.  
<br>
<br>
<center><img src="images/pem-cell.gif">
<br>
<i>A SPFC built by <a href="http://www1.usa1.com/~fuelcell/">ElectroChem 
Inc.</a></i>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><a href="index.html">Home<img src="images/left.gif"></a><a 
href="afc.htm"><img src="images/down.gif">AFC</a>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-65</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B022-304</DOCOLDNO>
