<HTML>
<body>
<title>PAFC</title>
<center><h1>Phosphoric Acid Fuel Cells</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>Phosphoric acid fuel cells (PAFCs) are the most commercially developed 
of all the fuel cells.  They are produced by <a href="">International Fuel 
Cells Corporation</a> at a cost of about $3000 per kW.  This is not low 
enough to compete with traditional power sources, but through government 
grants and incentives, the cost has been lowered to $1000.  PAFCs operate 
at moderate temperatures (~200 C) which, although hot, is not hot enough 
to convert the methane fuel internally, and an external reformer is 
needed.  Efficiencies have been historically proven to be around 45%.  
Perhaps the greatest advantage of the PAFC is its reliability.  Actual 
commercial products have been operated for more than 9000 hours (more 
than a year) without maintenance requiring shutdown or human 
intervention.  The problem with PAFCs are its low power density.  This 
limits their use to stationary applications due to size.  In order to 
become truly econmically competitive, cheaper manufacturing techniques 
must be developed.
<br>
<br>
<center><img src="images/phos.jpg">
<br>
<i>A 200kW PAFC made by ONSI corporation.  The module shown contains the 
fuel cell, the equipment for reforming methane, and the circuitry to 
convert DC to AC.</i>
<br>
<br>
<img src="images/pafc-cel.gif">
<br>
<i> A PAFC built by <a href="http://www1.usa1.com/~fuelcell/">ElectroChem 
Inc.</a>  This unit is listed at $1500.</i> <hr>
<center><a href="afc.html">AFC<img src="images/up.gif"></a><a 
href="spfc.html"><img src="images/down.gif">SPFC</a>
<br>
<a href="index.html"><img src="images/left.gif">
<br>
Home
</a>
</DOC>
