<HTML>
<body>
<title>SOFC</title>
<center><h1>Solid Oxide Fuel Cells</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>Solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs) operate at very high temperatures 
(~1000 C).  This allows the cell to reform methane internally without the 
aid of any external device.  SOFCs are very efficient, on the order of 
50%.  SOFC waste heat is of such high temperature that it in itself can 
be useful i.e. to boil water to run a steam turbine.  The problem with 
the SOFC is cost.  Few materials are capable of withstanding such 
temperatures for a prolonged period of time, consequently, most of the 
materials involved are costly ceramics.  The abundance of ceramic 
materials makes the unit sensitive to mehcanical shock.  Westinghouse has 
been developing a <a 
href="http://apollo.osti.gov/html/fe/west_so.html">Tubular SOFC</a> for 
industrial and large scale use.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><a href="afc.htm">AFC<img src="images/up.gif"></a><a 
href="mcfc.htm"><img src="images/down.gif">MCFC</a>
<br><a href="index.html"><img src="images/left.gif"></a>
<br><a href="index.html">Home</a>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-68</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B022-352</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/dforsyth/mcfc.html 128.174.200.146 19970303034646 text/html 995
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
