Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 813
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<body>
<title>MCFC</title>
<center><h1>Molten Carbonate Fuel Cells</h1></center>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>Molten carbonate fuel cells (MCFCs), like the SOFC, operate at very 
high temperature (~650 C).  This allows internal conversion of fuels 
without external equipment.  The lithium/potassium carbonate electrolyte 
operates in a molten state and actually requires the presence of CO2 to 
function.  MCFCs have a high efficiency, and also produce useful waste 
heat.  The main problem with MCFC is the use of a nickel catalyst in 
conjunction with lithium and potassium carbonate which is both very hot 
and corrosive, requiring the periodic replacement of the catalyst.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<center><a href="sofc.htm">SOFC<img src="images/up.gif"></a><a 
href="index.html"><img src="images/right.gif">Home</a>
</DOC>
