<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Breeder Reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Breeder Reactors</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 22
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<p></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 Though the supply of Uranium-235 is large and could last thousands
of years, it is ultimately limited.  Since LWR's need enriched
fuel, the productio nof new U-235 fuel rods could become expensive.
 It is possible to use the plentiful U-238 isotope as a reactor
fuel by &quot;breeding&quot; plutonium-239 from it.  Breeder reactors
&quot;produce more fuel than they use&quot; because they can create
more Pu-239 than is used.  There is nothing magic in the process
since U-238 is steadily used.  The use of breeder reactors could
extend the availibility of nuclear energy resources for more than
100,000 years.  Breeders have other advantages though as well
as disadvantages.  This lecture discussion will cover the physics
of breeders and their current applications.
<P>
<h2>Breeder Basics</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="physics.html">Physics</a>
<li><a href="advantages.html">Advantages</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Breeder Reactors</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="experimental.html">Experimental Breeder Reactors (EBR)</a>
<li><a href="liquid.html">Liquid Metal Fast Breeder (LMFBR)</a>
<li><a href="phenix.html">Phenix and Super Phenix</a>
</ul><P>
