<HEAD>

<TITLE> Energy Conversion </TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../backgrnd/marble3.jpg" TEXT=#000000 LINK=#4B0082 VLINK=#FF0000>

<A NAME="top">

<!-- Beginning of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<CENTER>

<B>

<FONT COLOR=#4B0082>
<FONT SIZE=7>E</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>NERGY</FONT>  
<FONT SIZE=7>C</FONT><FONT SIZE=6>ONVERSION</FONT>
</FONT>

<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4>

Lecture-Discussion #4

<BR>

Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems

<BR>

Professor David N. Ruzic

</FONT>

</B>

</CENTER>

<!-- End of Page Title Graphics and Words -->

<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../../breaks/marble.gif" WIDTH=580 HEIGHT=5 ALT="Horizontal Marble Divider">
</CENTER>
</P>

<BR>

<!-- Beginning of Introduction -->

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=85% CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

<TR>

	<TD BGCOLOR=#1E90FF>
		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=4>
		<B>
		<FONT SIZE=+2>I</FONT>NTRODUCTION
		</B>
		</FONT>
	</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

	<TD>
		<BR>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>fter studying where energy is used, some statistics necessitate further understanding.  A quick look at the "spaghetti chart" of energy flow on the previous web page indicates that an enormous amount of energy is "wasted" through various outlets.  In particular, the generation of electricity and the transportation industry seem to throw away two-thirds of their energy input.  If technology could improve the efficiency of energy utilization in these two end-uses alone, much of the "energy crisis" can be averted.</FONT>
		</P>

		<P>
		<FONT SIZE=5>T</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>he generation of electricity and the internal combustion engine are both examples of "heat engines."  That is, they both convert the thermal motion of particles into directed work performance.  By the inherent laws of physics, particularly the Second Law of Thermodynamics, the efficiency of heat engines is extremely limited.  Improvements are possible, but even these advances will only elevate efficiencies on the order of a few percentage points.  This lecture-discussion will explain the basis for limitations on energy consumption in general and heat engines in particular.  Several typical combustion cycles will be explored.</FONT>
		</P>
	</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>

<!-- End of Introduction -->

