<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advances in Fusion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Advances and the Future of Fusion</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 26
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
  Magnetic controlled fusion is coming close to its ultimate
goal.  The next step device, ITER, will surpass break-even and
be the size of a proto-type power plant.  Though the experts agree
that it will work, they also agree that it will make an unattractive
power plant in terms of cost per Watt produced compared to coal
or advanced fission.  The argument is raised that first you have
to built one, then you'll find breakthroughs which make the design
more economical.  Others argue that you have to find those designs
first.  This lecture-discussion will focus on the future of fusion
and cover a &quot;competing fusion energy source--inertial confinement.
<P>
<h2>Progress in Magnetic Fusion</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="physics.html">Physics</a>
<li><a href="time.html">Time</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER)</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="design.html">Design</a>
<li><a href="divertor.html">Divertor</a>
<li><a href="materials.html">Materials</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Inertial Fusion</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="concept.html">Concept</a>
<li><a href="target.html">Target</a>
<li><a href="nova.html">NOVA</a>
</ul><P>
