   <TITLE>Solar Heating</TITLE>
<body background="sun.jpg">
<img src="sunline2.gif"><P>

    <H1><center>Solar Heating</center></H1><P>
<center><img src="SOLARHWH.GIF"><P>
By <a href="http://www.students.uiuc.edu/~k-lung">Kevin Lung</a></center><P>
<hr>
<a name=back>
<h2> Table of Contents</h2>
<dl>
<dd><a href= #motive>Motivation</a>
<dd><a href= #history>History of Solar Power</a>
<dd><a href= #tech>Current Technology</a>
<dd><a href= #houses>Several Solar homes</a>
<dd><a href= #future>Future Outlooks</a>
<dd><a href= #conc>Conclusions</a>
<dd><a href= #links>Other Solar Links</a>
<dd><a href= #feed>Feedback</a>
</d1
<hr>
<a name=motive>
<H2>  Motivation</H2><P>
	So why did I  decide to spend several hours creating a 
homepage on the benefits of solar heating?  Well, this page is a result 
of taking <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 
201.</a> Every student was required to create a homepage about different 
energy topics.  A <a 
href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201/students.html">list</a> of all 
our pages is available.  I choose solar heating for my topic, because I 
feel that all energy on earth was originally created by the sun.  Solar 
power is the root of all other energy systems, so why not cut out the 
middle man and deal with it directly.  Although solar home heating is 
only a small part of solar power, its technology is based on developments 
in all aspects of solar power. <p>
 <dd><a href= #back>Back to Table of Contents</a>

<a name=history>
<H2>  History</H2><P>
	The first practical photovoltaic was created in the United States by Bell 
Laboratoties in the early 1950s with the invention of the silicon solar 
cell.  However, public interest in such technology did not begin until 
the big oil shock of 1973.  The first fully functioning passive solar 
home powered by photovoltaics was built in 1980 by a joint venture 
between the Department of Energy and MIT in Carlisle, Massachusetts.  For a 
more detailed look at the history of photovoltaics and the Carlisle House, 
click <a href="http://nrelinfo.nrel.gov/research/pv/us.html">here.<img 
src="fig29.gif"></a><P> <dd><a href= #back>Back to Table of Contents</a>
	<hr>

<a name=tech>
<H2>  Current Technology</H2>
	There are basically two types of technology used in solar powered 
home heating.  Active systems include the use of <a  
href="http://www.rt66.com/aaasolar/tactivew.htm">solar water
heaters</a>, home space heating <a 
href="http://www.rt66.com/aaasolar/thotairs.htm">hot 
air</a> or <a href="http://www.rt66.com/aaasolar/tsphtwh2.htm">liquid</a> 
systems, <a href="http://www.rt66.com/aaasolar/tglycols.htm"> hot water 
glycol systems</a>, and <a 
href="http://www.rt66.com/aaasolar/tpv.htm">solar electricity.</a> 

 Passive 
home heating uses only the <a 
href="http://enertia.com/science.htm">sturcture of the house</a> to generate 
warmth.<P>
<center><img src="enrt_art.gif"></center><P>
This process is accomplished by using two layers of walls.  Solar heated 
air circulates between the two layers delivering heat all around the 
house while making use of the geothermal energy beneath the house.  The 
heavy wood walls store the heat during the day and release it at night.  
The entire house acts as one large heat pump.  The double walls also act 
as a buffer zone to outside noise, wind, and polution.	During the winter 
the attic and basement can be opened up to release heat while the cool 
earth beneath the house cools the circulating air. <img src="summer.gif">


<dd><a href= #back>Back to Table of Contents</a>
<hr>
<a name=houses>
<H2>   Several Solar Houses</H2>
	So now that you're in the market for a solar home, you might want 
to check out what has already been created by a few innovative home builders.
<a href="http://www.ncsc.ncsu.edu/sh.htm"><img 
src="housesml.gif"></a>
<a href="http://www.tuns.ca/~banderrj/solar.html"><img src="solar1.gif"></a>
<a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/wlord/solarhouse.html"><img 
src="test2.gif"></a>
<a href="http://www.netins.net/showcase/solarcatalog/index.html"><img 
src="homestead.GIF"></a>
 <hr>
<a name=future>
<H2>   Future Outlooks</H2>
	Ideally the final goal for solar home heating would be to supply 
every home with enough heat at a cost lower than that needed for nautral 
gas, heat pumps, or electrical heaters.  Some people have already been 
able to accomplish this, such as <a 
href="http://www.netins.net/showcase/solarcatalog/index.html">Mr. 
Solar.</a>  Although initial capital costs are high, due to advances in 
solar technology, the savings in the longrun will be worthwhile.<P>
<dd><a href= #back>Back to Table of Contents</a>
<H2>  Other Solar Links</H2>
<a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/wlord/index.html">Solar
House in Maine<a/><P>
 <a href="http://www-iea.vuw.ac.nz:90/">IEA Solar Heating and Cooling
Programme</a><P>
  <a
href="http://www.ise.fhg.de/Institute.Projects.SelfSuffSolHouse.english.html ">$
<a href="http://www.rt66.com/aaasolar/tactivew.html">Active Solar Water
Heaters - Text</a><P>
 <a href="http://www.engr.wisc.edu/centers/sel/info/research.html">SEL
Current Research</a><P>
 <a href="http://www.engr.wisc.edu/centers/sel/ases/homes.html">Solar
Homes<a/><P>
 <a href="http://princeton.lance.colostate.edu:8080/">Solar Energy
Applications Laboratory <a/><P>
 <a href="http://www.nando.net/prof/eco/int1.html">Sierra Solar Systems
