<html>
<head><TITLE>INTODUCTORY PAGE</TITLE></head>
<Body BGCOLOR="#0000FF"
text="#FFFFFF" link="#FFFF00" vlink="#FFFF00">


<center><h1>Introduction to Large Scale Wind Power</h1></center>

<h3>  Hello!  My name is 
<a href="http://www.cen.uiuc.edu/~jw10148">John Wolfe </a> 
and this is my 
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201 </a>
web project.  I chose large scale wind power as my topic not only because it 
is was part of the course material, but because I feel it is a prudent and 
viable energy source for today and the future.<p></h3>

<h3>The first question one might ask is, "Where does wind come from?".
No, the answer, suprisingly enough, is not that 
<a href="http://www.cen.uiuc.edu/~jw10148"> god </a> is coughing.  But rather
the answer is that wind develops from the uneven heating of the earth.  
The sun will heat the earth to a large degree in one area and to a 
"not-so-large" degree in another area.  The air in the heavily heated area 
has a higher temperature and will flow to the area of lower temperature.</h3>
<p>
<h3>The kinetic energy (energy of motion) of this moving air can be 
harnessed in many ways to perform two main tasks.  First, using high torque 
and low velocity blades, a windmill can be made to pump water.  Wind power's 
most important use to us, however, is for electrical generation.  Through 
the use of 
<a href="http://www.webpage.com/wpt/index.html">Wind Turbine Generators </a> 
(WTGs), engineers have been able to harness 
the flow of air in much the same manner that the flow of water is  harnessed 
in 
<a href="http://www.students.uiuc.edu/~buntic">hydro power.</a>  These (WTGs) are often grouped together in large numbers to 
create
<a href="http://www.umassd.edu/specialprograms/caboverde/windfarm.html"> wind farms</a>.  As time goes on, the technology 
is growing more advanced and it is becoming more and more difficult to 
overlook wind power as an alternative to 
<a href="http://www.nceet.snre.umich.edu/GAIN/homegoals.html"> 
fossil fuels </a>and other energy 
sources.</h3>
<p>


<IMG ALIGN=right 
SRC="http://keynes.fb12.tu-berlin.de/luftraum/konst/bilder/petra.gif">

<h4>Wind has often been called the "unseen power".
In addition to being invisible, it is a resource whose potential has been 
greatly underestimated and overlooked.</h4>
<HR>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
