<title>ICF Direct Drive Ignition</title>
<body bgcolor="0011DD" text="FFFFFF" link="FFFF00" vlink="00ff00">
<h1><center>ICF Direct Drive Ignition</center></h1>
<p>For inertial confinement fusion, the heating of the d-t fuel must be uniform.  One of the ways to obtain 
this uniform heating is through the use of lasers.  This is known as direct drive ignition.<p>
<p>The fuel sphere is heated on all sides equally by about 200 high-power, high-frequency lasers.
<p><img src="icf1.gif">
<p>This may seem rather simple, but in fact requires the latest in laser technology.  It need to be as 
precise as possible so that the sphere is heated uniformly.  If the sphere is heated on one side more than 
the other, the two sides will not compress the fuel, and one will probably blow out similar to a tire on a 
car.  Uniform heating is important to fusion.
<p><a href="ICFrxn.html">Return to Deuterium-Tritium Reaction</a>
<hr><br><i><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
