<title>ICF Deuterium-Tritium Reaction</title>
<body background="swirl.jpg" text="FFFF00" link="FF0011" vlink="FFFFFF">
<center><h1>ICF Deuterium-Tritium Reaction</h1></center>
<h3>How it works:</h3>
<p>First, the deuterium and tritium are fused through the surface of a spherical capsule with a radius of a 
few millimeters.  The capsule is then heated either <a href="ICFdir.html">directly</a> or <a 
href="ICFindir.html">indirectly</a>. 
<p><img src="icf1.gif">
<p>The capsule material then expands, compressing the fuel in the center to over 1000 times solid density 
and temperatures of about 200 million degrees.  
<p><img src="icf2.gif">
<p>The capsule material breaks down, and more heat is applied.
<p><img src="icf3.gif">
<p>The deuterium and tritium then become a <a 
href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201/webproject/lienemann/plasma.html">plasma</a>, ignite, and 
react, producing alpha particles which propagate the reaction, and energy is given off.
<p><img src="icf4.gif">
<p>Where does this take place?  In one huge <a href="ICFchmbr.html">reaction chamber</a>.
<a href=outline.html>Go back to the outline</a>.
<HR><BR><I><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
</DOC>
