Content-length: 1421
</DOCHDR>
<title>Ion Indirect Drive Ignition</title>
<body bgcolor="0011DD" text="FFFFFF" link="FFFF00" vlink="00ff00">
<h1><center>Ion Indirect Drive Ignition</center></h1>
<p>Instead of using lasers as driver beams for the ICF reaction, this method uses ion beams to indirectly 
heat the fuel.  
<p>In ion indirect drive, the fuel is located in a chamber calles a hohlraum.  At one end is a heat absorber 
which radiates soft-xrays when struck by an ion beam.  These x-rays then heat up the fuel.
<p><img src="iondrive.gif">
<p>Unfortunately, this process has never been proven to work experimentally.  Even if it does work in the 
future, there are some problems associated with ion indirect drive.  Refueling is the most difficult problem 
of electricity generation via indirect drive.  Either more than one fuel pellet is enclosed within the 
hohlraum, or multiple hohlraums are necessary for a continuous energy supply.  If the hohlraum contains 
several pellets, it will be difficult, if not impossible, to prevent all the pellets from burning at once.  Using 
several hohlraums will increase cost dramatically and make the reactor much larger.  Also any ion 
indirect drive ignition apparatus will have to allow for almost instantaneous refueling to have continuous 
energy output.
<p><a href="ICFrxn.html">Return to Deuterium-Tritium Reaction></a>
<hr><BR><I><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
