Content-length: 2705
</DOCHDR>
<title>The Government and ICF</title>
<body background="sea.jpg" text="FFFF00" link="00ff00" vlink="FFFFFF">
<h1><center>The Government and ICF</center></h1>
<p>The involvement of the US government is limited to mostly two areas:  The <a 
href=http://wwwofe.er.doe.gov>Department of Energy</a> (DOE) and the <a 
href=http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html>Department of Defense</a> (DOD).  Within 
DOE is the <a href=http://146.138.2.142/>Office of Fusion Energy</a>, whose goal is to use nuclear 
power as an energy source for the next century and beyond.  It wants to replace fossil fuel use with nuclear 
energy.  DOD looks at nuclear power as a defense strategy--if we have the technological edge on nuclear 
warpower, we are, for the most part, safe from attack.
<p><a href="map.gif">Click here</a> to see a map of national laboratories across the nation.
<p>In the early 1970s, the government spent $450 million on fusion research each year.  This number has 
since decreased to today's value of $350 million.  In 1992, Congress enacted the National Energy Policy 
Act which mandated research into the areas of magnetic and inertial confinement fusion.  It did not, 
however, provide more money for the programs.  Today, the government spends $10 million on ICF 
research each year--only 3% of the total fusion research.
<p>The problem with spending only $10 million on ICF research is that very little can be accomplished in 
any reasonable amount of time.  Research then depends upon corporate investment for support.  
Thankfully, industry is doing just that.
<p><a href="http://www-phys.llnl.gov/X_Div/nif.html">The National Ignition Facility</a> (NIF) in 
Livermore, California, is the world's largest ICF research laboratory.  Costs of operation and research total 
over $1 billion dollars every year.  
<p>Since the Clinton administration began, the goal of fusion research has shifted from developing a 
practical, technologically advanced reactor capable of creating electricity to concentrating on the 
underlying principles involved in fusion reactions.  The change has occurred because of budget 
constraints.  The reasoning for this shift is that with a better understanding of the concepts involved, we 
can later build a better, more practical--and economical--mechanism for changing nuclear power into 
electrical energy.  The issue is saving money.  Whether or not we agree with this approach--we don't--we 
must accept it.
<p>Why does the government (sort of) back nuclear power research?
<p><a href=ICFimp.html>What makes fusion so important?</a>
<p><a href=outline.html>Go to the outline</a>.
<hr><br><i><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-86</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B026-415</DOCOLDNO>
