Content-length: 1408
</DOCHDR>
<title>The Importance of Fusion</title>
<body background="blue.jpg" text="FFFFFF" link="FFFF00" vlink="FFFFAA">
<h1><center>The Importance of Fusion</h1></center>
<p>Fusion is important to DOE for energy.  They see fusion as a safe, environmentally acceptable, 
inexhaustible source of energy.  Fossil fuels will not carry us forever; we need to find alternative sources 
of energy.  We saw that we could get 17.6 MeV out of the reaction of one tritium and one deuterium atom.  
These two atoms are readily available, or can be easily made.  We do not have to worry about them 
running out in the near future.  Deuterium is found in about one out of every 2600 water molecules, which 
is about as plentiful as we could ask for, and tritium can be made from lithium, whose supply should last 
at least a few hundred thousand years.
<p>The burning of fossil fuels like coal can be detrimental to the environment.  It can put toxins in the air 
that contribute to the greenhouse effect and global warming.  Nuclear fusion has no toxic gases.  Using 
low-activation materials and advanced fuel cycles make waste less of a problem than in fission.
<p>The DOD sees fusion--ICF in particular--as a <a href="ICFdef.html>technological advantage</a> 
rather than environmental and economical one.
<p><a href=outline.html>Go to the outline</a>.
<HR><BR><I><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-87</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B026-427</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/webproject/lehner/ICFdef.html 128.174.200.146 19970303040700 text/html 2825
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
