Content-length: 2642
</DOCHDR>
<title>DOD and ICF</title>
<body background="dots.jpg" text="FFFFFF" link="FFFF00" vlink="FF00FF">
<h1><center>The <a href=http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html>Department of 
Defense</a> and ICF</center></h1>
<p>Inertial confinement fusion in its existing state shows little promise for electricity generation.  The 
main problems are (beside lack of funding) refueling and the extraction of heat for electricity--we know 
we can get energy, but can we convert it to electricity?
<p>The problem of refueling is keeping the reaction going to produce a constant energy flow necessary to 
generate electricity.  Each sphere with infused fuel can only supply so much energy.  It may be possible to 
set up a few spheres near each other so that one ignites another, which later sets off another, and the chain 
continues.  The problems arise when you have to specify how many fuel pellets you are going to put in the 
chamber.  Ion indirect heating would have to be used, because there would be too many spheres for the 
practical use of lasers.  Then you would have to prevent all the fuel pellets from igniting at once.  The 
other choice would be to have each pellet in its own hohlraum, and to burn them one at a time, but this 
requires multiple hohlraums, and virtually instantaneous refueling.   This is all problematic to the use of 
ICF in electricity generation.
<p>You may have guessed that ICF would be ideal for pulsing situations, where a lot of energy is needed 
for a small amount of time.  This is why DOD supports ICF.  It is perfect for warfare.  Ethical arguments 
aside, ICF is capable of producing the short, high-energy pulses needed for projects like the--now aborted-
-Star Wars program.  ICF doesn't have to produce a constant energy flow inherent to electricity generation 
if it is used in weapons.  Duane Sewell, Assistant Secretary of Energy for Defense promotes the use of <a 
href=http://web.gmu.edu/bcos/Outlaws/fusion>fusion to power fission reactions in weapons</a>.
<p>There are some problems with using ICF in nuclear weapons, though.  The largest of these is public 
response.  Most of the United States citizens want to see at least a decrease in the amount of nuclear 
weapons throughout the world, if not total disarmament.  It is almost political suicide for any government 
official to admit to supporting research into nuclear warfare.  The public doesn't want it.  Politicians will 
not outwardly support it.
<p><a href="ICFfut.html">Where is ICF headed, then?</a>
<p><a href="outline.html">Go to the outline</a>.
<hr><br><i><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
</DOC>
