<title>The Future of ICF</title>
<body background="rock.jpg" text="00ffff" link="FF0000" vlink="00ff00">
<center><h1>The Rocky Future of ICF</h1></center>
<p>Government support of inertial confinement fusion will probably not last long, considering the current 
Administration and the prospects for the next four years.  Without a highly visible campaign to keep ICF 
research funded, it will probably die silently while congressmen are reelected.  Also, when balancing a 
budget becomes even more important to congressmen than the economic security of the nation, you know 
there is no room for ICF.  
<p>ICF, as it is designed now, will not be capable of generating electricity for any practical use.  It will 
not run our computers or light our homes.  It is perfect for weapons operations, but public opinion will 
definitely destroy that application.
<p>The abandonment of practical research into fusion also hurts development of ICF.  ICf as it is 
designed now is not technically viable.  We need to research, design and test, until we come up with a 
solution that works.  Unfortunately, the current, and most likely future, Administrations will not support 
this practical research.
<p>ICF is not necessarily a lost cause, despite the government's waning support.  Private industry is 
funding most of the research today anyway.  Corporations understand the immediate need to learn about 
fusion, to make it practical for electricity generation, and to address the environmental concerns along 
with that.  
<p>All we can do now is wait and see.
<p>
<a href="ICFsrc.html">WWW sources</a><p>
<a href=outline.html>Go to the outline</a>.
<hr><br><i><a href=mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
