<head><title>Photovoltaics</title></head>
<body><center><h1>FUTURE DEVELOPMENTS</h1></center>
<center><img src="fig34.gif" align=center alt="[fig34]"><br 
clear=all><i>U.S National Renewable Energy Laboratory's New Solar Energy 
Facility</i></center>
<p>As PV technology continues to improve, it steadily moves into larger 
markets.  PV systems have been the best choice for many jobs since the 
first commercial PV cells were developed.
<p>For example, PV cells have been the exclusive power source fo 
satillites orbiting the earth since the 1960's.  In the 1980's, 
commercial and consumer product manufacturers began incorporating PV into 
everything from watches and calculators to music boxes.  In the 90's, 
many utilities are finding PV to be the best choice for thousands of 
small power needs.  During the next decade, a large part of the world's 
population will be introduced to electricity produced by PV systems. 
These PV systems will make the traditional requirements of building 
large, expensive power plants and distribution systems unnecessary.
<p>As the costs of the PV continue to decline and as PV technology 
continues to improve, several potentially huge markets for PV will open 
up.  For example, building materials that incorporate PV cells will be 
designed right into new high rises and holmes, helping to ventilate and 
light buildings.  Consumer products ranging from battery powered 
hard-ware tools to automobiles will take advantageof electricity 
producing components containing PV materials.  Meanwhile electric 
utilities wil find more and more ways to use PV to supply the needs of 
their customers. 
<p><a href="index.html">INTRODUCTION AND HISTORY</a>
<p><a href="CT.html">CURRENT TECHNOLOGY</a>
<p><a href="FD.html">FUTURE DEVELOPEMENTS</a>
<p><a href="C.html">CONCLUSIONS</a>
