<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Current Technology</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="gifs/bg03.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#008080" VLINK="#000080">
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>Current Technologies</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Combustion</FONT></B>:
<P>
Currently there are three predominant methods of burning coal
to make steam, power turbines, and generate electricity. Most
coal power plants either burn pulverized coal blown into a boiler
or use cyclone furnaces to burn coal in a vortex of air. The current
trend for new coal power plants is to use fluidized bed combustion
which has a number of advantages over the other methods. <BR>
<P>
<A HREF="gifs/pulvsys2.jpg"><B>Pulverized-Coal System:</B></A>
<P>
<A HREF="gifs/burner2.jpg"><IMG SRC="gifs/burner.jpg" ALIGN="left"></A>The
concept of burning coal that has been pulverized into a fine powder
stems from the belief that if the coal is made fine enough, it
will burn almost as easily and efficiently as a gas. The whole
process starts as the coal arrives at the power plant. Typically
the coal arrives in sizes suitable for the plant's coal pulverizing
mechanism (1-1/4&quot; dia. or less). Computers control the feeding
rate of coal according to the boiler demand and the amount of
air available for drying and transporting the pulverized coal
fuel. Numerous types of pulverizers or grinding mills exist but
the ones most commonly used today are the medium speed <A HREF="pulv.html">ball-and-race </A>and
roll-and-race pulverizers. Pieces of coal are crushed between
balls or cylindrical rollers that move between two tracks or &quot;races.&quot;
The raw coal is fed into the pulverizer along with air heated
to about 650&#176;F from the boiler. As the coal gets crushed
by the rolling action, the hot air dries it and blows the usable
fine coal powder out to be used as fuel. The powdered coal from
the pulverizer is directly blown to a burner in the boiler. The
burner mixes powdered coal in the air suspension with additional
pre-heated combustion air and forces it out of a nozzle similar
in action to fuel being atomized by a fuel injector in modern
cars. Under operating conditions, there is enough heat in the
combustion zone to ignite all the incoming fuel. To start the
burners in the first place, a spark is used to ignite fuel-oil
or gas which burns until operating temperatures are reached. Due
to the turbulent nature of the particles moving through the burner
and the high operating temperatures, part of the burner must be
replaced annually. <A HREF="source.html">(2)</A>
<P>
<B>Cyclone Furnaces:</B>
<P>
Cyclone furnaces were developed after pulverized coal systems
and require less processing of the coal fuel. They can burn poorer
grade coals with higher moisture contents and ash contents to
25%. In a cyclone furnace system, coal is delivered to the plant
is pieces with diameters of &#188;&quot; or less. The crushed
coal feed is either stored temporarily in bins or transported
directly to the cyclone furnace. The <A HREF="gifs/cyclon2.jpg">furnace</A>
is basically a large cylinder jacketed with water pipes that absorb
the some of the heat to make steam and protect the burner itself
from melting down. A high powered fan blows the heated air and
chunks of coal into one end of the cylinder. At the same time
additional heated combustion air is injected along the curved
surface of the cylinder causing the coal and air mixture to swirl
in a centrifugal &quot;cyclone&quot; motion. The whirling of the
air and coal enhances the burning properties producing high heat
densities (about 4700 to 8300kW/m<SUP>2</SUP>) and high combustion
temperatures. The hot combustion gases leave the other end of
the cylinder and enter the boiler to heat the water filled pipes
and produce steam. Like in the pulverized coal burning process,
all the fuel that enters the cyclone burns when injected once
the furnace is at its operating temperature. To initially heat
the furnace, fuel oil is injected in the burner in place of coal
and is spark ignited. The cyclone furnace has a very high operating
temperature of more than 3000&#176;F which melts the ash in the
coal into a liquid slag that collects around the cylinder surface.
Some slag remains on the walls insulating the burner and directing
the heat into the boiler while the rest drains through a trench
in the bottom to a collection tank where it is solidified and
disposed of. This ability to collect ash is the biggest advantage
of the cyclone furnace burning process. Only 40% of the ash leaves
with the exhaust gases compared with 80% for pulverized coal burning.
Cyclone furnaces are not without disadvantages. The coal used
must have a relatively low sulfur content in order for most of
the ash to melt for collection. In addition, high power fans are
required to move the larger coal pieces and air forcefully through
the furnace, and more nitrogen oxide pollutants are produced compared
with pulverized coal combustion. Finally, the actual burner requires
yearly replacement of its liners due to the erosion caused by
the high velocity of the coal. Missouri's <A HREF="http://www.ue.com:80/about-ue/power-plants/sioux.html">Sioux Coal Power Plant </A>uses
10 of these cyclone furnaces to heat a 21 story boiler. <A HREF="source.html">(2)</A>
<BR>
<P>
<B>Fluidized-Bed Combustion:</B>
<P>
Both the pulverized coal and cyclone furnaces emphasized maximizing
coal and air interactions in the combustion chamber in order to
maximize combustion efficiency. The fluidized bed combustors continue
this trend, and at the same time attempt to vastly decrease the
combustion pollutants of coal. In the fluidized bed combustion,
crushed coal between &#188;&quot; and &#190;&quot; in size is
injected into a bed above a grate-like air distributor. Air is
injected upward through the grate lifting and <A HREF="gifs/fluidbed.jpg">suspending the solid particles</A>.
The bed continues to expand allowing a greater air flow rate until
an equilibrium position is reached. At this point the particles
can move freely, and the bed behaves like a fluid. &quot;Bubbles&quot;
of air moving upward through the relatively dense &quot;fluid&quot;
of particles serve to rapidly mix materials added to the bed and
transfer heat rapidly from one part of the bed to another. The
bed is preheated by a gas startup burner which heats it to the
ignition temperature of the coal. The swirling coal particles
are then combusted forming the furnace. About half of the heat
generated is transferred to in-bed tubes and the hot gasses leaving
the bed pass through other tubes like a conventional boiler. Some
unburned carbon particles and ash escape with the gases, but they
are recaptured in a grit arrestor or cyclone separator and reinjected
into the bed to improve combustion efficiency (<A HREF="gifs/fluidpl2.jpg" >schematic diagram</A>).
 As indicated before, fluidized bed combustion has a number of
advantages over other combustion techniques. When limestone is
added directly to the fluidized bed it effectively absorbs sulfur
dioxide, a major pollutant from sulfur deposits in the coal. Limestone
(mostly CaCO<SUB>3</SUB>) reacts with the sulfur dioxide and some
oxygen to produce calcium sulfate in the following reaction: CaCO<SUB>3</SUB>
+ SO<SUB>2</SUB> + .5O<SUB>2</SUB> CaSO<SUB>4</SUB> + CO<SUB>2</SUB>.
The calcium sulfate is a dry waste product and accounts for up
to a 90% reduction in sulfur dioxide emissions. Fluidized bed
combustors operate at relatively low temperatures (1380&#176;C
-1740&#176;C) resulting in lower emissions of nitrogen oxides
and less ash fouling of heat transfer surfaces. Finally, coal
plants using fluidized bed combustion are more economical to construct
as they don't require expensive pulverization equipment or scrubbers
to control SO<SUB>2</SUB> emission, and they are typically much
more compact than a conventional plant as the fluidized bed is
much more efficient in transferring heat than a conventional boiler.
<A HREF="source.html">(3)</A> <BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Pollution Control:</FONT></B>
<P>
Pollution control is a very important part of modern <A HREF="http://www.doe.gov/html/fe/cctmap.html">&quot;clean coal&quot; </A>power
plant technology. It can be an integral part of the combustion
process as already shown or it can take place &quot;after the
fact&quot; using a number of post combustion devices. In either
case, pollution control represents a large portion of the <A HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/topics/advanced_coal_technologies/coal.html">cost of building and maintaining </A>a
coal power plant. The most widely used devices are described below.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Electrostatic Precipitation:</B>
<P>
<A HREF="gifs/elepre2.jpg">Electrostatic Precipitators </A>or
ESPs are the most widely used technology to remove particulate
matter from coal plant exhaust gasses. ESPs consist of two parts.
The first part is a set of electrically grounded vertical parallel
plates. In between them run a set of wire electrodes that produce
a high voltage direct current electric field. When gasses pass
through the wire electrodes and plates, particulate matter the
enters the electric field acquires a negative charge and is <A HREF="gifs/statifn2.jpg">attracted to the grounded plates</A>.
A layer of collected particles accumulates on the plates and is
periodically removed by rapping the plates. The collected matter
falls into hoppers and is removed for disposal. <A HREF="source.html">(2)</A>
<P>
<B>Sorbent Injection:</B>
<P>
Sorbent Injection involves the injection of a dry calcium based
reagent like powdered limestone into the furnace to react with
SO<SUB>2</SUB> as described in the fluidized bed process. The
<A HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/topics/advanced_coal_technologies/sorbent.html">reagent is blown </A>in
through burners, air ports, or wall jets that penetrate the furnace
to react with the sulfur dioxide and form calcium sulfate. Sorbent
Injection typically can remove around 50% of sulfur dioxide emissions.
Effectiveness is limited by the temperature where the reaction
occurs and the thoroughness of mixing the reagent with the exhaust
gasses. <A HREF="source.html">(4)</A>
<P>
<B>Scrubbers :</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="gifs/wetscrb.jpg">
<P>
In a wet scrubber the filtered exhaust gas (no particles) is sprayed
with a solution of lime (CaO), limestone, calcium sulfite, and
calcium sulfate to form a cleaned moisture-saturated flue gas
and a liquid by-product. The gaseous sulfur dioxide is absorbed
into the liquid where the sulfur dioxide combines with calcium
and precipitates out as CaSO<SUB>4</SUB>. The waste liquid is
filtered and centrifuged to remove most of the solid, and the
remaining liquid is mixed with fresh reagent and recycled in the
process. The wet scrubber has the advantages of high efficiency,
good reliability, and low energy requirements. The main disadvantages
are the formation of scale (calcium salts) in the spray tower
that can plug injectors and a waste sludge solution that requires
costly disposal. Dry (or semi-dry) scrubbing operates by the same
principle a wet scrubbing except that the lime is injected in
a very fine mist in the unfiltered exhaust gas. The water evaporates
in the hot exhaust leaving only the particulate CaSO<SUB>4</SUB>
which is then removed from the gas with the ash and other particulates
in electrostatic precipitators and filters (see baghouse below).
The dry powder waste of the dry scrubber is easier to handle and
dispose of than the waste slurry from the wet scrubber, but dry
scrubbing is less efficient. The biggest disadvantage to any type
of sulfur dioxide removal is the enormous <A HREF="scrub.html">capital and maintenance cost.</A>
Many coal plants elect to use more expensive low-sulfur coal as
fuel to reduce sulfur dioxide emissions to mandated levels rather
than pay the additional cost for scrubbers. <A HREF="source.html">(2)</A>
<BR>
<P>
<B>Low-NO<SUB>x</SUB> Burner:</B> 
<P>
<IMG SRC="gifs/lownox.jpg"><A HREF="source.html">(2)</A>
<P>
Low NO<SUB>x</SUB> burners replace conventional burners in pulverized
coal power plants. They achieve lower nitrous oxide emissions
by carefully regulating the air streams around the burner and
in the combustion zone so that only the necessary amount of air
is in the combustion region. Although NO<SUB>x</SUB> conversion
reaction are not completely understood, it is believed to depend
on the interaction of volatile fuel reactants in oxygen rich zones.
By controlling the air and hence the oxygen flow with the vanes
in the burner, nitrogen oxide emissions can be reduced by 20%
to 50%.
<P>
<B>Fabric Filters and Baghouses:</B>
<P>
<A HREF="gifs/baghse2.jpg"><IMG SRC="gifs/baghouse.jpg"></A><A HREF="source.html">(2)</A>
<P>
In a baghouse, dirty exhaust air passes through a series of long,
hollow, cylindrical filter elements similar to vacuum cleaner
bags. The filter elements are usually open on the bottom to allow
air to enter and closed on top to capture dust and other ash particles
as the carrier air passes through them. The filters are periodically
shaken or collapsed to dislodge the &quot;dust cake&quot; so that
it falls into a collection bin for removal. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
