<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>History and Background</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="gifs/bg01.jpg" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#800000" VLINK="#008080">
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>A Brief History and Background</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="gifs/erlyboil.jpg"> Coal has played a major
role in electricity production ever since the first power plants
were built in the United States in the 1880's. The earliest power
plants used hand fed wood and/or coal to heat a boiler and produce
steam. This steam was used in reciprocating steam engines which
turned generators to produce electricity. However, these early
engines were slow moving and relatively inefficient at producing
electricity, and the coal was being used in relatively large sized
pieces making complete combustion difficult. In 1884 the more
efficient high-speed steam turbine was developed by the British
Engineer Charles A. Parsons which rapidly replaced the use of
steam engines to generate electricity. As more powerful and efficient
turbines came into use (from 5,000kW in 1903 to 60,000kW in 1918
and 208,000kW in 1929) better ways of stoking and burning coal
started to be developed. <A HREF="stoker.html">Mechanical stokers </A>allowed
higher rates of combustion by continuously feeding coal into the
furnace by moving in a grate through the furnace. Pulverized-coal
firing was developed in the 1920's bringing advantages that included
higher combustion temperatures, improved thermal efficiency, and
a lower requirement for excess air for combustion. In the 1940's
the cyclone furnace was developed which allowed the combustion
of poorer grade coal with less ash production and greater overall
efficiency. Improvements in efficiency have continued to occur
throughout the years by learning to extract more energy from the
Rankine energy cycle through steam reheating and regeneration,
improving boiler efficiency, and further developing more complete
and cleaner methods of coal combustion. Overall, electricity production
from coal is based on the same methods started over 100 years
ago, but improvements in all areas have brought coal power to
be the inexpensive power source used so widely today. <A HREF="source.html">(1),(2)</A>
<HR>
