<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Future Developments</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="gifs/bg05.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#008080" VLINK="#000080">
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>Future Developments</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Coal Gasification/Combined Cycle:</B>
<P>
The coal gasification/combined cycle power plant is currently
in the demonstration project stage of development and may become
part of major utilities power plants in the 2000-2010 time frame.
In an integrated <A HREF="gifs/comcyc2.jpg">coal gasification combined cycle plant</A>,
both a high temperature gas turbine using a Brayton cycle and
a lower temperature steam turbine using a Rankine cycle are used
to generate electricity more efficiently. Crushed coal is first
gasified by reacting it with a mixture of air or oxygen and high
temperature steam to form a &quot;syngas&quot; fuel consisting
mostly of CO, H<SUB>2</SUB>, N<SUB>2</SUB>, and CO<SUB>2</SUB>.
This gas is then cooled, cleaned, and reheated using hot gas exiting
the gasifier in a gas-to-gas heat exchanger. Next the gaseous
fuel is combusted to turn a compressor and a gas turbine to generate
electricity. The compressor has a dual role. It pressurizes air
for combustion in the gas turbine and provides heated compressed
air to use in the gasification process. The exhaust gas from the
gas turbine is still very hot and is subsequently used to produce
steam in another heat exchanger. This steam turns a conventional
turbine to produce additional electricity. Advanced designs have
predicted efficiencies near 45 percent as compared to efficiencies
around 33 percent for other conventional coal power plants. Other
advantages include the removal of more than 98% of the sulfur
in the gasification process to prevent sulfur dioxide emissions,
and nitrous oxide emissions comparable to those from natural gas
fueled combined cycle plants. Indiana's Wabash River Power Plant
is currently the <A HREF="http://www.orsanco.org/orbcre/wrpp1301.html">world's largest gasifier</A>,
and is a joint venture between the <A HREF="http://www.doe.gov">US Department of Energy </A>and
Cinergy Corp's PSI Energy. Additional details about the progress
in developing integrated gasification combined cycle plants is
available on the <A HREF="http://www.fe.doe.gov/igcc_sum.html">DOE's IGCC page</A>.
<A HREF="source.html">(2)</A> <BR>
CaSO<SUB>4</SUB>.
<P>
<B>Combined Cycle <A HREF="http://www.metc.doe.gov/research/power/pfbc/homepage.html" ><B>Pressurized Fluidized Bed Combustion</B></A>:</B>
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.fe.doe.gov/pfb_dia.gif" >Pressurized fluidized bed combustion</A>
is an advanced spin-off of ordinary fluidized bed combustion that
is currently in the first generation stage of development. Fluidized
bed combustion can occur either at atmospheric pressure as described
previously or at a higher pressures ranging from 5 to 20 atmospheres.
When the bed is pressurized, the hot gasses produced from the
bed furnace are used first as before to heat water, produce steam,
and generate electricity using a steam turbine in an Rankine cycle.
In addition, hot exhaust is removed from the furnace, cleaned,
and then used in a Brayton cycle to turn a gas turbine and generate
electricity. A compressor attached to the gas turbine is turned
at the same time and is used to pressurize the fluidized bed chamber.
Advantages of the PFBC process include a higher obtainable power
output per square meter of bed area and greater plant efficiency
combined with all the advantages of conventional fluidized bed
combustion. <BR>
<P>
<B>Magnetohydrodynamics:</B>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="gifs/magbox.jpg">Magnetohydrodynamics (MHD)
is an experimental method of electricity production that is still
in the early development stage. In MHD hot ionized gas from combusting
coal is mixed with potassium carbonate (called &quot;seed&quot;)
to increase its conductivity. The ionized gas then flows through
a strong magnetic field inducing an electric field and setting
up a potential difference between the walls of the duct. Then
using a solid state inverter, the DC current generated is converted
to AC. After flowing through the magnetic field, the hot gasses
are then used to generate steam and turn a turbine as in a conventional
plant. As the heat is transferred, slag is removed for disposal
and the seed is captured for recycling. Early tests indicate that
this method should be viable for commercial electricity production
but more research is necessary. One considerable drawback is the
need to use expensive superconducting magnets that must be cooled
to -269&#176;C (4K) to generate the necessary magnetic fields.
<A HREF="source.html">(4)</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="gifs/magconc.jpg"> <BR>
<P>
<B>CO<SUB>2</SUB> Membranes and Underground Storage:<BR>
</B>Carbon dioxide is one of the major greenhouse gases and numerous
studies have linked higher atmospheric concentrations of CO<SUB>2</SUB>
with <A HREF="http://www.usatoday.com/life/science/environ/lse001.htm">global warming</A>.
Because CO<SUB>2</SUB> is mainly produced by the combustion of
fossil fuels and coal produces the <A HREF="http://www.unep.ch/iucc/fs025">most CO2 per energy unit derived</A>,
numerous research project are underway in an effort to determine
what can be done with all the carbon dioxide if it is too harmful
to release in to the atmosphere. One <A HREF="gifs/co2sep2.jpg">program</A>
suggests using advanced polymer membranes that serve as CO<SUB>2</SUB>
filters. Desulfurized exhaust gases are forcibly passed through
the membranes (reverse osmosis) separating the flue gas into a
CO<SUB>2</SUB>-rich permeate and CO<SUB>2</SUB>-lean retentate.
The CO<SUB>2</SUB>-rich gas is then collected and heavily compressed
for transport. The suggestion then is to store the carbon dioxide
underground in depleted natural gas fields, oil fields, and aquifers.
The storage capacities for these areas range anywhere from 200
to 1500 Gtonnes of carbon dioxide. Overall these proposals are
still in the experimental stage as membrane purification is expensive
costing about $65 per tonne of CO<SUB>2</SUB> avoided. Large scale
underground CO<SUB>2</SUB> storage is estimated to cost between
<A HREF="gifs/co2grph.jpg">$0.5 to $16 per tonne </A>but its side
effects if any are still unknown. <A HREF="source.html">(5)</A>
<BR>
<HR>
