<TITLE>Conclusions</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="gifs/bg04.jpg" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#800000" VLINK="#008080">
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>Conclusion</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
The use of electricity has been an essential part of the US economy
since the turn of the century and as supplies of oil and natural
gas diminish, electricity will likely become even more important.
Coal power is an established electricity source that will be able
to provide vast quantities of inexpensive, reliable power well
into the future. Although coal combustion has a number of negative
environmental impacts, current combustion techniques and pollution
control devices have significantly reduced emissions and new innovations
coming into use promise to lower emissions even further. Coal
may never be a completely &quot;clean&quot; power source as the
production and emission of carbon dioxide and some nitrogen oxides
are inevitable, but it will be our electricity mainstay at least
until <A HREF="http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/pubs_html/rea/tablecon.html">renewable</A>
or <A HREF="http://FusionEd.gat.com/webstuff/What-is-Fusion.html">nuclear fusion </A>technologies
have the capacity and economy to displace coal usage, prospects
that will likely take many years to develop.<BR>
<BR>
