<HEAD>
<TITLE>What is the environmental impact?</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF3333" VLINK="#FFFFFF" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<h1><CENTER><I>Electric Cars<BR>What is the environmental impact?</I></CENTER></h1>
<p>
<HR size=1>

<TEXTAREA NAME="" ROWS="" COLS="">Electric vehicle's don't burn gasoline in an engine (and thus don't give off any emissions), but they do require approximately 12 to 24 batteries per car.  These batteries are themselves an environmental hazard.  However, if they are properly recycled, their environmental impact can be minimized.  The largest environmental impact is in the increased electricity production that would be required.  The Energy Commission calculates that electric vehicles will consume about 7,483 gigawatt/hours of electricity by 2010.  This is approximately 3.2% of the total electricity consumed by California in 1993.  Most electric vehicles will recharge at night, however.  This off-peak recharging would make use of electrical power plant capacity that would normally sit idle.  Using these idle power plants would make the electricity system more efficient overall and would help to stabilize electricity rates.  Also, the emissions given off by the power plant are more localized than those by automobiles.  If the power plant is properly located in a rural area, this would result in a lessened environmental impact (since air pollution levels in these areas are currently low).</TEXTAREA>

<P><TEXTAREA NAME="" ROWS="" COLS="">Although electric cars are obviously not the perfect solution to air pollution, they would still have a lessened impact on the environment than gasoline cars currently have.  Thus, the electric vehicle is still a very viable solution.</TEXTAREA>

</DOC>
