<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Effects of Fossil Fuels</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Environmental Effects of Fossil Fuels</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 19
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 Buring fossil fules, especially coal, is dirty.  The impurities,
such as S also burn and produce potnetially dnagerous oxides.
 Since the air is made of 80% nitrogen, it is combusted into nitrous
oxides along with the fuel.  Since fossil fules are mainly carbon,
all fossil fule produces carbon dioxide when burned.  The sulphur
and nitrous oxides produce acids in the atmosphere which can lead
to acid rain.  The carbon dioxide helps trap heat in the atmosphere
contributing to the potential warming of the earth.  In this lectrure-discussion
we will examine these two large-scale environmental effects of
fossil fuels.
<P>
