<title>Nuclear Power for Transport</title>
<body bgcolor=#000066 text=#ffffff vlink=#ff0000 link=#ffff00>
<center><h1>
Nuclear Power for Transport
</h1></center>

<dd>Nuclear power has always been highly visible in the arms race
and in commercial electrical generation, but its greatest potential
lies in transportation.  Nuclear power is so important because of
its high energy to fuel mass ratio.  One pound of uranium-235 gives the power
of 5,000 barrels of crude oil.	Thus, vehicles using nuclear fuel can undergo
greater accelerations than their counterparts while yielding more
payload space.	Since World War II, this potential has inspired numerous
efforts and achievements over the last fifty years and continues to
excite new generations of great minds as we enter the next millenium.<p>


<dl><font size=+1>
<dd><a href=planes.html><img src=777-3.gif>Nuclear Aircraft</a>
<dd><a href=auto.html><img src=car.gif>Nuclear Automobiles</a>
<dd><img src=sub-1.gif>Nuclear Seapower</font>
<dl><dd><img src=yeldot.gif><a href=navy.html>Nuclear Navy</a>
    <dd><img src=yeldot.gif><a href=prvte.html>Nuclear Merchant Marine</a>
    <dd><img src=yeldot.gif><a href=ice.html>Nuclear Icebreakers</a>
</dl><font size=+1>
<dd><a href=space.html><img src=rocket.gif>Nuclear Spacecraft</a>
<dd><a href=media.html><img src=reel.gif>Nuclear Transport in Entertainment</a>
</dl></font>
<p>
For more information, check out a few of my
