<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> United States </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h2 align="center">  United States  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>The United States has had a long and varied relationship with breeder reactors.  Following the relative success of EBR-I, Congress appropriated large funds to explore breeder reactors.  From 1948 to 1977, for example, the United States invested a total of $2.8 billion dollars in providing an inexhaustible energy source through the liquid-metal-cooled fast breeder reactor (LMFBR) <a href="refrnc.html#8M">(8M)</a>.  EBR-I was a breeder reactor of this variety since it utilized the liquid sodium-potassium alloy.   Beginning in 1964, Experimental Breeder Reactor II (EBR-II) began operation.  Originally intended to show the entire nuclear cycle, EBR-II included a breeder reactor functioning as a power source with facilities on-site for <a href="glossary.html#reproc">reprocessing</a> metallic fuels.  Demonstration of the plant proceeded from 1964 to 1969, at which time the emphasis of the plant was shifted to testing materials and fuels for future fast breeder reactors.  Consisting of a sodium-cooled reactor, a secondary closed loop of sodium, and a steam plant, EBR-II produced 19 MW of electric power with conventional <a href="glossary.html#turbine">turbines</a> and <a href="glossary.html#generate">generators</a> <a href="refrnc.html#12I">(12I)</a>.  Since its inauguration, EBR-II has been continually remodified to provide both better research opportunities and better safety.  More recently, the EBR-II has been converted to the Integral Fast Reactor (IFR) prototype, a type of fast breeder reactor discussed under &quot;Current Technology.&quot;

<p>During the latter half of the 1970s, in part because of the <a href="glossary.html#energy">energy</a> crisis of 1973 and 1974, funding for breeder reactor research was greatly increased in the United States.  The Energy Research and Development Administration (ERDA) concluded in 1975 that after reassessment of the breeder reactor program, a shift towards non-nuclear alternatives should be advanced.  After review of a seven-volume environmental statement about nuclear <a href="glossary.html#reactor">reactors</a>, however, the breeder reactor was pursued with renewed interest.  A new Division of Reactor Development and Demonstration was organized to further the cause of breeder reactors.  Robert C. Seamans, Jr., administrator for the ERDA, cited that questions involving the areas of &quot;plant operation, fuel cycle performance, reactor safety, safeguards, health effects, waste management, and uranium resource availability&quot; still remained unanswered for the breeder reactor <a href="refrnc.html#5M">(5M)</a>.  Early in 1976, the plans for breeder reactors included the completion of a demonstration reactor at Clinch River near Oak Ridge, Tennessee (CRBR), a Prototype Large Breeder Reactor (PLBR), and the first Commercial Breeder Reactor (CBR-I) <a href="refrnc.html#5M">(5M)</a>.

<p>In an article entitled &quot;Breeders and the Numbers Game,&quot; <i>Science News</i> outlined the conflicting views about the expected gains from pursuing breeder reactors and the economic balance between investment and profit <a href="refrnc.html#6M">(6M)</a>.  Based on different interpretations of even subtle differences that may arise in the future, various sources predicted significant gains or losses from investment in breeder research.  The government predicted a $14.7 billion benefit from an $8 billion investment.  Brian G. Chow, author of <i>The Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor, An Economic Analysis</i>, estimated net losses of $200 million to $4.3 billion, while another study entitled <i>An Assessment of the Economic Incentive for the Breeder Reactor</i> placed a figure of $76 billion on benefits from the breeder reactor <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(6M)</a>.

<p>Utilities within the United States generally supported a series of breeder reactor development and construction projects.  In total, utilities representing eighty-five percent of electrical generating capacity in the United States contributed $250 million and a plant engineering team to the Clinch River Breeder Reactor project <a href="refrnc.html#56M">(56M)</a>.  Even by 1976, however, European nations and Japan had begun to show greater interest in breeder reactor technology.  Two scientists from the Electric Power Research Institute of Palo Alto, California, lamented this fact by focusing on the relative inaction of the United States in regards to the option of fast breeder reactors:</p>

<blockquote><i>Seven developed nations (six in Europe plus Japan) are aggressively developing and starting to deploy the breeder.  They see it as the only reasonably technically assured source of energy which is not dependent upon large domestic fuel resources and which is not interruptible by the changing winds of foreign relations.  In each of these countries, the immediate realities of development, both of energy and of the resources that depend on energy, have been experienced recently and much more intensely than at any time in the history of the United States.  With most Americans lacking in any personal experience with the realities of deprivation, this country luxuriates in debate, searching for near-zero hypothetical risks to man and environment from nuclear and fossil energy, while the far greater real risks of inaction grow and multiply.</i>  <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(56M)</a></blockquote>

<p>The same feelings regarding the declining interest in breeder reactors in the United States was cited in <i>Scientific American</i> in March 1977 <a href="refrnc.html#8M">(8M)</a>.  Despite the early U.S. lead in breeder reactors and the appropriation of sufficient funds by the government, the American program lagged behind those of other industrialized nations, most notably France, by this time.  A particularly optimistic and inconceivable forecast by the ERDA in March 1975 had predicted the operation of 128 <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeders</a> by 1998.  This date is only about eighteen months away from the present, but it was obviously a ludicrous goal even then.  Even the small scale forecast envisioned by the General Accounting Office of Congress concluded four to six commercial LMFBRs in operation by the year 2000, but even this goal will not be realized.  The General Accounting Office did recognize that &quot;public acceptance and institutional adaptation [of breeder reactors] may be more difficult than technical considerations&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#8M">(8M)</a>.  In short, by the late 1970s, the United States' had acquiesced superiority in the science of breeder reactors to more powerful programs abroad, the predictions of future accomplishments were too optimistic and less realistic, and commercialization of such plants on a large scale seemed implausible.

<p>Even the future of the Clinch River Breeder Reactor was in peril in November 1977.  President Jimmy Carter, who advocated the removal of programs which could aid the proliferation of nuclear weapons, was opposed to the Congressional bill authorizing $80 million in funds for the CRBR and exercised his veto power <a href="refrnc.html#11M">(11M)</a>.  The problem of safe-guarding breeder fuel and the plutonium purified in reprocessing plants was viewed as a major reason necessitating blockage of the bill.  Estimating the costs at $2.2 billion, President Carter also rejected the CRBR for technological and economic fallibility as well as from the perspective that it was no longer necessary.  By conventional reasoning, the plan was to switch to breeder reactors from normal fission reactors around 1990, and then abandon these reactors when solar energy and <a href="glossary.html#fusion">fusion</a> became sources for electric power on a large scale.  As a result of lowered expectations about the need for energy in the future, however, President Carter defended his veto of the bill that would have allocated funds to the CRBR.  This was the first veto of his administration.  The future of the LMFBR was summarized as being &quot;gravely ill,&quot; but &quot;not dead--yet&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#11M">(11M)</a>.

<p>In 1979, a reversal of fate regarding the CRBR was achieved as the House of Representatives approved funding of $183 million in the 1980 budget for the project.  The previous year, funds had also been approved despite President Carters stalwart objections <a href="refrnc.html#46M">(46M)</a>.  In general, support for nuclear power remained high in Congress, even despite the Three Mile Island incident that had happened earlier that year.  Overall, the years of politics as usual, accusations of pork-barrel projects, and endless debates about the direction of American energy policy had drained enthusiasm for the topic.  In April of 1977, President Carter had called for the end of the CRBR, and officially declared the project terminated.  Nevertheless, Congress continued to approve funding, but President Carter made it impossible for the Nuclear Regulatory Commission to issue the license needed to begin construction at the Clinch River site <a href="refrnc.html#17M">(17M)</a>.  Thus, by October 1980, the entire 1,364 acre site in Oak Ridge, Tennessee approved for the CRBR remained completely devoid of any evidence of construction.  With utilities paying some of the bill, 4,000 people in 24 states employed for the project, and 149 companies expecting business from providing hardware for the CRBR, the inactivity in Washington, D.C. clearly upset many people affiliated with the project.  Meanwhile, at the September 1980 World Energy Conference in Munich, West Germany, the United States was officially declared as being &quot;out of step with the rest of the world in development of nuclear energy&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#17M">(17M)</a>.

<p>The Clinch River Breeder Reactor began a long, slow, and agonizing death during the first half of the 1980s.  After Ronald Reagan ascended to the Presidency in 1981, this strong supported of nuclear power maintained appropriations of the CRBR for 1982 by lobbying in the House and winning the vote by the slim margin of 206 to 186 <a href="refrnc.html#13M">(13M)</a>.  The common views among many people at the time included belief in the CRBR as an &quot;unnecessary and colossally mismanaged boondoggle.&quot;  Indeed, even the arguments of proponents for the reactor, that the generation of new fuel would guarantee the United States an unlimited domestic supply of atomic fuel, had been eroded by the availability of conventional <a href="glossary.html#uranium">uranium</a> resources for another 50 years at least <a href="refrnc.html#13M">(13M)</a>.  The CRBR was cited as a major pork-barrel project for Senate Majority Leader Howard Baker, whose home state is Tennessee <a href="refrnc.html#4M">(4M)</a>.  Editorials began appearing in numerous magazines, newspapers, and journals regarding the progress of the CRBR.  Although very promising when proposed in the early 1970s, by the early 1980s the CRBR had come to symbolize nothing more than the political power of Senator Baker and had little to do with the science involved.  In fact, the technology and theory of the CRBR had become all but obsolete by 1982.  In addition, funding for solar, wind, and biomass energy was cut to release money for nuclear investment.  Even <i>Readers Digest</i>, which reaches a mass American audience every month, reported the CRBR as Senator Bakers &quot;Costly Technological Turkey&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#14M">(14M)</a>.  Originally proposed in 1969 as a means by which to perfect fast breeder reactor technology and ultimate make it commercially viable, the original scientific motivations had been decimated and overshadowed by the equally accurate reports of political infidelity.

<p>In May 1983, the House Science and Technology Committee finally eliminated funding for the CRBR <a href="refrnc.html#35M">(35M)</a>.  Congress decided not to approve the funding scheme in deference to more exigent matters.  A larger contribution from private companies and organizations was deemed necessary to continue the project.  Greater problems existed, however, in relation to the ultimate construction of the plant, if the project ever approached that level of completeness.  The Tennessee Valley Authority reported no interest in buying the plant or purchasing the electrical power.  Additionally, William Chandler of the Environmental Policy Institute reported the possibly unsalability of the breeder reactor in an environment of glutted production capacity <a href="refrnc.html#35M">(35M)</a>.  In response to the escalating use of electricity, utilities had purchased and planned to build more power plants than were necessary as a result of stalled energy consumption during the 1970s.  Excess capacity existed throughout the 1980s.  Therefore, the breeder reactor was becoming even more economically prohibitive.  Although the Reagan administration attempted one last plan to placate critics and rescue the CRBR, the proposal ultimately failed, and the CRBR became no more than a political mishap of the 1970s and 1980s <a href="refrnc.html#59M">(59M)</a>.

<p>Based on the reversal of fortune in relation to American breeder reactor technology, which was initially strong but more recently has faltered, the present and future of breeder reactors in the United States appeared to be nonexistent.  Some changes in policy were made, however, and the present and future are not as bad as the CRBR controversy implies.  The experiences of Europe and Japan during the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s, however, were much more promising.</p>

<br>
