<head>	
<title> Glossary for the IFBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/note.gif">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=25%>
<h1 align="center">  Glossary  </h1>
<hr size=3 width=25%>

<br>
<br>

<dl>
<dl>
<dl>

<br>
<a name="actinide"></a>
<dt><b>Actinides</b>
<dd>This term applies to a row of elements normally placed below the bulk of the periodic table.  The row represents the elements of atomic numbers 89 through 103, and the first one is actinium, from which the name of the row was derived.  Successive elements in this row result from inspection by adding one proton to the nucleus and one electron in the 5f electron orbitals.  All of these elements are radioactive, and those from atomic numbers 93, neptunium, to 103, lawrencium, are syntehsized artificially.  <a href="#uranium">Uranium</a> and <a href="#plutonm">plutonium</a> are included in this series, and various other actinides are products of nuclear <a href="#fission">fission</a>.
<br>

<br>
<a name="alpha"></a>
<dt><b>Alpha</b>
<dd>A type of <a href="#radiatin">radiation</a> consisting of helium nuclei, which consist of two protons and two protons each for a total charge of positive two.  This type of particle is the largest, slowest, and least penetrating of the three types of radiation.
<br>

<br>
<a name="beta"></a>
<dt><b>Beta</b>
<dd>A type of <a href="#radiatin">radiation</a> essentially constituting a high energy electron, which has very little mass and a charge of negative one.  Among the types of radiation, this type of particle is intermediate in terms of both energy and penetrating ability.
<br>

<br>
<a name="breeder"></a>
<dt><b>Breeder Reactor</b>
<dd>Any of a variety of nuclear reactors which produces more fuel than it consumes.  The laws of conservation of mass and energy are still observed.  The two rules of nuclear physics dictating this phenomenon include types of <a href="#fission">fission</a> that produce more than one neutron per nucleus and conversion of material through <a href="#capture">neutron capture</a>.  
<br>

<br>
<a name="ratio"></a>
<dt><b>Breeding Ratio</b>
<dd>In order to differentiate among the efficiencies of various breeder reactors, this number relates the number of new fissionable atoms produced per atom of fissionable material consumed.  Clearly breeder reactors must have ratios greater than one to be effective.
<br>

<br>
<a name="btu"></a>
<dt><b>British Thermal Unit (BTU)</b>
<dd>This unit of the English system parallels the Joule of the SI system.  One British Thermal Unit is defined as the energy required to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit.  Energy produced and consumed throughout the world is often reported in the form of Quads, a multiple of BTU's.
<br>

<br>
<a name="convert"></a>
<dt><b>Converter</b>
<dd>This type of nuclear reactor is exactly opposite the breeder reactor in basic principle.  A converter consumes more fuel than it produces.
<br>

<br>
<a name="coolant"></a>
<dt><b>Coolant</b>
<dd>The heat produced by nuclear reactions must be removed from the core and reaction chamber in all nuclear reactors.  This medium, normally a liquid, removes the heat through conduction.  Through incorporation of a heat exchanger into the system, this coolant transfers heat to a boiler which produces steam to power the plant generators.  In most normal fission reactors, water acts as the coolant because of its very high specific heat capacity.  In the Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor, liquid sodium serves as the coolant.
<br>

<br>
<a name="critmass"></a>
<dt><b>Critical Mass</b>
<dd>This term is mostly qualitative but is based on an exact mathematical and physical analysis of a particular fuel mixture of known purity.  Essentially, this amount of fissile material must be present to produce a self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction after initiation by an external electron source.  If the mass is subcritical, not enough neutrons will be produced, and the chain reaction will soon cease.  If the mass is supercritical, move away really fast from that location.  A supercritical mass is created by a chemical explosion in nuclear warheads the instant before the atomic detonation.
<br>

<br>
<a name="deut"></a>
<dt><b>Deuterium</b>
<dd>As an <a href="#isotope">isotope</a> of hydrogen with two neutrons, this element exists in the substance deuterium oxide, commonly referred to as &quot;heavy water&quot;.  The chemical formula of deuterium oxide is D<sub>2</sub>O.  Most of the current excitement surrounding this isotope of hydrogen is its potential use as a primary fuel for <a href="#fusion">fusion</a> power after electrolysis of the deuterium oxide.
<br>

<br>
<a name="discount"></a>
<dt><b>Discount Rate</b>
<dd>Since economics is so important to energy technology, this term applies to the loss of benefits that otherwsie would have been realized if the money invested in a project had been used elssewhere.  Estimation of a project's future costs includes consideration of the discount rate to establish an idea of the profit or loss margin.
<br>

<br>
<a name="double"></a>
<dt><b>Doubling Time</b>
<dd>A breeder reactor produces more fuel than it consumes.  Doubling time is the amount of time required for the mass of fissionable material produced to equal the amount normally contained in the core and elsewhere in the fuel cycle (fabrication, cooling, processing, and transportation).  The reason for this measurement is to predict the time by which another breeder reactor may be built and supported from the beginning with that excess fissionable material.  Logically, the number of breeder reactors in operation could &quot;double&quot; after each such quantity of time.
<br>

<br>
<a name="energy"></a>
<dt><b>Energy</b>
<dd>Energy exists in many varieties, such as solar, thermal, chemical, and nuclear.  Ultimately, all forms of energy are variants on potential energy (PE) and kinetic energy (KE).  Energy has the same units as work, which is the product of a force applied to an object over a distance.  Energy is best defined as the ability to do work through the rearrangement of chemical or nuclear bonds.  Common units of energy include the Joule, defined as the energy required to raise the temperature of one gram of water by one degree Celsius, which has the units of kilogram-meter(sup)2(/sup)/second(sup)2(/sup).  Other terms include the <a href="#btu">British Thermal Unit</a>, the <a href="#quad">quad</a>, the electron-volt, and the kilowatt-hour.
<br>

<br>
<a name="enrich"></a>
<dt><b>Enrichment</b>
<dd>Although this term could describe the changes within one who reads this web page, when applied to nuclear technology, enrichment is the process of increasing the percentage of uranium-235 within a uranium source from its average of only 0.7% of natural uranium.  Gaseous diffusion, which laboriously separates the uranium-235 and uranium-238 on the basis of slight differences in mass and therefore velocities of diffusion, has been the principal and oldest method.  The gas centrifuge and laser methods have been developed more recently.  Since the chemical nature of elements depends only on the electrons, and these two isotopes vary only in neutron number, physical rather than chemical separation methods must be employed. 
<br>

<br>
<a name="fast"></a>
<dt><b>Fast Breeder</b>
<dd>In contrast to a <a href="#thermal">thermal breeder</a>, a fast breeder operates by using high energy neutrons to effect nuclear reactions.  The <a href="#neutron">neutrons</a> have higher velocities in this case.
<br>

<br>
<a name="fertile"></a>
<dt><b>Fertile</b>
<dd>Fertile describes the nature of elemental isotopes that do not themselves easily react by fission, but that can be converted into fissionable atoms of a different variety in a breeder reactor.  Examples of such fertile matter include uranium-238, plutonium-240, and thorium-232.
<br>

<br>
<a name="fissile"></a>
<dt><b>Fissile <i>(same as Fissionable)</i></b>
<dd>Fissile or fissionable describes the nature of nuclear fuel, meaning those atoms which are capable of fission with large cross-sections of conversion.  This term applies to elements that undergo fission in fairly significant proportions only.  For example, uranium-238 does experience fission with high energy electrons, but only uranium-235 is describe as fissile between the two, because only uranium-235 decays by fission at rapid rates and to a sufficiently high degree to be economical as a nuclear fuel.
<br>

<br>
<a name="fission"></a>
<dt><b>Fission</b>
<dd>The term applied to the process by which atomic nuclei split into two or more nuclei of lower atomic weight.  From Einstein's relationship between mass and energy, the aggregate mass of the products must be slightly lower than the original mass of the nucleus, since some of the mass is converted to energy.  After initiation by capture of a neutron, various reactions describing the decay process can emit from one to three neutrons per original atom of fuel.
<br>

<br>
<a name="fissable"></a>
<dt><b>Fissionable <i>(same as Fissile)</i></b>
<dd>Fissile or fissionable describes the nature of nuclear fuel, meaning those atoms which are capable of fission with large cross-sections of conversion.  This term applies to elements that undergo fission in fairly significant proportions only.  For example, uranium-238 does experience fission with high energy electrons, but only uranium-235 is describe as fissionable between the two, because only uranium-235 decays by fission at rapid rates and to a sufficiently high degree to be economical as a nuclear fuel.
<br>

<br>
<a name="reproc"></a>
<dt><b>Fuel Reprocessing</b>
<dd>To obtain the most energy from an original amount of fuel, fuel reprocessing recycles the unconsumed fuel from the used fuel of a nuclear reactor by first recovering and then decontaminating the fissionable matter.  First, the spent fuel must be cooled for three to six months to remove decay heat, then cladding around the fuel is removed and the fuel and support structure is chemically dissolved.  Chemical separation isolates the desired atoms.  The remaining highly radioactive wastes are very concentrated and must be disposed of carefully.
<br>

<br>
<a name="fusion"></a>
<dt><b>Fusion</b>
<dd>Whereas <a href="#fission">fission</a> is the splitting of nuclei, fusion is the combination of two nuclei to yield one larger nucleus with less mass than the two initial nuclei.  Again, the loss of mass is reflected by the production of energy.  Fusion reactions are alternatively called thermo-nuclear reactions because of the tremendous temperatures and pressures which must be achieved to overcome the naturally repulsive electrical and nuclear forces on the atomic and subatomic level.
<br>

<br>
<a name="gamma"></a>
<dt><b>Gamma </b>
<dd>A type of <a href="#radiatin">radiation</a> signified by gamma rays, a high-energy species of the electromagnetic spectrum.  Although the wave-particle duality of nature describes gamma radiation as a photon as well as an energy wave, the properties of matter are not usually considered.  This type of radiation is the most energetic, most penetrating, and most dangerous, but it is also the least abundant form detected on the Earth's surface.
<br>

<br>
<a name="generate"></a>
<dt><b>Generator</b>
<dd>A generator is used to produce electricity through combination with a <a href="#turbine">turbine</a>.  A crude generator consists of multiple coils of wires wrapped around a rod and spinning within a magnetic field produced by surrounding magnets.  A conductor moving within a magnetic field causes electron, and therefore current, flow through the device.  Thus, a rapidly spinning generator attached to a turbine produces electricity which can be used to power television sets or food processors.
<br>

<br>
<a name="hang"></a>
<dt><b>Hang Time</b>
<dd>In contrast to <a href="#double">doubling time</a>, hang time is the time over which a basketball player stays aloft after overcoming the force of gravity when pursuing a slam dunk but before his or her feet return to the Earth.
<br>

<br>
<a name="isotope"></a>
<dt><b>Isotope</b>
<dd>Any of two or more different configurations of the same element through the variation of the number of neutrons present in the nucleus.  The number of neutrons in stable elements normally rises considerably relative to a steady increase in atomic number.  The hygrogen isotope with no neutrons exists as the principal species, while <a href="#deut">deuterium</a> is a hydrogen atom with one neutron and tritium is a hydrogen atom with two neutrons.  Carbon exists in the isotopes of mass number 12, 13, and 14, among others, indicating the presence of 6, 7, and 8 neutrons, respectively.  Carbon-14 is radioactive and commonly arises in applications to the geological and archeological dating of organic materials.  Many elements display isotopes, but although the physical properties differ with the number of neutrons, the chemical bonding properties are dependent only on the valence electron structure.  The characteristic behaviors associated with different <a href="#uranium">uranium</a> and <a href="#plutonm">plutonium</a> isotopes are imperative to the radioactive nature and power production capabilities of each one.
<br>

<br>
<a name="rangers"></a>
<dt><b>Mighty Morphin Power Rangers</b>
<dd>Originally manufactured in Japan, this children's television show has nothing to do with <a href="#power">power</a> in terms of energy per unit time--especially this show.  The characters show almost no acting ability over an entire half hour.  Power = 0 Watts.  
<br>

<br>
<a name="moderate"></a>
<dt><b>Moderator</b>
<dd>No, in this context it does not apply to Jim Lehrer at a Presidential debate.  Rather, a moderator is the substance used to slow neutrons to a speed at which <a href="#fission">fission</a> occurs at a higher probabilty.  That is, <a href="#fissile">fissile</a> fuels undergo fission more readily when the neutrons have relatively lower velocities and energies.  Some of the kinetic energy of the nuetrons is lost through collisions with nuclei of the moderator.  As a result of the translation of kinetic energy to thermal energy, the moderator must be cooled.  Graphite, water, and heavy water are common moderators.  The problem at Chernobyl resulted because the plant used a graphite moderator but a water <a href="#coolant">coolant</a>.  When the water level dropped, the presence of the moderator still caused fission at a high rate.  In American nuclear reactors, the water is both moderator and coolant.  If the water is removed, the reactions essentially cease.
<br>

<br>
<a name="mrfusion"></a>
<dt><b>Mr. Fusion</b>
<dd>A hypothetical realization of <a href="#fusion">fusion</a> in only the year 2015 in <i>Back to the Future Part II</i>.  Doc Brown uses garbage from the McFly residence to power the reactor on his car named Mr. Fusion, a pun relating to the Mr. Coffee appliances.  This is a classic movie.  Fusion on such a scale will not happen by 2015 though.
<br>


<br>
<a name="neutron"></a>
<dt><b>Neutron</b>
<dd>The neutrally charged constituent of atoms, this particle was not discovered and defined until the first half of the twentieth century.  Although neutrons have no bearing on the chemical reactivity of various elements, they do result in <a href="#isotope">isotopes</a> of various elements.  The mass of a neutrons is nearly equivalent to that of a proton, the positively charge member of nuclei.  The emmission of neutrons during <a href="#fission">fission</a> is responsible for the chain reactions in <a href="#reactor">reactors</a> and bombs. 
<br>

<br>
<a name="capture"></a>
<dt><b>Neutron Capture</b>
<dd>In breeder reactors, <a href="#fertile">fertile</a> material such as uranium-238 experiences neutron capture when a neutron is absorbed by the nucleus.  From ensuing decay reactions, the uranium-239 ultimately produces the desired fissile material plutonium-239.
<br>

<br>
<a name="nucleus"></a>
<dt><b>Nucleus</b>
<dd>The central part of an atom, which is composed of mostly empty space.  The electrons move around the nucleus in orbitals of various shapes corresponding to their various energies.  The nucleus is composed of <a href="#neutron">neutrons</a> and protons in different numbers.  Most of the mass of atoms is present in the nucleus, since one electron has on the order of only one-thousandth of the mass of a proton or neutron.
<br>

<br>
<a name="plutonm"></a>
<dt><b>Plutonium</b>
<dd>An element listed on the period table as an <a href="#actinide">actinide</a>.  The atomic number of 94 indicates the presence of 94 protons and 94 electrons.  The chemical symbol for plutonium is Pu.  The mass number depends on the particular <a href="#isotope">isotope</a>.  Plutonium-239 is a particularly valuable <a href="#fissile">fissile</a> fuel for reactors and is the product in breeder reactors.
<br>

<br>
<a name="power"></a>
<dt><b>Power</b>
<dd>Power is energy or work per unit time.  This term is important in consideration of nuclear reactors in relation to how fast a given power plant produces a given amount of electricity.  Common units include the Watt, symbolized by W, which is one Joule per second, and its multplicative derivatives.  For example, a kiloWatt (kW) is 1000 Watts, while a MegaWatt (MW) is 1,000,000 Watts.
<br>


<br>
<a name="quad"></a>
<dt><b>Quad</b>
<dd>A quad is a unit of energy short for quadrillion, which is 10 to the power of fifteen, or the number 1 followed by fifteen zeros.  One quad is equivalent to 10(sup)15(/sup) <a href="#btu">British Thermal Units</a> (BTU).  The quad is a very large unit of energy used to describe use by individual countries and the world as a whole.  For example, in 1994, the United States consumed 88.5 quads of energy as a whole nation.
<br>

<br>
<a name="radiatin"></a>
<dt><b>Radiation</b>
<dd>Microscopic particles or types of radiation which are emitted upon upon radioactive decay of certain nuclei or nuclear reactions.  The three varieties are <a href="#alpha">alpha</a>, <a href="#beta">beta</a>, and <a href="#gamma">gamma</a>.  Radiation refers only to these three resulting types; the term <a href="#radioac">radioactivity</a> means something very different.  Differentiation between these two terms is important.
<br>

<br>
<a name="radioac"></a>
<dt><b>Radioactivity</b>
<dd>Radioactivity, in contrast to <a href="#radiatin">radiation</a>, describes the nature of a particular piece of material.  Matter is radioactive if it emits radiation.  A person can be exposed to radiation or radioactive material, but radiation is consumed and gone the moment it hits something or is absorbed, while radioactive material will not just disappear.  People are constantly exposed to radiation of all types, but exposure to radioactive material is much more serious, particularly if the material is ingested or inhaled.  Nevertheless, a person cannot store up radiation within the body, whereas radioactive material can be incorporated into biological structures.
<br>

<br>
<a name="reactor"></a>
<dt><b>Reactor</b>
<dd>In short, a reactor is an assembly of nuclear fuel compiled in such a way that it can sustain a <a href="#fission">fission</a> chain reaction.
<br>

<br>
<a name="thermal"></a>
<dt><b>Thermal Breeder</b>
<dd>In contrast to a <a href="#fast">fast breeder</a>, a thermal breeder operates by using lower energy neutrons to effect nuclear reactions.  The <a href="#neutron">neutrons</a> have lower velocities in this case.
<br>

<br>
<a name="turbine"></a>
<dt><b>Turbine</b>
<dd>In terms of technical definitions, a turbine is a rotary engine turned by the impulse from a current of fluid under pressure.  In most nuclear, coal, or gas power plants, the fluid is steam produced from the boiling of water and maintained at high pressures.  A windmill or waterwheel are some of the oldest types of turbines.  Today, turbines are used principally for the generation of electricity by connectin of the rotating spindle containing curved vains to a <a href="#generate">generator</a>.
<br>

<br>
<a name="uranium"></a>
<dt><b>Uranium</b>
<dd>An element listed on the periodic table as an <a href="#actinide">actinide</a>.  The atomic number of 94 indicates the presence of 94 protons and 94 electrons.  The chemical symbol for uranium is U.  The mass number depends on the particular <a href="#isotope">isotope</a>.  While uranium-235 is readily <a href="#fissile">fissile</a>, uranium-238 is <a href="#fertile">fertile</a> and can be transformed into useful plutonium-239 fuel within breeder reactors.

</dl>
</dl>
</dl>

<br>
<br>

<dl>
<dl>

<dd><a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a><br><br>

<dd><a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

</dl>
</dl>

<br>
<br>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
