<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Great Britain </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h2 align="center">  Great Britain  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Although the United States clearly held the early lead in <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeder</a> technology, European countries soon surpassed the United States in physical manifestations of plants if not technological knowledge about their construction.  Great Britain, France, and West Germany were examples of such countries, and France is probably regarded as the leader today.  By 1976, the Soviet reactor BN-350 had been operating since November 1972, the French Phenix reactor began in August 1973, and the British Prototype Fast Reactor (PFR) was functioning by March 1974 <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  One problem which those countries were encountering was the nature of the novel <a href="glossary.html#coolant">coolant</a>, liquid sodium, which caused problems because of its corrosive reactivity with reactor elements.    All the countries recognized that changes had to be made before the operations could be used commercially to produce electricity.</p>

<p>The British reactor PFR was built on the shore of the North Sea at Dounreay, Scotland, and could produce a total of 250 MW.  In contrast to the sodium &quot;loop&quot; design typical of American fast breeder reactors, by which liquid sodium was pumped through the uranium-238 blanket and core, British reactors adopted the &quot;pot&quot; concept during the 1960s.  In this case, the reactor core, primary sodium pumps, and intermediate heat exchangers are all immersed in a tank of liquid sodium <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  In the loop design, the pumps and heat exchangers remain outside the reaction vessel, a situation which the British and French scientists believed was not as safe as the alternative.  A schematic diagram of an example of British design appears below:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/british.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="British Breeder Reactor">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 7.  A schematic diagram of the &quot;pot&quot; design of the<br>British breeder appears with the heat exchangers, turbine,<br>and generator. Note that the reactor is almost entirely below the<br>sodium level.  Diagram by UKAEA. <a href="refrnc.html#23M"> (23M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The problems with the PFR up until 1976 had principally been invested in the steam generators, which translate heat from the hot liquid sodium to water in order to produce steam for the turbogenerator system.  The PFR had to be shut down several times for repairs to this system.  The system for the steam generators is simple in concept but complex in design, since the hall required for the intricate network of pipes requires nearly as much room as the reactor hall <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  The PFR should have been completed before the French Phenix reactor, however, but some components were not delivered on time because of industrial problems <a href="refrnc.html#23M">(23M)</a>.  In another fluke accident, which is actually somewhat humorous, 500 tons of seaweed were sucked into the condenser of one of the electricity generating systems, requiring further delays as the organic contaminants were removed.

<p>The British system included three large complex steam generators, but they were designed with minimalist philosophy so that the costs could be maintained.  Economies of scale were also realized, and scientists noted that the generators could easily be produced on a commercial scale.  Each steam generator exhibited a thermal capacity of 200 MW.  Of the three different units, one functioned as an evaporator, the second a steam superheater, and the third a reheater.  Unfortunately, the British had become experts on handling leaks, since the steam generator system developed so many.  One problem noted with the leaks was propagation.  Not only did the small leaks enlarge because of water vapor and sodium approaching from opposite sides, but they also propagate in terms of number.  The cause for this propagation, which seriously weakened entire sheets of metal through the creation of entire networks of fissures, was established to be sodium migration to the tips of the cracks.  The corrosive nature of the pure sodium then induced stress fractures <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  Gymnasts are prone to another type of stress fracture not associated with sodium.  You can find more information about that sport <a href="http://www.usa-gymnastics.org/usag/">here</a>.

<p>While generally pleased with the performance of the PFR, the British also planned a 1200 MW Commercial Fast Reactor (CFR) which would include sweeping changes in the steam generator design.  One difference between nations of importance in this field was that the British do less full-scale testing than their French counterparts.  Rather than spend money unnecessarily as they perceive it, the British limited testing to only the most essential and complicated components.  The results were mixed; although the reactor worked very well, the steam generators did not.  Trade-offs between costs and expected risks must always be considered carefully before undertaking such capital intensive operations.  Another factor which the British have been considering carefully is the amount of &quot;burnup,&quot; or the amount of time which passes and power produced before the fuel must be removed from the breeder reactor for <a href="glossary.html#reproc">reprocessing</a>.  This figure is very important for considerations of commercial investment, since a reactor cannot operate during the time that the fuel is removed and new fuel is added.  In general, the British program has not been as advanced as the breeder program in France.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="france.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;France.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="us.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;United States.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
<p><i>
<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a></i></p>

