<head>	
<title> Experimental Breeder Reactor I (EBR-I) </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=65%>
<h2 align="center">  Experimental Breeder Reactor I (EBR-I)  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=65%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Several years after the Atomic Energy Commissions launch of &quot;Operation Bootstrap,&quot; Experimental Breeder Reactor I had been built in Arco, Idaho.  The reactor began operation on December 20, 1951, not much more than six years after the end of World War II <a href="refrnc.html#5I">(5I)</a>.  In September 1952, Newsweek reported information obtained from Walter H. Zinn, director of Argonne National Laboratory.  The fast <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeder</a> consisted of a fissionable core of uranium-235 approximately the size of a football, but this core was surrounded on all sides by a thick layer of nonfissile uranium-238, reflective shielding to prevent excessive neutron loss, lead, and finally concrete <a href="refrnc.html#10M">(10M)</a>.  In order to obtain heat from the nuclear reactions, a closed circuit of a liquid sodium-potassium alloy was filtered first through the uranium-238 blanket and then pumped up through the internal core.  By use of a heat exchanger, the heat from the metal was transferred to a steam boiler, which produced steam from water to run electric generators by spinning turbines.  The liquid metal exited the reactor at a temperature of 660 degrees Fahrenheit, and the amount of steam produced could generate 250 kW (0.25 MW) of power <a href="refrnc.html#3M">(3M)</a>.

<p>Although simple in theory, some technological and engineering solutions still had to be discovered.  Many problems were cited, among which the principal one in terms of ultimate commercialization was the prohibitive cost of the project.  The efficiency of the operation had to be improved.

<p>Nevertheless, the most important step in any complicated process is the first one.  Experimental Breeder Reactor I was the first step towards the perfection of the fast breeder reactor.  This reactor did provide the town of Arco, Idaho with electricity, and therefore the town proudly claims the right as the &quot;First City in the World to be Lit by Atomic Power,&quot; on the sign denoting entrance to the city <a href="refrnc.html#6I">(6I)</a>.  To find out more about EBR-I, look at <a href="http://www.oz.net/~chrisp/ebr.htm">this site</a>, which has pictures and information about it.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="us.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;United States.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="econ1.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;Past Economics of the FBR.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
<p><i>
<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a></i></p>

<p><i>
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201 - Advanced Energy Systems</a></i></p>
</center>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<font size=5>
<img src="icons/mailbox.gif">  <i> Send comments or questions to Daniel P. Bailey at <a href="mailto:dpbailey@students.uiuc.edu">dpbailey@students.uiuc.edu</a>.</i>
</font size>
</center>

