</DOCHDR>
<html>

<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> France </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=20%>
<h2 align="center">  France  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=20%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Today, the French provide a very high percentage of their electricity through nuclear power, although only a small amount derives from <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeder</a> reactors.  Nevertheless, beginning with the Phenix in 1973 and continuing with the remarkable Superphenix during the following decade, the French program has been an enviable accomplishment.  In 1976, when the breeder reactor comprised the largest share of the United States energy research budget, France was already a decade ahead <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(23M)</a>.  In foreign countries, in contrast to the United States, a greater attitude of public acquiescence regarding environmental decisions usually exists.  The French public is generally impartial to the breeder concept, while in the United States, where active voices of the public have continuously caused decisions to be drawn out in party politics, moving ahead with risky decisions is much more difficult.  Nevertheless, the Phenix is a safe device and a technological achievement, not a cavalier operation built in a day.

<p>The Phenix is housed in one large building that may be completely sealed in case of an accident, and the radiation exposure within the cavernous room surrounding the reactor is less than for a typical light water <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a> reactor.  A mix of computer and human controls insure the best possible reactions to unusual conditions.  The <a href="glossary.html#double">doubling time</a> of the Phenix was still too inefficient to allow widespread construction of similar models.  The Phenix could not match the safety standards and regulations imposed by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in the United States, meaning that at the time, such a model could not be constructed in the United States <a href="refrnc.html#23M">(23M)</a>.  After beginning electrical generation in 1973, the Phenix produced over 2 billion kilo-watt-hours of electrical <a href="glossary.html#energy">energy</a> when running at full power for slightly over one year.  In contrast to the plague of problems with the British PFR, the Phenix ran smoothly for several years, although through 1976 the Phenix had only operated for one thirtieth of its expected lifetime, and future malfunctions were expected <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.

<p>The French Atomic Energy Commission conducted many full-scale tests, and the French have more extensive testing facilities than the British.  Before the Phenix first began producing electricity, components from the fuel-handling apparatus and control rods to the intermediate heat exchangers and even a large ramp used to eventually remove spent fuel were all pretested in liquid sodium.  Like the PFR, the French Phenix was of the &quot;pot&quot; design, and the total expected capacity was 250 MW of power.  The fuel for the Phenix was designed to produce power for one year before <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a>.  Every two months, one-sixth of te fuel assembly would be removed.  The system designed for the Phenix to remove and replace fuel assemblies was ingeneous.  As a result of the spaciousness of the pot design, a fixed ramp was installed in the liquid sodium chamber.  When a spent fuel assmebly needed to be removed from the reactor, it was pulled up the ramp, through an airlock, into a tank of sodium in an adjacent room <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  Of course, this entire operation occurs below within the thick shielding surrounding the reactor vessel and associated components.  The American loop design could not incorporate such a device; the benefits to the Phenix include improved safety and less time for the fuel removal.  A diagram of the Phenix reactor illustrates the pot design and ramp with labels:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/phenix.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="French Phenix Breeder Reactor">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 8.  The French 250 MW fast breeder reactor Phenix.  Liquid sodium<br>fills the void of the vessel exposed here for purposes of<br>labeling.  Note the fuel ramp and transfer arm for simplified<br>fuel assembly removal. <a href="refrnc.html#38M"> (38M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>
   
<p>The Phenix reactor was far from perfect.  Among the concerns was the poor breeding quality of the reactor, a characteristic indicated by the <a href="glossary.html#ratio">breeding ratio</a>.  The entire purpose of the fast breeder reactor concept is the production of more fuel, but the Phenix did not achieve this quality.  Additional considerations in the total fuel cycle of the Phenix reactor included fuel fabrication and fuel reprocessing.  The cost of the facility to form fuel pins from basic uranium oxide fuel at Cadarache in southeast France, including provisions for both building and equipment, was $12 million <a href="refrnc.html#39M">(39M)</a>.  This plant produced two cores for the Phenix through 1976.  Reprocessing was not yet fully accomplished, however, for neither France nor Great Britain had approached this subject from more than a test level.  Not until early 1976 was a large reprocessing plant designed to handle light water reactor fuel operating in France <a href="refrnc.html#39M">(39M)</a>.

<p>In terms of safety, the basic French philosophy has been construction of the reactor in such a way that large increases in radioactivity of the core as a whole become very improbable.  Since the cooling circuits of fast breeder reactors are not pressurized, the French and British designs avoided consideration of the case of overpressurization <a href="refrnc.html#39M">(39M)</a>.  The United States had planned solutions for such problems.  The Phenix finally showed significant wear in 1977, as <i>Science</i> reported that the Phenix was shut down for removal of two heat exchangers for repairs <a href="refrnc.html#37M">(37M)</a>.  Plumbing leaks similar to those experienced in Great Britian ultimately caused the necessary disabling of the system.  One small leak of sodium was detected in July 1976, and another in October of the same year.  Despite these temporary setbacks which resulted in power production at only one-third capacity, the problems did illustrate the success of the safety and fault detection systems <a href="refrnc.html#37M">(37M)</a>.  The excellent computer systems used for the Phenix reactor and the simplified nature of the control room, picture below, made certain that safety would be maintained:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/room.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="French Phenix Breeder Reactor Control Room">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 9.  The control room of the 250 MW French fast<br>breeder reactor Phenix. <a href="refrnc.html#23M"> (23M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Often in real world applications, the question of whether or not something operates correctly will not be answered until something else goes wrong.  Still, as C. Zaleski noted in <i>Science</i> in 1980, the overall French breeder reactor program was successful <a href="refrnc.html#55M">(55M)</a>.  The persuasive argument highlighted the experience derived from the breeder program in France, the rationale for the program, and the problems to be resolved in the future.  The practicality and desirability of breeder reactors was noted.  Most importantly, the author displayed great hope in the Superphenix which was to be completed by 1983.  This revolutionary and powerful breeder reactor is discussed further in &quot;Current Technology.&quot;</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

