<head>	
<title> Past Economics of the FBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/coins.gif">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=55%>
<h2 align="center">  Past Economics of the FBR  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=55%>

<br>
<br>
<br>

<p>When breeder reactors were first proposed in the 1940's and 1950's, the expected costs of this type of <a href="glossary.html#reactor">reactor</a> were expected to be cheaper than coal plants in the future.  In 1949, it was predicted that it would take only about ten years to determine if breeder reactors could be installed commercially and economically <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(51M)</a>.  A total length of time of twenty to thirty years was given as the span before atomic <a href="glossary.html#power">power</a> replaced other sources of electricity exclusively.  Walter H. Zinn, director of Argonne National Laboratory, cautioned anxious scientists and the media by proclaiming that despite the progress, uranium had not become a &quot;virtually costless fuel&quot; overnight <a href="refrnc.html#2M">(2M)</a>.  As a broad estimate, however, Zinn had earlier reported that the new Experimental Breeder Reactor I should produce 269 times the electricity of a conventional power system at the same cost <a href="refrnc.html#10M">(10M)</a>.  Clearly, if such a case could be realized with breeder reactors, they would have been implemented in the national power system already.  He did note that moving from a model version of a breeder reactor to a fully functional plant on a commercial size was not yet feasible, and would probably realize economies of scale as well as new problems not considered on a small level <a href="refrnc.html#10M">(10M)</a>.

In June of 1953, <i>Fortune</i> magazine outlined the expected costs and benefits of three types of nuclear reactors based on the best knowledge available <a href="refrnc.html#33M">(33M)</a>.  The first one, described as a &quot;burner-upper,&quot; was so named because the reactor consumes some of the <a href="glossary.html#uranium">uranium</a> fuel and the rest is removed as waste or reprocessed.  No new fuel is created in this case.  The second one, called a &quot;stretcher-outer,&quot; was intermediate between a conventional <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a> reactor and a breeder reactor.  Finally, the last one was the breeder reactor.  Appearing below is a diagram showing the relative costs, processes, and coal equivalent for the &quot;burner-upper,&quot; the reactor analogous to the prominent light water fission reactors of today:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/burn.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Non-Regenerative Reactor">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 5.  General process and fuel cycle of the non-regenerative<br>reactor as well as electric power and fuel cost comparisons with coal. <a href="refrnc.html#33M"> (33M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The breeder reactor, appearing below, requires more steps in the processing of fuel and the operation of the plant, but note the very inexpensive cost and the tremendous coal equivalent from an original amount of uranium.  The same amount of uranium labeled 20 is used in both the non-regenerative and the breeder reactors:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/breed.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Breeder Reactor">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 6.  General process and fuel cycle of the breeder<br>reactor as well as electric power and fuel cost comparisons with coal. <a href="refrnc.html#33M"> (33M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In 1953, the Atomic Energy Commission purchased ore containing uranium at $3.50 per pound, and refining costs of this ore wer classified.  Based on assumptions, however, <i>Fortune</i> placed the 0.14 pounds of uranium-235 in bar of original uranium metal as being worth $1,270, a very valuable commodity indeed <a href="refrnc.html#33M">(33M)</a>.  One mill is equal to one-tenth of one cent.  The following price figures represent 1953 dollars.  For the non-regenerative reactor, the unused uranium-235 and uranium-238 are descarded, and the total cost of fuel is 7 mills per kilo-watt-hour (kWh), while the coal equivalent is half of that figure at 3.5 mills per kWh.  The total coal equivalent was estimated as 91 tons.  For the breeder, the cost of fuel was an incredibly low 0.013 mills per kWh, but bear in mind the important disclaimer that <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a> costs are not included in this figure <a href="refrnc.html#33M">(33M)</a>.  As this same article concedes, reprocessing was relatively untested and expected to be expensice.  The total electric power and coal equivalent for the breeder far outweight those of the non-regenerative reactor, clearly indicating the preference towards breeder reactors.

<p>Another critical observation regarding these two diagrams is that the cost is only in terms of cost for fuel.  The investment and appropriations necessary for actual plant construction are not considered.  Therefore, these figures are misleading; they only indicate the potential for using nuclear power as a source for electricity in the future, assuming the costs for plants could be lowered to those of coal plants.  Today, nuclear plants cost more than coal plants, but the fuel is considerably cheaper in the nuclear case.  The minimal cost of fuel for the breeder reactor as indicated by <i>Fortune</i> is akin to the present hype regarding nuclear fusion, which may someday use nearly free water as an energy source.

<p>Overall, the economic outlook for breeders through the 1950's was overly optimistic.

<p>As the United States and European countries continued research into the 1960's and 1970's, it became evident that the cost comparison analysis between breeder reactors and conventional sources had been incorrect.  The costs had escalated considerably as new problems in breeder technology were discovered.  Meanwhile, light water breeder reactors actually became cheaper than coal plants.  Both the United States and Europe invested heavily in such conventional breeder reactors until the onset of the 1980's, public concern over nuclear power and extremely comprehensive safety regulations and guidelines imposed by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission halted growth.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

