<head>	
<title> Japan </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=20%>
<h2 align="center">  Japan  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=20%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>In terms of breeder reactor technology, Japan lagged behind France, Great Britain, and even the United States through the 1960s and early 1970s.  More recently, however, Japan has invested capital in the Monju reactor, discussed under &quot;Current Technology.&quot;  The first significant breeder reactor in Japan, completed in 1976, was named Joyo and located 72 miles northeast of Tokyo <a href="refrnc.html#9M">(9M)</a>.  The cost of $85 million was divided over the fourteen year construction of the reactor.  Compared with the British PFR or French Phenix, the Toyo was only a model reactor, producing 50 MW of heat.  In terms of future plans, Japan hoped to build a 250 MW fast breeder reactor for electricity generation and to install 129 million kW of capacity in breeders and related reactors by the year 2000.  Since all these plans were proposed in 1977, the objectives were fairly optimistic, and like those plans of the United States from that era, they proved to be unrealistic.  Today, however, Japan has surpassed the United States in its breeder program and technology.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="present.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to the &quot;Current Technology&quot; main page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="france.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;France.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

