<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Background </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/screen.jpg">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h1 align="center">  Background  </h1>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<br>

<p>The following sections provide a comprehensive &quot;Background&quot; about breeder reactor technology and the societal attitudes from which nuclear power first originated.  After atomic power was exercised for destructive means near the end of World War II, the American government and science programs began to pursue nuclear power.  Presidents and scientists alike lauded the potential of nuclear energy as a replacement for fossil fuels.  The context from which these novel ideas about the atom and atomic power developed makes the accomplishments and dreams all the more remarkable.  The neutron, an essential constituent of nuclear reactions and a member of all atomic nuclei apart from simple hydrogen, had only been discovered and classified a couple decades before the onset of World War II.  Indeed, nuclear science was an intense area of ground-breaking during the middle of the twentieth century.  The ideas that germinated during this period, and the reactions and generation of fuel intrinsic to breeder reactors, are discussed in brief.  These basic tenets of the breeder philosophy are still accepted today and provide the fundamental chemical basis for new investigation.</p>

<p>
<img src="icons/gls_ball.gif"><a href="move.html">The Move to Atomic Power</a><br><br>

<img src="icons/gls_ball.gif"><a href="atom.html">First Ideas About the Power of the Atom and Use in Breeder Reactors</a><br><br>

<img src="icons/gls_ball.gif"><a href="reaction.html">Nuclear Reactions of the FBR</a><br><br>

<img src="icons/gls_ball.gif"><a href="fuel.html">Generation of Fuel in a FBR</a><br>

<br>
<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="move.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;The Move to Atomic Power.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="intro.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;Introduction.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
<p><i>
<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a></i></p>

<p><i>
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201 - Advanced Energy Systems</a></i></p>
</center>

