<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor (LMFBR) </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=70%>
<h2 align="center">  Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor (LMFBR)  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=70%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Among the general types of breeder reactors, the Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor (LMFBR) has always been one of the most widely applied and tested models, at least until recent developments.  Indeed, even Experimental Breeder Reactor I was a variation on this general type, in that a liquid sodium-potassium alloy was used to cool the reactor core through heat transfer.  The LMFBR is not a specific <a href="glossary.html#reactor">reactor</a> in a specific location.  Rather, LMFBR simply refers to the fact that liquid metal is used as <a href="glossary.html#coolant">coolant</a>, and the type of metal most widely used for this application is sodium.  Pure sodium melts at a reasonably low temperature compared to most metals, and the availability of sodium means that costs remain relatively cheap.  Beginning in December of 1974, the United States Energy Research and Development Administration maintained the LMFBR as one of its most important goals <a href="refrnc.html#1B">(1B)</a>.  The conclusions of the report indicated that the light water reactor (LWR) in common existence today had been preferentially chosen and commercialized first for several reasons.  The LWR was selected and developed for naval nuclear propulsion, and the LWR represented a less significant departure from standard coal and gas steam plants for the generation of electricity.  Meanwhile, the LMFBR was viewed as a more expensive, albeit more efficient, future consideration.

<p>By the mid 1960's, the Atomic Energy Commission declared that the LMFBR was to become its main priority for various reasons <a href="refrnc.html#1B">(1B)</a>:

<ul>
<li>Predicted performances
<li>Existing industrial support
<li>Technological experience
<li>Proven basic feasibility
<li>Fear of draining uranium reserves
</ul>

<p>The principal argument advocated by proponents of the LMFBR was the last of the five reasons.  The future availability of economically recoverable uranium resources was doubtful.  Additionally, other nations had invested in LMFBR research, since both the British PFR and the French Phenix were of this variety.  But what about the present situation and technology in regards to the LMFBR?  There have been many changes and improvements in technology in regards to the LMFBR since EBR-I.  Several of these points must be discussed.

<p>The fuel used in the LMFBR is uranium-235.  This substance is contained inside thousands of thin metal pins, each of which is several meters in length.  A collection of pins forms a subassembly, and a collection of such subassemblies forms a fuel assembly <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  Cladding surrounds each of the fuel pins.  The subassembly cans are normally hexagonal in shape so that they may be packed efficiently in support structures on the base of the reactor floor.  Examining the picture of the Phenix reactor included in the &quot;History&quot; section, for example, shows the hexagonal floor and subassemblies.  Two current examples of reactor cores illustrating their hexagonal nature and variations on packing of the fuel pins appear below as cross-sectional diagrams:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/core.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Core of the LMFBR">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 10.  Two possibilities for the cross-sectional apperearance of<br>the reactor core in an LMFBR. <a href="refrnc.html#9B"> (9B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>From the side, the fuel assemblies have a much more complicated appearance.  Control rods within the assemblies normally prevent a fission chain reaction, because too many neutrons are absorbed by these safety features.  When a reactor must begin producing power, some of the fuel rods are removed, and an intense neutron flux initiated by the chain reaction permeates the reactor core.  The blanket of uranium-238 surrounding the core is also bombarded by neutrons, and various other subassemblies within this blanket also contain fuel in addition to uranium located at the tops and bottoms of fuel pins <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  Cans filled with steel surround the blanket and reflect neutrons back into the core, obtaining the maximum number of fission reactions or <a href="glossary.html#capture">neutron captures</a> per fissionable atom, while preventing the neutrons from escaping through the reactor vessel.  The entire reactor vessel is usually contained within multiple thick lead and concrete shields.  When viewed from the side, fuel assemblies have a complicated appearance as illustrated in the following diagram from the book <i>Fast Breeder Reactors</i>:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/assembly.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Fuel Assembly of the LMFBR">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 11.  A side view of the fuel assembly of an LMFBR <a href="refrnc.html#9B"> (9B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In the breeder reactor, the ultimate goal is production of an abundance of neutrons so that the uranium-238 in the core may absorb neutrons by <a href="glossary.html#capture">neutron capture</a> and form plutonium-239.  Although LWR produce some plutonium, they do so inefficiently, because the water <a href="glossary.html#moderate">moderator</a> slows the neutrons considerably.  Whereas fast fission produces 2.9 neutrons per fissile atom that undergoes fission, slow fission involves only 2.4 neutrons per fissioning atom <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  The LMFBR must contain a larger percentage of fissile material than a LWR, because the cross sections of fissionable fuel dictate that fission is less likely with increasing neutron velocities <a href="refrnc.html#5B">(5B)</a>.

<p>In general, the LMFBR must have highly packed fuel and high power density, because the generation of plutonium-238 and other impurities otherwise slows reactions considerably.  Regardless, the core material of the LMFBR must be removed periodically to extract the valuable plutonium-239 produced and remove the still fissile uranium-235 through reprocessing.  When fully assembled, the reactor of the LMFBR is indicative of the following schematic diagram.  Note the isolation of the steam generator components in a separate room:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/lmfbr.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Schematic Diagram of the LMFBR">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 12.  Schematic diagram of the LMFBR, illustrating the various<br>buildings and separated cooling loops. <a href="refrnc.html#3I"> (3I) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The fuel for the LMFBR must withstand very high temperatures.  Therefore, a ceramic fuel consisting of mixed oxides, uranium dioxide and plutonium dioxide, is formed in small pellets <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  These pellets are sealed in metal cladding to trap gaseous fission products from overly contaminating the core during operation and to protect the fuel.  The structure resulting from this process is defined as the fuel pin.

<p>The liquid metal used in cooling the reactor vessel of the LMFBR is sodium.  Sodium does not moderate the neutrons like water does in the LWR.  That is, no moderator is used in fast breeder reactors since the <a href="glossary.html#neutron">neutrons</a> must be moving rapidly for the concept to work.  Between 98 and 880 degrees Celsius under normal pressure, sodium exists as a liquid phase <a href="refrnc.html#38M">(38M)</a>.  In the LWR, the water coolant must be maintained under pressure, but this is not the case with the denser liquid sodium in the LMFBR.  The high operating temperatures of the LMFBR and the lack of a pressure system both result in the inherent safety and heat transfer efficiency of the system.  Normally, intermediate heat exchangers are used to transfer heat from the sodium in the reactor to a secondary closed liquid sodium circuit.  This circuit then transfers heat to the water in the production of steam and power generation.  By this method, leaks in the steam generators do not involve the release of highly radioactive sodium.  At the worst, a small amount of sodium vapor from the secondary circuit escapes.  For a thorough analysis of the mechanical engineering and nuclear engineering aspects of the cooling system, examine <i>Coolant Boundary Integrity Considerations in Breeder Reactor Design</i> published by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1978 <a href="refrnc.html#6B">(6B)</a>.  The isolation of the steam process and reactor process is one of the more attractive features of the LMFBR <a href="refrnc.html#5B">(5B)</a>.

<p>The Congressional documents referencing the LMFBR are vast and comprehensive.  In 1972, hearings before the Joint Committee on Atomic Energy of the Ninety-Second Congress were held for the liquid metal fast breeder reactor demonstration plant <a href="refrnc.html#8P">(8P)</a>.  In 1975, the national breeder reactor program was reviewed by the Ad Hoc Subcommittee to Review the Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor Program, a division of the Joint Committee on Atomic Energy of the Ninety-Fourth Congress <a href="refrnc.html#10P">(10P)</a>.  The following year, a study on the fast breeder reactor decision was compiled for the Joint Economic Committee of the Ninety-Fourth Congress <a href="refrnc.html#9P">(9P)</a>.  Consult the Congressional Record for additional government information bearing on breeder reactors.

<p>At present, variations on the LMFBR include the Integral Fast Reactor (IFR), Superphenix, and Monju, all of which are discussed in following sections.  For more information about the LMFBR, consult the web page maintained <a href="http://www.nuc.berkeley.edu/thyd/ne161/shir/project5.html">here</a>.  Completed by Ren Ruan Shi for a class at the University of California at Berkeley, this site is a project on the LMFBR.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="ifr.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;Integral Fast Reactor (IFR).&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="present.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to the &quot;Current Technology&quot; main page.</i></a></p>

