<html>

<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Integral Fast Reactor (IFR) </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=45%>
<h2 align="center">  Integral Fast Reactor (IFR)  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=45%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>In response to the opponents' of fast breeder reactors claims that the necessary reprocessing of the fuel within breeders would cause a breach in security, the Department of Energy proposed the construction of the Integral Fast Reactor (IFR) in 1984 <a href="refrnc.html#47M">(47M)</a>.  The main features of the IFR which make it particularly attractive are the elimination of all <a href="glossary.html#plutonm">plutonium</a> flows outside the plant complex and maintenance of a mixture of plutonium and highly radioactive fission products throughout reprocessing operations.  As a result, no concentrated, bomb-grade stores of plutonium-239 can be removed from an IFR complex.  Use of the term &quot;integral&quot; refers to the fact that all the components for power production, <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a>, and waste treatment would be contained within a single facility <a href="refrnc.html#44M">(44M)</a>.  Even if a terrorist group infiltrated the reactor complex and somehow escaped with some fuel, the fuel would still have to be reprocessed elsewhere.  The cost and complexity of reprocessing plants make the construction of such places by foreign countries less skilled in science a strong improbability.  The IFR also removes the concern about sabotage of plutonium-239 fuel during transportation to or from reprocessing plants, since all operations occur on site.  Indeed, the novel design of the reactor was cited as a &quot;proliferation-resistant&quot; reactor in accordance with its tendency to dissuade potential terrorists ruminating over the idea of owning nuclear stockpiles <a href="refrnc.html#47M">(47M)</a>.

<p>The design of the IFR included several changes over the conventional LMFBR.  The use of metal rather than mixed oxide fuels, for example, greatly simplifies the reprocessing <a href="refrnc.html#47M">(47M)</a>.  Reprocessing of spent fuel would produce a new uranium-plutonium mixture for use as a new fuel through removal of the <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a> products.  Reprocessing of the uranium-238 blanket materials would remove fission products as well, but two product streams would result:  the first would be purified uranium-238 for the new blanket, while the second would be enriched plutonium-239 for new core fuel.  The newest feature that still had to be tested and perfected was the electrolytic reprocessing step, by which the desired metals would transfer to the electrode from a mixture of fuel in molten salt solvent <a href="refrnc.html#47M">(47M)</a>.  The deposits of uranium can produce beautiful crystalline structures on the electrodes:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/crystal.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Purple Crystals of Uranium Chloride">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 13.  No, its not some type of fungus.  Rather, the picture shows<br>purple crystals of uranium chloride (3% of<br>crystal) along with lithium and potassium (97% of crystal)<br>deposited on the negative electrode during a small-scale<br>electrorefining test.  Electrorefining is the only IFR technology not<br>yet proven on a significant scale. <a href="refrnc.html#44M"> (44M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The long-lived highly radioactive fission products, the <a href="glossary.html#actinide">actinides</a> commonly referred to as transuranics, remain locked in the recycled fuel material.  By the time these products are removed, the IFR has reduced the volume, heat generation, and longevity of those nuclear wastes, reducing the current problem of long-term nuclear waste storage.  The IFR was viewed as a means by which the United States could regain leadership in the area of breeder reactors.

<p>Argonne completed a small prototype of the IFR by renovating Experimental Breeder Reactor II (EBR-II), located in Idaho <a href="refrnc.html#12I">(12I)</a>.  The following shows an illustration of the reactor at Argonne-West:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/anl-west.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Argonne National Laboratory-West">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 14.  An outside view of the reactor facilities at<br>Argonne National Laboratory-West in Idaho. <a href="refrnc.html#12I"> (12I) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Work on refining the IFR concept did not begin until the fall of 1983.  In retrospect, the failure of the Clinch River Breeder Reactor (CRBR) project rejuvenated the new Department of Energy to pursue the IFR.  The cancellation of the CRBR in 1983 freed funds that would have been tied to that project for other uses <a href="refrnc.html#44M">(44M)</a>.  In finalizing the IFR concept, therefore, while placating the fierce opponents of the CRBR, clear divergence from the muddled CRBR concept had to be established.  The Department of Energy also conducted a competition among the three primary nuclear contractors, namely General Electric Co., Westinghouse Electric Corp., and the Atomics International Division of Rockwell International Corp., to generate new breeder designs.  The IFR corrected the problem with loop designs by accommodating a pit design akin to the British and French reactors, whereby the core and support system were submerged entirely in a liquid sodium tank.  The following schematic diagram illustrates the reactor vessel of the IFR:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/ifr-draw.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Diagram of the Internal Structure of the IFR">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 15.  Diagram of the internal structure, no pun<br>intended, of the Integral Fast Reactor. <a href="refrnc.html#27M"> (27M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Sources from Argonne National Laboratory indicated that the reactor would shut down automatically in the case of an accident with the auxiliary steam and power production section.

<p>Another unusual safety feature of the IFR is related to the problem of melting fuel which is a source of potential catastrophe both in terms of human and economic loss in conventional reactors.  The fuel in the IFR cannot melt.  Since the sodium boils at 900 degrees Celsius, 200 degrees below the melting point of the fuel, by the time the fuel would begin melting, the intense vapor pressure above the sodium will have initiated the hoisting of some fuel up the cladding and out of the core, effectively stopping the chain reaction <a href="refrnc.html#44M">(44M)</a>.  The overall concept of the IFR, incorporating all the features in its fuel cycle and electricity production, is presented below:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/ifr-idea.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Diagram of the Entire IFR Process">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 16.  The ideal process flow diagram for an integral fast reactor, illustrating the flow<br>of materials and ultimate generation of electricity.<a href="refrnc.html#12I"> (12I) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Some uncertainties regarding the IFR remained by 1985.  The potential weakness to Argonne's IFR program was the focus on safety at the expense of supplemental costs.  Whereas the commercial contractors focus principally on cost, the national laboratories work on perfecting the safety of a particular design, making a specific reactor the best possible.  While the companies produced Chevrolets, Argonne produced Rolls Royces according to one automobile analogy <a href="refrnc.html#44M">(44M)</a>.  Among the various tests performed at EBR-II in April of 1986 were termination of the primary cooling pumps and interruption of the secondary cooling loop.  These tests were conducted individually with the reactor operating at full power of 62.5 thermal MW <a href="refrnc.html#12I">(12I)</a>.  In both cases, the reactor shut itself down without any damage to the reactor, illustrating the safety of the IFR even if normal safety systems no longer operate because of malfunctioning.  In short, the IFR is a safe reactor.

<p>In terms of wastes, the IFR does not place the transuranic elements with other fission products in a waste stream.  Instead, the IFR incorporates such elements into the fuel sent back to the reactor.  The <a href="glossary.html#radioac">radioactivity</a> of the ultimate waste will decay to a value less than that of uranium ore in only 200 years, as opposed to the many thousands of years necessary for decay of wastes from LWR to reach safe levels <a href="refrnc.html#2N">(2N)</a>.  Additionally, the IFR produces fewer low-level wastes than current LWR <a href="refrnc.html#12I">(12I)</a>.  In comparison to coal power plants, a 1000 MW IFR plant would produce 1700 pounds of waste per year, while a coal plant with the same capacity would produce 2,550,000 pounds per year, assuming operation during 70% of the year <a href="refrnc.html#12I">(12I)</a>.

<p>In terms of costs, the IFR does not require the expensive features of LWR such as the emergency core cooling system or as much emphasis on control of low-level radioactive wastes.  The fuel supply available for IFR facilities is astounding, since enough exists to provide sufficient power for well over 100,000 years.  Enough uranium-238 has been mined and placed in barrels to provide all the electricity for the United States for over 500 years <a href="refrnc.html#12I">(12I)</a>.  One of the best features of the IFR is still the advantage of on-site reprocessing using methods divergent from those of Europe, which require isolated reprocessing plants at which security is crucial <a href="refrnc.html#1N">(1N)</a>.

<p>Despite all these advantages of the IFR and the tremendous progress which had been made at Argonne National Laboratory, the Clinton administration called for the termination of the IFR program in February 1994.  While prominent Illinois representatives and senators lobbied for the program to continue, the program was ultimately removed from the Department of Energy budget.  To find out more about the Integral Fast Reactor, look at <a href="http://neutrino.nuc.berkeley.edu/ifr.html">this site</a> developed at the University of California at Berkeley.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
