<html>

<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> French Superphenix Breeder Reactor </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=60%>
<h2 align="center">  French Superphenix Breeder Reactor  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=60%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Originally proposed in the 1970's, the French Superphenix fast breeder <a href="glossary.html#reactor">reactor</a> has been and continues to be the most remarkable example of <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeder</a> technology on a large scale.  The site for the Superphenix was selected as Creys-Malville.  A number of other European utilities also contributed to the project <a href="refrnc.html#53M">(53M)</a>.  In its original design, the Superphenix was to be a 1200 MW electrical generating plant.  The overall structure of the Superphenix was a large central circular reactor with four steam-generator buildings located at right angles coming radially outward from the reactor.  The reactor building would contain all of the nuclear components and be built of one-meter thick concrete.  Each of the four steam-generator buildings houses some of the secondary sodium circuit.  The final heat transfer process would occur between the secondary sodium circuit and water to produce steam to power the turbines.  A horizontal cross section of the reactor and four steam-generator buildings illustrates the cycling concept.  The turbines and generators are not pictured here:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/super1.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Horizontal Cross-Section of the Superphenix">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 17.  The horizontal cross-section of the French<br>1200 MW fast breeder reactor Superphenix.  The central round<br>portion is the reactor room, and the four auxiliary structures<br>contain the secondary sodium circuits for heating water.<a href="refrnc.html#53M"> (53M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The statistics regarding the interior of the Superphenix reactor vessel are impressive.  Classified as a pool or pit reactor because of the location of all the equipment in a tank of liquid sodium, the main steel containment vessel would measure 21 meters across and ultimately contain 3,300 tons of liquid sodium.  Four primary pumps force the sodium upwards through the core, the hot sodium leaving at 545 degrees Celsius as new sodium enters the core at 395 degrees Celsius.  Eight intermediate heat exchangers transfer the heat to the secondary sodium circuits, each of the loops corresponding to two heat exchangers.  The ultimate steam-generators of the Superphenix are considerably larger than their counterparts in its predecessor, the Phenix:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/steam.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Comparison of the Steam Generators in Phenix and Superphenix">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 18.  Steam generators in the Phenix and Superphenix.<br>Note the increased complexity of the Superphenix model,<br>designed to improve heat transfer efficiency, while the Phenix<br>incorporates a more conventional style.<a href="refrnc.html#55M"> (55M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>These final heat exchangers transfer heat from the secondary sodium loops to the water.  In essence, the only difference between fossil fuel and various nuclear power plants is where the initial heat comes from--either from chemical or nuclear reactions--and what medium conveys that heat to the awaiting water boilers.  The concept of steam to run turbines and power generators is as old as windmills and waterwheels.

<p>In terms of nuclear fuel assembly, each subassembly of the Superphenix consists of 271 long fuel pins of the type described under the LMFBR section.  In subassemblies of the active core, the central portion of the pin contains <a href="glossary.html#fissile">fissile</a> material, either plutonium-239 or uranium-235, and on the top and bottom of this fissionable material is <a href="glossary.html#fertile">fertile</a> fuel, uranium-238, contained in fewer and larger pins.  The diagnostics of the Superphenix include a gross efficiency of 41.5%, a rate of fuel burnup of 70,000 MW-days per ton of fuel, a neutron flux of 6.2 x 10<sup>15</sup> neutrons per square centimeter per second, a breeding ratio of 1.24, and an interval of 12 months between refueling operations <a href="refrnc.html#53M">(53M)</a>.  In contrast to present LWR, the Superphenix must not be refueled as often.  A diagram labeling the parts of the Superphenix appears below:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/super3.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Side View of the Superphenix Reactor">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 19.  A side view of the Superphenix reactor.  The<br>general desing is the pit or tank style, because all the components<br>exist below the level of liquid sodium.<a href="refrnc.html#9B"> (9B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In September 1983, Great Britain decided to join European nations as development partners in pursuing breeder reactor technology.  Proposing experiments with the French as an option, the entry fee for collaboration on the Superphenix reportedly charged to the British was from $75 to $110 million, too steep to draw the immediate participation of the British <a href="refrnc.html#18M">(18M)</a>.  Rather than join the United States or Japan, Great Britain recognized the better future of breeder technology rested in Europe.  In 1984, the French government formally invited United States participation in the Superphenix reactor project.  In part to make the offer to the United States more attractive, France had recently agreed to accept international safeguards with respect to Superphenix <a href="refrnc.html#20M">(20M)</a>.  Clearly, the Superphenix had provided for substantial international rapport in relation to breeder reactors.  Ultimately, the Superphenix, originally scheduled to begin producing power in 1982, did not begin actual operation until September 7, 1985 <a href="refrnc.html#43M">(43M)</a>.  The date of initial critically had been moved forward slightly from September 9 in order to coincide with the birthday of Georges Vendryes, one of the founding fathers of the French breeder reactor program.

<p>Currently, the Superphenix appears as follows from an aerial perspective:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/super2.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Aerial Photo of the Superphenix">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 20.  Aerial photograph of the current appearance of<br>the French Superphenix fast breeder reactor.<a href="refrnc.html#41M"> (41M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Thus, beginning in 1985 and continuing today, albeit not without interruptions and a long hiatus, the 1200 MW Superphenix fast breeder reactor has served as the best example of the breeder reactor.  A sodium leak deep within the reactor was discovered in March 1987 <a href="refrnc.html#22M">(22M)</a>.  One of the subsidiary tanks that contain the fuel rods temporarily after removal from the reactor core had lost 20 of 700 tons of liquid sodium.  The main cooling tank containing the reactor core had not been harmed, but although the crack in the tank was mechanically minor and conceptually insignificant, the location and nature of the problem were expected to be long and costly.  During this same time, the French government had been seeking support from Germany and Italy for the proposed Superphenix 2, so the problem with the sodium leak came at a particularly difficult time.  Another major problem relating to economics developed in October 1987, as the France's state-run electric power utility reported that costs for electricity from the Superphenix were twice as high as those from conventional LWR <a href="refrnc.html#21M">(21M)</a>.  If the costs were not decreased within three to five years, the utility threatened major revisions to its future breeder reactor plans.  After a long hiatus, the Superphenix has been running since 1995 <a href="refrnc.html#58M">(58M)</a>.  To find out more about the French nuclear energy program, if you can read French, check out <a href="http://www.polytechnique.fr/poly/~www/Binets/X-Passion/xp7nucle.html">this site</a> from the French Polytechnique University.

<p>The British and German programs have not done so well.  The thought of reprocessing spent nuclear fuel had grown increasingly unpopular in Germany when it had originally been viewed as an interesting alternative to conventional fuel resources <a href="refrnc.html#48M">(48M)</a>.  Plans for a German national reprocessing plant were abandoned after violent opposition from environmentalists.  A <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a> facility at Wackersdorf, located in Bavaria not far from the border with Austria, became the site for numerous demonstrations against nuclear power in the months and years following Chernobyl.  In 1988, Great Britain announced severe cuts in its fast breeder reactor program, reducing its budget from $85 million in 1988 to only $17 million in 1990 <a href="refrnc.html#19M">(19M)</a>.  Citing fast breeder reactors as still being decades away from economic feasibility, British Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson authorized the cuts.  The British Prototype Fast Reactor (PFR) located at Dounreay in northern Scotland was shut down in 1994, and the reprocessing at that site is scheduled for termination in 1997 <a href="refrnc.html#19M">(19M)</a>.  Meanwhile, Great Britain continued to support the Superphenix despite the removal of its own breeder reactor programs.  During this time, however, the Superphenix was still not operational as a result of the sodium leak.  Thus, through the first half of the 1990's, essentially no breeder reactors of significance were operating anywhere in the world.

<p>The Superphenix will most likely stand as an isolated engineering feat for the next couple decades, although the future for breeder reactors is not that bleak.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

