<head>	
<title> Japanese Monju Breeder Reactor </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=55%>
<h2 align="center">  Japanese Monju Breeder Reactor  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=55%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>While the United States and Europe were pursuing their individual programs, Japan made great strides in the area of breeder reactors.  In 1988, Japan's Atomic Energy Commission presented its long-term nuclear program with specific goals for installed nuclear capacity by the year 2000 <a href="refrnc.html#49M">(49M)</a>.  The 280 MW Monju reactor was expected to be completed and operating by 1992.  One concern of the United States has been Japan's ability to safeguard the reprocessing and transportation of <a href="glossary.html#plutonm">plutonium</a> resources.  In particular, since the late 1970's, Japan and the United States were at odds over the transport of Japanese nuclear fuels to Europe for <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a>, since the long distance and voyage by ocean could make theft of enriched plutonium-239 a real possibility <a href="refrnc.html#49M">(49M)</a>.  Japan presently plans to build a large commercial scale breeder reactor like the Superphenix.

<p>A problem noted with the Monju was a miscalculation of the length of the cooling pipes, an anomaly noticed in 1991 before the reactor began operation <a href="refrnc.html#31M">(31M)</a>.  Extra lengths of pipe were welded in place, correcting the problem temporarily but adding to the system's instability in the long run through the increased risk of leaking.  In similar fashion to the Superphenix, the Japanese Monju also developed a leak in the secondary sodium cooling system.  The plant was shut down in December 1995 as a result <a href="refrnc.html#31M">(31M)</a>.  By this time, Japan had become the only country energetically promoting breeder reactors, since even France had become somewhat skeptical of the possibly benefits. Overall, 250 tons of sodium had to be removed from the auxiliary room next to the reactor.  Since the Monju had not been producing electricity since August 1995, generation had only been occurring for four months when the accident occurred.  Although plagued by delays, technical problems, and cost over-runs, the Monju was the first large-scale prototype fast reactor built in Japan, and together with the French Superphenix, represents one of only two clearly established types of breeder reactors existing in operation today.  Other models do exist, but they have not gained enough prominence or have not proven effective on a plant of prototype scale.  The Power Reactor and Nuclear Fuel Development Corporation (PNC) in Japan maintains a web site with a lot of periodical information about the Japanese Monju breeder reactor.  Click <a href="http://www.pnc.go.jp/indexe.html">here</a> to visit the main page of that site.</p>

<p>Paul Leventhal, President of the Nuclear Control Institute of Washington, D.C., gave a presentation entitled &quot;Separating Myths From Reality: Awakening From Japan's 'Plutonium Dream'&quot; on April 16, 1996 at Aomori, Japan.  Check out <a href="http://www.wideopen.igc.org/nci/sp41696a.htm">this site</a> to see a fairly lengthy dissertation about what Leventhal views as the misguided Japanese nuclear energy policy.  Comparisons to other national programs are made as well.  Note that biases may be inherent in the text of the presentation based on the nature of the organization.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
