<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Current Economics of the FBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/coins.gif">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=55%>
<h2 align="center">  Current Economics of the FBR  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=55%>

<br>
<br>
<br>

<p>Most of the current situation facing fast breeder reactors has been discussed in preceding pages of &quot;Current Technology.&quot;  To a large extent, fast breeder reactors are not economical on the basis of severe cost over-runs, the needs for repairs as witnessed with the British PFR and the Superphenix, and the large percentage of the year that such plants are not operating.  The Superphenix, the most successful and most ambitious of the breeder projects, produced electricity at a cost double that of the conventional light water reactors in France.  Since France provides upwards of 80% of its electricity through nuclear power, the cost differential is remarkable and precludes much further breeder reactor development.

<p>The leader of the French advanced reactors program until its culmination in realization of the Superphenix was Georges Vendryes.  When asked about the current outlook for breeder reactors during an interview at the Edison Hotel in New York, he showed clear disappointment about the near-term economic prospects.  He summarized the gist of the situation by stating, &quot;The problem is that they are simply more expensive than pressurized water reactors&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#50M">(50M)</a>.  He estimated the current economic backlash regarding fast breeder reactors as lasting another twenty years, or until the first decade of the twentieth century.

<p>In related economic analysis, the Integral Fast Reactor program was essentially stopped because of the apparent lack of progress and potential for the program.  The funds from that project, like the Superconducting Super Collider project in Texas, were appropriated to more meaningful projects.  Currently, the funds for fast breeder reactor research derive from the government, corporations, or academic institutions.  With government outlays for these projects decreasing and firms increasingly interested in maintaining a positive bottom line, universities and educationally funded research teams remain the only real alternatives for breeder reactor research.  On this level, however, massive projects are not possible, and much of the research must be directed towards specific concerns on a singular plane rather than entailing broad scope.

<p>The following figure provides a graphical understanding of why breeder reactors are currently very economic from the perspective of fuel.  Requirements for uranium fuel throughout the world will continue to increase, but not at extremely high levels accordant with normal light water reactors <a href="refrnc.html#8B">(8B)</a>:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/graph1.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Future World Uranium Requirements">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 21.  The effect on world uranium requirements by introducing fast<br>breeder reactors is quite remarkable.  From a current standpoint,<br>implementing advanced fast breeder technology could nearly level off<br>uranium requirements by 2030.  Numbers are based on the Organization<br>for Economic Cooperation and Development findings.  The unit of TEU on<br>the vertical axis denotes &quot;Ton Equivalent of Uranium.&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#8B"> (8B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Based on current reactor economics, therefore, fast breeder reactors cannot be introduced commercially, but if and when the bugs are removed from that system, the low uranium fuel requirements mean low fuel costs.  Currently, the dangers regarding fuel reprocessing have also limited the potential economic boon in the area of fast breeder reactors.  The future economics of fast breeder reactors depend on the variability of fossil fuel costs and the availability of such fuels in the future; such topics are discussed in the final economic section associated with &quot;Future Developments.&quot;</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="miscell.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;Miscellaneous Advances.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="monju.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;Japanese Monju Breeder Reactor.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
<p><i>
<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a></i></p>

<p><i>
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201 - Advanced Energy Systems</a></i></p>
</center>

<hr size=5>

<center>
