<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Miscellaneous Advances </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=40%>
<h2 align="center">  Miscellaneous Advances  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=40%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>While the current situation facing large fast breeder reactor programs is not very inspiring, research has been conducted and is ongoing on a small scale in relation to nuclear breeder technology.  For example, one ingenious approach in the past discussed the possibility of using fusion-generated neutrons to convert fertile material to <a href="glossary.html#fissile">fissile</a> plutonium-239.  Instead of using the uranium-235 as the neutron donor through nuclear fission, a fusion process could incorporate a thermal breeder reactor within the blanket of a fusion reactor <a href="refrnc.html#28M">(28M)</a>.  In addition, the authors of the article appearing <i>Science</i> also commented about the role of the possible arrival of fusion and how that technology would mesh with the current dependence on LWR and supposed installation of breeder reactors.  Indeed, discussion of the current technology of breeder reactors is impossible without consideration of the advances and likely realization of <a href="glossary.html#fusion">fusion</a> reactors on a commercial scale.  Breeder reactors were originally proposed to bridge the time gap of several decades between LWR and fusion reactors.

<p>The nuclear fuel cycle has always been of central interest to energy policy formulators and to scientists in nuclear fields.  The generally accepted nuclear fuel cycle, at least under ideal conditions operating at greatest efficiency, is represented by the following simple diagram:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/cycle.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="The Nuclear Fuel Cycle">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 22.  A simple diagram of the nuclear fuel cycle.<a href="refrnc.html#8B"> (8B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The first step in the fuel cycle is mining of the uranium ore and then fabrication of the fuel pellets.  In March 1994, researchers in Bombay, India announced tests on a different type of fuel pellet from the metal type of the IFR or the mixed oxide type of other LMFBR.  In short, the fuel pellets had the general chemical formula (Pu<sub>0.55</sub>U<sub>0.45</sub>)C, and were produced through the consecutive processes of vacuum carbothermic synthesis, cold-pelletization, and finally sintering <a href="refrnc.html#29M">(29M)</a>.  The acceptable limits for various elements in the fuel pellets were established, and the characteristics for various batches were reported graphically:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/impure.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Contents of FBTR Fuel Pellets">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 23.  The range of plutonium, uranium, oxygen, nitrogen,<br>carbon, and other compounds permissible in fuel pellets of<br>chemical formula (Pu<sub>0.55</sub>U<sub>0.45</sub>)C for the FBTR.  Data<br>are shown for various pellet batches.<a href="refrnc.html#29M"> (29M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In the present time, India has begun its own breeder reactor program, and this new fuel was synthesized for use in the Fast Breeder Test Reactor in India.  Although Indian science as a whole is a recent explorer in this field, several national research programs have proven accomplishments.  In order to comprehend and appreciate the vast complexity of nuclear reactors and the coincident facilities, look at the large JPEG (125 KB) image on an HTML file by clicking on the figure name below.  The image is not included within the text like the others because of its large size:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<h5><p><b><a href="fbtr.html">Figure 24.  Detailed diagram of the Fast Breeder Test Reactor in India.</a><a href="refrnc.html#3B"> (3B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Extensive research has also been done on various accident scenarios in the LMFBR.  Using a mathematical model known as the near-characteristics method rather than the more conventional Eulian, Lagrangian, and mixed calculus formulations, a team of Indian scientists prepared detailed scenarios of &quot;pressure disturbance propagation through a weakly compressible medium, bound by rigid structure as well as material interfaces&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#30M">(30M)</a>.  As an interesting extension of statistics and mathematics to safety analysis, the team planned to pursue fluid structure interactions and complex internal structures in future applications of the method.

<p>Another ingenious project conducted by a team at the University of Tokyo was the systems design of a direct-cycle Supercritical-Water-Cooled Fast Reactor (SCFR) <a href="refrnc.html#40M">(40M)</a>.  This proposal was to correct the problems with both conventional light water reactors (LWR), mainly the saturation of economic improvement compared with coal plants, and with liquid-metal-cooled fast breeder reactors (LMFBR), primarily their high capital costs.  For example, the LMFBR requires intermediate sodium <a href="glossary.html#coolant">coolant</a> loops, an argon cover gas system, and as the prototypes had illustrated, sodium leaks were unfortunately prominent.  By use of the SCFR, both the LWR and the FBR could potentially be improved.  The corrosive nature of sodium in LMFBR, for example, means that moving toward a version of an FBR based on water coolant technology would reduce the costs and maintenance problems.  For the direct-cycle SCFR, no intermediate loop is needed, and no steam-water separation is necessary <a href="refrnc.html#40M">(40M)</a>.  The high enthalpy of the water coolant also raises thermal efficiency in the SCFR.  In contrast to boiling water reactors (BWR), the SCFR would be very small, as a comparison of size illustrates:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/compare.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Comparison of Sizes of BWR and SCFR">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 25.  Comparison of the relative sizes of the Boiling Water Reactor (BWR)<br>and the proposed Super-Critical-water-cooled Fast Reactor (SCFR).<a href="refrnc.html#40M"> (40M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Although not an actual operating reactor yet, the SCFR was basically designed by using the best characteristics of the other types of reactors that exist in the present day.  By considering the forty year history of breeder reactor technology, only those features that proved to operate well were combined and incorporated in the design of the SCFR.  Such a reactor, and the other types that will inevitably result from the imaginations of scientists throughout the world, provide the possibility for exciting breeder technology in the future.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
