<head>	
<title> The Move to Atomic Power </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=50%>
<h2 align="center">  The Move to Atomic Power  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>In the decades of the 1930s and 1940s, incredible advancements were achieved in the discipline of nuclear and quantum physics.  Over just the span of one generation, the world moved into a new era of international relations defined not by conventional measures of national strength, such as finances and size of the armed forces, but by the ability to manipulate the innate power of the atom to effect mass destruction.  The unfortunate and unpredictable social context into which the world was thrust after the first successful atomic bomb blast at Trinity Site, Los Alamos, New Mexico on July 16, 1945, would render previous alliances unreliable while placing science in a paradoxical position of greater respect and power.  For more information on this move to the brink of nuclear war, check out <a href="http://members.aol.com/JTankard/trinity/home.html">this site</a> entitled &quot;The Unofficial Trinity Site Page.&quot; Fortunately, the cruel lessons of Hiroshima and Nagasaki were realized by most, and apart from the sheer wastes associated with the arms build-ups of the Cold War, nuclear weapons have had only a superficial, albeit influential, role in international politics over the past five decades.

<p>Soon after the conclusion of World War II, however, a different type of excitement about the atom arose in the United States.  Beginning literally months after the end to the bloodshed, scientists were already working on plans to produce useful electrical <a href="glossary.html#power">power</a> by harnessing the energy within atoms.  By practicing Albert Einsteins famous mass-energy equation, E=mc<sup>2</sup>, some of the mass (m) contained within atoms could be converted to <a href="glossary.html#energy">energy</a> (E).  The constant (c) is the speed of light in a vacuum.

<p>Surprisingly, the prevalent science magazines of the 1940s reported a somewhat significant amount of information regarding progress in nuclear science, given that the U.S.S.R. was at that time in close competition with the United States.  In the June 1949 issue of <i>Popular Science</i>, a lengthy article entitled &quot;U.S. to Breed Own Atoms&quot; explained the new program inaugurated by the Atomic Energy Commission to build two test <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeder</a> reactors <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(51M)</a>.  Named &quot;Operation Bootstrap,&quot; the program was intended to answer questions regarding breeder reactors, including the designs of the best models, the hazards, and the costs.  Only four years after the end of the war, the three basic goals of the breeder reactor program were outlined:</p>

<ul>
<li>More fuel for more atomic engines
<li>Heat convertible into electricity
<li>Isotopes as useful as radium
</ul>

<p>Of the two breeders highlighted for construction by the Atomic Energy Commission, the first was to be an intermediate-speed reactor installed by General Electric near Schenectady, New York, for the Knolls Atomic Power Laboratory.  At a cost of eighteen million dollars and an estimated construction time of two years, comparisons to modern plant requirements in terms of capital and duration devalue those of the 1940s considerably.  The second breeder was identified as being a fast-speed reactor, and designers at Argonne National Laboratory had already been working on the design aspects for two years prior to December 1949, indicating the rapid speed with which breeder reactor hopes had been stirred.  At that time, a fast <a href="glossary.html#reactor">reactor</a> had been running in Los Alamos, but the unit was extremely small and commonly referred to as a simple model for future reactors.  Therefore, although these early articles did not yet mention more specifics, the fast breeder assigned by the Atomic Energy Commission through &quot;Operation Bootstrap&quot; was soon to become the Experimental Breeder Reactor I (EBR-I), the first reactor to produce electricity for communities.  One interesting clarification within the <i>Popular Science</i> article which is particularly indicative of the sentiments and general ignorance about nuclear issues at the time was the following sentence:</p>

<blockquote><i>A fast reactor that will not explode has been running for some time at Los Alamos...</i>  <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(51M)</a></blockquote>

<p>It was a common misconception at that time that nuclear reactors could explode just as the bombs used during the war and in tests had so visibly detonated.  The media coverage and ubiquitous footage and photographs of frightening, billowing mushroom clouds did not aid the cause.  As will be discussed in the area of &quot;Future Developments,&quot; however, many people still have the incorrect notion that nuclear reactors can explode in the manner of nuclear weapons.  This notion is not true!  Although <i>Science Digest</i> included an article in its October 1948 issue from pages 70-73 on this very topic, few, if any, general news magazines of the modern era have done as well.

<p>Nevertheless, coverage of the events surrounding the breeder reactors was more uplifting and less biased during the 1940s than at present.  <i>Time</i> magazine also reported the proceedings of the Atomic Energy Commission in 1949 <a href="refrnc.html#7M">(7M)</a>.  Even brief descriptions from a physics standpoint pertaining to the viability of such reactors was discussed.  The news was reported with a subtle but apparent double meaning for the prospects of breeder reactors.  While the peaceful aspects were emphasized, the Atomic Energy Commission also recognized the military value behind the <a href="glossary.html#reproc">reprocessing</a> and recycling necessary for breeder reactors.  Purified and concentrated <a href="glossary.html#fissable">fissionable</a> material could function either as fuel in a reactor or in a nuclear weapon.  Through its blatant statements, which appear significantly audacious and charismatic in the modern age, &quot;Time&quot; left no doubt as to the military obligations:</p>

<blockquote><i>If the new converter works as well as expected, it will help the U.S. make more bombs out of less uranium.</i>  <a href="refrnc.html#7M">(7M)</a></blockquote>

<p>Even at this early date of 1949, however, the magazine indicated that the theoretical calculations for breeder technology were complete, and only a few of the engineering designs had to be completed.  The site for the breeder of the fast variety was identified as Arco, Idaho.

<p>One must take such lofty goals for breeder reactors and nuclear power in perspective.  In a 1948 <i>Time</i> article which appears humorous today but was respected as a definite possibility in the past, &quot;Atom-Driven Planes&quot; were noted as a strong possibility:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/jet.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Atomic Turbojet">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 2.  A basic diagram of the atomic turbojet engine proposed by<br>Dr. Andrew Kalitinsky in 1948.<a href="refrnc.html#1M"> (1M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>By placing nuclear reactors, which the article described as &quot;essentially a controlled, slow-exploding bomb&quot; in the place of normal combustion chambers of turbojet engines, powering the plane with over two million times as much energy as the gasoline equivalent <a href="refrnc.html#1M">(1M)</a>.  Of the many problems cited by Dr. Andrew Kalitinsky of Fairchild Engine and Airplane Corp. were the following:</p>

<ul>
<li>How to keep from killing the crew by <a href="glossary.html#radiatin">radiation</a>.

<li>How to avoid release of massive quantities of <a href="glossary.html#radioac">radioactive</a> material upon crashes.

<li>How to keep the plane light enough, when shielding is included, to get off the ground.
</ul>

<p>In terms of modern rules of science and society, such a notion for nuclear-powers planes seems ludicrous or even comical.  Of course, this is not the first idea in history which has never really been advanced much beyond planning stages.  Take, for instance, the submarine with the screen door.

<p>Speaking of submarines, the keel-laying of the first atomic submarine, appropriately named Nautilus after the fictitious vessel whose energy source is unknown in Jules Vernes <i>20,000 Leagues Under the Sea</i>, provided the backdrop for President Harry S. Trumans speech entitled &quot;The Threshold of a New Age&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#52M">(52M)</a>.  At Groton, Connecticut, on June 14, 1952, President Truman stressed the achievements of the Nautilus as a movement towards nuclear energy on a national and global scale, while he generally steered away from the fact that the submarine was principally a war machine:</p>

<blockquote><i>But the peaceful significance of the Nautilus is even more breath-taking.  When this ship has been built and operated, controllable atomic power will have been demonstrated on a substantial scale. . . . If we could devote a full share of our energies to the peaceful development of the atom, it should soon be possible to bring this new source of power into daily use.  Self-contained power plants, able to run almost indefinitely without refueling, and capable of being moved from place to place, would be within reach of our industry, our transportation systems, our cities, and our farms. . . .  It could set man free from servitude to geography and climate.</i>  <a href="refrnc.html#52M">(52M)</a></blockquote>

<p>Although the rhetoric and several references to the Kremlin, Iron Curtain, and Soviet Union somewhat cloud President Trumans message, the impetus for pursuing nuclear power was definitely present within the federal government, a sharp contrast from todays situation.  Politicians, eager to rectify the public state of confusion about the energy of the atom and to illustrate that the Manhattan Project was not merely an exercise in proving the power of the United States science program for destructive purposes, informed the public of the new direction of atomic energy.  No speech was more famous in this regard than President Dwight D. Eisenhowers address entitled &quot;An Atomic Stockpile for Peace,&quot; delivered before the General Assembly of the United Nations on December 8, 1953 <a href="refrnc.html#26M">(26M)</a>.  President Eisenhower noted the danger and power to which nuclear weapons had escalated, but also recognized that the United States no longer held a monopoly on nuclear power.  He proposed the new, ideal direction in which the United States should be headed:</p>

<blockquote><i>My country wants to be constructive, not destructive.  It wants agreements, not wars, among nations. . . .  So my countrys purpose is to help us move out of the dark chamber of horrors into the light, to find a way by which the minds of men, the hopes of men, the souls of men everywhere, can move forward toward peace and happiness and well-being.</i>  <a href="refrnc.html#26M">(26M)</a></blockquote>

<p>Additionally, President Eisenhower outlined an initiative, the main two points of which were to pursue and encourage global participation in peacetime uses of fissionable material while also diminishing already escalating nuclear weapons stockpiles.  Already by 1947, articles about the health effects--both harmful as well as helpful--of various radioactive materials had appeared in the <i>American Journal of Public Health</i> <a href="refrnc.html#24M">(24M)</a>.  Thus, research in nuclear energy proceeded via a tri-fold approach.  First and foremost were the nuclear weapons.  Second were the nuclear reactors for power and electricity.  Third were the medical uses of radiation and radioactive materials.  It may seem that this preceding discussion was extraneous to the topic of fast breeder reactors, but in reality it is not.  In order to fully comprehend the history and background out of which arose the first reactors, one must first consider the attitudes of those people and countries in power regarding nuclear issues.  Additionally, by performing analysis of this type--examining information and the biases inherent in the popular media, as well as the speeches and hearings of politicians--over generations to the present, the drastic changes help illustrate the present and future developments of breeder technology.  Breeder reactors must be considered within the chronological and societal context from which they derive.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
