<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> First Ideas About the Power of the Atom and Use in Breeder Reactors </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=100%>
<h2 align="center">  First Ideas About the Power of the Atom and Use in Breeder Reactors  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=100%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Already by 1949, much of the necessary physical and chemical processes by which nuclear reactions and specifically fast breeder reactors could operate had been defined.  The three <a href="glossary.html#fissable">fissionable</a> materials, or those which have long half-lives but dissociate upon impact with <a href="glossary.html#neutron">neutrons</a>, are uranium-235, plutonium-239, and uranium-233.  While the first type appears naturally in the Earth, the latter two must be manufactured from <a href="glossary.html#fertile">fertile</a> material, such as uranium-238 and Thorium-232.  There is a relatively large amount of uranium-238, since the uranium-235 mined for most nuclear reactors represents only 0.7% of natural uranium.  The other 99.3% is uranium-238.  Within the nucleus of atoms, the positively charged protons tend to repel one another; a <a href="glossary.html#nucleus">nucleus</a> with an odd number of neutrons causes greater dispersal of the protons as opposed to the case of atoms with an even number of neutrons.  In order to be fissionable, the nuclei of atoms must be slightly elongated beyond the size of the average nucleus.  The addition of a neutron provides such elongation in the case of uranium-238, which has 92 protons and 146 neutrons, and can therefore achieve an odd number of neutrons with the absorption of one neutron.  This process is neutron absorption or <a href="glossary.html#capture">neutron capture</a>.

<p>The theory that an atom of <a href="glossary.html#uranium">uranium</a> might split upon bombardment with neutrons was first proposed by the Germans O.R. Frisch and Lise Meitner, but Enrico Fermi intuitively established that more neutrons would be evolved from the uranium dissociation.  Thus, fissionable fuel could be produced from fertile but nonfissile material.  The incorporation of a neutron into an uranium-238 nucleus depends critically on the speed of the neutrons; when striking a nucleus at the particular speed called the &quot;resonance&quot; speed, the neutron will be absorbed, but in the other cases it may simply bounce away, which is most likely, or split nonfissile material, which is relatively unlikely <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(51M)</a>.  The relationship among fertile uranium-238 and fissile uranium-235 is best illustrated by an neutron energy cross-section for various fertile fuels:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/graph3.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Cross-sections for Fertile Fuels">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 3.  Fission Cross Sections for Common Fertile Fuels.  The unit<br>of barns on the vertical axis basically gauges to what<br>extent fission of the materials occurs.<a href="refrnc.html#9B"> (9B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>As one moves right on the horizontal axis, the <a href="glossary.html#energy">energy</a> of neutrons is first measured in kilo-electron-volts and then in mega-electron-volts.  Since the kinetic energy (KE) of a moving particle is the product of one half the mass (m) times the square of velocity (v), an increase in energy indicates greater speed.  Even though the area under the curve is larger at high neutron energies (and velocities), uranium-238 does not rise above 1.0 barns even at its peak.  In contrast, the same type of diagram for fissile fuels gives a different scenario.  While the graph for the fertile fuels slopes upward and to the right, the graph for fissile fuels slopes downward and to the right.  Neutrons of lower velocities and energies cause <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a> more easily in fissile fuels, and thermal reactors employ slow neutrons.  In terms of barns, the peaks for such fuels are on the order of 1000 barns <a href="refrnc.html#9B">(9B)</a>.  Clearly, therefore, a <a href="glossary.html#thermal">thermal</a> reactor operates efficiently with neutrons of slow speed.  At high velocities, fission of fissile fuels decreases significantly, while fission of fertile but normally nonfissile fuels increases as shown in the graph.  Therefore, when uranium-238 and uranium-235 are combined in a <a href="glossary.html#fast">fast</a> breeder reactor, the larger cross-section for uranium-238 with fast neutrons partially offsets the reduction in fission of uranium-235.  A fast breeder normally requires a fissile fraction four to five times larger than that within a thermal reactor as a result of the low cross-sections for fission <a href="refrnc.html#9B">(9B)</a>.

<p>The role of fast breeder reactors in the chain of neutron propagation is that more neutrons should be liberated from neutron capture by uranium-238 than are consumed by the fission of uranium-235 needed to provide the initial neutrons.  Some uranium-235 must be present in the breeder reactor to function as a sort of spark plug for the production of plutonium-239 from the nonfissile material.  Within the breeder, some of the neutrons liberated by nuclear reactions will split other atoms, while the remainder will elongate the atoms of nonfissile material <a href="refrnc.html#51M">(51M)</a>.  Whereas the fast breeder utilizes neutrons at a fast speed relative to other reactors, the thermal breeder includes sufficient use of moderators to slow the neutrons to lower speeds.  The velocities with which the neutrons move is difficult to conceptualize; the neutrons in the both cases are still moving considerably faster than any man-made source of transportation.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

