<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Nuclear Reactions of the FBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=50%>
<h2 align="center">  Nuclear Reactions of the FBR  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Now that the basic atomic and nuclear interactions within the breeder reactor have been identified, the picture can be specifically refined for the case of fast breeder reactors through discussion of the nuclear reactions.  Since the conversion of nonfissile uranium-238 to fissile uranium-239, generally regarded as the <sup>238</sup>U-<sup>239</sup>Pu cycle, is the reaction of principal interest, reactions of this type will be discussed.  First consider the following diagram of chemical reactions which proceed in the formation of plutonium-239:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/equation.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Nuclear Reactions in Fast Breeder Reactors">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 4.  Nuclear reactions of importance in the fast breeder reactor.<a href="refrnc.html#3I"> (3I) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The first equation involves the absorption of one neutron by uranium-238 with the release of gamma <a href="glossary.html#radiatin">radiation</a>.  The second reaction consumes the uranium-239 through further <a href="glossary.html#gamma">gamma</a> radiation as well as the release of one <a href="glossary.html#beta">beta</a> particle.  Note that the half-life of uranium-239, indicated by &quot;t&quot; in the parenthetical, is only 23.4 minutes, meaning that this reaction occurs to a great level of completion relatively quickly.  The next equation entails the decay of neptunium-239 by more gamma and beta particle radiation.  With a half-life of 2.35 days, this reaction also proceeds relatively often, resulting in the desired fissionable fuel plutonium-239.  Although further reactions can occur, such as neutron absorption to form plutonium-240, plutonium-241, and plutonium-242, such reactions have longer half-lives and are usually insignificant.  These reactions are not pictured above either.  Through beta decay, however, plutonium-241 can form americium-241, a useful isotope in many scientific fields.  The large half-life of 24,400 years for the <a href="glossary.html#alpha">alpha</a> decay of plutonium-239 means that once formed, this fuel will remain generally intact until required as fuel in nuclear reactors.

<p>The first equation in the previous image shows the absorption of a <a href="glossary.html#neutron">neutron</a> by uranium-238.  But from where does that neutron derive?  The answer is the decay of uranium-235, which is a reaction typical of the conventional <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a> reactors.  In general, a bar of uranium produced from natural sources contains one unit of already fissile urainum-235 per 140 units of uranium-238.  During the high-speed chain reaction typical of <a href="glossary.html#fast">fast</a> breeder reactors, decay of each uranium-235 atom produces approximately 2.5 neutrons <a href="refrnc.html#10M">(10M)</a>.  (Obviously, half a neutron can not be emitted; this means some reactions evolve two while others evolve three neutrons.)  Of the average 2.5 neutrons, one neutron causes fission of a neighboring uranium-235 atom, while the remainder produce <a href="glossary.html#fissable">fissionable</a> plutonium-239 from the reactions previously illustrated.  Some of the neutrons are invariably absorbed by impurities or shielding, or they may escape from the pile.  Inspection of those equations above shows that no new neutrons are produced.  Therefore, it is imperative that the fission of uranium-235 produces more than two neutrons per every atom, since this is the only source of neutrons in the reaction chamber.

<p>The <a href="glossary.html#double">doubling time</a> is an important measurement used to compare the effectiveness of various reactors.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

