<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Generation of Fuel in a FBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=50%>
<h2 align="center">  Generation of Fuel in a FBR  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>In general, this topic has already been necessarily discussed in the preceding paragraphs, but this notion is so central to the concept of <a href="glossary.html#breeder">breeder</a> reactors, it must be emphasized.  While the fraction of uranium-238 in natural uranium sources is very large, this nonfissile material is useless unless it is converted to plutonium-239 by the equations described earlier.  In order to actually breed nuclear fuel, however, a pile must produce more than one plutonium-239 atom per every uranium-235 atom consumed <a href="refrnc.html#2M">(2M)</a>.  That is, both fuels are <a href="glossary.html#fissile">fissile</a> and produce about equal amounts of energy when used in reactors, but more fuel must be generated in the form of plutonium than is consumed in the form of <a href="glossary.html#uranium">uranium</a>.

<p>A case to the contrary would be akin to skating 1 meter forward on a frozen lake only to have the wind produce a force that moves you 2 meters in the reverse direction.  After a period of time, you will have traveled farther in the direction opposite to the one in which you were headed.  You will have diverged from your starting point.

<p>So it is with breeder reactors.

<p>The generation of fuel is critical, otherwise normal <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a> reactors of the light-water variety could be used.  For this reason, fuel in the core of the breeder reactor must be periodically processed to remove impurities and other actinides that might otherwise absorb <a href="glossary.html#neutron">neutrons</a> or deflect them from the uranium-238.  Such a case would reduce the effective yield of neutrons from fission of uranium-235.  If the average evolution of neutrons ever drops below two neutrons per atom of uranium-235, the reactor no longer sustains its breeder quality but rather becomes a solely consumptive reactor, as one article described as a &quot;burner-upper&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#33M">(33M)</a>.  The entire case for breeding is dependent on the production of more fuel than it consumes.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="history.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to the &quot;History&quot; main page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="reaction.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;Nuclear Reactions of the FBR.&quot;</i></a></p>

