<head>	
<title> Introduction </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/screen.jpg">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h1 align="center">  Introduction  </h1>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<br>

<p>Energy is a precious commodity in the United States and throughout the world.  Most people in the United States take the availability of gasoline, heat, air conditioning, hot water, and electricity for granted.  Such items are often treated as basic necessities.  In reality, however, energy is only available to the extent that it can be extracted from materials already present on the Earth or through solar input.  Examination of a chart of energy use in the United States and throughout the world over the last century illustrates the logarithmic escalation of energy use:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/enrgyuse.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Energy Use Graph">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 1.  A chart illustrating the energy use of the United States and the world<br>over the past century.  The United States use is represented by the lower<br>line.  The unit of energy on the vertical axis is <a href="glossary.html#quad">quads</a>.  </a href="refrnc.html#4I">(4I)</a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In contrast, the estimation of remaining fossil fuel reserves other than coal is very low.  Various sources predict oil to last anywhere from 40 to 80 additional years, while the range for natural gas is slightly higher.  These fossil fuels produce large quantities of carbon dioxide and other pollutants, although they are still very useful sources of energy, particularly for heating and transportation applications.  In terms of renewable fuels, biomass, solar heating, solar photovoltaics, geothermal reserves, hydroelectric plants, and wind all provide energy, and the technologies associated with these various forms are continually improved.  For analysis of the potential for wind power in the United States, look <a href="http://nwtc.nrel.gov/publish_papers/potential.html">here</a> at a paper prepared by D.L. Elliott and M.N. Schwartz entitled &quot;Wind Energy Potential in the United States.&quot;  The capability of such forms of energy to replace the significant share of fossil fuels is implausible.  Nuclear power bears several problems, but most of the current backlash is vested in paranoia and presumptions about the instability of nuclear reactors.  Fission is the splitting of fissile material to produce energy, which in the case of nuclear reactors is often used to evolve steam, power turbines, and generate electricity.  Since atoms were first split at the University of Chicago in 1943, during the first test of a self-contained chain reaction, nuclear power has been perceived as an inexpensive and abundant energy source.

<p>In reality, the costs of building power plants with nuclear reactors have been rising in the past several decades as a result of more stringent regulations imposed by the <a href="http://www.nrc.gov/">United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission</a>.  Although such guidelines are essential, the lenghty processes of design, proposals, and debate have increased the costs in the United States dramatically.  Coupled with the overwhelming media exposure of the Three Mile Island incident in 1979 and the Chernobyl accident in 1986, no new nuclear reactors have been proposed in the United States over the past decade.  Click <a href="http://polyn.net.kiae.su/polyn/manifest.html">here</a> for more information about the Chernobyl accident.  Fusion reactors, which operate on the principles of nuclear fusion, were first identified as a potential eternal source of energy fifty years ago, and the date of realization of such reactors on a commercial scale was then placed in the 1990s.  Fusion is one of the energy resources receiving the most intensive research during the present day, but commercial actualization is still at least three decades in the future.

<p>Breeder reactors are a type of fission reactor that produce more fuel than they consume, providing nuclear fuel for reactors while simultaneously generating electricity.  Specifically, fast breeder reactors operate on the physical foundations that nonfissionable materials may capture neutrons to form fissionable fuel and that certain nuclear reactions may produce more neutrons than they consume.  In terms of history, fast breeder reactors were proposed as early as the late 1940s, and such reactors must have been behind President Dwight D. Eisenhowers famous &quot;Atoms for Peace&quot; speech in front of the General Assembly of the United Nations in 1953.  Since the first Experimental Breeder Reactor (EBR-I) was completed in 1954, the United States and other nations have launched extensive programs to refine and advance the technologies.  Although the costliness of the Cold War, both in terms of monetary funds and international scientific cooperation, limited progress on fast breeder reactors below its potential, promising empirical results were obtained for several types of fast breeder reactors.  A diverse approach to present breeder reactory technology offers hope for improvements in several realms of nuclear technology.  The future of breeder reactors is as yet indeterminate.  Although the present French Superphenix and Japanese Monju are reasonably successful, funding for Argonnes Integral Fast Reactor was cut recently by the present administration.

<p>As the United States and the rest of the world approach the twenty-first century, the prospect for another energy crisis akin to the OPEC oil embargo of 1973 is existent; the instability of the Middle East region, which provides the majority of the worlds oil, was demonstrated yet again only several months ago.  Fast breeder reactors not only use fuel in present abundance; they also reduce the amount of high-level radioactive wastes, the storage of which is of critical concern to the present generation.  Breeder reactors can provide a significant amount of energy until renewable fuel sources are perfected or until fusion becomes economically feasible on a commercial scale.

<p>Energy is very important to all nations around the world, but even moreso for the industrialized nations.  Entire economies, standards of living, and Gross Domestic Product all depend on the energy needed to power industrial plants and factories.  One can never have enough energy, just as it is supposedly true one can never have enough money.  Well, there is one exception noted here from the original <i>Star Trek</i> television series involving too much energy.  Download the WAV (57.5 KB) file below.</p>

<center><img src="icons/speaker.gif"><a href="audio/trek.wav">WAV:  &quot;An Immensely Powerful Field of Energy&quot;</a></center><br>

<p>First a disclaimer regarding this audio file.  The author has never been, nor really plans to be, a <i>Star Trek</i> fan or any other type of television science fiction fan.  The exceptions are the great works of the authors like Jules Verne, Ray Bradbury, Arthur C. Clarke, and Isaac Asimov, and the three television series <i>The Twilight Zone</i>, <a href="http://www.cjnetworks.com/~mkelley/macgyver/"><i>MacGyver</i></a>, and <a href="http://earth.ast.smith.edu/~patten/ql/ql.html"><i>Quantum Leap</i></a>.

<p>The following sections of &quot;History and Background,&quot; &quot;Present Technology,&quot; and &quot;Future Developments&quot; essentially describe, analyze, and interpret the past, present, and future of fast breeder reactors.  Please proceed to &quot;History and Background&quot; to read more about fast breeder reactors.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

