<head>	
<title> Motivation </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/clouds.gif">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h1 align="center">  Motivation  </h1>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/marble.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p><font size=4>
Welcome to the best home page about Fast Breeder Reactors available on the World Wide Web.  Although the fairly complicated and advanced nature of this subject allows me to predict with a considerable amount of certainty that you have specifically searched for the topic of Fast Breeder Reactors, perhaps some of you were just randomly surfing the Web and alighted on either this page or the most excellent home page for Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems here at the University of Illinois.  Regardless of the location or page from which you embarked, you have arrived at this page seeking further knowledge about this subject, and I believe that you will not be disappointed.</font size></p>

<h3 align="center">Motivation for the Choice of Fast Breeder Reactors as a Web Topic</h3><br>

<center><img src="icons/homer.gif"></center>
<p>Well, no, it was not exactly Homer Simpson that prompted this choice of topic, although the portrayal of Montgomery Burns and the presentation of nuclear power on <a href="http://home.eznet.net/~davlin/homer.htm">&quot;The Simpsons&quot;</a> are less than supportive.  Indeed, the media does influence perceptions about nuclear power--either positively or negatively, depending on the social context--a topic discussed later in this presentation.  Click below to download one of Homer's classic songs in a WAV (52 KB) file.</p>

<center><img src="icons/speaker.gif"><a href="audio/homer.wav">WAV:  &quot;Meow meow meow moew...&quot;</a></center><br>

<p>
<a href="http://ne43.ne.uiuc.edu/Nuclear/faculty/ruzic.html">Dr. David N. Ruzic</a>, Professor of Nuclear Engineering at the University of Illinois, teaches a class entitled <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems</a>.  In place of the usual mid-term exam or research paper, however, the assignment for the fall 1996 semester was the completion of a web project based on one of the class topics.  By this approach, the information compiled by students could be shared with others, educating others about topics of interest.  I am a student in the Department of Chemical Engineering at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  As a resident of <a href="http://www.vil.downers-grove.il.us/">Downers Grove</a>, Illinois, which is near <a href="http://www.anl.gov">Argonne National Laboratory</a>, the topic of nuclear energy, and specifically the Integral Fast Reactor, was of great importance to myself and to others in the community.  The University of Chicago in conjunction with the United States Department of Energy operates Argonne National Laboratory in Lemont, Illinois.  Over the last several years, Argonne was established as a possible depository for low level nuclear wastes generated by research facilities around the country, but this site was removed from further consideration by Congress during the spring and summer of 1996.  Nuclear issues, although losing media coverage in recent years to more pressing domestic problems of crime, drugs, and the economy, nevertheless have maintained a peculiar position within the national press and American public.  While many people have firm views about particular aspects of nuclear power, often these preferences and biases result not so much from an analytical basis as from a skewed or misleading perspective.  There seemingly exists little motivation to increase education in these regards since nuclear power has been relegated to an inferior status among the energy sources.</p>

<p><h4>
In summary, the topic of Fast Breeder Reactors was chosen for five specific reasons:</h4></p>

<ol>

<li>The relevance of the Fast Breeder Reactor to communities near Argonne National Laboratory and Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.  As a whole, the state of Illinois also contains more nuclear reactors than any other state.

<li>The definite need and clear objectives for improvement in education about nuclear matters.

<li>The apparent apathy of many people towards the sensitive and critical issues of energy production, utilization, and national priorities.

<li>The intriguing possibility for commercializing a reactor that can produce more fuel than it consumes and that reduces the surplus of hazardous nuclear wastes.

<li>The tangential technological advances in other scientific fields which should result from continued emphasis on breeder technology.

</ol>

<br>

<p><i><font size=4>
Several questions may be running through your mind at this point, such as the following:</font size></i></p>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What exactly is a Fast Breeder Reactor?</b></p>

<br>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  In brief, a Fast Breeder Reactor is a type of nuclear reactor that produces more fuel than it consumes, meaning that the nuclear fuel reserves in the United States and throughout the world can be utilized more completely.  Several other advantages, such as reduction in nuclear wastes, and some disadvantages, such as a lack of substantial precedents and positive public opinion, also pertain to the FBR concept.  Read the remainder of this page and all the headings under the main page to expand your mind.</p>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What other organizations, clubs, people etc., are not intended by use of the acronym FBR?</b></p>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  All of the following should not be mistaken for the fast breeder reactor.</p>

<ul>

<li>Franklin Belanoe Roosevelt (FBR):  President Franklin Delano Roosevelts lesser known younger brother.  Although a terrible politician, FBR was an acquaintance of the relatives of several contemporaries, including Teve Torbes, Dob Bole, Llamar Alexander II, and Ched Choppel.  FBR achieved brief national fame for his ability to carve cool sculptures out of spam.<br><br>

<li>Federal Bureau of Any Word Beginning with the Letter R (FBR):  Such agencies probably do exist within some department of the federal government, but the reference to FBR on this home page does not indicate any of those organizations.  Nor is FBR a typographical error intended to signify the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI).  I would explain further as to why the FBR and the FBI are not the same, but then I would be saying too much and SWAT team members would storm my room.<br><br>

<li>Florida Bureau of Any Word Beginning with the Letter R (FBR):  The same disclaimer applied to the federal case functions here as well.<br><br>

<li><i>Ferris Bueller Returns</i> (FBR):  Although this is a nonexistent movie as of the present, to avoid any conflicting notions to the contrary, be advised that FBR on this home page does not signify the sequel to <i>Ferris Buellers Day Off</i>.<br>


</ul>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>Why did I find a page where I have to learn when there are so many other entertaining pages on subjects such as the stellar <a href="http://styx.ios.com/~damone/gconan.html">&quot;Late Night with Conan OBrien&quot;</a> and various <a href="http://www.cs.bc.edu/~kawashim/deniro.html">Robert DeNiro</a> home pages?</b></p>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  You have an insatiable thirst for knowledge and were lured away from the movie and television pages by your inner drive to understand the world in which we live so that you can help thrust your country into the twenty-first century with confidence.  Or you are writing a report on this topic.  Or you desire more information on this topic.  Or none of the upcoming guest on &quot;Late Night with Conan OBrien&quot; seem interesting.  Or the Chicago Bulls do not have a game tonight.  Or this was the only open site.  Or you wanted to find something that could possibly be more boring than a lecture by your chemistry or mathematics professor.  Of course, as you shall soon see, if either of these last two directives was the impetus for your arrival at this page, then you will unfortunately be disappointed.  This site is nearly always full.</p>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>How will the perusal of this page on Fast Breeder Reactors better enable me to explore the world of science and understand nature?</b></p>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  As human beings, we have an innate nature to discover and explore all facets of the world--arts, humanities, mathematics, science, nature, and technology.  In the particular areas of science, society, current events, and economics, the availability and consumption of energy in the world is always an important topic.  As a nearly unlimited source of energy, at least across the horizon of foreseeable human existence, Fast Breeder Reactors offer many advantages over other types of reactors and conventional sources of fuel.  This page is not an endorsement of Fast Breeder Reactors, however, for the intention of this production is education with impartiality.  Discover the facts, make informed decisions for yourself, apply the newly acquired knowledge to future situations, and illustrate and teach these skills to others.</p>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What is the average air speed velocity of a swallow?</b></p>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  African or European?  (Okay, so maybe this was a cheap rip-off of <a href="http://www.mpython.com/">Monty Python</a>, but it does maintain interest!  And now for something completely different...)</p>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What is the meaning of life?</b></p>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  Source unknown.  Cannot find file.  No server.  Reboot hard drive.  Decide for yourself.</p>

<p>
<img src="icons/question.gif"><b>When should I eat breakfast/lunch/dinner?</b></p>

<p>
<b>Answer:</b>  As soon as you finish viewing this page on Fast Breeder Reactors and bestow this knowledge upon your friends.</p>

<br>
<center><img src="breaks/marble.gif"></center>
<br>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<font size=4></p>
Continue with the &quot;Introduction&quot; to develop your knowledge about fast breeder reactors further.  As Biff says in <a href="http://www.hsv.tis.net/~bttf/"><i>Back to The Future</i></a>, remember to &quot;Think, McFly, think!&quot;  Only if you think about problems in this world and work at them can you expect any solutions.  If you really want to hear Biff say this classic movie line, you may download the WAV (58.3 KB) file below.</p><br>

<center><img src="icons/speaker.gif"><a href="audio/mcfly.wav">WAV:  &quot;Think McFly, think!&quot;</a></center><br>

