<head>	
<title> Prospectus for All Forms of Nuclear Energy </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=60%>
<h2 align="center">  Prospectus for All Forms of Nuclear Energy  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=60%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Beginning in the 1980's and continuing into the current decade of the 1990's, the prospectus for nuclear power as an energy source competitive with fossil fuels has not been realized.  In part because of the accidents at Three Mile Island and Chernobyl, the public attitude towards nuclear energy has not been as supportive as it once was.  Additionally, the pressures from the accumulation of nuclear wastes from light water reactors (LWR) and numerous &quot;Not in my Backyard&quot; campaigns have diminished support for  nuclear energy.  A wide variety of organizations falsely condemn nuclear power without factual basis.  Editorials and political cartoons in popular journals, newspapers, and magazines create images that perdure in the psyche long after numbers defending nuclear power disintegrate in the mind:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/cartoon2.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Radioactive Statue of Liberty">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 26.  A cartoon illustrating the Statue of Liberty surrounded by heavy barbed<br>wire fence and shrouded by radioactive material.  Instead of clutching the<br>famous tablet with the date of American independence, a Geiger counter used<br>to measure radiation count replaces it.  The nobility and symbol of freedom<br>associated with the statue have been reciprocally replaced by subversion<br>and a somber tone of imprisonment.  Drawing by Richard Willson.  Reprinted<br>from <i>Stockholm Conference Eco</i>.  Copyright 1972 by Friends of the Earth. <a href="refrnc.html#4P"> (4P) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>As a result of these conflicting messages, the consideration of nuclear power arises at best amidst a nebulous and unsound environment.  With the current escalation in the popularity of natural gas, primarily because of its clean-burning nature, consumption of this fuel will probably continue to rise in the near future.  As always, coal remains an abundant fossil fuel, the pollution characteristics and enhanced technologies of which continue to be examined and refined.

<p>Before the Korean Section of the American Nuclear Society in 1986, Alan Schriesheim, Director of Argonne National Laboratory, predicted a &quot;Second Coming of American nuclear power&quot; with global growth in the nuclear industry <a href="refrnc.html#45M">(45M)</a>.  In April 1990, <i>Popular Science</i> featured a full-length article entitled &quot;Next Generation Nuclear Reactors&quot; <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a>.  The moribund state currently describing the nuclear power industry may continue to decline, some even predicting that the fission industry is dying.  Paul E. Gray, President of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, offered a contradictory opinion about the future of nuclear power:</p>

<blockquote><i>I am convinced that this new generation of passively safe, smaller, simple, and modular nuclear reactors can provide an economic, environmentally sound source of energy for the next century.</i> <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a></blockquote>

<p>As of 1990, there were 108 operating commercial nuclear plants in the United States, producing a total of about 20% of national electricity, but no new <a href="glossary.html#reactor">reactors</a> have been ordered since 1978, a span of eighteen years to the current year of 1996 <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a>.  The excitement about advanced nuclear reactors of the near future results from the fact that they would incorporate greater simplicity, lower operating costs, and greater inherent safety mechanisms.  The established and not untrue contention exists that the options to nuclear energy have not been explored to a great extent, and the funding and commitment to efficiency in this country in other areas are not significant.  Christopher Flavin of the Worldwatch Institute believes that the room for growth in alternative energy areas is very large <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a>.  In contrast to this argument, a reduction in the emissions of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases would require better non-fossil sources; in this case, nuclear power is the closest to attaining the level of performance, cost and social approval necessary to compete with fossil fuels.  While the public is supportive of renewable fuels, these can not be implemented for electricity production at high performance and low cost.

<p>In terms of evolutionary LWR's for the next several decades, consideration of safety is increasingly utilizing a common sense approach:</p>

<ul>
<li>Lower running temperature
<li>Lower power rating
<li>Increase the coolant to fuel ratio
<li>Change geometry so even in the event of leaks, the water level will be above the core
<li>Lower the probability of fuel failure
</ul>

<p>All of these various changes in the new reactors will improve safety; some are even being classified as &quot;passively safe&quot; or &quot;inherently safe.&quot;  In conjunction with these changes was the realization across the industry and the Department of Energy that the sizes of plants to be pursued in the future should be around 600 MW ideally, as opposed to the 1200 MW Superphenix monstrosity or similar large capital projects.  Lower construction duration and costs, as well as simplified incorporation into the existing grid, are realized when utilities have the incremental 600 MW options <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a>.  In addition to the liquid water and sodium <a href="glossary.html#coolant">coolants</a>, helium has also been proposed for investigation as a coolant.  For more information about the advanced nuclear reactors, consult <a href="http://www.uic.com.au/nip16.htm">this site</a> entitled
&quot;Advanced Reactors,&quot; a briefing from May 1996 provided on-line by the Uranium Information Centre (UIC) of Melbourne, Australia.

<p>Growing problems in the necessary step of <a href="glossary.html#radioac">radioactive</a> waste disposal are imminent.  While a portion of the cost of electricity from nuclear power fills a general fund for the placement, evaluation, and construction of a permanent disposal site for high-level radioactive wastes, the date such a repository could be opened was pushed back from 1998 to 2010.  The temporary cooling ponds for the storage of fuel rods adjacent to nuclear plants are filling rapidly.  As a result of the abandonment of <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a> in 1977, the reduction in the volume of wastes is not possible <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a>.

<p>While plans for evolutionary nuclear reactors are proceeding, the prospectus for the future of nuclear power would be incomplete without consideration of the funding aspects.  Congress has made deep cuts in the energy science budget over the past six years, the current Republican Congress going so far as to propose the dissolution of the Department of Energy as well as the Department of Education.  Since 1979, federal funding for magnetic <a href="glossary.html#fusion">fusion</a> has fallen 44% in real terms <a href="refrnc.html#32M">(32M)</a>.  A report released by the Department of Energy's Fusion Policy Advisory Committee in 1990 envisioned construction of a demonstration plant by 2025 and a commercial model by 2040.  Plans for the Compact Ignition Tokamak, the next generation nuclear fusion plasma experiment, was placed in sever jeopardy.  In general, therefore, the future of nuclear power is highly uncertain, since large projects are directly dependent on unpredictable funding and economics of other fuels.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="prosfbr.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;Prospectus for the FBR.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="future.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to the &quot;Future Developments&quot; main page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
<p><i>
<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a></i></p>

<p><i>
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201 - Advanced Energy Systems</a></i></p>
</center>

