<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Prospectus for the FBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h2 align="center">  Prospectus for the FBR  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>While in most cases the prospectus for fast breeder reactors is even worse than that of nuclear power in general, there exist bright spots in an otherwise mediocre vista.  Funding for the Integral Fast Reactor (IFR) was cut during the current administration.  A new reactor called the Advanced Liquid Metal Reactor (ALMR), which incorporates a design called Power Reactor Innovative Small Module (PRISM), has been explored and persists as a potential future breeder reactor although funding has been discontinued recently.

<p>When referring to the ALMR/PRISM, interconversion of these two terms is concentional, menaing that stating one immediately implies the coexistence of the other.  With substantial work being done by General Electric with the aide of Argonne National Laboratory, the basic ALMR is a fast reactor that will not breed significant amounts of plutonium.  There are nine reactors at any given ALMR site; each of three power blocks consists of three modular reactors.  Since each reactor produces 160 MW of power ideally, simple math indicates the potential for 1440 MW of power from three steam <a href="glossary.html#turbine>turbines</a>.  An important aspect of this system is the simplified reduction or escalation in plant size.  By adding or removing single power blocks, the power supply can be moderated in 480 MW intervals.  Additionally, since each reactor is licensed separately, the first power block built at a site could begin producing electricity while the others remained in construction.  Finally, applying the wisdom of Eli Whitney and Henry Ford in relation to interchangeable parts and assembly lines, reactor components of the PRISM can be standardized and manufactured easily in factories <a href="refrnc.html#15I">(15I)</a>. 

<p>The ALMR has several benefits but is not without fault.  Plans for the ALMR do not foresee high breeding capability as a priority, but the <a href="glossary.html#ratio">breeding ratio</a> could be increased by core modifications.  The ALMR core would consume valuable weapons-grade plutonium.    By employing the fast neutron flux associated with fast breeder reactors, the  ALMR will eliminate a significant portion of the long-lived radioactive <a href="glossary.html#actinide">actinides</a> produced by the cycle.  Fear regarding the breeding capability of the ALMR, even despite the observation that plutonium removed from the core would have to be reprocessed to be useful, is a detriment.  Like with all other fast breeder reactors employing sodium as the <a href="glossary.html#coolant">coolant</a>, physical isolation of sodium and water is essential to preventing violent oxidation-reduction reactions.  The ALMR currently includes a positive sodium void coefficient, which basically means that voids produced in the coolant channels by temperature transients tend to propagate, leading to possible meltdown.  Other fast breeder reactors do not bear this potential.  As with the IFR, the  favorable continuation of research was eliminated in deference to more urgent concerns <a href="refrnc.html#15I">(15I)</a>.  The future of fast breeder reactors can only prosper with the initiation of such projects in the coming decades.  For more information about the ALMR/PRISM, look at <a href="http://www.nuc.berkeley.edu/neutronics/gav/almr/01.intro.html">this site</a> from the University of California at Berkeley.

<p>The reduction in fast breeder reactor technology elsewhere has similarly come to the forefront of debate.  Rather than being viewed as a sign of international harmony and a strong desire to realize the fast breeder, the European collaboration on fast breeder reactors in the 1980's was in stark contrast a reduction in fast breeder technology <a href="refrnc.html#43M">(43M)</a>.  Like General Pickett rallying his troops for one last insane charge at Gettysburg, cooperation in Europe was a ploy to reduce funding by all countries in order to salvage national programs to satisfy the level of political investment.  The fast breeder situation in Europe became &quot;an institutional power struggle&quot; as programs divested themselves from the original goal of energy supply.  Ironically, the contention to use plutonium as a commercial fuel incites disfavor and costs global diplomatic prestige.  In many cases national science programs, in addition to the public, have irrationally lost site of the real purpose of energy and science.

<p>The same media bearing on the general nuclear power debate has also come to influence fast breeder reactor discussion substantially in terms of fear of reactor failure and pork-barrel politics.  The following cartoon illustrates the view of the fast breeder reactor as a runaway, uncontrollable  beast:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/cartoon1.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="The Runaway Fast Breeder Reactor">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 27.  A cartoon proposing that the fast breeder reactor is not safe but<br>will disintegrate and produce a fiery sodium trail.  The stereotypical<br>image of the &quot;mad scientist&quot; is attempting to subdue the reactor.<br>The man standing at the fence in a cowboy hat appears to be a portrayal of<br>President Richard Nixon.  Drawing by Richard Willson.  Reprinted from<br><i>Stockholm Conference Eco</i>.  Copyright 1972 by Friends of the Earth. <a href="refrnc.html#4P"> (4P) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>The point that such cartoons reflect relatively extreme views must be stressed.  Most people recognize the safety records associated with nuclear power, especially important in light of the fact that the dangers associated with coal and oil combustion are seldom uttered.  Nevertheless, improvements must be made in the area of education.  More information in this regard is covered in forthcoming sections.

<p>In May 1986, Alvin M. Wienberg addressed the question of whether or not breeder reactors were still necessary <a href="refrnc.html#54M>(54M)</a>.  Citing the remaining world reserves of uranium at six million metric tons and the world's installed nuclear capacity of 100 gigawatts electric in 1986, extrapolation revealed a 100 year lifetime for easily obtainable and fissionable uranium.  Fast breeder reactors, because of their more efficient consumption of fuel and possible waste reprocessing, could extend the fuel lifeline indefinitely.  The prospectus for fast breeder reactors in this regard is favorable.

<p>Georges Vendryes, in charge of the French advanced reactor development program from its inauguration until the 1980's, is particularly impressed with the progress made by India with fast breeder reactors <a href="refrnc.html#50M">(50M)</a>.  Once a nonplayer in nuclear games, the technology they developed to produce fuel pins cheaply excited Vendryes.  Currently, much research is conducted in India, and will continue in that nation.  If any nation will have an economy based on breeders in the near future, remarked Vendryes, India will be the most likely site.  The lack of many natural fuel resources in India and Japan has elevated the urgency for breeder reactors in those countries <a href="refrnc.html#58M">(58M)</a>.  In desiring more self-sufficiency, these two countries will be doing the most breeder research in the coming years.

<p>When the Superphenix was shut down again in October 1995 as a result of another cooling circuit leak, the future of the venerable reactor was already questioned <a href="refrnc.html#41M">(41M)</a>.  In 1994, the main objective with Superphenix was altered to serve as a waste-disposal plant rather than a plutonium breeding plant.  Saving the Superphenix from proposed shut-down and decommissioning is of principal importance to the entire future of breeder reactor technology.

<p>Most recently, optimism in the field of fast breeder reactors was discussed in an artile entitled &quot;Return of the Breeder&quot; in <i>Scientific American</i> in January 1996 <a href="refrnc.html#58M">(58M)</a>.  In August 1996, a panel assembled by the American Nuclear Society and led by Nobel laureate Glenn T. Seaborg called on industrialized nations to develop and use breeder and other reactors to make fossil fuels more available to developing countries.  The same panel concluded that the United States government acted unwisely in eliminating fast breeder reactor research.  The ability of fast breeder reactors to dispose of highly radioactive plutonium and actinides has become more an esoteric, futuristic notion than the proven truth it has historically been.  The idea of converting the Superphenix to consume 150 kilograms of plutonium a year is not new, but was proposed by Enrico Fermi during the 1940's <a href="refrnc.html#58M">(58M)</a>.  The fast breeder reactor completes the ideal fuel cycle, whereas light water reactors stop at an intermediate point with abundant mostly unspent fuel resulting in large quantities of wastes for which there is a dearth of storage space.

<p>Overall, the prospectus for future use of fast breeder reactors is not as promising as in the past, but the new uses and applications of old reactors, as well as evolutionary technologies, should continue to advance breeder research.  Unfortunately, some time may pass before the United States and Europe vigorously approach breeder research again, but in the meantime, Japan and India are leading the way.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

