<head>	
<title> Outlook on Prevailing Attitudes Regarding Nuclear Issues </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=85%>
<h2 align="center">  Outlook on Prevailing Attitudes Regarding Nuclear Issues  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=85%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>The discussion for the prospectus of nuclear power in general and fast breeder reactors in particular within the last two sections could not proceed without consideration of the prevailing attitudes regarding nuclear issues.  In many ways, the public perception about the safety of nuclear reactors has declined over their forty year history.  Mention the word radiation to a person unknowledgable about the basics of nuclear science, and you will often receive an anxious or negative response.  Television shows from <i>Saturday Night Live</i> during the 1970's and the CBS television movie <i>The Day After</i> about nuclear holocaust in 1983 have chided the curiosity of nuclear science.  But what does the future hold for attitudes about nuclear issues?

<p>In conjunction with the following section on &quot;Improvements in Education,&quot; the proper course for advancing knowledge about nuclear issues must present information from an impartial source to the public.  Since prevailing attitudes will continue to be negative for the most part, aims to present a clear picture of nuclear energy by removing the distortion is essential.  The Internet is actually a great means by which to achieve this correct portrayal of information, although it does allow exceedingly radical institutions to present their views as well.  In general, the forum for free speech is to be desired, but on either side of the issues, all claims must be factually based and representative.  The crux of the anti-nuclear argument has been the possibility for desultory environmental and human health effects, for example, but such effects have not come to pass.  On the flip side of the issue, however, the nuclear industry must not approach the public with shallow statements of safety.  Explanations through literature and public forums will present the facts; trust is critical.

<p>An example of a great source of information for Americans is the Neighborhood Environmental Watch NETwork (NEWNET).  This web site is operated by the Los Alamos National Laboratory and is a spacious repository of information.  The organization is, in its own words, a &quot;network of meteorological and radiological monitoring stations, central data storage and processing system, and public access to the data via Internet and Environmental Teller Machines (ETM's).&quot;  Most importantly, the organization approaches the topic of nuclear and other environmental issues from an unbiased perspective.  Find out more about balancing national security and energy needs with the environment and safety at <a href="http://newnet.jdola.lanl.gov/newnet.html">this site</a> from Los Alamos National Laboratory.

<p>As the power and market penetration of the Internet escalates, the role of this medium for conveyance of information will gain significance.  The basic problems enveloping the nuclear power debate that will remain in the future were outlined from the onset of nuclear industry.  From a 1953 issue of the &quot;Bulletin of Atomic Scientists,&quot; several scientists noted the needs for guaranteeing the military and health aspects of nuclear power, safeguarding the public interest with assurance of integrity, and presenting suitable incentives for private initiative <a href="refrnc.html#36M">(36M)</a>.  Unfortunately, all three of those tasks have proven more difficult in practive than in theory, meaning that over forty years later, the future will still have to resolve these issues regarding nuclear power for it to advance.  The foundation of nuclear power and fast breeder reactors must on rock rather than sand.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

