<head>	
<title> Improvements in Education </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=45%>
<h2 align="center">  Improvements in Education  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=45%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>Education about nuclear issues has long been a constant source of frustation for scientists and politicians alike.  Many people simply have a lack of knowledge about nuclear energy in general, not by any fault of their own, but by the failures in the system that must deal with current events.  The incorrect notion that a nuclear reactor can explode as would a bomb is unfortunately more widespread among the populace than one would postulate.  If fast breeder reactors and the nuclear industry in general are to impact the energy portfolio of the world significantly in the next century, then education must be improved.

<p>When one mentions the subject of nuclear matters, the image conjured up in the minds of most participants is a mushroom cloud from an atomic detonation.  Such an image clearly causes distortion of nuclear energy and nuclear power.  Education about nuclear issues, particularly radiation and radioactivity, has been developed further, but the capacity for change is still large.  Most students are introduced briefly to nuclear issues at the elementary school level, but not until high school chemistry classes are nuclear reactions covered more thoroughly.  Physics classes may also include such topics in relation to optics, energy, and power.  In high school biology classes, discussion of radiation does not advance beyond the use of radioactive tracers or carbon dating.  In all three science disciplines, the context of nuclear issues as they relate to the nuclear power industry is usually disparate from the curricula of the science classes.  Therefore, students lack knowledge about how the nuclear reactions and <a href="glossary.html#radioac">radioactive</a> materials play a role in the nuclear fuel cycle.

<p>The Internet plays a role in education as well.  One page for &quot;The Rad*Scanner,&quot; a personal nuclear <a href="glossary.html#radiatin">radiation</a> monitor, was located at <a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/Metercon/">this site</a>.  Provided by the Meter COnversions, Inc., the overall appearance of the page is an advertisement for people to buy the product by taking advantage of their irrational fears.  To its merit, the page does provide factual information about radiation, but the commercialistic enterprise is unavoidable.  The Environmental Technical Information Project by ECOLOGIA is another site containing technical information about radiation and its impact on the environment as well as links to other useful sites.  This page can be obtained by clicking <a href="http://ecologia.nier.org/english/level1/radiate.html">here</a> to go to this location.  The universities and government agencies from countries around the world sponsor sites which are often more informative and factual.  In any regard, the Internet will become increasingly important to conveying information so long as it is not used for proselytizing.

<p>One must recognize the inherent inequalities in terms of economic standing that often correlate with access to computers.  It will likely be the case for some time that the &quot;haves&quot; in the terms of Mortimer Adler will continue to have more money for better education and computers, while the &quot;have nots&quot; will be excluded from the information superhighway until such computers become as commonplace as telephones.  Thus, fear of divergence of educational trends is a real concern, and the nuclear industry must take note of this fact when proposing new reactors to cities or states.

<p>Various nuclear agencies release literature about radiation, common questions about the nuclear industry, and concerns of the public.  For example, the following figure shows the cover of a pamphlet entitled &quot;The Decommissioning of Nuclear Plants&quot; released by the International Atomic Energy Agency:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/decomm.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="The Decommissioning of Nuclear Plants">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 28.  The cover of a pamphlet printed in the United States and prepared<br>by the International Atomic Energy Agency.<a href="refrnc.html#5P"> (5P) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In general, the nuclear industry probably would not be trusted in providing such literature.  It is very difficult for the groups that must promote the economics of nuclear power to also promote the safety aspects, since these objectives appear diametrically opposed.  The American Nuclear Society and International Atomic Energy Agency, as well as many private science foundations, will continue to be better avenues for such information.

<p>In conclusion, the educational improvements necessary for the future include a focus on providing the truth to the public at an early age, beginning in elementary school, and then advancing knowledge through junior high and high school through a multi-faceted approach of units in classes, the Internet, and information through television science.  In the adult world, the presence of the nuclear industry must be reported in terms other than reports of system failures or accidents.  The success of a fast breeder reactor, unfortunately, does not make news as entertaining as an explosion.  To restore at least an impartial view of nuclear power, education is key.</p>

<br>
