<head>	
<title> Future Economics of the FBR </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/coins.gif">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=50%>
<h2 align="center">  Future Economics of the FBR  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%>

<br>
<br>
<br>

<p>New investment in nuclear power and fast breeder reactors in the future is less likely than it has been in the past.  Of the companies that have employed nuclear generation, 40% have had to reduce or eliminate the divedends on stocks to their stockholders, seriously dissuading people and banks from further investment.  The typical utility investor realizes a profit shortly, but this is not so in the nuclear industry recently <a href="refrnc.html#27M">(27M)</a>.  Richard Slember of Westinghouse's Energy Systems Division denigrated the lack of standardization in the United States; each of the more than one hundred nuclear reactors in the United States is different with components and reactors from a variety of vendors.  France, in contrast, uses one basic design at three alternative power levels which can be built in areas according to the additional amount of power required.  The cost differential for fast breeder reactors is even more counterproductive to their construction.  

<p>The direct cost comparison for the future between conventional light water reactors (LWR) and breeder reactors provides critical information about their viability.  The cost of electricity is composed of capital, fuel, and operating and maintenance.  The uranium fuel for the fast breeder reactor is cheaper than for the LWR, and the former is less sensitive to fluctuations in <a href="glossary.html#uranium">uranium</a> ore prices, because the breeder consumes fuel more efficiently than other reactors.  In reality, however, the capital costs for breeder reactors are higher than for LWR.  One mill is one-tenth of one cent.  The cost per kilowatt-hour for electric power from LWR, in terms of mills, is the following:</p>

<center>C<sub>LWR</sub> = 5.8 + 0.033 p</center><br>

<p>where p indicates the price in dollars of a kilogram of uranium.  Denoting the breeder reactor by B, the same type of equation for the breeder reactor yields:</p>

<center>C<sub>B</sub> = 7.5 + 0.01 p</center><br>

<p>In each equation, the first term is the capital allotment and the second term indicates fuel cost.  Note the higher capital but lower fuel cost for the breeder reactor <a href="refrnc.html#54M">(54M)</a>.

<p>But what do these price comparisons mean for the future economics of breeder reactors?  The key is that based solely on current economics, breeder reactors are not necessary and cannot be deployed throughout the world.  In order to compete, the fuel cost of the breeder reactor must compensate for its higher capital costs.  As more experience in the complex breeder technology is acquired, costs should decrease.

<p>Another important discovery andhope regarding fast breeder reactors is that  longevity of liquid metal fast breeder reactors (LMFBR) may be greater than originally predicted.  Although based on a design life of 40 years, LMFBR's may generate power for upwards of 100 or even 150 years.  Such numbers are not unreasonable, since the liquid sodium causes no evidence of corrosion to the system components.  If the LMFBR is able to last longer than the amortization time, electricity after all debt has been removed will cost less than 1.5 cents per kilowatthour, which is less than the cost of electricity from any other current energy source <a href="refrnc.html#54M">(54M)</a>.  The lack of a clear precedent in the area of commercial fast breeder reactors exacerbates the anxiety national science programs and corporations have about investing billions of dollars in research.

<p>Alvin M Weinberg summarized the future economics of fast breeder reactors through comparison with current trends:</p>

<blockquote><i>Thus, despite the disappointing economics of today's breeder (as well as the other inexhaustibles), at least as judged by current conceptions and technology, a prudent concern for the energy future of our grandchildren, if nor our children, justifies continuing a vigorous quest for an economical safe breeder.</i> <a href="refrnc.html#54M">(54M)</a></blockquote>

<p>If costs of fossil fuels, particularly the natural gas used for electricity production, continue to increase at faster rates and the depletion of <a href="glossary.html#fissile">fissile</a> uranium reserves without adequate provisions for uranium reprocessing and permanent waste storage, the fast breeder reactor will triumph as a boon for the world energy supply.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

<p>
<a href="#start"> <img src="icons/up.gif"> <i> Return to the top of this page.</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="factors.html"> <img src="icons/right.gif"> <i> Proceed to &quot;Positive and Negative Factors Facing FBR Development.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="educate.html"> <img src="icons/left.gif"> <i> Return to &quot;Improvements in Education.&quot;</i></a></p>

<p>
<a href="main.html"> <img src="icons/home.gif"> <i> Return to the most excellent Fast Breeder Reactor home page.</i></a></p>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<p>
<img src="icons/uofi2.gif"></p>
<p><i>
<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</a></i></p>

<p><i>
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201 - Advanced Energy Systems</a></i></p>
</center>

<hr size=5>

<center>
<font size=5>
