<html>

<!--This page was designed and the text was written by Daniel P. Bailey.  Some of the programming codes were modified from versions found on other pages.  In cases where drawings, diagrams, pictures, or logos were used from official copywritten or trademarked World-Wide Web locations, books, newspaper, magazines, or other media, the sources have been noted conspicuously.  The text of this document is Copyright 1996 by Daniel P. Bailey-->

<head>	
<title> Positive and Negative Factors Facing FBR Development </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=80%>
<h2 align="center">  Positive and Negative Factors Facing FBR Development  </h2>
<hr size=3 width=80%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p>The positive and negative factors facing further development of fast breeder reactors are ultimately analyzed with parallels to the educational improvements and prevailing attitudes.  As is often true in complex cases, one must return to the first proposals about fast breeder technology.  During a lecture at Argonne National Laboratory on April 23, 1952, the director Walter H. Zinn stated the following before the administrative staff in regards to breeder reactors:</p>

<blockquote><i>Improved technical knowledge can be expected to answer the economic challenge and will place vast quantities of nuclear energy in our hands at a competitive cost.  No promise exists for substantially cheaper power but there is every prospect that this source of energy will become available to our ever-expanding needs for electricity.</i> <a href="refrnc.html#57M">(57M)</a></blockquote>

<p>In terms of the future, the hopes expressed by Zinn were clearly much more optimistic than realistic, but by viewing the proposal with the positive and negative challenges for the future, the changes that must be made to advance fast breeder reactors rise to the surface.  Problems exist at several levels of the nuclear fuel cycle for fast breeder reactors.  Capital costs for plants are still too high to result in widespread investment.  In terms of fuel use, problems remain in the area of <a href="glossary.html#reproc">fuel reprocessing</a> and <a href="glossary.html#plutonm">plutonium</a> wastes.  The so-called &quot;back-end&quot; of the fuel cycle consists of the following steps:</p>

<ul>
<li>management of irradiated spent fuel
<li>storage of irradiated spent fuel
<li>possible disposal of irradiated spent fuel
<li>chemical reprocessing of spent fuel
<li>management and transportation of separated plutonium
<li>management and disposal of high-level radioactive waste
</ul>

<p>The problems with breeder reactors in this regard involve environmental development, public health and safety, and the spread of nuclear weapons-grade plutonium fuel.  Some cessation of national autonomy may be necessary to insure safety of plutonium fuel through international arrangements <a href="refrnc.html#7B">(7B)</a>.  As John Abbotts discussed in an article appearing in <i>The Nation</i>, the battle over plutonium has not yet been resolved <a href="refrnc.html#12M"> (12M)</a>.  In particular, in light of the recent end of the Cold War and the emergence of powerful and wealthy rogue groups, the chance for a single terrorist nuclear attack is rising at the same time nuclear holocaust appears to be an antiquated concern.  Thus, protecting plutonium from such groups is essential.  The Computational Physics and Engineering Division of Oak Ridge National Laboratory uses computational methods for the
modeling of radiation transport and physics phenomena and to apply these methods to problems of national importance.  Visit <a href="http://epmnas.epm.ornl.gov/home.html">their site</a> about current research being performed in nuclear analysis and shielding.

<p>In <i>The World Press Review</i> in March 1993, the question of what to do with the world's plutonium was addressed.  Except in Japan, the article sited the declining role of the fast breeder reactor.  The article concluded, however, that the new generation of nuclear wastes will continue to outpace current reprocessing facilities, even if all spent fuel is hypothetically processed.  By the year 2000, world reprocessing capacity may rise to 7,600 tons, but the amount of spent fuel discharged globally is currently 10,080 tons and rising <a href="refrnc.html#34M">(34M)</a>.  Therefore, long-term storage must still play the leading role, but since space for storage is not extensive, the fast breeder reactor can play a role by reducing the amount of waste significantly.

<p>The <a href="glossary.html#discount">discount rate</a> for fast breeder reactors is such that investment in other energy technologies is more lucrative and much more secure.  Stringent economic constraints and minimization of costs must be implemented.

<p>The expected total capacity of fast breeder reactors expected in the future was graphed with time by Dr. J.K. Wright <a href="refrnc.html#8B">(8B)</a>.  While the number of <a href="glossary.html#thermal">thermal reactors</a> has been expected to rise and fall, the projection of possible fast breeder capacity, assuming certain restrictions, was established:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/graph2.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Projection of Possible World Nuclear Capacity">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 29. The projection of possible world nuclear capacity, assuming<br>maximum burning of 10 megatons of U<sub>3</sub>O<sub>8</sub>, over the<br>period from 1970 to 2030. <a href="refrnc.html#8B"> (8B) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>One positive factor facing future fast breeder reactor development is the large amount of uranium-238 which exists for the breeding process.

<p>The French Superphenix project, often plagued by operational problems, has been cited in several cases as essential to the future of fast breeder reactors:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/quote.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Quote on the Future of the Superphenix">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure 30. The Superphenix project in France, originally intended to be a<br>landmark 1200 MW fast breeder reactor generating plutonium fuel, has not<br>held up to predictions.  Presently, the future of the Superphenix is in<br>serious jeopardy. <a href="refrnc.html#41M"> (41M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In similar fashion to the funding cuts by other foreign national programs, the termination of the breeding program in the United States is a very serious detriment to the future development of fast breeder reactors.  In particular, the Integral Fast Reactor solved many problems that opponents had been stressing, particularly reprocessing, but funding was still removed.  Since the time lag between investment and market penentration of new models is so great, decreased energy science funding during the present day means an ominous energy future when the fossil fuels of oil and natural gas become less prominent.  As long as other fuel prices remain low, the country and public may unwisely continue to approach the energy question appathetically.

<p>Education is still the best means by which to improve the prospects for fast breeder reactors, but the public tends toward distrust of large organizations.  Even the federal government is not respected by a segment of the population as a result of the <a href="glossary.html#radiatin">radiation</a> research conducted during the Cold War using human subjects.  The Office of Human Radiation Experiments has been created within the United States Department of Energy to resolve this sad time of the American past.  Click on <a href="http://www.ohre.doe.gov/">this site</a> to see the home page of that office.  The media focus on problems of nuclear energy rather than on triumphs is currently a negative factor, but impartial reporting would aid in  the development of fast breeder reactors.

<p>The likely realization of <a href="glossary.html#fusion">fusion</a> energy on a commercial scale within the next 50 to 75 years will probably put an end to the future of fast breeder reactors, just as wood was replaced as the primary fuel in the United States a century ago.</p>

<br>
<hr size=5>
<br>

