<head>	
<title> Conclusions </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/screen.jpg">

<a name="start"></a>

<hr size=3 width=35%>
<h1 align="center">  Conclusions  </h1>
<hr size=3 width=35%>

<br>
<br>
<br>

<p>The concept that resulted in the first Fast Breeder Reactors (FBR) was borne out of the nuclear physics program that produced the atomic bomb.  Unfortunately, this stigma will always be applied to nuclear power.  Beginning in the 1950's, however, fast breeder reactors have been investigated in many countries both in theory and in practice, primarily in the United States, Europe, and Japan.  Although the predictions have historically been more optimistic than realistic, the Experimental Breeder Reactor I (EBR-I), Experimental Breeder Reactor II (EBR-II), Phenix, Superphenix, and Monju have all been relatively successful.  Currently, many national programs and specific reactor projects have been cut due to high costs, lack of clear direction, fear of plutonium theft, and the low prices of fossil fuels.  In general, since the Three Mile Island and Chernobyl incidents, public attitudes regarding nuclear energy have been less than supportive.  The American projects named the Integral Fast Reactor and the Advanced Liquid Metal Reactor with the Power Reactor Innovative Small Module have been terminated.  Miscellaneous advanced continue to be made on a small-scale level, and India and Japan are the nations most actively pursuing breeder reactors now and into the near future.  The prospectus for nuclear power and breeder reactors is not favorable, although the use of new breeder reactors in new ways has been productive.  The economics of fast breeder reactors have proven to make such large projects prohibitive simply on an economic basis.

<p>The future of fast breeder reactors, and energy science in general to some extent, is not very promising.  If fusion energy is developed within the first half of the next century, the need for fast breeder reactors will essentially be removed.  The merits of breeding technology--very low cost fuel, abundance of fuel, and certainty of energy supply--will have been replaced by nuclear fusion, which produces power without the worry of radioactive wastes or stores of bomb-grade plutonium.

<p>For a summary of the fast breeder reactor projects that have been accomplished to 1980, look at the large JPEG (143 KB) image on an HTML file by clicking on the figure name below.  The image is not included within the text like the others because of its large size:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<h5><p><b><a href="projects.html">Figure 31.  World progress in the design, construction, and operation of<br>liquid metal fast breeder reactors (LMFBR) from 1945 up until 1980.</a><a href="refrnc.html#53M"> (53M) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Note that in general, the bar graph showed that as breeder reactors have been pursued more recently, the design phase has begun to take significantly longer as more problems are tackled.  The duration of the construction phase has also generally increased over the years to date.

<p>One disclaimer must be made regarding messages, figures, etc. appearing on the main page and on subsequent pages.  This page entitled &quot;Fast Breeder Reactors&quot; is in no way associated with the International Olympic Committee (IOC), cabbages, the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG), the American Civil War, any corporations or companies mentioned herein, &quot;Seinfeld,&quot; any television shows or pesonalities mentioned herein, Spam, or any other canned foods.  Of course, you the viewer probably knew that, since nuclear energy is not exactly associated with any type of sport or show or person or vegetable.  Although with ballroom dancing becoming a demonstration sport, who knows what the future will hold...  Neither monetary nor administrative correspondence occurred in any respect with those parties.  Sources for all figures are clearly indicated.  The characters of Calvin and Hobbes were created and are copyright by Bill Watterson.  The characters of Homer, Itchy, and Scratchy are copyright by Twentieth Century Fox.

<p>If you have made it this far through the dissertation on Fast Breeder Reactors, you should be commended for your curiosity and desire to learn (or perhaps your stubborness).   Although I do not even like any of the &quot;Star Trek&quot; spin-offs, the original was still the best, a classic like <a href="http://free.websight.com/Ashley/">&quot;Welcome Back, Kotter&quot;</a> or &quot;The Twilight Zone&quot; but not &quot;Lost in Space&quot; (Danger Will Robinson!).  Here you may download  two neat WAV (68.5 KB and 13.9 KB) files simulating energizing on the Starship Enterprise.</p><br>

<center><img src="icons/speaker.gif"><a href="audio/enrgize1.wav">WAV:  &quot;Long Energizing&quot;</a></center><br>

<center><img src="icons/speaker.gif"><a href="audio/enrgize2.wav">WAV:  &quot;Short Energizing&quot;</a></center><br>

<p>I leave the viewer with one lasting thought from &quot;The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock,&quot; a well-known T.S. Eliot poem written in 1915 <a href="refrnc.html#25M">(25M)</a>.</p>

<blockquote><i>And indeed there will be a time<br>To wonder, &quot;Do I dare?&quot; and, &quot;Do I dare?&quot;<br>Time to turn back and desced the stair,<br>With a bald spot in the middle of my hair...
<dl>
<dd>Do I dare
<dd>Disturb the universe?
</dl>
</i>
</blockquote>

<br>
<font size=4><p>When you have the chance to change the world for the betterment of humanity, dare to disturb the status quo.  But the key to this is education.

