<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Nuclear Waste</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" LINK="#0510CC" VLINK="#CC0E0E" 
ALINK="#CC0609">
<center><H1>Hyphen-Man's Nuclear Waste Site!</H1>
<IMG SRC = "rancel2.jpg"></center>
<p></p>
<center><IMG SRC = "bar_neon.gif></center>
<P>Welcome to <A HREF = "http://www.cen.uiuc.edu/~d-chang/">Hyphen-Man's</A> 
Nuclear Waste Site!  If you've ever wondered 
how Hyphie got the hy-phen in his name, and how his super-hyphenating 
powers came into being after he mistook a beaker of radioactive waste for 
a glass of Tang,  you're certainly not going to find the answers here.  
Hyphie is too embarrassed to talk about it.  </P>

<P>Instead, you'll find in this page some interesting stuff about nuclear 
waste and also, some links to other cool nuclear sites on the Web. 
</P>

<P>Nuclear waste disposal is a very controversial issue. There are more 
than 100 nuclear power plants in the United States generating nearly twenty 
percent of our country's electricity, and some of them have been in 
operation for almost 30 years.  A significant amount of nuclear waste has 
already been generated, and although the total volume of nuclear waste 
generated in a year is small compared to the generation of other poisonous 
wastes, that waste must still be permanently and safely disposed of.  So 
far, almost all nuclear waste is kept in temporary storage facilities at 
the nuclear plant where it was generated. </P>  

<P>Finding a permanent method of disposing nuclear waste is one of the 
most pressing environmental issues facing us today.  In more ways 
than one, nuclear waste disposal is a very hot topic.  The problems of 
nuclear waste disposal are both scientific and social in nature.  </P>

<P>From the scientific perspective, nuclear waste is very difficult to 
handle.  New technologies and advancements in waste treatment processes 
make waste disposal safer, but still not absolutely and indisputably 
safe.  Not only do scientists have to worry about treating and containing 
radioactive wastes, they also have to find sites which will not allow 
the wastes to spread even under the worst circumstances.</P>    

<P>From the social perspective, nobody wants to have radioactive waste 
dumped into their backyard.  The phrase "nuclear waste" is bound to 
conjure up images of three-eyed fishes and Teenage Mutant Ninja 
Turtles.  Radiation is very scary since it is invisible and its effects 
are long-term.  Some scientists may feel that public opinion against 
nuclear waste and nuclear power is based more on fear than fact, but 
there are still many good reasons for being wary.</P>  

<P><img src = "question.gif"><A HREF="nuce201b.html">Hold on, just what 
exactly is nuclear waste?</A></P>
<P>

<img src = "eyesline.gif">
