</DOCHDR>
<title> THE  SMALL SCALE HYDROELECTRIC HOME PAGE</title>
<body background="58.jpg">
<h1><center> WELCOME TO THE SMALL SCALE HYDROELECTRIC HOME PAGE</center></h1>
<hr>
<center><img src="waterfall.jpg"><p>
BY <a href="index.html">DAVID JENNINGS</a></center>
<hr>
<a name=contents>
<h2> Table of Contents</h2>
<dl>
<dd><a href=#motivation>Motivation Behind this Page</a>
<dd><a href=#basic>Basic Principle</a>
<dd><a href=#how>How Does Hydropower Work?</a>
<dd><a href=#history>Hydro - History</a>
<dd><a href=#why>Why Small Scale?</a>
<dd><a href=#advantages>Advantages to Small Scale Hydro</a>
<dd><a href=#disadvantages>Disadvantages to Small Scale Hydro</a>
<dd><a href=#turbines>Hydraulic Turbines</a>
<dd><a href=#license>Licensing of a Hydroelectric Plant</a>
<dd><a href=#conclusions>Conclusions</a>
</dl></a>
<hr>
<a name=motivation>
<h2>Motivation Behind this Page</h2>
<p>Why would anyone want to write a homepage on small scale hydroelectric power?  Well, first of all, I am required to create a homepage, which relates to course material, for my<a href="http://www.uiuc.edu/admin_manual/Courses/C_D/latest/NUCE201.html"> Nuclear Engineering 201, Energy Systems</a> class (If you would like to see the NucE 201 class homepage click <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">here</a>).  My reasons for choosing small scale hydropower specifically are quite simple.  Hydroelectric power is practical and it is economical.  For these two reasons, I think any engineer with the desire and some entrepreneurial flare could make a small fortune through small scale hydroelectric power generation.  An example will better illustrate my point:
<p>Let's say an aspiring millionare builds a small scale hydroelectric plant.  The plant's capacity is 10 MW or 10,000 KW of electricity.  Small scale hydropower is generally defined as any system generating under 30 MW, so this is a valid generating output.
<p>(10,000 KW)x(365 days)x(24 hr/1 day) = 87,600,000 KWh
<p>Each year the hydroelectric plant will produce 87,600,000 KWh of electricity which the young entrepreneur can sell to the local power authority who will make this electricity available to the public through the grid.  If the power authority buys this electricity at three cents per kilowatt-hour, our friend will take in:
<p>(87,600,000 KWh)x($.03/KWh) = $2,628,000 each year
<p>Typical wholesale prices for electric power are around 5 to six cents per kilowatt-hour, so keep in mind that 3 cents is a lower bound.  In all likelihood, he would receive more, but for the sake of proving my  point, let's keep the estimate conservative.
<p>He should begin to see a profit as soon as his initial capital costs are covered, which shouldn't take long at all since he's bringing in over $2.5 million each year.  He won't have to worry about operation costs either.  Operation and maintenance costs of hydroelectric facilities are small. 
<p> While this example does not include all of the intricaces involved in developing a hydroelectric power plant, it does illustrate that there is money to be made in hydroelectricity.  If your feeling a bit adventurous and would like to see some information on how you can go about obtaining the materials necessary to build your own small scale hydroelectric system, check out the hydroelectric power information in the <a href="http://www.nando.net/prof/eco/aee5.html">Alternative Energy Engineering 1995 Design Guide and Catalog.</a>  Let's remember, however, the motivation behind small scale hydroelectric power is not purely monetary.  Check out the <a href=#advantages>advantages</a> section of this page for more reasons to use small hydro.
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a> 
<hr>
<a name=basic>
<h2> Basic Principle</h2>
<p>The unending natural process resulting from the action of the sun's radiant energy on the earth's atmosphere, called the hydrologic cycle, provides a continual renewable supply of water on the earth's surface.  A portion of this water returns to the sea during the cycle in the form of surface water runoff.   It disposes of a definite potential energy as the runoff flows to lower altitudes which can be harnessed and used as a viable energy source.
<hr>
<center><img src="cycle.jpg"><p></center>
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=how>
<h2> How Does Hydropower Work?</h2>
<p>Hydropower systems use the energy in flowing water to produce electricity or mechanical energy.  The water flows via channel or penstock to a waterwheel or turbine where it strikes the bucket of the wheel, causing the shaft of the waterwheel or turbine to rotate.  When generating electricity, the rotating shaft, which is connected to an alternator or generator, converts the motion of the shaft into electrical energy.  This electrical energy may be used directly, stored in batteries, or inverted to produce utility-quality electricity.  The amount of power a specific hydropower site can produce depends on its head, or the height of the falling water, and the flow rate.  The amount of head determines the useful potential energy of a site--remember PE = mgh.  Why don't we see an example? 
<p>Hydro Power Example:
<p>Water falls a distance (h) of 90 meters through an 80% efficient turbine (Modern turbines have efficiency ratings in the 90% to 95% range, so 80% is a conservaitve estimate) at a flow rate (Q) of 1 liter/sec.
<p>1 liter/sec = 1 kg/sec for water
<p>Potential Energy = PE....mass = m...acceleration due to gravity =g
<p>Power = mgh/t = (m/t)(gh) = Qgh
<p>Power = (1 kg/sec)(9.81 m/s^2)(90 m) = 882.9 W
<p>At 80% efficiency...Power = (.80)(882.9 W) = 706.3 W
<p>This would amount to 6187 kWh of electricity each year.  Wowsers!!!
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=history>
<h2> Hydro - History</h2>
<h4>The Origins of Hydropower</h4>
<p>Water power has contributed to the development of mankind since Biblical times.  References to the use of waterwheels for milling, pumping, and other functions date back to 300 B.C. in Greece, although they were probably in use long before that time.  In the years between these early uses of the waterwheel and the onset of the Industrial Revolution, running water and wind were the only sources of mechanical power, other than that generated by animals, available.  Improvements in power recovery from flowing water were steadily introduced as exemplified by the sophisticated waterworks designed in the 1600s for the palace of Versailles outside Paris, France.  This system had a capacity equivilant to an estimated 56 kW of power.
<h4>Early Hydro Developments</h4>
<p>Water power systems, and eventually hydroelectric generating plants, were developed from attempts at improving the efficiency of the waterwheel.  Much of the early research took place in France because at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution, France, unlike many nations did not have access to large coal deposits.  The French relied heavily on their water resources to generate the energy needed for industrial expansion.  In fact, waterpower is still called<i> houille blanche,</i> or white coal, in France.
<p>Much theoretical work was done during this period by mathematicians and engineers such as Bernard Forest de Belidor, John Smeaton, Jean Victor Ponceler, Leonhard Euler, Clarde Burdin, and Benoit Fourneyron.  Their work resulted in significant improvements in turbine efficiency and laid the ground work for the development of modern turbines of the Francis, Kaplan, and Pelton type.  As an example of the progress achieved, the original vertical-mid turbine designed by Belidor attained an efficiency of 15 to 20 percent.  By the mid 1850s this rose to 60 to 70 percent.  The Francis and Kaplan turbines, which are the modern counterparts of the Belidor turbine, now achieve efficiencies of 90 to 95 percent.
<h4>The Birth of Hydroelectricity</h4>
<p>During the 1870s electricity was introduced as a popular source of energy to the public thanks to Thomas Edison and the dynamo.  Not too long after that the dynamo was coupled with the waterwheel and the technology of hydroelectricity was born.  The first hydroelectric unit in the United States is reported to have been a 12.5 kW plant installed in 1882 on the Fox River at Appleton, Wisconsin.
<h4>Shift to Large Scale</h4> 
<p>With the development of high voltage transmission lines in the early part of the twentieth century, a shift occured from small scale plants serving local electricity markets to large scale plants feeding into extesive distribution grids.  Large hydroelectric projects like the <a href="http://www.vegas.com/vegas/outdoors>Hoover Dam</a> (See figure below), Parker Dam, Davis Dam, and Glen Canyon Dam on the Colorado River; <a href="http://www.owt.com/users/chubbard/gcdam/index.html>Grand Coule Dam</a>, <a href="http://www.npd.usace.army.mil/npp-op/bonneville.html>Bonneville Dam</a>, and Chief Joseph Dam on the Columbia River; and the entire Tenesee Valley Authority hydropower system have made an enormous impact on the electrical generation capacity of the U.S. Thermal power plants fired by fossil fuels also experienced this large scale trend.  Large scale plants, both hydroelectric and thermal, benefit from economies of scale.  That means it is cheaper per unit of power produced to operate a larger plant than it is a smaller one because of the large capital investments incurred in building either a large or small plant.
<hr>
<center><img src="dam.gif">
<p>A spectacular view of the Hoover Dam on the Colorado River</center>
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=why>
<h2>Why Small Scale?</h2>
<p>Hydroelectricity provides the U.S. with 7% of its total electricity demand.  1.87 Q of hydroelectric energy is produced by a small number of large dams.  0.63 Q of hydroelectric energy is produced by 1614 small dams. Why don't we build more large dams--Electricity plants operate under economies of scale, right?  Although we've only tapped 30% of what's available for hydroelectric power, almost all of the possible large sites have already been used.  We must turn to small-scale hydroelectric.
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=advantages>
<h2>Advantages to Small Scale Hydro</h2>
<p>The advantages of small scale hydropower, according to Ellis Armstrong, the former head of the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation, are that<b> Small Scale Hydro:</b>
<p><ol>
<p><li>is a<b> non-consumptive</b> generator of electrical energy, utilizing a <b>renewable resource</b> which is made continually available through the hydrologic cycle by the energy of the sun.
<p><li>is essentially <b>non-polluting</b> and releases no heat.  Adverse environmental impacts are negligible and, for small installations, may be totally eliminated.
<p><li>plants can be <b>designed and built within one or two years' time</b>.  Licensing requirements are minimal, equiment is readily available, and construction procedures are well known.
<p><li>plants require some type of water control, up to and including full regulation of watershed discharge.  They are thus an important element in the multipurpose utilization of water resources and can reduce potential flood damage.  Where storage facilities are involved, <b>floodwaters are retained</b> and can be better directed to agricultural production, river regulation, improved navigation, fish and wildlife protection, recreation, municipal use and better control of waste water.
<p><li>in remote areas using relatively simple technology can be a catalyst in mobilizing productive resources and creating <b>enhanced economic opportunities</b> for local residents.
<p><li>is a <b>reliable resource</b> within the hydrologic limitations of the site.  The relative simplicity of hydraulic machinery makes energy instantly available as needed.  Since no heat is involved, equipment has a <b>long life</b> and malfunctions are rare.
<p><li>is characerized by <b>reliability and flexibility</b> of operation, including fast start-up and shut-down in response to rapid changes in demand.  It thus becomes a valuable part of any large electrical system, increasing overall economy, efficiency, and reliability.
<p><li>has an <b>excellent peak-power capability.</b>  While approximately four units of energy input are required for three units of output, the input is low-cost hydraulic energy and the output is high value electrical energy.  In a large eletrical system, the alternative for handling peak loads may be utilization or costly expansion of old and relatively inefficient thermal units
<p><li>technology is <b>well-developed and proven</b>, with turbine efficiencies running in the <b>90 percent</b> range.  Small units ranging from a few kilowatts to larger ones of several megawatts have been in operation since the turn of the century.  While the equipment must be adapted to the specific site for greatest efficiency, its performance will generally live up to manufacturers' claims.
<p><li>facilities have a <b>long life.</b>  As a rule, dams and control works will peform for a century or more with little maintenence.
<p><li>requires few operating personnel.  Some small-scale installations are operated entirely by remote control.  Freedom from fuel dependence, together with the long life of equipment, make hydroelectric power installations <b>resistant to inflation.</b>
<p><li>development can make maximum use of local materials and labor.  When compared to thermal facilities, small hydro usually provides more <b>local employment</b> in the construction of civil works.
<p><li>resources remain <b>untapped</b>, especially in developing countries where less than seven percent of potential has been developed.  In some countries the figure is less than two percent.
<p><li><b>economic feasibility</b> is improving when compared to other energy sources that use finite fuels. With more realistic methodologies for economic evaluation, including full recognition of the value of non-consumptive water use, freedom from fuel dependence and minimum environmental impact, small hydropower has become increasingly desirable.
<p><li>potential in the industrialized countries can be developed to augment hydropower capacity at existing powerhouses and dams.  The possibility of <b>retrofits</b> and <b>additional turbines</b> and generators makes the <b>upgrading</b> of present installations attractive.
</ol>
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=disadvantages>
<h2>Disadvantages to Small Scale Hydro</h2>
<p>Aside from the high capital costs up front of building a hydroelectric facility, the primary disadvantage of hydroelectric is its environmental effects.
<p>Hydroelectric sites create several problems for fish, salmon in particular:
<p><ul>
<li>Dams present a migratory barrier.
<li>Fish can be killed in the turbines (especially young ones swimming downstream).
<li>Spilling of water over spillways can result in supersaturation of the water with gases from the air.  The gas bubbles, which are absorbed into fish tissue, may cause damage and ultimately kill the fish.
<li>Reservoirs have limited natural flow in the summer.  Water becomes stratified, with warmer water collecting at the surface and cooler water lying at the bottom.  Because the bottom water is isolated from aeration, it loses its oxygen.  Many species of fish cannot live in this environment due to the temperature and low oxygen content.</ul>
<p>Also, silt which would have naturally traveled to the mouth of the river and out to sea, builds up steadily at the wall of the dam.  In addition, tree clearing from the development of hydroelectric dams can result in soil erosion and landslides, also causing a buildup of sediments that clog up streams.
<p>The basic problem with is that when the hydrology of a river is changed through a hydroelectric project, major habitat changes can occur.  No matter how many studies one does, there is no accurate way to determine all of the repercusions a hydroelectric plant will have on Mother Nature.
<p>For more information on the environmental effects of hydroelectric power and what can be done to reduce those effects, check out <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev26-34/text/hydmain.html">Hydropower:  Licensed to Protect the Environment</a> sponsored by ORNL.
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=turbines>
<h2>Hydraulic Turbines</h2>
<p>Hydraulic turbines are used to derive mechanical energy from the potential enegy of water.  These hydraulic turbines are generally of two fundamental designs, <b>"impulse" </b>turbines and <b>"reaction" </b>turbines.
<h3>Impulse Turbines</h3>
<p>The most commonly used impulse type is known as the Pelton turbine.  It is generally used in higher head installations - normally in the range of 200 feet to several thousand feet.  The production of mechanical energy with a Pelton turbine is from the force of water passing through nozzles and striking on cups arranged on the periphery of a runner, or wheel, which causes the runner to rotate.  The runner is fixed on a shaft and the rotational motion of the turbine is transmitted by the shaft to the generator.  By adjusting the flow through the nozzles, a Pelton turbine operates at a high efficiency over a wide range of head and flow conditions.  Pelton turbines can be designed with either a vertical or horizontal shaft arrangement.
<p><center><img src="pelton.gif">
<p>A basic example of the Pelton Turbine</center>
<p><h3>Reaction Turbines</h3>
<p>The most common reaction turbines are of the Francis and propellor types.  Francis turbines are generally used in a head range of 25 to 1,000 feet.  A Francis turbine contains a runner which has water passages through it formed by curved vanes, or blades.  As the water passes through the runner and over the curved surfaces it causes rotaion of the runner.  The rotational motion is transmitted by a shaft to the generator.  A Francis turbine operates efficiently over a fairly narrow range of head and flow conditions for which it was designed.  Adjustable guide vanes, or wicket gates, are generally added to control the angle of the flow into the runner, thereby increasing the range of head and flow conditions over which the turbine will operate efficiently.  As with Pelton turbines, Francis turbines can be designed with either a vertical or horizontal shaft arrangement.
<p><center><img src="francis.gif">
<p>An example of a Francis Turbine</center>
<p>A propellor turbine contains a runner which has blades similar to a propellor used to drive a ship and is generally used in a head range of less than 100 feet.  As water passes over the curved propellor blades it causes rotation of the shaft to which the blades are attached.  As with Francis turbines, a propellor turbine with fixed blades operates efficiently over a fairly narrow set of head and flow conditions.  A propellor turbine can be designed with blades whose pitch is adjustable and/or with wicket gates to control the angle of the flow into the blades.  A propellor unit equipped with both is called a Kaplan turbine and operates at a high efficiency over a wide range of head and flow conditions.  Propellor turbines can be designed in a variety of configurations a shaft arrangements.
<p>For more information on hydraulic turbines click <a href="http://www.npd.usace.army.mil/hdc/hd-units.html>here.</a>
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=license>
<h2>Licensing of a Hydroelectric Plant</h2>
<p>Water resources have long been considered a natural resource whose development should consider the needs of the public on a regional or national basis.  To ensure that all hydroelectric power potential is developed with the needs of the public considered, the Federal government requires that all non-Federal hydroelectric developments be licensed for construction and operation.  The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) is the agency with the responsibility for such licensing.  The FERC has a very lengthy and structured process for applying for and receipt of a license for hydroelectric power plants.
<p>The initial step in the process is submittal to the FERC of an "Application for a Preliminary Permit" to study a potential hydropower site.
<p>When the FERC has awarded a Preliminary Permit, the permittee has a specified period of time in which to study the site and prepare an application for a license to construct and operate the project.  Normally, the term for a Preliminary Permit for a small-scale hydroelectric project is 2 to 3 years.  The holder of a Preliminary Permit has preference in terms of applocation for a license.
<p>An application for license to the FERC must address all legal and institutional considerations; such as legality of the applicant to produce and sell power and energy, agreements for access to and use of the hydropower site, identification of a market for the output, demonstration of project financial feasibility, compliance with all state and Federal agencies for permits and or other requirements (can be extremely difficult and lengthy), and compliance with the provisions of the National Environmental Protection Act.  After a review period in which all affected ans intrested state and Federal agencies are consulted, the FERC will decide on granting a license which entitles the licensee to construct and operate the hydroelectric facility for 50 years.  After that period, applocation for renewal of the license can be made.
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<hr>
<a name=conclusions>
<h2>Conclusions</h2>
<p>By now you know that small scale hydropower is attractive because unlike other generating sources, it does not consume water, heat water in streams, or contribute to air pollution.  You also know hydroelectric plants have the ability to start quickly and make changes in power output, which is particularly suitable for carrying peak loads.  Unscheduled outages of hydroelectric plants are less frequent than at thermal plants and down time for overhaul is of short duration.  In some cases, hydroelectric power developments also provide other water resource benefits such as flood control, recreation, water supply, water quality management, and fish and wildlife enhancement.
<p>"That's all fine and dandy," you say, "but is this really a viable energy source?" 
<p> You're darn right it is! 
<p> Hydroelectric supplied six times more power to the United States than all of the other renewables combined in 1993. 
<p> In 1992 the total remaining hydroelectric capacity in the US was estimated at around 73,200 MW.  Total developed capacity was 73,500 MW, which means we've only tapped about half of our potential.  Most of the potential sites fall under the small scale hydro category.
<p>There is an estimated 1,300 MW that can be gained from recommissioning retired small scale hydro sites.
<p>In 1985, 143 non-federal hydroplants began operation.  Of those plants, 126 had capacities of under 10 MW.
<p>The numbers don't lie.  The potential exists to expand our nation's use of small scale hydroelectric power.  It is a proven and reliable source of energy.  Whether or not we take advantage of it is entirely up to us.  
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href=#contents>Table of Contents</a></a>
<p>I would be delighted to hear your comments and criticisms.  E-mail me at <a href="mailto:jennings@uiuc.edu">Davey's Mailbox</a> 'cause I love to get mail (especially from you!!!)














