<HEAD>
<TITLE> Abbott Home Page</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h2> ABBOTT POWER PLANT HOME PAGE</h2></center>
<center><img src="appview.gif"></center>

 The Abbott Power Plant supplies all of the steam required by the <a href = "http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois</a> as well as almost a third of the electrical power demand.  This page will attempt to provide basic information on the plant as well as answer questions such as "What are those short concrete things that are so nice to walk by in the winter?" <p>

 
<h3> History</h3>
The power plant is named after William Lamont Abbott, an 1884 mechanical <a href="http://www.engr.uiuc.edu">engineering</a> graduate of the <a href = "http://www.uiuc.edu">University of Illinois</a>.  He became an expert in electrical power production and distribution, as well as in the use of coal for energy.  He was the chief operating engineer for <a href="http://www.ceco.com/">Commonwealth Edison</a> between 1898 and 1935, when he retired.  In 1905 he was elected to the University Board of Trustees where he served 18 years, 14 of which as President.  When the Washington Award Commision recognized him with their engineering award he was called "the dean of the electric light and power industry."<p>

Abbott Power Plant entered service in 1941 as a coal plant, replacing a smaller plant on the engineering campus.  Since then the plant has undergone many changes and additions, including updates to burn fuel oil, natural gas, as well as inprovements in the coal burning capabilities.<p>

<h3>General information</h3>
Abbott Power Plant is a cogeneration plant.  The purpose of the plant is to produce both steam and electricity.  The primary purpose of the plant is to produce steam.  This steam is used to heat all the buildings on campus, cook food in the dorms, and heat water.  Some steam is also used for research as well as to run air conditioning units in the summer.  The steam is distributed through 35 miles of pipe in over 7 miles of tunnels under the campus.  The little concrete structures all over campus that release heat are the tops of ventilation shafts for the tunnels.  This is especialy important since every foot of the tunnels is walked each week to check for leaks or problems.<p>

    
The electricity generated is a byproduct of the steam.  Currently the plant generates approximately one-third of the demand of the university.  The remainder is purchased from <a href="http://www.illinova.com/">Illinois Power</a>.  During high demand times in the summer however, Illinois Power may ask the plant to operate at peak capacity.  The excess steam is then condensed.  The plant uses both Illinois coal from a mine near Sprinfield and natural gas to generate steam, and has the capability to burn fuel oil in reserve.<p>


<h3> Technical Information</h3>
The plant has a peak capacity of 30 Megawatts.  There are seven steam turbines. Five are 3000 kw low pressure variable extraction units, and two are 7500kw high pressure variable extraction turbines that can only be run off the coal boilers. There are six boilers total.  Three produce 325 psi steam at 700 F at a rate of 175,000 lb/r.  All of these three operate on either gas or fuel oil.  There are also two 150,00 lb/h boilers and a 200,000 lb/h boiler that produce 875 psi steam at 760 F. These three burn coal only.<p> 

 
The coal for the boilers is delivered by truck from a mine near Springfield.  About 9-11 trucks arrive each day with 25 tons of coal.  Currently, $27.30 will buy you one ton of coal.  The gas is dilivered by pipeline.  The plant generates electricity at a cost of 2.75 cents per kilowatt-hour.  The university pays 5.25 cents per kw-hr through its deal with Illinois Power Co.  A regular consumer pays about 11 cents.<p>  


<h3> Generation Proccess</h3>
The heat from the <a href="http://www.ems.psu.edu/~pisupati/EFRC.html">combustion</a> of the coal or gas boils water inside the steam drum, which is inside the boiler.  The boilers at Abbott use mechanical stokers, meaning the coal is "thrown" into the boiler by a spinning bladed drum.  25% of the coal is burned in the air by this old yet practical method.  A more modern coal boiler would probably use a <a href="http://www.fluent.com/applications/FLUENT/627/ScaleBoiler627.html">fluidized bed.</a>  Next, the steam is separated from the water by a cyclone, and is then superheated to close to 900 F.  This dry steam is then sent to the turbine where work is done and the energy is extracted. The turbine spins the generator.  Steam can be extracted at two places in the turbine, and is sent to campus as either high or low pressure steam.  At the buildings on campus the heat form the steam is extracted, and it is then sent back to the plant as a condensate, or water.  This water is then checked for purity (to avoid fouling the boiler) and then reentered in the cycle. 

<h3>Emmisions controls</h3>
There are strict <a href="http://www.eia.doe.gov/neic/press14.html">government regulations</a> concerning emmisions with which the plant must comply.  The most important one concerns Sulpher Dioxide, SO2, a gas that reacts in the atmosphere to create acid rain.  The exhaust gases from cumbustion go through many steps before they are released into the air.  First, they are used to prheat the water and air entering the boiler.  Next the exhaust gases past through the precipitator, where particles in the gas are ionized.  These charged particles are then attractred to a positive or negative plate, where they collect.  If you ever are near the plant you might hear the plate rappers knocking the particles off the plates to be collected.  Next, the gases enter the scrubber, where the SO2 removal takes place.  The high level of scrubber technology allows the plant to burn high-sulpher Illinois coal.<p>

The first part of the scrubber is the prescrubber.  In the prescrubber a water mist cools the flue gas and removes any remaining particles.  After this step the gases enter the jet bubbler reactor. Here the gas is bubbled through a slurry of finely crushed limestone and water.  The limestone or calcium carbonate (CaCO3) reacts with the sulpher dioxide to yield calcium sulphate (CaSO4), commonly known as gypsum. The gypsum is then siphoned off, filtered from the water, and then dried.  The gypsum is then sent back to the mine along with all the ash to be disposed of.<p>       The jet bubbler reactor at Abbott is very effective because it is also a forced air oxidation reactor.  This means that air is bubbled into the reactor also, as a catalyst, to cause almost complete limestone usage.  After all this, the So2 free flue gas is reheated and sent out the stack.  The large puffy clouds seen coming out of the stack on a cold day are nothing but condensed water.  Very little particulate material is sent into the atmosphere.<P> 

One unique point about Abbott's jet bubbler reactor is that the large tank of the reactor is made of fiberglass.  This was an improvement on the origional Japanese design.  Steel tanks were corroding due to the acidic ph of 4 inside the tank.  A U.S. company spun the tank in two parts right next to the plant.  The use of the fiberglass tank at Abbott was studied, and later a report was published.  The scrubber design at Abbott has been very successful, the only disadvantages being a need for higher quality limestone and little more electricity for operation.<p>
 
<h3> Energy and Coal Related links</h3>
Here is a link concerning anything you ever wanted to know about <a href = "http://www.newcastle.edu.au/department/gl/cfkd/undp.htm">coal.</a><br
>  

This is a very interesting Oak Ridge National Laboratory page comparing radiation released from <a href= "http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev26-34/text/colmain.html">coal and nuclear power</a>.<br>


This page has links from around the world all related to different types of <a href = "http://www.ecn.nl/eii/main.html">energy.</a><br>

<a href="http://www.dcet.csiro.au/">Coal and Energy Technology</a><br>

Argonne National Lab <a href="http://www.anl.gov/PCS/pcshome.html">premium coal samples.</a><br>
<a href="http://www.access.digex.net/~miner/colminrs.html">United Mine Workers of America</a>--explains the job of a modern coal miner.<br>  

University of Florida cogeneration plant. <a href="http://gatorpwr.che.ufl.edu/cogen/general/cogen_booklet/">Gator Power</a>.<br>

<a href="http://home.ptd.net/~sjrubin/pubutil.htm">Public Utilities Home Page</a>.<br>

For information related to the energy industry read <a href = "news:sci.energy">sci.energy.</a><p>


  

