<title>Mission to Mars Fact Sheet</title>
<body bgcolor=#000066 text=#ffffff vlink=#ff0000 link=#ffff00>

<center><h1>
NASA Space Technology: Nuclear Propulsion Fact Sheet</h1>
December 1991</center><p>
The mission to Mars proposed by the President as the ultimate goal of the nation's Space Exploration Initiative involves travel across vast distances. Under many of the mission plans being considered, nuclear propulsion offers advantages over engines that use only chemical fuels such as liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen.<p>A Mars-bound spacecraft using nuclear engines would require smaller amounts of fuel and associated storage tanksQweight that first has to be launched into Earth orbit. Nuclear propulsion also gives mission planners more flexibility in choosing launch dates because of its increased power and fuel efficiency compared to all-chemical systems. <p>One concept, nuclear thermal propulsion, would use a nuclear reactor to heat propellants before they are expelled through a rocket nozzle. Nuclear thermal systems have about twice as much energy per pound of propellant as chemical engines.<p>Spacecraft can journey between Earth and Mars only when the planets are properly aligned. The amount of fuel and the time required for the voyage can vary dramatically depending on the planets' relative positions. Nuclear thermal propulsion would permit space vehicles using that technology make the trip much more economicallyQand at more of the available opportunitiesQthan craft that use only chemical engines.<p>The astronauts will be shielded from radiation generated by the nuclear reactor that provides propulsive thrust. They will also have sufficient protection against the intergalactic cosmic radiation that is a major medical hazard to human interplanetary spaceflight.<p>For  cargo-only missions, where a quick transit time is not as important, nuclear electric propulsion technology may apply. This type of engine produces very low thrust levels, but also uses only small amounts of propellant during an interplanetary trip. The main benefit of nuclear electric propulsion is that less fuel resulting in a lower launch weight must be hauled from Earth to orbit for the voyage to Mars.<p>Recent studies have also suggested that a combination of nuclear electric and chemical propulsion could produce short Earth-Mars trip times and thus be applicable to human planetary missions as well. Chemical rocket engines would power the spacecraft out of Earth orbit and the nuclear electric system would take over for the cruise to Mars.<p>The idea of using nuclear propulsion for space travel is not new. NASA played a key role in the ROVER and NERVA nuclear propulsion programs in the 1960's and early 1970's.  That effort stopped in 1972 because of  shifts in funding priorities and a decision not to pursue a Mars mission the main justification for NERVA at that time. <p>NASA is now defining propulsion options for the Space Exploration Initiative and nuclear propulsion is a leading candidate. The agency established a Nuclear Propulsion Office at Lewis Research Center, Cleveland, in 1991 to lead the technology development activities for NASA in cooperation with Department of Energy laboratories.	<p>NASA will study possible mission plans for some time;  a decision to develop  flight hardware will probably be made between 1995 and the year 2000.  Non-nuclear technology development will take place at Lewis and other NASA centers, industry facilities and at universities.  Nuclear technology development and system testing will take place at a Department of Energy laboratory.<p>Safety is the number one priority in NASA's nuclear propulsion program. Inter-agency safety teams will review and approve ground test facilities and mission plans. Every precaution will be taken to ensure that there is no negative impact on the environment as a result of the testing.  The site selection process will include safety analyses,  environmental impact assessments and public reviews and strict compliance with environmental regulations.<p>There will be no radiation hazard from the reactor during launch or assembly of the spacecraft in Earth orbit, because the reactor will not be turned on (no fission products will exist until the reactor is started in space).  When the spacecraft is ready to leave for Mars, the astronaut crew will be in a shielded module.  Radiation from the reactor source will be below acceptable limits for radiation workers and well below levels from intergalactic cosmic radiation.<p>When the engine system is no longer needed, it will be put into a nuclear safe orbit where the reactor will remain while its radioactive components decay to a safe level possibly as long as several hundred years. Current NASA mission plans recommend disposal of space reactors into an orbit around the Sun, where there is no chance that they will reenter Earth's atmosphere.

<p>
