<title>What Went Wrong?</title> <p><b><u><font color="#bb00ff"><font
size=+3>What Went Wrong?</font></font></b></u></p> <hr>
<p><fontcolor=#"000000"><font size=+1>Things started to go wrong at four
o'clock in the morning (the reactor was running at full power!), when a
feedwater pump stopped working.  An auxiliary pump was then started and
the reactor was <a href="scram.html">scram</a>med, which caused the
pressure in the reactor vessel to rise because te heat removal in the
steam generators was not fast enough.  To lower the pressure, a relief
valve was then opened, but it failed to close when the pressure returned
to normal.  In the secondary loop, no feedwater was reaching the steam
generator since another valve was closed when it should have been open. 
The warning light which came on to warn the operator of the open valve
malfunctioned.  The reactor primary coolant circuit continued to blow off
water and steam through the relief valve into the containment building. 
Because the operator thought the valve was open, he turned on the <a 
href="eccs.html">ECCS</a>,
which normally would have been a good thing had the valve been closed, but
since it was open, radioactive water continued to be pumped into the
building, and because the water continued to evaporate without being
replaced with new water, the cooling system wasn't working, and a partial
core meltdown occured.  Finally, after two hours, the relief valve was
closed, yet by this time, the core had been exposed.  The fuel rods had
been ruptured, so fissile materials (products of fission), were released
into the building. Some radioactive gases were released into the
atmosphere.</font.</font></p> <hb><hr> <p><a
href="mailto:browde@students.uiuc.edu">Shana
Browde</a>browde@students.uiuc.edu</p>

