<h4><CENTER>THE IMPACT OF DRILLING ALONG THE ANWR COASTAL PLAIN</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
The oil industry claims that it can develop the Arctic Refuge in an
"environmentally sensitive" manner, pointing to Prudhoe Bay. Yet there, oil
spills have averaged 500 annually, and permitted emissions of air pollutants
exceed the total emissions of at least six states.  12,650 acres on the coastal
plain would be directly affected by development under a full-leasing scenario.
Under such a scenario, the following facilities would be needed:<p>
<ul><li>50 to 60 gravel drill sites, 20 to 35 acres each 40 to 50
        wellheads per drill site<br>
<li>50 to 60 waste pits, 13 million gallon capacity each<br>
<li>3 central production facilities<br>
<li>1 to 3 sea water treatment plants<br>
<li>indeterminate mileage of water pipeline<br>
<li>3 or more airports<br>
<li>280 miles of main and spur roads<br>
<li>10 to 15 gravel excavation sites<br>
<li>100 to 150 miles of main oil pipeline<br>
<li>indeterminate mileage of connector oil pipeline<br>
<li>1 to 5 pump stations<br>
<li>2 to 3 marine facilities or ports<br>
<li>2 to 3 gravel causeways, 1to 4 miles long<br>
<li>2 or more solid waste disposal dumps<br>
<li>housing for 1,500 to 1,600 workers<br>
<li>sewage treatment facilities<br>
<li>administrative facilities <br>
<li>maintenance facilities<p>
</ul><A HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org/refuge/impact.html">[11]</A>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
All of these potential impacts threaten the willdlife which depends on the
continued uninterrupted wilderness ecosystem. Caribou, Raptors, Muskoxen, Moose, Dall
Sheep, Wolves, Arctic Foxes, Wolverines, Brown Bears, Polar Bears, Ringed
Seals, Bowhead and Gray Whales could all be affected by environmental damage
caused by exploration, as well as the Native people who depend on these
animals.
<P>
In addition, even tough many of the natives support oil drilling, all agree
that the development should not harm caribou, caribou calving grounds, polar
bears and all of the other animals listed above due to their dependence on them
for survival. Because the calving takes place in the summer months, natives
prefer that any exploration take place in the winter months.  Yet, if full
scale development is granted, it will be a year round deal, and the calving
grounds will definitely be disrupted.   In addition, Natives support the idea of
using Native guides for exploration crews to ensure the protection of
archeological, cultural and historical sites. [12]</h4>

<P>
<hr>
<P>
