<h3><CENTER> Are there any alternatives to the development of the ANWR Coastal
Plain?</CENTER></h3>
<P>
<P>
<HR>
<h4>
From the discussions and lecture topics in the UIUC <A
HREF="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201">Nuclear Engineering 201</A> class, we
see that there are numerous alternatives to developing the coastal plain of the
ANWR.  Simple energy conservation measures for general purpose usage could act
as a starting ground.  Yet, this probably will not be enough in itself. 
<P>
However, incorporating regulations such as higher standards for automotive fuel
economy in the 30 mpg range would, by the year 2020, save approximately twice
as much energy as the Department of Interior believes might be recovered from
the coastal plain.  According to World Watch Institute, United States
homeowners have as much energy loss through poorly insulated glass windows
annually as moves through the Trans-Alaska pipleline in a year. <A
HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org/refuge/alt.html">[13]</A>.
<P>
As stated in the previous page on <A HREF="back.html"> background about the
ANWR</A>, the expected recoverable oil would only add 0.4 percent to the
present world oil reserves, which doesnt seem like a whole lot.  This 0.4
percent is not going to solve the United States domestic oil supply situation,
especially if this estimate says that this recoverable amount is only enough
for 200 days worth of domestic consumption at the surrent rate.
<P>
Alternative energy sources need to be further investigated.  The use of solar
power, hydro-electric, wind, biomass, and geothermal are all technologies which
are being further developed in order to compete with the petro-fuels necessary
for the manufacture of electricity. In addition, other measures such as
fuel-cells for automobiles and enhanced engine efficiencies would greatly help solve a mojor portion of the
domestic oil supply problem.</h4>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<h5>
<p><a href=future.html>The Future of the ANWR</a>
<P>
<address><a href="mailto:m-duffy1@.uiuc.edu">m-duffy1@uiuc.edu</address>
