<h3><CENTER>What Lies Ahead for the ANWR?</CENTER></H3>
<P>
<P>
<HR>
<H4>
The US Department of Interior estimates that by developing the coastal plain of
the ANWR, the net economic benefits could reach as high as $325 billion.  In
addition this development could create as many as 735,000 jobs (estimate from
the private sector).
<P>
<hr><Center>
<img src="usa.gif">
</CENTER>
<P>
But what about all of the jobs which could be created if the solar energy
business or the fuel-cell industry were to boom?  
<P> 
What fate lies ahead for the animals and the Native poeple who depend on these
animals for their continued survival?  It is not fair for big business to come
and muscle out the people who have inhabited this land for over 12000 years
because there is a buck to be made.  From the estimates it is obvious that the
development of the coastal plain will not solve the domestic oil problem.
Furthermore, the driving factor seems to be the greed for profit, seeing that
the companies which pressure the development are also investigating selling the
oil overseas.  The cost of clean-up for all of the possible damage to the
environment has not been taken into account in any of the estimates, which goes
to show that the developing companies have no interest in the safekeeping of
the land, and are insensitive to the people and animals who live there.
<P>
Presently there has been no approval to develop the ANWR.  However, seeing that
Congress has included $1 billion in revenue from the area in its forecasted
budget,the issue is at hand.  An invaluable natural landscape and unique
wilderness area might be destroyed, we need to ask if it is worth it.
</h4>
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<h5>
<P>
<address><a href="mailto:m-duffy1@.uiuc.edu">m-duffy1@uiuc.edu</address>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER> 
<img src ="boo.gif">
</CENTER>
</h5>


