<h3><CENTER> A Little Bit of Background is in Order</h3></CENTER>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<h4>
Currently, the ANWR is the best hope for a continued large scale domestic oil
supply.  The United States Department of the Interior says that there is a 1 in
2 chance of finding 9.2 billion barrels of oil along the 125 mile coastal plain
of the ANWR.  However, other estimates say that there could be as few as 600
billion barrels of recoverable oil, and a recent article in <A HREF = "http://
www.igc.apc.org/audubon">Audubon magazine</A> cited the net recoverable 
oil from the coastal plain to be 0.4% of the worlds oil resources.  One of the 
problems in determining the accuracy of these estimates is that the sub-surface 
geology of the land is not fully understood.  The depths that the predicted oil
lies within is not known at present. 
Therefore, it is difficult to say which, if any, of the oil
would be economically feasible to recover and what quality the recoverable oil
would be.  In 1986, Chevron was granted the right to drill an exploratory well
in the area (not in the coastal plain though).  This is where the estimates for
the yield come from, yet since it was not on the plain, accurate measures are
hard to determine. Usually a 2-4% chance of finding recoverable oil is
justification for further exploration,<A HREF
="http://alaska.alaskan.com/anwr/anwr_background.html">[1]</A>  yet in the case of the coastal plain of
the ANWR, we need to address the question of whether it is worth it to cause
severe impact to the environment and the fragile ecosystem that has existed
without disruption for thousands of years.
<hr>
<P>
The only permanent settlement on the ANWR coastal plain is the Village of
Kaktovik, inhabited by 220 Inupiat Native residents.  These people are familiar
with the effects of oil exploration and production, due to the development of
the Prudhoe Bay oil fields 120 miles west of the ANWR coastal plain.  The
Kaktovik people enjoy many of the benefits provided by the development,
including jobs, money, electricity, improved schools, a fire station, and a
medical clinic.  Yet, they are not willing to sacrifice the rich heritage that
provided them with subsistence for so many years - the natural wilderness that
provides the animals such as caribou for meals, and the presently
uncontaminated water which provides whale, fish and water foul for meals and
utilities also. <A HREF
="http://alaska.alaskan.com/anwr/anwr_background.html">[2]</A> 
<P>
<hr>
<P>
In addition, the ANWR is also home to the Arctic Village, a 125 person village
of Gwich'in Athabaskan Natives, as well as 7000 other natives which inhabit
areas within the ANWR continental shelf.  These people have inhabited this area for over
12000 years and have depended on the natural resources that the land provides
such as the caribou and bears that inhabit the ANWR. <A HREF 
="http://alaska.alaskan.com/anwr/anwr_background.html">[3]</A> 
<P>
Even though these natives depend on the resources provided by the land,
suprisingly enough, Natives support the proposed drilling along the coastal
plain of the ANWR. In a vote conducted in June of 1996, a committee of Natives
supported the movement 19-9 to develop the coastal plain.<A HREF
="http://alaska.alaskan.com/anwr/anwr_background.html">[4]</A>
This support is strictly based upon the premise that the development can be
done without significant impact to the land.  It should also be noted that this
support comes from a group of Natives which have vested business interest with
the developing companies. 
<P>
Yet, President Clinton opposes the prospective development for drilling along
the 125 mile coastal plain. In June, Congress included over $1 billion in
projected lease revenue from the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, despite the
fact that oil development in the ANWR is currently not authorized.  In order to
veto opening the area to drilling, President Clinton would have to veto the
entire budget, which is highly unlikely. <A HREF
="http://alaska.alaskan.com/anwr/anwr_background.html">[5]</A> It should be
noted that further development on the budget issue and voting has taken place
since, yet no additional information on the outcome is readily available at
this time.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
Bottom line is that the 125 mile coastal plain of the ANWR is the only Arctic
coast in the United States that is not open to oil development.  Presently 90%
of the Alaskan coastline and 100% of the US Arctic Outer Continental Shelf is
open for oil exploration.  If found, predictions also say that the amount
of oil recovered over the lifetime of the oil field would only be an amount
equivalent to 200 days worth of oil for the current rate of consumption
for our nation. <A HREF
="http://alaska.alaskan.com/anwr/anwr_background.html">[6]</A>
 What needs to be asked and determined is whether development of this land is 
worth the environmental and cultural impact.<P>
<P>
<hr>
</h4>
<h5>

