<title>Who's Fault Was It?</title><p><font size=+3><font 
color="#bb00ff"><b><u>Who's Fault Was It?</b></u></font></font></p>
<hb><hr><p><font size=+1><font color="#000000">The first to blame for 
what went wrong at TMI is lack of routine maintenance.  If the reactor 
had been checked and maintained as it should have been, there would never 
have been a faulty valve to begin with, and the warning light which 
informed the reactor operator that the valve was closed was defective.  
Really, there was no fault that can be attributed to the reactor 
operator, since he performed up to expectations:  when he realized the 
pump valve was closed, and the back - up pump couldn't add more water to 
the core vessel, he hit the SCRAM.  This stopped the reactor;  however, 
the radioactive fissile materials were still hot.  The relief valve 
should have stayed shut;  however, it stayed open.  Again, this problem 
could've been avoided if routine maintenance had occured.  Because the 
ECCS was used according to procedure, and it shouldn't have been (again, 
the fault of a broken indicator light), a partial core meltdown occured.  
All in all, there was nothing and noone to blame for this accident 
besides the lack of maintenance.  If the regular, routine maintenance had 
been performed as it was supposed to, then Three Mile Island could most 
likely have been prevented.</font></font></p>
<hb><hr><p><a href="mailto:browde@students.uiuc.edu">Shana Browde</a> 
browde@students.uiuc.edu</p>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-166</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B026-36</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
