<heat><tittle>Bernard's Home Page</title></head>
<body background="rain.gif">
<center><h1>History and Background</h1></center><p>
 	The wind turbine which is used to generate electricity originated from 
the windmill. The difference of a windmill is that it performs work like 
milling grains, pumping water, specially when the shaft is connected to a 
load to pump water. What a wind turbine and a windmill have in common are 
that they both are machines that convert wind into useful energy. <br>
	Wind turbine power was pioneered but, in Denmark during the 
1890's. In the United States small wind turbines started generating 
electricity to rural communities and in the 1930's the wind turbine power 
was extended across the nation. Large turbines were built like the 
largest one called Smith-Putman in 1941 at Grandpa's Knobs, near Ruthland, 
Vermont.<br>
 	It was invented in the 16th or !7th century. In 1947 the first
 wind turbine was built around the industrial revolution by a Dutch 
architect 
Joap Schipper. During the 1980's the wind rush started in California at 
the Tehachapi's California bars, you could hear speak: English, Danish, 
or German. These people came to install wind turbine in America, of 
course many of them successed and other failed. <br>
	Wind power in California was a complete success during the 1980's, so 
there is a second project of wind development that will bring another 
2 TWh of electricity to the state of California. Which means 2.8 TWh 
production. Making California along the biggest wing turbine power 
producer in the world. California's  wind power has more capacity than 
Europe combined. <p>
<a href="http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/users/gdr11/fiction/in-the-zeeland.html"> 
Link </a><br>

 







