<title>nuclear energy</title>
<body background="brushed_.gif" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#OOFFFF" VLINK="#FFFFOO" ALINK="#9932CD">
<font size=+4><center>NUCLEAR ENERGY                           
</font><br><br><img src="atom.jpg"></center>


<br><br>
The subject of nuclear energy is often controversial. Experts and citizens alike argue over its place in this world, or if it should even have one. But much of the problem stems from the fact that 
anything related to nuclear is misunderstood and misinterpreted. In its short life, nuclear energy has had more problems and progress than most other energy sources. However, with the impending growth 
of the world's <a href="http://sunsite.unc.edu/lunarbin/worldpop">population</a> 
and the possibility of an energy crisis, more and more people are looking to nuclear as a solution. But is this attention warranted and will good come from it? Such is the question 
that is facing politicians, scientists, and citizens throughout the world. <br><br>
The theory behind nuclear has and can be used for runway lights, pacemakers, smoke
detectors, criminal investigation, and exploring for gas and oil. Not to mention the impact it could have on the generation of electricity. No one denies that we are going to need new sources of energy in 
the future. So why not nuclear? Of all electricity generating methods, nuclear is the cleanest and least damaging to our environment. In addition, there is a great deal of uranium, the main ingredient in
fission, just sitting in the soil going to waste. And when that runs out, scientists already know that thorium, which is three times as abundant as uranium, can be used as the main source for fission. 
Many argue that the cost of nuclear is too great, yet in actuality the cost of nuclear power per kilowatt hour is only a fraction of a cent higher that coal, and is less that the cost of oil. Nuclear is already 
said to have saved money in areas where it has been implemented. <br><br>
Moreover, we can cannot depend on alternative sources such as wind or 
<a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu/ne201/webproject/mcconnell/solar.html">solar</a> 
power to make our electricity when fossil fuels run out. The technology currently present in the these areas is just not strong enough 
to provide all of the world's energy.
There are also limitations which result from location. Wind energy is only a viable option in areas where there are constant winds of rather high speeds. Solar will be more effective in areas near the equator,
and of little use in areas near the poles. Also fossil fuels are having more and more trouble meeting the emission standards set by the EPA. They simply cannot burn clean enough to reduce levels of pollution to a 
low enough amount.
Therefore, we must seriously consider the power nuclear can provide as a solution to our energy problems.  


<br><br>
<img align=left src="atomblas.gif">
The <a href="http://www.students.uiuc.edu/~jurgovan/nuc/intro.html">history</a> 
of nuclear energy began in 1942 when the first sustained nucelar chain reaction gave birth to the atomic age.
The first battle nuclear energy had to face was overcoming the origin of its existence. For most people, the first look at the cabalities of nuclear power was the bombs dropped on 
<a href="http://web.mit.edu/afs/athena/org/t/techreview/www/articles/aug95/AtomicDower.html">Hiroshima and Nagasaki</a>.
After this, most people demanded that no more research or work be done on anything relating to nuclear. However, those who had worked with nuclear power and saw the benefits of what it could do would
not give up without a fight. They believed this could be the energy source of the future. And so, experts started experimenting with the same uranium which was used to make the bombs. Government officials and leaders
everywhere saw the potential problems this could lead to, and so an alternative source was needed. It was discovered that low enriched uranium, while not as powerful, could be used to produce the same basic effects 
as its more volatile counterpart. Great advantage was taken in regards to this finding and nuclear research continued. 
<br><br><img align=left src="fermi.gif"><br><br><br><br>
The earliest reactors were generally gas-cooled reactors which were direct descendants of the first reactor built by Enrico Fermi 
and used to create the atomic bomb. Through this method, a new fissionable material,
plutonium, could be produced and used to create energy. The next major development in the world of nuclear came with the advent of the fast reactor. Plutonium-enriched fuel elements were packed closely together, giving
a compact core. Those neutrons which were fast enough would then escape from the core area and were absorbed by the breeder elements to produce plutonium. Since then, a number of different types
of <a href="http://fantasia.ncsa.uiuc.edu/~aijuin/nuclear/">reactors</a> have been developed and used.<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<img src="bombfina.gif"> 
<br><br>
<img align=left src="nonuke.gif>
<br><br>
Some believe that nuclear energy can only lead to harm and are fighting hard to <a href="http://www2.iijnet.or.jp/nuke/links.html">stop nuclear testing</a> and achieve
<a href="http://www.miis.edu/nriguide.html">nonproliferation</a>.
Yet others believe that the threat of nuclear war and the damage and destruction which would certainly follow is enough to keep the world powers at 
 <a href="http://web.mit.edu/afs/athena/org/t/techreview/www/articles/aug95/AtomicRoland.html">peace</a>.
<br><br><br><br>
These questions are not expected to be answered in the near future, so we must work hard at understanding the various aspects of nuclear energy.
<br><br>
