<title>Nuclear Reactors</title>
<body bgcolor=#000066 text=#ffffff vlink=#ff0000 link=#ffff00>

<center><h1>
Nuclear Reactors
</h1></center>

<a name=pwr>
<h3>Pressurized Water Reactor</h3></a>
<dd>A pressurized water reactor uses water to transfer the heat
of the nuclear reactions to the engine.  For submarines,
uranium-235 is used in the fission process.  The water,
pressurized to prevent it from boiling, is pumped past the
fuel elements which both heat the water and make it radioactive.
The water is then routed through a heat transference device (see
generator in the <a href=pwr.gif>schematic</a>), where it is
cooled before being pumpedback through the reactor.  The steam
generated by the cooling of the water spins a turbine which
produces electrical and/or mechanical power.  This secondary
system is a Rankine cycle.  No shielding is needed on this cycle
because the primary cycle is fully shielded.
<img src=ybar.gif><br><p>

<a name=space><h3>Isotopic Nuclear Power Generator</h3></a>
<img align=left src=spacegen.gif>
The most common form of the isotopic thermal generator
is the Radioisotope Thermal Generator (RTG).  RTGs are used
to provide power when the need is less than one kilowatt.
  Heat generated by radioactive decay is converted to
electricity by thermoelectric converters.  The generator
pictured is the SNAP-27, a typical RTG which was used
to power an instruments package left on the moon by
Apollo 12 from 1969 to 1977.<p>
<p>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<img src=ybar.gif><br><img align =right src=kiwi.gif>
<a name=kiwi><h3>KIWI Reactors</h3></a>

The KIWI-A consisted of an annular stack of flat plate, graphite fuel elements loaded
with highly enriched urania particles surrounding a central hole of heavy water as a
moderator and a coolant.  It used hydrogen as a propellant.  A few problems were
anticipated and seen with the initial design, but they were all remedied in later KIWI
reactors.
<p>
<br>
<br>
<br>
