<title>Inertial Confinement Fusion</title>
<body background="dots.jpg" text="FFFFFF">
<center><h1>Inertial Confinement Fusion--Today and Tomorrow</h1>
<img src="rocket.jpeg">
<h3><i>"Fusion offers the promise of abundant energy from readily available fuels with low 
environmental impact..."  --President Bill Clinton </i></center></h3>
<hr><br>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>Coal cannot do everything.  It will not take us into space.  It will not power all our cars.  It will not 
heat all our homes forever.  We use more coal than can possible be replaced in our lifetime, or even ten 
lifetimes.  Supplies will eventually run out.
<p>Liquid fossil fuels like oil and natural gas will not last forever either.  At the present rate of 
consumption, these natural resources will only last at best a few hundred years.  With electricity demand 
on the rise, they may not last even that much.
<p>So, we must find another source of energy.  We want something that will last for a long time, 
something that will yield a large amount of energy, something that is economically, environmentally, 
politically, and technically viable.  This need for alternate energy sources has lead engineers down several 
different paths:  ethanol as fuel, solar power, wind power, and nuclear power.
<p>Of these sources, <a href=ICFnuc.html>nuclear power</a> seems the most promising and attractive 
energy source.
<p>For an outline of this paper, <a href=outline.html>click here</a>.
<hr><br>
<p><i><a href="mailto:c-lehner@students.uiuc.edu">feedback</a></i>
	
