<html>
<head>
<title>Conclusions</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h2>Conclusions</h2><img src="line2.gif"></center>
<h3>Money, Money, Money</h3>
<p>The most dreaded question in contemporary physics:  So what's the whole point?  The most dreaded question in renewable energy development:  So how much is it gonna cost?  Geothermal energy has an enormous potential, is environmentally safer than conventional fuel, and the technology is within reach.  That's all great, but what it all boils down to is money.  As long as coal, oil, and gas remain cheap (4 to 6 cents per kWh), newer technology such as geopressurized reservoirs, hot dry rock, and magma will have difficulty receiving enough funding and investment.</p><br>
<center><img src="line2.gif"></center><h3>Some Number Crunching and Wishful Thoughts</h3>
<p>Nevertheless, geothermal power has made a noticeable contribution in world energy production.  According to a 1989 estimate, geothermal resources generated a total of 6.3 million tonnes of oil equivalent (TOE) that year.  In the year 2000, geothermal power plants are predicted to generate 19.8 TOE of energy.  Even though these values represent less than 0.10 and .22% of the world's energy consumption, respectively, one should not be discouraged.  The gradual (and I mean gradual) replacement of fossil fuel is a multi-faceted effort, combining various resources like solar, wind, biomass, hydrothermal, and geothermal energy.  Besides, we can still use coal in limited amounts, as long as we use effective pollution control.  A final message from the author for the readers that actually made it all the way to the conclusion (or just skipped a few pages):  energy crisis is real and everyone should be aware of it -- but don't lose 8 hours of sleep over it.</p>
<center><a href="future.html">[Previous]</a> | <a href="web.html#contents">[Table of Contents]</a> | <a href="web.html">[Home]</a>
<br><a href="mailto:sw-choi@uiuc.edu">E-mail Bad Boy</a></center>
