<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B025-132</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/sw-choi/future.html 128.174.200.146 19970303035916 text/html 6695
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 03:56:18 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Last-modified: Sun, 27 Oct 1996 23:40:06 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 6512
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Future Developments</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img src="line2.gif"><br><h2>Total Expansion Systems</h2></center>
<p>Total expansion cycles, or total flow prime movers, can possibly improve efficiency of water-dominated hydrothermal systems.  This conversion process uses the total resource of the geothermal fluid (steam, hot water, and pressure) to obtain mechanical energy instead of flashing and separating the steam.  The fluid is directed into a rotating unit that captures its the kinetic energy.  The advantage of a total expansion system is that its theoretical conversion efficiency is thermodynamically equivalent to having an infinite number of flashers.  A prototype called the Helical Screw Expander was tested in Italy, Mexico, New Zealand, and the United States through the International Energy Agency (IEA).  Unfortunately, current designs have low conversion efficiency and are less reliable than flash cycles.  The only commercial total expansion system available today is the rotary separator turbine, and the technology suffers from a lack of interest.</p>        
<center><img src="line2.gif"><h2>Hot Dry Rock Systems</h2></center>
<p><img src="howforme.gif" align="right">The most promising technology for the future of geothermal energy is hot dry rock (HDR) systems.  HDR has an enormous potential because it is much more widely distributed than hydrothermal systems.  It is estimated that HDR accounts for about 70% of all geothermal resources in the U.S.  First research was initiated in 1974 at Los Alamos National Laboratory, and preliminary tests began in Fenton Hill, New Mexico.  Testing of hot dry rock are primarily being conducted in Japan, the United Kingdom, France and the United States.</p><br>
<p>Since HDR does not have a reservoir of fluid that can circulate heat, artificial injection of water is required.  The most popular technique involves drilling two parallel wells and hydraulically fracturing the rock in order to establish a connection.  Water is injected into the first well so that the fluid circulates through the fractures collecting heat in the process.  The hot water is then pumped up to the surface through the second well into a binary cycle (HDR temperatures are usually moderate) where power is generated.  The cooled water is reinjected into the first well.  This system minimizes scaling and corrosion of equipment and also emission of harmful material to the environment.</p>
<p>Several technological limitations need to be overcome before hot dry rock can be commercially exploited.  First, a better method of determining the durability of a particular HDR reservoir must be developed in order to encourage private investment.  Second, the drilling technology must be improved.  Drilling two parallel wells through more than 3 km of high-temperature rock is very expensive, and the cost prevents exploration of deeper resources.  Finally, a better understanding of the hydraulic fracturing process is essential.  Without proper fracturing, several fatal problems may occur.  The rock should be fractured so that a large surface area is produced to allow more efficient heat circulation, but uncontrolled fracturing leads to great fluid loss.  Because rock compositions vary even within the same formation, fracturing is often erratic.  Establishing sufficient connection between the injection and the production well may require several attempts.</p>
<center><img src="line2.gif"><h2>Geopressurized Reservoirs</h2></center>
<p>Geopressurized systems are deep fluid reservoirs that are much like hydrothermal systems.  Geopressurized reservoirs, as the name suggests, are characterized by extremely high pressures ranging from 50 to 100 megapascals (about 500 to 1000 times greater than atmospheric pressure) and temperatures between 150 to 200 deg C.  The reservoirs also have large amounts of methane, or natural gas, dissolved in the liquid, anywhere between 3 to 12 grams per liter.  Geopressurized systems can generate electricity in three ways.  First, the hot fluid can provide heat for a binary cycle.  Second, the mechanical (hydraulic) energy of the high-pressure fluid can do work on an impulse turbine.  Finally, the dissolved methane can be separated from the geopressurized fluid for use in a conventional gas power plant.</p><br>
<p>Geopressurized systems account for approximately 20% of all geothermal resources in the United States.  The most researched geopressurized sites are located along the Gulf Coast in Texas and Louisiana.  Wells in this region have produced about 700 million cubic feet of natural gas since 1985, and a 1 MW plant utilizing the thermal energy and methane was built in 1989.  Geopressurized energy, however, is wrought with some major technological difficulties.  First, it is difficult to estimate how much energy is contained in geopressurized systems.  Second, the depth of the reservoirs, 3000 to 6000 m, make drilling very costly.  Moreover, geopressurized fluid is extremely high in salinity, about 20 to 200 g per liter, causing a great deal of scaling and corrosion.  Finally, reinjection of the fluid into the deep reservoir is not easy, requiring injection into shallower aquifers nearby.</p>
<center><img src="line2.gif"><h2>Magma Systems</h2></center>
<p><img src="puu_oo.gif" align="left">The most advanced geothermal technology in consideration today is the magma system.  Magma systems are chambers of molten rock material that occur near (within 10 km from) the surface such as volcanoes.  The main advantage of magma is that it is very hot (~2000 deg C), much hotter than HDR or hydrothermal systems.  One way to use the heat would be to circulate water into the top part of the magma chamber and power a closed Rankine cycle with a heat exchanger.  Estimates show that each well can have a generating capacity ranging from 25 to 45 MW.  In addition to generating electricity directly from the heat, the chemical reactivity and high temperature of the magma can produce hydrogen gas from water or synthesize gas from water/biomass mixtures.  Active research of magma energy was proposed in 1973 by Sandia National Laboratories, and tests have been conducted in Hawaii and California.</p>
<center><a href="current.html">[Previous]</a> | <a href="web.html#contents">[Table of Contents]</a> | <a href="web.html">[Home]</a> | <a href="conc.html">[Next]</a>
<br><a href="mailto:sw-choi@uiuc.edu">E-mail Bad Boy</a></center>
</body>
</html>
  




