</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Current Technology</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img src="line2.gif"><br><h2>Hydrothermal Systems</h2></center>
<p>The only commercially feasible method of geothermoelectric generation available today is through hydrothermal systems.  Such systems form when an underground reservoir of water is trapped in fractured rock formations in a region of high temperature gradient.  The heat turns the reservoir into a mixture of steam and water.  Power is generated by drilling a well and using the steam that comes out to turn a turbine.  Hydrothermal systems can be classified into three main categories:  steam systems, high temperature systems, and low to moderate temperature systems.</p><hr>
<h3>Steam Systems</h3>
<p><a href="images/pic3.gif"><img src="pic3.jpg" align="left"></a>Generating power from steam systems is the simplest and most efficient.  The geothermal fields in Larderello, Italy, and The Geysers in California (see picture) are both examples of steam-dominated systems.  Steam systems employ two types of cycles to generate power.  The first is exhausting-to-atmosphere cycle.  As the name implies, all of the excess steam is exhausted into the atmosphere after the turbine is turned.  In the second type, the condensing cycle, the exhaust steam from the turbine is condensed and reinjected into the reservoir.  The condensing cycle is often preferred because reinjection of the fluid partially recharges the reservoir and also reduces emission of harmful materials such as hydrogen sulfide and brine.  Steam rates for commercial plants range from 6 to 9 kg per kWh for condensing cycles, and turbine sizes from 50 to 60 MW.  Larger plants use two turbines in tandem and range from 110 to 120 MW.</p><hr>
<h3>High Temperature Systems</h3>
<p><a href="images/pic5.gif"><img src="pic5.jpg" align="right"></a>High temperature systems, although not as simple to exploit as dry steam, are more common.  They are characterized by highly pressurized mixture of water and steam with temperatures exceeding 200 deg C.  While the steam component can be directly used in a turbine, the liquid phase must first be "flashed" into steam.  Flashing occurs because the water from the reservoir has a temperature higher than the normal boiling point; when the liquid is pumped up to the surface, the lowered pressure causes it to vaporize.  The flashed steam is then used to generate power.  A "double-flash" cycle has a second flasher that recovers lower pressure steam from the hot water separated in the first flasher.  As in a steam system, hot-water plants can either exhaust to atmosphere or condense and reinject into the reservoir.  Single and double flash condensing plants have total flow rates ranging from 40 to 80 and from 30 to 60 kg of geothermal fluid per kWh, respectively.  Because flashing cycles require much more fluid than steam cycles, turbine sizes are limited to 30-50 MW.</p><hr>
<h3>Low to Moderate Temperature Systems</h3>
<p><a href="pic1s.gif"><img src="pic1s.jpg" align="left"></a>Low to moderate temperature, or low enthalpy, systems are the most complex and therefore the least used of the three hydrothermal systems.  Like high temperature systems, low to moderate temperature is water dominated; however, the temperature in these systems are below 200 and usually around 150 deg C.  Because of the low temperature, a regular flashing cycle is inefficient, not to mention uneconomical.  Instead, low to moderate temperature reservoirs utilize a binary cycle, a relatively new technology in terms of actual use.  In a binary cycle, the hot water from the reservoir is kept under pressure and run through a heat exchanger, boiling a secondary fluid with a low boiling point such as ammonia or a fluorocarbon refrigerant.  The secondary fluid operates in a closed Rankine cycle similar to conventional power plants.  Binary cycles are advantageous in that none of the geothermal fluid is released to the environment.  However, at moderate temperatures 80 to 400 kg of fluid per kWh are required, and the capacity of each operating unit is only 1 MW.</p>
<h3>Hybrid Plants</h3>
<p>In addition to the various cycles mentioned in previous three sections, geothermal energy can be harnessed more efficiently through combining the different technologies.  For example, the binary cycle can operate on the exhaust steam from dry steam and high temperature cycles and also on the hot water separated from flashers.  Another possibility is supplementing low enthalpy systems with fossil or biofuels.  This type of hybrid design would burn much less fuel than conventional power plants while producing the same amount of electricity.</p>
<h3>Problems with Current Technology</h3>
<img src="or_ball.jpg">Drilling
<p>Currently, geothermal resources that are deeper than 5 km are not economically viable.  Improving the drilling technology will expand the amount of geothermal resources accessible for power generation, as well as reducing the cost of exploratory drilling.</p>
<img src="or_ball.jpg">Corrosion and Scaling
<p>Chemicals from geothermal fluid such as brine and hydrogen sulfide corrode the plant material.  Fluids also produce carbonate, sulfide, silica, and silicate deposits in plant equipment.  The problem can be partly solved by adding scale inhibitors to the geothermal fluid.</p>
<img src="or_ball.jpg">Emissions
<p>Exhaust from geothermal fluid contains toxic material, most important of which are hydrogen sulfide and brine.  Geothermal plants also produce carbon dioxide, although in much less amounts than coal or gas power plants.  Reinjection and pollution control mechanisms can reduce emissions significantly.</p>
<img src="or_ball.jpg">Geological Impact
<p>Extracting a large amount of fluid from an underground reservoir sometimes causes subsidence (sinking of the land).  Reinjection of the fluid eliminates subsidence but it can also increase microseismic activities.</p>
<img src="or_ball.jpg">Noise
<p>Geothermal plants make a lot of noise, but this is not a great problem when the field is located far away from residential areas.  Also, a better design of the plants can easily reduce noise pollution.</p>
<img src="or_ball.jpg">Renewability
<p>A major drawback to geothermal energy is that it is not renewable in human terms.  Years of exploitation eventually cools down the reservoir so that it no longer generates power efficiently.  Nature may take thousands of years to restore the used heat.</p>
<center><a href="history.html">[Previous]</a> | <a href="web.html#contents">[Table of Contents]</a> | <a href="web.html">[Home]</a> | <a href="future.html">[Next]</a>
<br><a href="mailto:sw-choi@uiuc.edu">E-mail Bad Boy</a></center>
</body>
</html>                 

