<html>
<head>
<title>History and Background</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h2>Where Does Geothermal Energy Come From?</h2>
<img src="line2.gif"></center><br>
<p><img src="origin2.gif" align="left">Geothermal energy is associated with the heat that evolved from the formation of the earth and the radioactive decay of the unstable elements such as potassium and uranium in the earth's mantle.  The heat from the core, a molten mass having a temperature of about 4200 deg C, conducts toward the surface and is lost through atmospheric convection.  The flow of heat causes an average temperature gradient of approximately 30 deg C per km in the crust.  Because incident solar radiation is much greater than the geothermal heat conducted to the surface, the latter is often difficult to observe.  In certain regions of high geological activity, however, the magma from the mantle gets close enough to the surface to manifest itself as volcanoes, geysers, and hot springs.  Exploitation of geothermal energy has been conducted almost exclusively in such regions.</p><br><center><img src="line2.gif"></center><br>
<center><h2>History of Geothermal Power Generation</h2></center>
<p><a href="images/pic2s.gif"><img src="pic2s.jpg" align="right"></a>Although direct use of geothermal energy can be traced back to ancient times when people bathed in hot springs for therapeutic purposes, geothermoelectric generation was not explored until the 20th century.  The first geothermoelectricity production took place in 1904 in Larderello, Italy.  Initially geothermal energy was used to process boric acid and other useful minerals abundant in the region, but eventually the electricity became more important.  Following Italy's success, the United States began development of geothermal power in The Geysers in California (see picture) in 1916, and New Zealand also started to explore its geothermal fields.  Until the 1960s, above three countries dominated world geothermoelectric power production.  Partly due to the oil embargo in the '70s and also an increased awareness of fossil fuel pollution, more countries began to develop geothermal resources.  Annual growth rate of geothermoelectricity production peaked at 16% in 1978, and today the rate has gone down to about 8%.</p> 
<center><a href="web.html#contents">[Table of Contents]</a> | <a href="web.html">[Home]</a> | <a href="current.html">[Next]</a>
<br><a href="mailto:sw-choi@uiuc.edu">E-mail Bad Boy</a></center>
</body>
</html> 




