<DOCNO>WT08-B26-176</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA042-000771-B040-342</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/webproject/mcconnell/solar.html 128.174.200.146 19970303022347 text/html 11779
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 02:20:49 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Last-modified: Thu, 07 Dec 1995 21:50:29 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 11595
</DOCHDR>
<head>
	<title>Solar Electric Power</title>
</head>

<body background="gray_roc.gif">

	<center><h1>Solar Electric Power</h1></center><p>
	<img src="bluemarb.gif"><br><br>

	<h2><center>Introduction</center></h2><p>
	<h4>Solar electric power is becoming an increasingly important and useful source of energy around the world.  It uses are varied, with <a href="http://www.rt66.com/rbahm/heating.htm">solar heating for buildings</a> (both <a href="http://www.nrel.gov/documents/erec_fact_sheets/4.html">passive</a> and <a href="http://www.nrel.gov/documents/erec_fact_sheets/sbar4-1.html">active</a>) and electricity generation using <a href="http://www.gl.umbc.edu/~mpanun1/research.html">photovoltaics</a> and <a href="http://powerweb.lerc.nasa.gov/pv/DOC/tpv.html">thermophotovoltaics</a> as its two main branches.  This document will serve as an introduction to the history, current technology, and future developments of solar power technology and its applications.
	</h4>
	<br><img src="bluemarb.gif"><br><br>

	<h2><center>History and Background</center></h2><p>
	<h4>Development of solar power technology began over 100 years ago.  Some engineers in the 1800's were concerned with the industrial revolution's heavy dependence on nonrenewable fossil fuels and began to examine solar power as a viable energy source.  Experimentation with solar motors utilizing concepts such as the "Power Tower" and the parabolic trough was conducted both in Europe and the United States between the Civil War and World War I.	However, much of this research ceased due to low prices and plentiful supplies of fossil fuels.  After the OPEC oil embargo of the 1970's, however, development of renewable energy sources was once again viewed as important.  To learn more about the beginnings of solar power development, an excellent source is Charles Smith's article <a href="http://web.mit.edu/afs/athena/org/t/techreview/www/articles/july95/Smith.html>Revisiting Solar Power's Past</a> written for MIT's Technology Review magazine.<p>
	<center><img src="smith2.gif"><p><h3>Parabolic troughs used in the late 1800's</h3></center><p>
	<hr><br>A brief general overview of the history of <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/re-kiosk/solar/solar-thermal/history/index.shtml>solar thermal energy</a> and background information about <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/re-kiosk/solar/pv/overview.shtml>photovoltaics</a> are also available.
	</h4>
	<br><img src="bluemarb.gif"><br><br>

	<h2><center>Current Technology</center></h2><p>
	<h4>Beginning in the 1970's, there has been much interest in the area of solar space and water heating.  An important research center in the United States is Colorado State University's <a href="http://princeton.lance.colostate.edu:8080/Solar.html>Solar Energy Applications Laboratory (SEAL)</a>.  Some of their current projects include:
	<ul>	<li>development of <a href="http://princeton.lance.colostate.edu:8080/domestic.html>advanced domestic hot water systems</a><br>
			Improvements are being made to this system consisting of three solar collector arrays.	The improvements will increase performance, reduce costs, and allow the system to perform in many types of climates.<p>
		<li>analysis of <a href="http://princeton.lance.colostate.edu:8080/analysis.html>seasonal performance of solar water and space heating systems</a><br>
			Development of component and system models allows for assessment of the performance of solar hot water and space heating systems.<p>
		<li>development and designing of the <a href="http://princeton.lance.colostate.edu:8080/build.html">"Zero Energy" Building</a><br>
			The energy consumption of this office building is expected to be less than one fifth of a traditional building.  Both passive and active solar systems contribute to its energy conservation.<p>
	</ul>
	<center><img src="page8b.gif"><p>
	<h3>A computer-generated view of the "Zero Energy" Building</h3></center>
	<p><hr><br>
	The Fraunhofer Institute for Solar Energy Systems has built a <a href="http://www.ise.fhg.de/Institute.Projects.SelfSuffSolHouse.english.html">self-sufficient solar house</a> near Freiburg, Germany.	All of its energy needs are supplied by thermal and photovoltaic applications of solar energy.	Since half of the primary energy consumption in Germany is used to supply buildings, this project has important implications for energy politics as well as for the development of new solar power technology.<p>
	<center><img src="solhouse.gif"><p>
	<h3>The self-sufficient solar house near Freiburg</h3></center><p><hr><br>
	There are many experimental solar houses located in different climates with information on the internet.<p>
	<ul>	<li><a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/wlord/solarhouse.html">Maine</a>
		<li><a href="http://www.netins.net/showcase/solarcatalog/homestead.html">Utah</a>
		<li><a href="http://www.ncsc.ncsu.edu/sh.htm"/>North Carolina</a>
		<li><a href="http://www.tuns.ca/~banderrj/solar.html">Halifax, Canada</a>
	</ul>
	<p><hr><br>
	The <a href="http://zoo4.isburg.ch/lab/pv/pub/erz9404/erz9404p.html">highest grid connected PV-plant in the world</a> at the research station on Jungfraujoch, Switzerland (3454m above sea level) has been operational since October 27, 1993.  Compared to nearby installations in lower parts of Switzerland, this system has had amazing winter energy yields.  <a href="http://zoo4.isburg.ch/lab/pv/pub/joch94e/joch941e.html">Operational results</a> for this facility from 1994 are available.<p>
	<center><img src="jungfra2.gif"><p><h3>The grid connected PV-plant in Jungfraujoch, Switzerland</h3></center>
	<p><hr><br>
	Providing energy for satellites and space vehicles is a perfect application of solar electric power because it would be difficult to periodically send fuel into space.  An example of this is the use of solar arrays to power the <a href="http://stsci.edu/proof/arrays.html">Hubble Space Telescope</a>.  A recently developed solar array system known as <a href="http://powerweb.lerc.nasa.gov/psi/DOC/scarlet.html">SCARLET (Solar Concentrator Array with Refractive Linear Element Technology</a> has lower production costs, lighter weight, and greater stiffness than current solar arrays.  Tests of its key components were successful, and it is schedule for use in some upcoming missions.
	<p><hr><br>
	<img align=left src="kakuma.gif">
	An interesting application of thermal solar energy is <a href="http://www.accessone.com/~sbcn/95sep15a.htm">solar cooking in Kenyan refugee camps</a>.	For $10.00 the United States can provide a Kenyan family with a <a href="http://www.accessone.com/~sbcn/cookit.htm">solar cooker</a>, food, and instruction in its use.  This program has been extremely <a href="http://www.accessone.com/~sbcn/kakuma-m.htm">successful</a>.<p>
	</h4>
	<br><img src="bluemarb.gif"><br><br>

	<h2><center>Future Developments</center></h2><p>
	<h4>One of the major drawbacks of photovoltaic cells is their high cost in comparison to most other forms of electricity generation.  However, the development of thin film technology may help change this situation in the future.  According to Ken Zweibel in his article <a href="http://www.nrel.gov/research/pv/thinfilm.html">Thin Films:  Past, Present, Future</a>, the future for thin films looks strong:  there are both technological and economical advantages to using thin films over the traditional wafer-based crystalline silicon cells.  The primary advantage of thin films is cheaper materials and manufacturing costs.  Depending on the type of thin film material, the efficiency, outdoor stability, and lifetime may all be improved.  Zweibel predicts that amorphous silicon thin films may eventually dominate the world photovoltaic market.	Even if this very optimistic outlook does not come true, thin films are definitely a way to produce low price photovoltaics.<p><hr><br>
	New solar technology for use in space applications is also being developed.  Recently, a NASA/industry team successfully tested a <a href="http://powerweb.lerc.nasa.gov/soldyn/DOC/SDGTD.html">Solar Dynamic space power system</a>.  The United States Air Force is also developing <a href="http://www.plk.af.mil/PLhome/PA/FACTSHEETS/thinfilm.html">thin-film polycrystalline solar cells</a> for improved performance in space.<p><hr><br>
	<img align=left src="demosite.gif">Research at the Fraunhofer Institute for Solar Energy is attempting to understand how to effectively <a href="http://www-iea.vuw.ac.nz:90/task16.html">integrate photovoltaics into buildings</a>.  A <a href="http://lesowww.epfl.ch/PV/demosite.html">"demosite"</a> in Lausanne, Switzerland is used for testing and developing new methods for mounting photovoltaic modules on buildings.<p><hr><br>
	The future for solar power looks encouraging in many countries.  For example, in November 1990, the Swiss government began a 10 year national program known as <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/tour6.html#24">Energy 2000</a>.  In compliance with this program,  photovoltaic grid-connected installations producing a total of 50 MWp will be installed by the turn of the century.  A few experimental <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/toc.html">applications</a> of solar energy are already being used, such as providing power for:
	<img align=right src="church.gif" width="225" height="165">
	<ul>	<li>a <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/tour1.html#2">high school</a>
		<li>a <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/tour3.html#11">church</a>
		<li>an <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/tour4.html#16">elementary school</a>
		<li>a <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/tour6.html#21">granary</a>
		<li>a <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/pv-tour-switzerland/tour6.html#22">village hall</a>
	</ul><br>
	</h4>
	<br><img src="bluemarb.gif"><br><br>

	<h2><center>Conclusions</center></h2><p>
	<h4>The continued research, development, and use of solar power technology in the future looks very promising.	Although currently not economically competitive with fossil fuel energy, continued advances in technology will most likely reduce costs and increase effectiveness.  In the immediate future, however, solar electric power will find rapidly increasing use in developing nations.  For example, in the village of <a href="http://solstice.crest.org/renewables/indonesia/lebak.html#l1">Lebak, Indonesia</a>, a successful solar energy program was started to provide the residents with electricity.  Due to high costs for an electricity distribution grid, low demand for electricity, and lack of fossil fuels in these regions, it would be nearly impossible to provide electricity by traditional power plants.  Photovoltaics are good for low demand, localized applications such as this.  Since approximately 70% of the world's population does not have access to electricity, a very large potential market exists.
		In order to help decrease dependence on fossil fuels, it is important to develop alternative energy sources that can be utilized in the relatively near future.  Although solar electric power will not solve the energy problems of the world, it will eventually become a much more important energy source when fossil fuels are eventually depleted.
	</h4>
	<br><img src="bluemarb.gif"><br><br>

	<center><h3><i>Please send any feedback about this page to:<br>
	<a href="mailto:mcconnll@ux5.cso.uiuc.edu">Angie McConnell</a>
	</i></center></h3>

</body>
