<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Supplement C: Future Developments
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="stars.gif">
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=5 CELLSPACING=3><TR><TD><B>Lighting R & D In Progress</B></TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<p><img src="spotlight.gif" align=middle><font size=5>Advanced Lighting Technologies on the Horizon
</font><br>
<img src="rainbow.gif">
<h3><font size=4><U><b><A NAME="LED">LED Lighting System</A></b></u></font></h3>
<img src = "LEDsystem.gif"> 
</center>

<br><p>
A joint venture between Jade Mountain and the World Bank is using 
LEDs(light-emitting diodes) in lighting systems to offer compact, efficient lighting services
in remote areas of the world.  The new system will provide affordable
reading light using merely 1.5 Watt of power (equivalent to a 25-Watt
incandescent light bulb) through a solar module attachment.  Rated life
is a whopping 68 yrs! (running 4 hours per day) <a href="http://www.indra.com/jade-mtn/LEDsystem.html">
MUST KNOW MORE!</a></p>
<br>


<p>Although billions of LED devices are manufactured per year, their range of 
uses has been limited because of the absence of the color blue.  When blue light
is combined with green and red, LEDs can create the full spectrum of visible light. Ultimately, such a full-color light 
emitter could replace the cathode ray tube and the incandescent light bulb.  
Researchers at <A href="http://www.bl.gov/Science-Articles/Research-Review/Highlights/1994/blue-light.html">
Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory </a>are collaborating with Hewlett Packard in an attempt
to grow materials that will ultimately produce a bright, reliable, and
affordable blue LED, and eventually a blue semiconductor laser. 
<BR><image align=right src ="blue-light.gif" align=middle>
<blockquote><em>This hollow-anode nitrogen plasma source reduces atomic
defects and create maximum luminescence as a tool to construct blue-light
emitting semiconductors under precise conditions.</em></blockquote>
<Br>
LEDs represent an ideal light source with long lifespans and remarkable efficiency. 
LED-based flat panel computer and television displays could be brighter and more energy-efficient 
than the current liquid crystal display devices. As a white light source, low cost and high brightness
LEDs could potentially be developed to replace incandescent and other types of light bulbs.
</p>
<br>
<img src ="rainbow.gif">
<br>

<h3><b><A NAME="sulfur">Microwave Sulfur Lamp</A></b></h3>
<P>The US Department of Energy and US manufacturer Fusion Lighting
creates a new light source using induction lamp technology called a sulfur
microwave lamp.  Sulfur and argon in a small, electrodeless glass bulb are turned into a plasma by
microwave energy at 2.45 GHz. The physical properties of the excited sulfur atoms ensure that most of
the microwave energy is converted into light while little energy is emitted as ultraviolet or infrared
radiation.<br></p>
<p><center><img src="sulfur.gif"></center><TT>A small, electrodeless bulb is powered by microwave energy, stirring the
sulfur atom within to convert the energy into usable artificial sunlight.</TT><p>
<BR>

<p>The main advantage of induction lamps is their longer life compared with other fluorescent technologies.
The presence of electrodes also drastically limits the types of substances that
can be used to generate light since many substances will attack the electrodes.
Almost 75% of the energy emitted from the bulb is emitted as light in a full-color continuous spectrum.
Possible applications include warehouses, shopping malls, factories, arenas, and street lights. Given
the lamp's spectral qualities, they also hold great promise for use in greenhouses.
For the full report on this cutting edge technology, click 
<A href="http://www.webcom.com/~lightsrc/archive/article3.html">here</a>.</p>
<img src="rainbow.gif">
<br>
<center><h3><b><A NAME="ge">Leading Edge Development from GE Corporation</A></b></h3>
<img src="gemhl.gif" align=middle>
<u><font size=4>Ceramic Metal Halide Lamps</Font></u>
</center>
<p><A href="http://www.facilitiesnet.com/PS/ge/">General Electric Lighting</a>,
a major manufacturer of consumer lighting products, is introducing a new category
of Metal Halide lamps that enlists ceramic material to form the arc body.  This new
technology replaces the quartz arc tube with an innovative ceramic arc tube to deliver improved color performance, higher
CRI(over 80 color renditio index) and increased lumen output of 10 to 20% as compared
to standard quartz Metal Halide lamps.  

</p> 
 

<center><img src="geheliax.gif" align = middle>
<u><font>"Haliax" Series of Compact Flourescent Lights</font></u></center>
<p>
A new series of compact flourescent lights (CFLs) are under development by GE for the
general public.  These unique, helical-shaped lamps called Heliax(TM) offers more light in a
smaller package.  Heliax is more similar in size and shape to an A-line incandescent bulb than
any CFL on the market and its rugged, single-tube construction increases the durability of the
product over other CFLs.  Heliax's open spiral design minimizes light trapping and light absorption, providing a more optically
efficient lamp with uniform light distribution. 
<br>The lamp's short length and bulb-like shape make it ideal for applications where
lighting space is limited, cut-off angles are important, or small apertures are desired. Additionally, the
screw-in Heliax is an excellent, energy saving incandescent retrofit. 

Heliax offers significant energy savings compared to incandescent lighting. For example, the 32W plug-in
Heliax saves an average of $82 in energy costs over its long 10,000-hour life as compared to a 135W
incandescent A-line bulb, providing a payback in as little as 3 months. 
</p>
