<H1><CENTER>Fuel Cells, Biogas and Hydrogen</H1><BR>
Lecture-Discussion # 13 <BR>
Nuclear Engineering 201 <BR>
Professor Ruzic </P></CENTER>
<H2>Introduction</H2>
<P>The conversion of organic matter to gaseous form has many advantages.
At low cost a burnable low-grade gas still containing air can be used for
heating nearby locations. At the high cost end hydrogen gas can be made
which will burn completely and clean. With the invention and adoption of
fuel cell technology, gaseous fuels can be converted directly to electricity
without the need for a boiler, gnerator, condensor combination. The potential
coupling of a renewable biomass source for the fuels cell's input is an
exciting development to consider for future electrical generation. </P>
