<HTML>
<body BACKGROUND = "backwave.jpg"

<head><H2>Electric Transmission and Storage</h2><br>
</head>



<p>In this category there are many very exiciting, money saving, fuel saving, pollution saving and hassle saving applications of superconductors.  First, superconducting electric transmission could save millions of dollars in fuel alone.  They have the potential to save a quad of energy per year in transmission losses and another 0.5 quads in motor losses.  Since superconducting wires would not have resistance, they would not lose any electricity when in transmission.  Thus, utilities would burn much less fuel to make the same amount of electricity get to the consumer. 

<p><a href="http://www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/1755/smes.html">Superconducting Magnetic Energy Storage (SMES)</a> could be used by electric utilities as cost-effective, high-efficiency, high-capacity energy storage systems to compensate for large daily swings in power requirement and to stabilize transmission systems against transient disturbances.  Also, this type of technology could make some types of renewable energys more feasible.                                     

<p>Compact, <a href="http://www.harc.edu/corollary/corollary_winter_95/energy.html">Micro-SMES</a> systems could help prevent momentary disruptions of power that shut down computer systems and cause major financial and information losses.  Power fluctuations of this type now cost U.S.industry more than $10 billion annually. The systems could be located near key machinery and computer loads in offices, factories, hospitals and laboratories. <br><br>

<a href="http://rpgopher.aist.go.jp:8000/nss/text/SuperC.html">Present Technology</a><br><br>

<a href="http://www.ornl.gov/~vhk/rabits.html">New Superconducting Wire</a>
