<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Supplement A: History&Background
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY Background=tan_pape.gif>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=5 CELLSPACING=1><TR><TD>Electric Lighting History and Background</TR>
</TABLE>
<H2> <A NAME="History"><u>HISTORY & BACKGROUND OF ELECTRIC LIGHTING</u></A>
</h2><br>
</center>
<P>
First and foremost, electric lighting revolves around the basic concept in which
elecrical energy is converted into light.  The American inventor, Thomas Alva Edison, 
might be remembered as the "Father of Modern Illumination" with the production of his
commercially successful  carbon-filament lamp in 1879.  However, experiments in electric
lighting exised decades earlier with British chemist Sir Humphrey Day, who developed a fine
platinum wire incandescent in air by passing a current through it.  Gradual advancement in
lighting components through the 20th century allowed lighting devices to become more
affordable and increase in efficacy.  The two primary electric light source in the market
are:
</p>
<BR>
<font size=6><img align=left src="on.jpg"><img align=right src="on.jpg">
<P align=Center><A NAME="Incandescent"><B>Incandescent Bulbs</B></A></P>
</font><br>
<BR>
<p><img align=right src="new-1.jpg" align=top>  An incandescent bulb harnesses light from
a heated material.
<h3><b><u>Functionality</u></b></h3>
<br>
Electric current flows through a thin tungsten wire (filament) and heats the fiament
to about 3000 degrees Celsius, which causes heat and light to emit.  The bulky globe or shell
is under a vacuum, forming a heat insulator to keep the bulb and socket from getting too hot.
The filament also  produces infrared (heat) radiation, some of which is
  absorbed by the glass bulb wall as it passes,  contributing more heat to the bulb.
In addition, an inert gas is inside the bulb to prevent the filament from burning out.
<h3><b><u>Advancements</u></b></h3>
<DL compact>
<dt>1907  
<dd>Filament transition from carbon to tungsten (a higher melting point allows for more efficient lighting)
<dt>1913
<dd>Gas-filled bulb instead of a regular vacuum bulb to slow the evaporation of the filament
(commonly nitrogen or argon)
</dl>
<BR>

</p>
<BR>
<font size=5><center><A NAME="Flourescent">Flourescent Lighting</A></center>
</font><br>
<p><img align=right src="new-2.jpg" align=top> 
First introduced in 1938, a flourescent lamp is a type of 
electric-discharge device used for general-purpose illumination.
<h3><b><u>Functionality</u></b></h3>
It is a low-pressure mercury vapor lamp confined in a glass
tube, which is coated on the inside with a flourescent material known
as phosphor.  The energized filament delivers electrons to the ionized
inert gas within (usually argon), forming a plasma that conducts electricity.
The ballast limits the flow of the current through the tube.  Consequently, the plasma
excites the mercury vapor atoms, which then emits a spectra of red, green, blue, and
ultraviolet lights.  The internal phosphor coating then converts the ultraviolet light into 
other colors.  
<br>
<h3><b><u>Advancements</u></b></h3>
<img align=right src="change.jpg" align=top>
<br><DL compact>
<DT><u>Higher lighting quality</u>....visualize the difference >
<DD>The efficacy of the ultraviolet light transmission is dependent on the type of phosphor used
<DT><u>Increased energy-efficiency</u>
<DD>On average, 40 Watts of energy in a flourescent tube produces as much as a 150-Watt incandescent bulb
<DT><u>Less heat</u>
<DD>Compared to traditional incandescent bulb, less heat is generated from the filament at similiar lighting output
</DL>
<BR> 
<br>
<BR>
</p>

<HR>
<TT><center><Font size=5><B><A NAME="Waste">WASTEFUL </A>LIGHTING IN AMERICA</B></font></center>
<BR>
<I>Here is a grave description of the extent in which energy in this country is
 callously wasted through inadequate lighting.
</I><P><B><img src="merc_vapor.gif" align=bottom>First consider a regular mercury-vapor lamp that is used as an outdoor
security streetlight. At least 30% of the lighting output is unleashed
angles where it goes up, away from the ground, or where it only causes glare. This light is totally wasted,
as is the energy that goes to produce it. 

Let's consider the energy waste: A 175 W lamp uses about 200 watts when one counts ballast losses as
well. The lamps burn about 11 hours a night; most security and street lights burn close to 4100 hours a
year. Multiply: 200 W X 4100 hours = 820 KWH of energy use per year. At 8 cents per KWH, about the
average cost of such energy nationally, each fixture costs close to $65 per year to operate. This is twice
as much as the initial cost of $30. In an area where electricity costs 11 cents per KWH, the lamp costs 3
times as much to operate per year as it costs to buy it. The situation is a prime example of where those
who look at front end costs alone are killing themselves. Valuable energy is therefore squandered.</b></p></tt>
(Transcribed from an <A href="http://www.darksky.org/~ida/">International 
Dark-Sky Association</A> (IDA) Report)</P><BR>
<IMG SRC="rainbow.gif">
<A HREF="home.html"><IMG SRC="home.gif" Align=Middle></A>
