<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Supplement B: Current Technology
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="grywheat.jpg">
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=5 CELLSPACING=3><TR><TD><B>Current Lighting Technologies</B></TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>
<H2> <A NAME="Current"><u>CURRENT TECHNOLOGY IN LIGHTING</u></A>
</h2><br>
</center>
<p><TT>The quality of the present stock of electric lighting devices for use is diverse.
In general, the market consists of incandescent lamps, flourescent lamps, and the
various types of electric arc and electric discharge vapor lamps. Their sales appeals and benefits in
energy conservation are listed under each device heading.</TT></p>

<h3><b><em><A NAME="bulbs">Modern Incadescents</A></em></b></h3>
<p>Incandescent bulbs are now considered the least energy-efficient light source
  and are considered the traditional format of electric lighting (for
<a href=http://www.boma.com.au/magazine/apr96/light.htm">General Lighting Services </a>).  It dissipates
a lot of the electricity it uses as heat to accompany the light emitted from its glowing filament.<BR>
 <dl compact><dt><img src ="dotred.gif"><dd>The rare gas krypton is mixed with the nitrogen and argon
       inside the glass bulb so to allow the filament to operate at a highter temperature
       (brighter light)
<dt><img src ="dotwhite.gif"><dd>Potential life maximized to 1000 hrs of operation and 22 lumens of light 
output per watt
<dt><img src ="dotblue.gif"><dd>Available in compact fused-quartz glass tubes
<dt><img src ="dotred.gif"><DD>Relatively inexpensive ($0.60-$1), convenient installation 
and availability
<dt><img src ="dotwhite.gif"><dd>10% of energy emitted is in the form of light
<Dt><img src="dotblue.gif"><DD>
Has highest color rendition index (i.e. how accurately a light source represents an object's color compared to an ideal source like the sun)
with  a CRI of around  95 
</dl>
</p>



<h3><b><em><A NAME="tubes">Modern Flourescent Tubes</A></em></b></h3>
<p>The minute proliferation of flourescent tubes into homes and older 
commercial properties are due to expensive refitting costs and inconvenient
handling of the narrow tubes.  However, introduction of <a href ="#compact">
compact flourescent lights </a> are making their debut to consumers . 
<DL compact>
<DT><img src ="dotred.gif">
<DD>Standard lifespan is 7500 hours with a light output of 104 lumens per watt
<DT><img src ="dotwhite.gif">
<DD>Energy consumption reduced to a quarter of an incandescent bulb
<DT><img src ="dotblue.gif">
<DD>Initial cost is still high ($15-30) for commercial 4' or 8' lamps, but will balance out during the
third or fourth year
</dl><br>
In addition, improved <a href="http://www.hetherington.com/ballasts.html"><i>ballast</i></a> technology, a central component of most florescent fixtures which
regulates the current drwan by the lamp, contributes to greater energy savings. Electronic ballasts are available today 
for the 4ft. and 8ft. fluorescent lamp. These ballasts drive the lamp at high frequency, provide improved
lumen output, and exhibit very low energy loss in the ballast. Some manufacturers claim the electronic upgrade has double the life
expectancy of a magnetic ballast.

</p>

<h3><b><em><A NAME="electroluminescence">Electroluminescence</A></em></b></h3>
<p>Often referred to as "panel lighting," this device utilizes particles of 
suspended phosphor in a thin layer of nonconducting material. Sandwiched between two plate conductors, one of which 
is a translucent substance(glass).  The two conductors act as electrodes,
and an alternating electric current cause the phosphor to luminesce,
<DL compact>
<DT><img src ="dotred.gif"><DD>Widely used in lighting watch and clock dials
<DT><img src ="dotwhite.gif"><DD>It requires large panels and wide fixtures to adequately
light spacious areas
</DL>
</p>


<h3><b><em><A Name="compact">Compact Flourescent</a> <A Name="lights">Lights</a></em></b></h3>

<p>The classic applications for compact
fluorescents are outdoors lighting and security lighting where they run steadily for
extended periods.   
<DL compact><DT><img src ="dotred.gif">
<DD>Frequent on/off switching affects its claimed life noticeably
<DT><img src ="dotwhite.gif">
<DD>Specialized designs and smaller size<BR>
<image src ="eco.jpg"  Align=middle>An "<A href ="http://www.primex.com.hk/">Ecolite</a>" Compact
<DT><img src ="dotblue.gif">
<Dd>Compatible with existing screw sockets; hence, relamping expenses aren't an issue
<A href="http://www.webcom.com/~lightsrc/archive/article5.html"><center><img src="screwbase.gif"></center></A>
<dt><img src="dotred.gif">
<dd>Average life of CFL is roughly 10,000 hours
<DT><img src="dotwhite.gif">
<dd>A 13-Watt compact flourescent lamp replaces a 60-Watt incandescent (ballast loss amounts to about 2 watts)
</dl>
</p>


<h3><b><em><A Name="halogen">Halogen Lamps</a></em></b></h3>
<p><img align=right src="halogen.jpg" align=top>
A halogen is an incandescent bulb with a halogen gas added to reduce evaporation. Halogen lamps run at
a higher temperature providing a whiter light and greater efficiency.
Widely used for display, accent lighting, halls and lobbies, halogen lamps are used in many of the more
modern lighting fixtures.  Other types of popular halogen lamps are described here >
<A href="http://www.dalice.ca/halogens.html"><img src="halogen2.gif" align=middle></a>

<br>
</P>
<H3><b><EM><A NAME="low-pressure">Low-Pressure Sodium</A></em></B></h3>
<p><img align=left src="lpsodium.gif"Align=bottom><em>< An outdoor low-pressure sodium lamp fixture for public lighting</em><br>
<BR>This lght source converts nearly 35% of its energy consumed into
light. Low-pressure sodium bulbs should last at least 10,000 hours and deliver as much light at the end if their life as in the
beginning. However, they are the most expensive lighting source. They are also the largest, and hence, most difficult to
control in terms of light distribution. In addition, because of their singular yellow color, they have very low CRI. Objects
under low-pressure sodium illumination appear either yellow, gray, or black. 
</p>

<H3><b><EM><A Name="discharge">High Intensity Discharge Lighting</A></em></B></h3>
These light sources are the elite, energy-efficient lighting devices on
the market today for outdoor lumination.  Each of these lamps requires a specially designed ballast and has a high initial cost. However, their lower operating cost
rapidly returns the initial investment. HID lamps have one potential drawback that may limit their use -- a start up delay
from one to sevenminutes from the time they are switched on until they fully illuminate.
There are two particular types:
<BR>
<br>
<b><TT>Metal Halide Lamps</TT></b><br> 
Metal halides have the best CRI of the HID lamps. They are sometimes used for commercial interior lighting because of
their excellent color and are the preferred light source for stadiums where there are TV broadcasts. They are more efficient
than mercury vapor lamps while having the same light output.
<p><DL compact>
<DT><img src ="dotred.gif">
<DD>System's efficacy level is 100 lumens/watt
<DT><img src ="dotwhite.gif">
<DD>50% of emitted energy is in the form of light
</dl><br></p>

<b><TT>High Pressure Sodium Lamps</TT></b>

<BR>They produce a golden white color that tends to
blacken red and blue objects. Because their CRI is about 25, these lamps are rarely used for interior commercial lighting.
They are used more frequently for interior industrial applications, such as in warehouses and manufacturing. Their small
size and excellent efficiency make them the most popular choice for street and area lighting.
<p>
<img align=right src="light1.gif">

<DL compact>
<DT><img src ="dotred.gif">
<DD>A high-pressure sodium lamp has a system efficacy of 110 lumens/watt
<DT><img src ="dotwhite.gif">
<DD>A 50 Watt sodium fixture equals to the light output of a 250 W incandescent bulb
<DT><img src ="dotblue.gif">
<DD>Provides powerful illumination for outdoor activities or evening security
<DT><img src ="dotred.gif">
<DD>No lumen depreciation (in contrast to mercury-vapor lamps which gets fainter and fainter while
    using the same amount of watt to produce less light)

</dl><br>
 

</p>

<IMG SRC="rainbow.gif">
