<HTML>
<BODY>
<b>
<TITLE>Current Technology</TITLE>
<BODY BACKGROUND="yellowback.gif"
TEXT="#000077" VLINK="#336633" LINK="#ffff00">
<hr>
<font size=7><center>Current Technology</center></font>
<hr>
<p>
There have been numerous developments in biomass as an energy source, particular in wood waste and residues.  The research has been focused on productivity, costs of harvesting, drying, and transporting wood products. 
<p>
<font size=+1>Productivity</font>
<br>
 To increase plant productivity and reduce growing costs research has been done to improve species selection, genetic selection, and plant breeding.  These studies have examined the leaf arrangment, leaf area, and productivity of various trees.
<p>
 <font size=+1>Harvesting</font>
 <br>
The current research in harvesting has developed a tractor mounted device capable of harvesting 1000 small trees (up to 15 cm diameter) per hour.  Another development is a process called chunking with minimizes the cost of transporting wood products.  Chunking produces blocks of wood which are more dense and require less energy than conventional wood chips.
<p>
<font size=+1>Drying</font>
 <br>
For drying, a process called crushing or splittering small trees can dry up to 20% moisture in the tree fields within several days.  The end result is lower cost in transportation compared to green wood chips.  





<font size=4>
<br>
<p>
<dd><a href=future.html><img src=arrow.gif>Future Developments</a>
<br>
<p>
<dd><a href=index.html><img src=return.gif>Biomass Home Page</a>
</font>
</b>
