<BODY>
<B>
<TITLE>Conclusion</TITLE>
<BODY BACKGROUND = "redback.gif" TEXT=
"#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#00FF00">
<hr>
<font size=7><center>Conclusion</center></font>
<hr>
<p>
Biomass can become very competive supplier of energy if we continue to research better and more efficent ways in converting it into an energy source.  It is the
only renewable energy source that can be converted to a liquid transportation fuel using present technology.  It is also better for the enviroment when compared to oil or coal based systems.  This is due to near-balancing of carbon dioxide.  In a biomass system the crops take in approximately the same amount of carbon dioxide as is emited when burned.  This system can also be used to help out current environemental problems like the disposal of wastewater and sewage sludge can be used to fertilize the short-rotation woody crops.  It can also provide jobs in rural areas.  Since only a fraction of the total corn production is used to make ethanol, the by products can be still used for animal feed.  Todays corn production can provide approximately five billion gallons of ethanol per year without disrupting food prices.  With all these advantages, biomass as an energy source can very promising for the U.S.
<br>
<p>
   



