<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Nuclear Waste</title>
</head>
<body background="nuce.jpg" text=#000000>
<br><font size=+4><center><img src="atom.jpg">Nuclear Waste</center></font><br>
One of the main concerns regarding nuclear technology is over the disposal of nuclear waste.  

<br> Nuclear power plants produce two types of waste.  First, the fission process produces radioactive products.  Most of this radioactivity remains in the fuel rods and is classified as High-Level Waste.  High level waste is the highly radioactive materi


al, such as uranium and plutonium.  The second waste product of a nuclear power plant is the nonfuel material, such as the reactor structure, containers, etc., which is classified as either Low Level or Intermediate Level Waste.  Low level waste can be cl


assified as the materials which have come into contact with small amounts of the high level waste. <br> 
<br> The two types of waste, High Level and Low Level, are treated very differently.  Low level wastes are compacted and sent to shallow burial sites.  High level wastes are stored in sealed containers <br>
<br>
<br><center><img src="contain.jpg"></center>


<br>and buried in deep geologic structures.    <br><br><br>
<center><img src="burial.jpg"></center><br>


Technology for the treatment of high level waste is being developed at <A 
href="http://www.anl.gov/">Argonne National Laboratory</A>.  In a 
process called <A 
href="http://www.anl.gov/OPA/news95/news950208.html">"electrorefining"</a>, 
spent nuclear fuel rods can be separated into HLW and LLW forms.  This drops the volume of HLW significantly.  Also, this HLW may someday be reprocessed and used again.  That is, when technology develops a more economical and efficient way to reprocess spent fuel and to replace it in the reactors.  <br>  
<br><center><img 
src="http://www.cmt.anl.gov/brochure/appl525.gif"></center><br>






<br><br><ADDRESS><A href="mailto: dpreuss@students.uiuc.edu">Comments/Suggestions</A></ADDRESS><br><br><br>
</body>
