<html>

<head>
<title>tok2</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="water" bgcolor="#C0C0C0" text="#FFFFFF" link="#FF0000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<h1 align=center>TOKAMAK</h1>
<h1 align=center><!--VERMEER 
   BOT=ImageMap
   rectangle=" (0,0) (238, 163)  http://www.pppl.gov/index.html"
   src="TFTR.gif"
   align="bottom"
   border="0"
   width="243"
   height="165"
 --></h1>
<p align=left>&#160; </p>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>	We have already decided that a tokamak fusion reactor</font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>needs to utilize plasma. In a reaction, the lifetime of </font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>plasma is determined by the ability to keep plasma away from</font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>solid material surface. Seeing that plasma is essentially a </font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>gas this can get pretty tricky. A magnetic field makes this </font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>possible by keeping the plasma away from the walls. Plasma </font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>contains ions so is thus affected by a magnetic field. It</font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>was discovered in the 1940's that a simple toroidal magnetic</font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>field can not contain a hot plasma. A spiraling field on top</font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>of the toroidal field can help stabilize the field. The two</font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>different currents that are employed in plasma stabilization </font></pre>
</div>
<div align=left>
<pre><font size=4>in a tokamak reactor are illustrated below:</font></pre>
</div>
<p align=center>&#160; </p>
<p align=center><img src="nestedtoriddt1.gif" align=bottom width=351 height=458></p>
<pre><font size=4>The advantage here behind the tokamak reactor is that the </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>current is a source of power that can heat and sustain the </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>plasma.</font></pre>
<div align=center><center>
<pre>	<font size=5><b>Plasma Heating</b></font></pre>
</center></div>
<pre><font size=5><b>	</b></font><font size=4>The key to nuclear fusion using plasma is the </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>heating of the plasma. The sufficient heating requires </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>15Kev. There are several different methods for plasma heating</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4> that are employed in a tokamak reactor.</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>OHMIC </strong>Heating that occurs when current flows through a </font></pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>medium. This is not sufficient for achieving fusion </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>temperatures.</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>Neutral Beam </strong>Theory of utilizing energy from fast moving</font> </pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>particles. If the particles used are neutral atoms such as</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>He-4 then there is no reaction caused. The typical potential</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>needed to accelerate particle is 140,000V.</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>RF </strong>Basically microwaves. The electromagnetic energy is</font> </pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>directed into the plasma by antennae rays. The heat gained </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>can be several MW of heating power.</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>Self Heating</strong> When D-T (deuterium-tritium) occurs helium</font> </pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>nucleus carries a 3.5 MeV of energy. This occurs when excess</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>helium nuclei heat plasma enough to continue reaction. This </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>has yet to be achieved. </font></pre>
<p>&#160; </p>
<pre><font size=4>Several of these methods are employed to heat the plasma </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>sufficiently.</font></pre>
<h1 align=center><font size=5>Development</font></h1>
<pre><font size=4>	The United States Department of Energy currently has</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>at least three tokamak reactors in operation and plans to </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>build a series of engineering scaled up tokamaks, with hopes</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>of generating a commercial tokamak plant by the year 2040.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>United States congress research service estimated that the </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>tokamak and fusion research programs would cost thirty </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>billion dollars over the next 45 years. That infuriates many</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>opponents of fusion research and thus makes it a possible </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>target for future governmental budget cuts. </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>	The commercial value of tokamaks is in question </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>because the reactors have only generated energy by using</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>even more initial energy in the first place. Tokamaks have </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>never generated net energy.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>	There are several successful tokamak projects </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>currently being developed.</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><a href="http://www.jet.UK/"><font size=4>JET</font></a><font size=4> (Joint European Tokamak)</font> </pre>
</li>
<li><pre><a href="http://www.uni-giessen.de/~g123/innen.html"><font size=4>TEXTOR</font></a><font size=4> </font></pre>
</li>
<li><pre><a href="http://www.acl.lan..gov/GrandChal/Tok/whatsnew.html"><font size=4>Numerical Tokamak</font></a> </pre>
</li>
<li><pre><a href="http://elvis.neep.wisc.edu/~medusa/MEDUSA.html"><font size=4>Medusa</font></a> </pre>
</li>
<li><pre><a href="http://www.pppl.gov/index.html"><font size=4>TPX</font></a> </pre>
</li>
<li><pre><a href="http://www.pppl.gov/index.html"><font size=4>TFTR</font></a><font size=4> (Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor) The TFTR is undoubtedly</font> </pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>the most successful nuclear fusion project to date. In 1994</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>the TFTR reactor produced 10.7MW of power. This far exceeded</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>the JET production of 1.7 MW and shattered its own previous</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>record of 6 MW. The fuel makeup was 50:50 deuterium and </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>tritium.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>And Finally...</font></pre>
<h1 align=center><a href="ITER.html"><font size=4>ITER</font></a></h1>
<p>&#160;</p>
<pre>			<!--VERMEER 
   BOT=ImageMap
   rectangle=" (0,0) (32, 28)  mailto:amhumphr@uiuc.edu"
   src="mailbox.gif"
   align="bottom"
   border="0"
   width="33"
   height="34"
 --></pre>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
