<html>

<head>
<title>ITER</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="water" bgcolor="#C0C0C0" text="#FFFFFF" link="#FF0000" vlink="#800080" alink="#00FF00">
<h1 align=center>ITER</h1>
<p align=center>&#160; </p>
<pre><font size=4>	There is currently an international project underway</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>to construct and operate the larges Tokamak fusion reactor </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>ever. This is the International Tokamak Engineering Reactor.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4><!--VERMEER 
   BOT=ImageMap
   rectangle=" (61,14) (477, 476)  http://www.pppl.gov/oview/pages.html"
   src="reactor.gif"
   align="bottom"
   border="0"
   width="752"
   height="585"
 --></font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>The international project consists of temas from the United</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>States, Europe, Japan, and Russia. The central team in the</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>U.S. is centered in </font><a href="http://www.iterus.org"><font size=4>San Diego</font></a><font size=4>, California.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>	The ITER project is basically a plan do design the</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>largest (and hopefully most productive) tokamak reactor ever.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>The main vacuum vessel in the reactor is expected to have </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>dimensions of a main vacuum vessel of thirty to thirty five </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>meters in diameter and thirty meters high. ITER is designed</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>to have fusion power of about 1000MW or more and to operate</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>with pulses of flat top duration about 1,000 seconds. Below </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>is a graph thatshows the estimated production of ITER as </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>compared to other tokamak projects.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4><img src="advancem.gif" align=bottom width=595 height=375></font></pre>
<p>&#160;</p>
<pre><font size=4>The mechanic behind the ITER reactor, and every other fusion</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>reactor, is that a gas fuel (D-T) is pumped into an evacuated</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>chamber. The reactor heats the gas in pulses to achieve </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>fusion temperature. The plasma then reacts. Once the energy</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>is released the plasma cools and another pulsed reheats</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>the plasma to fusion temperature. </font></pre>
<h1 align=center><font size=4>ENGINEERING</font></h1>
<pre><font size=4>	The superconducting magnets needed for plasma </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>containment in thereactor need the most development.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4> When completed, thesemagnets will be the largest ones</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>ever manufactured. The toroidal coils will produce a </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>magnetic field of about eleven to  thirteen tesla at the</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>magnetic windings. This is a huge project which requires a </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>great deal of development.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>	Another item that needs substantial development </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>before the reactor is operational an productive is a </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>divertor in the plasma chamber wall that will control </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>impurities and provide for exhaust of the helium ash. This </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>is a problem in selection of proper physics operations and</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>materials for the divertor and for the first wall lining</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>of the plasma chamber. This wall lining is ecspecially </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>important because the containment atoms are knocked off </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>when the nuclei hit the walls.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>	There are currently three different co-centers</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>for the engineering and development of the ITER project</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>San Diego, California </strong>is headquarters and the site for</font> </pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>design integration, safety building, and nuclear systems</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>research. </font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>Garching, Germany</strong> researches in-vessel components and </font></pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>related systems.</font></pre>
<ul>
<li><pre><font size=4><strong>Naka, Japan </strong>focuses an out of vessel components and </font></pre>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><font size=4>related systems.</font></pre>
<h1 align=center><font size=4><strong>Politics</strong></font></h1>
<pre><font size=4><strong>	</strong>The estimated cost of the ITER project is about</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>1.2 billion dollars, but will most likely end up being even</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>higher. That is assuming that the project is actually </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>pursued. As of right now, the four parties haven't agreed</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>to construct ITER. This decision is expected to be made about</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>1996-98. The construction is expected to take about 7 years.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>A facility has not yet been proposed.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>	</font></pre>
<h1 align=center><font size=4><strong>CONCLUSION</strong></font></h1>
<pre><font size=4>	Despite these enormous complications, scientists </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>still propose the year 2050 for commercial fusion reactors.</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>Nuclear fusion may not prove to be a viable commercial </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>energy source, but it is well worth the time and money to</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>attempt to develop it. Anything is worth of research as a </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>viable future energy source. Even if it proves not to be </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>successful, at least the world and the scientists concerned</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>know to divert their energy into different areas. Knowing</font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>what not to do, is as helpful as knowing what to do. It </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>is very common in science that more is learned when our </font></pre>
<pre><font size=4>hypotheses fail than when they do work. </font></pre>
<p>&#160; </p>
