</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>

<link rev="made" HREF="mailto:alevinsn@coewl.cen.uiuc.edu">
<title>
Sonoluminescence Overview and Possible Applications for Energy Use
</title>
<!-- Changed by: Nuce Web User, 19-Nov-1995 -->

</head>

<body background=sono3b.jpg text="#FFFFFF" link="#00FF00" vlink="FF00FF">

<CENTER>

<img src=sono1b.jpg border=2>

<h1>
Sonoluminescence Overview and Future Applications
</h1>

</center>

<HR>

<h2>
Introduction
</h2>

<p>
The brilliant blue glow in the picture above is one of many
examples of sonoluminescence. The scientific-sounding word basically
translates to "sound into light." The idea is very simple--a small
bubble, surrounded by some liquid, is bombarded with sound. Due to
the high energies now in the bubble, it starts to luminesce, or
produce light. When researchers first discovered this phenomenon, they
called it <strong>sonoluminescence</strong>.
</p>

<p>
While sonoluminescence was first discovered in the 1930's, it received
little attention until recently. In the past few years, a number
of discoveries have been made, opening up even more mysteries. While
most people have heard nothing about sonoluminescence, it has great
potential in many scientific areas. High on the list for many
researchers is its applications to <a
href="http://fusioned.gat.com/webstuff/What-is-Fusion.html">fusion</a>,
since it is predicted that as sound bombards a bubble, the
temperatures can get so hot as to allow fusion to occur within the
bubble. Accordingly, there is some exciting research going on in this
new field, and, according to <a href="http://www.aaas.org/science/science.html"><em>Science</em></a>, it is "a remarkable
laboratory for physics and chemistry." [<a href="#ref1">1</a>]
</p>

<br>

<h2>
History and Background
</h2>

<p>
As mentioned previously, sonoluminescence was first discovered in 1934
by a pair of German physicists at the University of Cologne, where
they observed the characteristic glow while exciting water with sound
waves. Other researchers then proceeded to investigate the phenomena,
but their results were inconclusive, and interest in the subject
dwindled. Interest, however, resumed in the late 1980's, and
now there are a few strong research groups that are trying to piece
together the mysteries.
</p>

<p>
When sonoluminescence was first discovered, what was seen was not the
glow from a single bubble as seen in the picture above, but the glow
from many bubbles of air in water. Since the glow for these bubbles is
so faint, it must be viewed in a darkened room. This type of
sonoluminescence is called multiple-bubble sonoluminescence
(MBSL).  Single-bubble sonoluminescence (SBSL), however, can be seen in
a lighted room.  1990, however, was the first year that SBSL was
observed, discovered by D. Felipe Gaitan and Lawrence A. Crum, who
after extensive research, found just the right conditions for SBSL to
occur. After their discovery, many of the current results were found
because it is difficult to characterize the many glowing bubbles in
MBSL.
</p>

<p>
To create SBSL, a single bubble of gas must be placed in the
liquid. This can be done by injected a bubble of air with a syringe,
but researchers today use more elaborate setups. After being injected
into the center of a cylindrical flask, the bubble would normally
rise, but it is held in place by the force of the sound waves
bombarding it. Around 110 decibels are required for sonoluminescence,
and while this volume might seem high enough to cause deafness, the
frequency of the sound is also important for SL, and it lies just
beyond the range of human hearing.
</p>

<BR>
<BR>

<img src=sono5.jpg>

<BR>

<p>
The bubble starts out with a radius of several microns, and when the
sound waves first hit it, it starts to expand due to a drop in
acoustical pressure, swelling to a radius of 50 microns. As can be
seen from the picture, this expansion occurs on the "bottom" part of
the sound wave sinusoidal curve. After the sound wave reaches half of
its period, the situation rapidly changes. With such a large radius
compared to the start radius, the interior of the bubble is
practically a vacuum, since the gas is greatly dispersed. After this
maximum radius, the acoustic pressure begins to increase, and the
resulting pressure difference between the inside of the bubble and the
outside leads to its rapid collapse. Its radius decreases from 50
microns to about .5 microns in a very short amount of time, and at
this point, the bubble suddenly stops shrinking because of the
repulsive forces of the gas atoms inside the bubble. As the bubble
compresses, sonoluminescence occurs. After reaching .5 microns, the
radius bounces up and down for a short amount of time, and then a new
burst of sound can create the effect all over again.
</p>

<p>
The time scales involved in the process are also interesting. <a
href="http://www.physics.ucla.edu/faculty/ladder/putterman.html">Seth
J. Putterman</a>, at U.C.L.A., is one of the leading researchers in
the field, and he and his research group first discovered the flash
time for sonoluminescence. To the naked eye, the glow does not appear
to be flashing and instead appears to be continuous. However, using
the most sophisticated light sensor currently available, a very
sensitive photomultiplier tube, Putterman and his group discovered
that the flashes have an upper bound of 50 picoseconds (ps), and these
flashes come out with incredible regularity. What makes this so
remarkable is the fact that this result is "1/1000 of that predicted
by conventional theory of cavitation bubble collapse." [<a
href="#ref2">2</a>] (Cavitation is "the formation and activity of
bubbles (or cavities) in a liquid." [<a href="#ref3">3</a>]) In
addition, the incredible regularity exceeds the stability of the
frequency generator (a device that determines the sound wave's
frequency) that drives the system. As of now, these and most
characteristics of sonoluminescence are unexplained.
</p>

<p>
Along with the flash rate, the spectrum of the light emitted also is
not obvious. In 1991, a graduate student of Putterman, Robert
A. Hiller, discovered that much of the light is ultravoilet. After a
photon energy of 6 electron volts (eV), which corresponds to an
ultravoilet wavelength of .2 microns, the spectrum can no longer be
determined (currently) because energies above 6 eV cannot go through
water, the liquid surrounding the bubble. However, 6 eV corresponds
to a temperature within the bubble of 72,000 K, which is incredibly
hot. This is understandable after considering that the
"volume of a sonoluminescent bubble drops by a factor of one million
as its radius decreases 100-fold." [<a href="#ref4">4</a>]
</p>

<p>
So, one might ask, why water?  As mysterious as it may sound (and it
<strong>is</strong> mysterious to researchers), sonoluminescence does
not occur in water under normal conditions.  However, using a
different gas than air for the bubble does work, at least some of the
time.  After unsuccessfully trying other surrounding liquids,
researchers then focused on the bubble of gas.  Since air is comprised
of nitrogen and oxygen and more gases, two of the first gases tried
were nitrogen and oxygen.  However, no sonoluminescence occurred with
these two.  A mixture of the two also produced nil light.  Even using
compressed air didn't work!  However, it was not long before the
reason was discovered--normal air contains a faint amount of argon,
which was not included in the compressed air.  For some reason, a
small impurity of argon produces the sonoluminescence affect.  The
same occurs with helium and xenon, and each noble gas has its own
spectrum of light.  The optimum impurity amount is 1% of the total
gas, although the reason for this, as well as the reason for
sonoluminescence occurring upon addition of a noble gas are mysteries.
</p>

<p>
However, there may be an answer for the absence of sonoluminescence in
liquids other than water.  In August, a short news brief was published
in <em>Science News</em>, detailing a new theory.  A group of
scientists at the University of Chicago have proposed that there are
two major mechanisms that a liquid must overcome for sonoluminescence
to occur.  The first, parametric instability, "occurs when the bubble
wall oscillates, distorting the bubble's spherical shape."
Eventually, these distortions would cause the bubble to "collapse in
on itself."  The second mechanism, Rayleigh-Taylor instability,
affects the bubble when it is at its smallest radii.  Then the large
number of liquid molecules surrounding it can have enough force to
cause it to burst.  As it turns out, parametric instability provides
some protection against Rayleigh-Taylor instability.  The parametric
oscillations allow the bubble to adjust its size before it is crushed
by the surrounding liquid molecules.  However, if the outside pressure
is allowed to reach 1.15 atmospheres, the bubble collapses.  In
liquids that are more <a
href="http://c.gp.cs.cmu.edu:5103/prog/webster?isindex=viscosity">viscous</a>
than water, the parametric oscillations do not occur as rapidly, and
accordingly, the Rayleigh-Taylor instability overwhelms the bubble.  By
the time the bubble is destroyed, the pressure has not reached the
level for sonoluminescence to occur. [<a href="#ref5">5</a>]
</p>

<p>
There have been recent advances in using other liquids than water.
Heavy water has been used (Heavy water is just like regular water
except the two hydrogen atoms are replaced with two deuterium atoms.
Deuterium is an isotope of hydrogen with two neutrons instead of one.)
instead of water, and if the bubble contains a gas that is an isotope
of hydrogen (both H2 and D2 have been used), the sonoluminescence
spectrums for H20 and D20 are drastically different.
<BR>
<img src=sono7.jpg>
<BR>
As can be seen from the graph, the peak for H20 is at a wavelength of
about 250 nm., while the peak for D20 is at a peak of about 400 nm.
This affect has yet to be explained. [<a href="#ref6">6</a>]
</p>

<p>
As stated previously, no liquids other than water have been used under
<strong>normal conditions</strong>.  However, from the homepage of <a
href="http://www.physics.ucla.edu/faculty/ladder/williams.html">Gary
Williams</a>, a colleague of Putterman, writes that brilliant
sonoluminescence was observed with "xenon gas in ethanol at -115 C."
The experiment will be tried with other "cryogenic liquids such as
nitrogen, neon, and helium."
</p>

<BR>

<h2>
Current Technology
</h2>

<p>
The apparatus used to create sonoluminescence is very simple and incredibly
cheap for a scientific laboratory.  To create sonoluminescence in a
single bubble of air, it can cost from $100 to $300, and with this
setup incredible pressures and temperatures can be produced.  <a
href="http://www.history.rochester.edu/Scientific_American"><em>Scientific
American</em></a> even has an article for the "Amateur Scientist" on
<a href="makesono.html">how to assemble a single bubble
sonoluminescence device</a> for about $100, and it
<strong>really</strong> works.  The major costs are an audio amplifier
(any home stereo will do here), a function generator (can easily be
found in any physics laboratory), and an oscilloscope (very common and
easily accessible).  Therefore, the major equipment probably does not
even have to be purchased!
</p>

<p>
To create bubbles of other gases, all air must be removed from the
liquid, and the device must be put in a vacuum.  Obviously, this
experiment is not in the domain of the "amateur scientist," but the
laboratory is still relatively unexpensive.
</p>

<p>
The equipment used to investigate the sonoluminescence effect is not
cheap, however.  To measure the flashes of light, the most
state-of-the-art <a
href="http://www.sti.nasa.gov/thesaurus/P/word11396.html">photomultiplier
tubes</a> are needed.  To measure the radii of a bubble, a laser is
focused on the bubble, and the intensity of the reflected beam is
measured.  It just happens that "the intensity of the light scattered
by a spherical object depends on the square of the object's radius,"
so this is the way the different radii are measured. [<a
href="#ref7">7</a>]
</p>

<BR>

<h2>
Future Developments
</h2>

The primary goal right now for scientists is answering the many
questions generated by previous research.
<BR>
<BR>
Some of the questions posed are:
<BR>
<BR>
<ol>

<li> What is the light-emitting mechanism?
<BR>
<BR>
<li> Why is the duration of the flashes so short?
<BR>
<BR>
<li> What is the spectrum beyond the cutoff induced by water?
<BR>
<BR>
<li> Why is water the easiest liquid to use? (a possible answer above)
<BR>
<BR>
<li> Why is SL strongly influenced by the fluid temperature?
<BR>
<BR>
</ol>

<p>
By far, more time and effort has been put into answering the first
question.  Currently, there are a number of different theories, each
more exotic than the next.
<BR>
<BR>
The main explanations are as follows:
<BR>
<BR>
<ol>

<li> As the bubble collapses from sound bombardment, spherical shock
waves occur.  "A shock wave takes place when material moves faster
than the sound traveling through it."  The resulting temperatures and
pressures could be incredible, and the temperature could soar as high
as 1,000,000 C.  The pressure inside the bubble could be as much as
"100 million or more times normal atmospheric pressure." [<a
href="#ref8">8</a>] With temperatures and pressures this high, the gas
inside the bubble could turn into a plasma, "a super-hot cloud of
electrons and particles that emit light." (Putterman's group)
<BR>
<BR>
<li> The light could come from "collisions between neutral molecules"
from the shock waves in the bubble, as opposed to electrons in the
first case.  This would possibly produce temperatures around 10,000 to
20,000 C. (Lothar Frommhold of the U. of Texas and Anthony Atchley of
the Naval Postgraduate School in Monterey, Cal.)
<BR>
<BR>
<li> Instead of shock waves, "the bubble's oscillations inject tiny
jets of liquid carrying electric charge into the bubble," and these
produce light. (Theirry Lepoint and his team at the Institut Meurice
in Brussels, Belgium)
<BR>
<BR>
<li> The high pressure causes the water around the bubble to freeze,
and then the light is produced as the ice cracks. (Robert Hickling of
the U. of Mississippi)
<BR>
<BR>
<li> The glow could come from "a subtle quantum effect involving
electrons" called the Casimir effect.  For more information, consult a
<a href="http://www.hooked.net/users/rgeorge/homeb.html">paper on
sonoluminescence (and cold fusion)</a>. (Julian Schwinger, former
physicist and Nobelist from UCLA)
<BR>
[<a href="#ref9">9</a>]
</ol>

<p>
While the first theory with sonic waves is the most readily accepted,
all of them have yet to be tested thoroughly, and no one is anywhere close
to determining which of the theories is correct.  An important
link is the missing spectra that water is absorbing.  If this part of
the spectrum includes x-rays, some incredible temperatures are being
reached within a bubble.
</p>

<p>
Scientists are really thrilled about the shock wave theory because
generating a plasma within a bubble may indicate fusion.  The idea of
another method for generating fusion caught the attention of a number
of people, and researchers are searching for evidence of fusion in
these bubbles.  With temperatures as hot as proposed, atoms of the
hydrogen isotopes deuterium and tritium could fuse, releasing helium
atoms (alpha particles), neutrons, and energy.  Since neutrons, unlike
the negatively charged alpha particles, are not controlled by electric
fields, scientists are trying to detect stray neutrons that may be
generated in sonoluminescence.  So far, no one has discovered them.
</p>

<p>
Even if fusion occurs inside a bubble, the amount of energy that will
be produced is so minuscule that "`If you covered the earth with these
[sonoluminescence] machines, after an hour you'd have enough energy to
heat a cup of water a couple of degrees,'" says William Moss, a
scientist at <a href="http://www.llnl.gov">Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory</a>. [<a href="#ref10">10</a>] Obviously, there will not be
enough energy released to power the world, but the idea of a compact
fusion system that costs a few hundred dollars is practically amazing.
To produce <a
href="http://neutrino.nuc.berkeley.edu/fusion/icf/icf.html">inertial
confinement fusion</a> (ICF) in the past (ICF is one type fusion, the
type that could possibly occur within the bubble) and future, the
government has spent billions of dollars.  The <a
href="http://www-phys.llnl.gov/X_Div/nif.html">National Ignition
Facility</a> (NIF), currently being developed, will cost even more
billions of dollars.  The size of a sonoluminescence device does not
even compare to even one of the many lasers that will power NIF, but
if it creates ICF, it will accomplish the same task as NIF (to a
lesser degree, of course).  Besides, if ICF occurs in a bubble, it
will be a great, cheap way to study hot fusion.  It is important to
note that while some people identify sonoluminescence with <a
href="coldfusion.html">cold fusion</a>, it has nothing to do with it.
ICF, is a type of hot fusion, and hot fusion is the power source for
the sun.  Hot fusion has also been reproduced in laboratories, while
it is doubtful that cold fusion has ever existed, despite the claims
of its researchers.
</p>

<p>
If sonoluminescence cannot be used for generating energy, it certainly
has a number of other useful applications.  With the ultrafast flashes
of light in sonoluminescence, the system could be used as a high speed
laser, faster than any of the expensive lasers currently in
production.  It could also be used to destroy toxic chemicals.  With
temperatures as high as 100,000 C, toxic chemicals would be broken
down in a short amount of time.  One area where sound is playing a
major role today is <a
href="http://www.chem.duke.edu/~coury/sonic1.html">sonochemistry</a>,
and the temperatures found in sonoluminescence could help to create
some exotic materials.
</p>

<BR>

<h2>
Conclusion
</h2>

<p>
Sonoluminescence is one of those rare and interesting fields that is
fascinating a number of scientists.  In the past several years,
scientists have made many discoveries and opened many mysteries.
Maybe they will be solved some time in the near future, and maybe it
will take many years, but everyone involved will agree that they are
excited about the future challenges, and they are learning and
discovering things never even considered before.
</p>

<BR>
<BR>

Created by <a href="http://www.cen.uiuc.edu/~alevinsn">Aaron
Levinson</a>.<BR>
