<HEAD>
	<TITLE>What.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Back.jpg" TEXT="#ffffff" LINK="#FFFF00" VLINK="#C0C0C0">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 CELLSPACING=0 WIDTH=0 BORDER=0>
<TR><td> </td>
<TD><H1>Solar Electric Cars</H1></td></tr>
<TR><td> </td>
<TD>Solar electric vehicles are a source of excellent commuter and inner-city transportation.  According to a study by the US Government in accordance with auto manufacturers, the average person travels less than 50 miles per day.  <STRONG><A HREF="current.html">Current technology</A></STRONG> electric vehicles get anywhere from 50-75 miles per charge. This type of charging is called opportunity charging and would require upgrading infrastructure by install charging facilities at our places of employment, shopping area and other public facilities.
	While electric vehicles may be viable for short distances, they are not suited for long distance travel.  This is due to the current state of technology associated with the battery, which has remained virtually the same for the past 100 years.  However, current technology is just starting to rapidly conform to the idea of more efficient batteries ever since California has mandated that electric cars must be sold starting in 1998. 
	So how do solar cars work?  First, it is important to understand what a solar cell is how it works in conjunction with the car to produce power.  Solar cells are semiconductor devices that convert light into electrical energy. In a semi-conductor, the electrons are in bonds, but once you give the electron enough energy to get out of its bond, it can occupy a number of energy states and it is free to move. Once an electron has been freed, another one wants to replace the "hole".  This pattern of electrons moving from "hole" to "hole" explains the basic theory behind quantum tunneling.  If a diode, or junction is introduced to this phenomenon, such that two materials (one with an extra valence electron, the other deficit of an electron) abut each other, the transfer of electrons or electricity can occur.  This is the case in photovoltaic cells .  The side with extra valence electrons is called a "n-type" material (for negative) and the side with a deficit of valence electrons is called "p-type" (for positive). <BR><BR>

<CENTER><IMG  SRC="chart.jpg" WIDTH=134 HEIGHT=111 BORDER=0></CENTER><P><BR><BR>

If light shines on the cell, such as the case with solar cells, a current will continually flow resulting in a voltage drop. The voltage is a property of the materials used to make it, while the amperage is a function of the amount of light falling on the device. The greater the surface area of the junction exposed to light, the greater the current obtained from the cell.  The type, cost, and <STRONG><A HREF="http://www.pv.unsw.edu.au/eff.html">efficiency of PV cells </A></STRONG>vary greatly and influence the design of solar cars.   To learn how to build your own solar car, check out these sites
</td>
<TR><td> </td>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.umn.edu/umnsvp/bld_body.html"><H3>University of Minnesota's Learn to Build Your Own Solar Car</H3></A><P>
<A HREF="http://www.mit.edu:8001/activities/solar-cars/generalinfo/scinfo.html"><H3>MIT's Everything You Need to Know About Building a Solar Car</H3></A>
</td></tr>
</table>
</BODY>
