<title>What Was the Siginificant Damage?</title><p><font size=+3><font 
color="#bb00ff"><b><u>What Was the Significant
Damage?</u></b></font></font></p><hb><hr><p><font size=+1><font
color="#000000">The media would've had you believe that there was a major
environmental impact.  Truth to tell, there was no nuclear fallout; 
evacuations were not necessary because there were no health problems;  the
only environmental impacts were a minor amount of radioactive gases that
were released into the air.  The amount of these gases was minimal;  the
general public's radiation dosage from the gases released was extimated to
be 2mrem per person.  This amount of radiation is less than the amount of
exposure one gets from drinking a cup of <a 
href="http://www.tmcm.com">coffee</a>.  The significant <a 
href="http://www.oz.net/~chrisp/atomic.html">damage</a>
was the fact that TMI could never again operate;  if the building is ever
opened, radioactive material (mostly in the form of gas) will be released
into the surrounding environment.  The economic disaster by far outweighed
the nearly negligible environmental one.  The biggest disaster of all that
occured as a result of TMI was the 
psychological effects that the accident 
had on the public with regards to 
concern of the safety of nuclear power. 
 This instilled fear of nuclear power 
both locally and nationally, which 
greatly reduced advancement in nuclear 
energy.</font></font></p><hb><hr><center><img
src="http://nuke.handheld.com/images/WorldNuke.gif"></center><HB><HR><p><a
href="mailto:students.uiuc.edu">Shana Browde</a>
browde@students.uiuc.edu</p>

