<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Fuel Issues  
</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="58.jpg">

<H2><FONT SIZE=+3>Fuel Issues for MHTGR</FONT></H2>

<P>
<HR>An interesting aspect of the MHTGR is its fuel. From the orientation
and geometry of the fuel core to the design and construction of the fuel
pellets, the MHTGR uses these characteristics to increase safety.</P>

<P>The way the fuel core is oriented provides an increased safety. A cross-section
of the core reveals the hexagonal-shaped, graphite fuel blocks. These looks
like:</P>

<P><IMG SRC="cross.gif" HEIGHT=512 WIDTH=633> </P>

<P>These fuel columns are vertically stacked to form an annular shape.
The center of the reactor contains unfueled graphite and the entire core
is surrounded by unfueled graphite. This allows the annular shape of the
reactor to promote heat dissapation in case of loss of active cooling systems.
In other words it is part of the passive design of the MHTGR.</P>

<P>The other major design aspect of the fuel for MHTGR is the fuel pellet
design. Most fuel pellets are just pellets of uranium stacked upon each
other. But with with the MHTGR, the fuel is the form of coated particles
of low enriched fissile uranium oxycarbide and fertile thorium oxide among
other ingredients. The fuel pellets are then stacked into rods that make
up the anuular core. The coating aids in keeping the temperaure of the
fissile uranium at a reasonable level. The coating never allows the heat
level of the fuel pellets to reach a temperature where they will melt.
Thus it also is a passive safety design. The coating is shown below:</P>

<P><IMG SRC="fuel.gif" HEIGHT=448 WIDTH=608> 
<HR><A HREF="link2.html"><IMG SRC="back.gif" HEIGHT=40 WIDTH=40 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<A HREF="link4.html"><IMG SRC="fwd.gif" HEIGHT=40 WIDTH=40 ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
<BR clear="all">

<HR></P>

<ADDRESS><A HREF="mailto:npederso@uiuc.edu">Nick Pederson</A> / npederso@uiuc.edu
</ADDRESS>

