<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Inherent Safety Features
</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="raster.gif">

<H2><FONT SIZE=+3>Inherent Safety Features of the MHTGR</FONT></H2>

<P>
<HR>The distinguishing feature of the MHTGR as compared to other high-
temperature gas cooled reactors is the passive safety designs. There are
several examples of these including, fuel core design, fuel pellet design,
reactor internal materials, inert coolant, a strongly negative power coefficient,
and the passive secondary cooling system.</P>

<P>The first passive saefty feature is the materials that make up the inside
of the reactor core, primarily graphite. These materials have a high heat
capacity and keep their structural integrity at temperatures beyond 2760
C (5000 F). Thus extreme temperature, such as those that occur in accidents
and other situations do not damage the core and thus no radiation is released
into the environment.</P>

<P>Another passive design is the RCCS which was mentioned on an earlier
page. The RCCS is only used if both active cooling systems fail. When that
happens the excess heat from the reactor is transferred to the RCCS by
means of conduction, convection and radiation. There the excess heat is
dissipated. Thus the maximum fuel temperature always remains below the
temperature that the silicon carbide degradation begins. Thus the reactor
fuel can never meltdown even with the loss of coolant.</P>

<P>The inherent safety features pertaining to fuel pellet design, fuel
core design, and other fuel related features will be discussed on a later
page.</P>

<P>All of these passive design lead to the strongly negative power coefficient.
When the reactor is in operation there is always a negative power coefficient.
This coefficient ensures that if there ever was a reactor accident, the
core will control heat generation. The power coefficient is just a result
of all of the other safety features.</P>

<P>Basically, for a coolant accident to occur, both of the active cooling
systems would have to fail. Even if this happened the RCCS would still
dissapate the heat before it reached the critical temperature. There is
no way to get rid of the RCCS or to turn it off. The RCCS convects, conducts,
and radiates the heat because of the annular shape of the fuel core and
the materials that compose the core. Finally, as you will see in the fuel
issues link, the design of the fuel pellets also inhibits fuel meltdown.</P>

<P>
<HR><A HREF="link1.html"><IMG SRC="back.gif" HEIGHT=40 WIDTH=40 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<A HREF="link3.html"><IMG SRC="fwd.gif" HEIGHT=40 WIDTH=40 ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
<BR clear="all">

<HR></P>

<ADDRESS><A HREF="mailto:npederso@uiuc.edu">Nick Pederson</A> / npederso@uiuc.edu
</ADDRESS>

</BODY>
</HTML>
