<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Plant Design and Operation
</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="creme.jpg">

<H2><B><FONT SIZE=+3>Plant Design and Operation</FONT></B></H2>

<P>
<HR>The design for the MHTGR plant divides it into 2 major areas, the Nuclear
Island (NI) and the Energy Conversion Area (ECA). The NI has 4 reactor
modules while the ECA has two turbine generators. Each of the four reactor
modules produces 350 MW(t) of thermal energy which is converted by the
300 MW(e) turbine generators into electricity.</P>

<P>The reactor modules are located in concrete reinforced structures below
the ground. This also allows each module is independent of each other module,
including plant protection and decay heat removal systems. This is part
of the passive design described in the other link. An example of a MHTGR
reactor building is shown below: </P>

<P><IMG SRC="bldg.gif" HEIGHT=382 WIDTH=665> </P>

<P>Inside each reactor module there is a steel reactor vessel, steam geberator,
and a steel connecting cross vessel. Mounted on the bottom of the reactor
vessel is a shutdown heat exchanger and a shutdown cooling circulator.
Mounted on the top of the reactor is the control rod drive mechanisms and
the hoppers containg the boron carbide pellers for reserve shutdown. A
reactor is shown below:</P>

<P><IMG SRC="mhtgr.gif" HEIGHT=533 WIDTH=480> </P>

<P>During power generation and core heat decay removal, the medium for
transferring heat is helium gas. As it flows down through the core, it
is heated and then collected in the plenum. From there it flows through
the cross vessel and to a helical steam generator. After flowing over the
steam generator tubes and disposing of most of its thermal energy, the
helium then flows to a electronic circulator where it is pumped back through
the cross vessel and into the a differnent plenum above the reactor.</P>

<P>The final major component of the reactor, besides the core itself is
the reactor cavity cooling system (RCCS). Its job is the backup to the
forced cooling and it will be discussed more on the link about passive
safety features.</P>

<P>The reactor core is supported by a steel core located at the lower end
of the reactor along with the surrounding graphite neutron reflectors.
Located inside the core is the fuel blocks but I will also discuss those
in a later link.</P>

<P>Overall, the thermal energy is coverted to 538 MW(e) of electric power.
The cycle used to produce energy is the same as conventional coal plants
except it does not use a reheat staem cycle.</P>

<P>
