<hr size=3 width=70%>
<h1 align="center">  Compendium of Pertinent Web Sites  </h1>
<hr size=3 width=70%>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<b>
<p><font face="arial, helvetica">The following list of &quot;hot&quot; sites contains a lot of links to interesting and informative reservoirs of knowledge about nuclear energy.  In general, web sites on nuclear energy span the entire spectrum from die-hard pro-nuclear warmongers to die-hard anti-nuclear environmentalists.  Most sites are in the moderate bias range, however, and good sources of information in this regard include the United States government, the United States Department of Energy, national science programs of foreign nations, and established universities and colleges.  Organizations that either promote or destroy nuclear energy are not to be considered as reliable as those previous sources.</font></p><br>

<center><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"></center><br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Advanced Reactors.</font>  Nuclear Issues Briefing Paper 16, May 1996.  Uranium Information Centre (UIC).  Melbourne, Australia.  This site discusses possible nuclear reactors of the near future, including some in operation and some in the design phase.  Although not fast breeder reactors, this page does have current information.  Click <a href="http://www.uic.com.au/nip16.htm">here</a> to go to this location.  The integral of sin (x) is negative cos (x) plus a constant.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>Advances in Breeder Technology.</font>  Professor David N. Ruzic.  Department of Nuclear Engineering.  University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  This site contains a lot of diagrams and graphs about advanced fast breeder reactor designs and concepts.  Click <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/topics/advanced_in_breeder">here</a> to go to this location.  This site contains no links to Tomorry the Ostrich or other exciting characters from &quot;Late Night with Conan O'Brien.&quot;
<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Argonne National Laboratory.</font>  This site is the home page for Argonne National Laboratory, operated by the University of Chicago in conjunction with the United States Department of energy.  Click <a href="http://www.anl.gov/">here</a> to look at this really nifty page.  General Stonewall Jackson of the Confederacy was wounded by his own troops one night during the Battle of Chancellorsville, a pivotal battle of the American Civil War, and he died soon thereafter.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Argonne National Laboratory History.</font>  This site provides a thorough and interesting history of energy development at Argonne over the past half century.  A lot of images are here too.  Click <a href="http://www.anl.gov/OPA/history/">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>Belgian Nuclear Research Centre.</font>   Yes, they do conduct nuclear research in Belgium, and this site is the home page for the Research center there.  Click <a href="http://hades.sckcen.be/">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>   

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Breeder Reactors.</font>  Professor David N. Ruzic.  Department of Nuclear Engineering.  University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  This site provides some equations and basis for breeder reactors as well as simple diagrams, but no written explanations.  Click <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/topics/breeder_reactors">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Chernobyl and Its Consequences.</font>  Russian Research Center &quot;Kurchatov Institute.&quot;  This site contains a history of the Chernobyl accident, including its causes and consequences, and is written in English by a Russian group of scientists.  Click <a href="http://polyn.net.kiae.su/polyn/manifest.html">here</a> to learn more about Chernobyl and to dispel the myths.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>Energy Usage.</font>  Professor David N. Ruzic.  Department of Nuclear Engineering.  University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  This site outlines the history of energy consumption in the United States and the world through graphs and charts.  Click <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/topics/global_energy">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Environmental Technical Information Project.</font>  ECOLOGIA.  This site contains technical information about radiation and its impact on the environment as well as links to other useful sites.  In terms of theme, the page is geared slightly towards exaggerating nuclear issues.  Click <a href="http://ecologia.nier.org/english/level1/radiate.html">here</a> to go to this location and find out about lots of neat stuff.  Spanky the Wonder Gnome commands you to do so.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Experimental Breeder Reactor #1.</font>  Idaho National Engineering Laboratory.  If you are interested in visiting Experimental Breeder Reactor I in Idaho, this site provides useful travel and location information.  Click <a href="http://www.ohwy.com/id/e/experime.htm">here</a> to go to this location.  (Of course, you'd probably rather go to France.)<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>Experimental Breeder Reactor-I.</font>  If you don't exactly want to travel all the way to Idaho but would like information about EBR I, this site provides background information.  Click <a href="http://www.oz.net/~chrisp/ebr.htm">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>French nuclear energy program.</font>  French Polytechnique University.  This site does contain information about the French nuclear programs, but there may be a language barrier.  If you can read French, click <a href="http://www.polytechnique.fr/poly/~www/Binets/X-Passion/xp7nucle.html">here</a> to go to this location.  Even if you can't read French, just link to the page and nod your head knowingly.  People will be impressed!  Maybe.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Frequently Asked Questions About Nuclear Energy.</font>  John McCarthy.  Stanford University.  This site goes into detail about many questions that people often have about nuclear energy, including its need, safety, and potential.  Click <a href="http://www-formal.stanford.edu/jmc/progress/nuclear-faq.html">here</a> to go to this location.  Sources say John Tesh music is the leading cause of migraines.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).</font>  United Nations system.  This site is the home page for the IAEA, often called the &quot;Atoms for Peace&quot; organization since its objectives are the &quot;peaceful development and verification of nuclear energy's uses.&quot;  Click <a href="http://www.iaea.or.at/">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Introduction to the ALMR/PRISM.</font>  Darren Bleuel, John Scott, Larry Sevigny.  Department of Nuclear Engineering.  University of California at Berkeley.  This site has a lot of information about the ALMR and PRISM, two developments in fast breeder technology of very recent imact.  Click <a href="http://www.nuc.berkeley.edu/neutronics/gav/almr/01.intro.html">here</a> to go to this location.  One tablespoon is equivalent to three teaspoons.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Liquid Metal Fast Breeder Reactor.</font>  Ren Ruan Shi.  Department of Nuclear Engineering.  University of California at Berkeley.  Look, a nuclear engineering class at another university requires web projects!  This site is one student's project on the LMFBR.  Click <a href="http://www.nuc.berkeley.edu/thyd/ne161/shir/project5.html">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>NEWNET (Neighborhood Environmental Watch NETwork).</font>  This site is operated by the Los Alomos National Laboratory and is a repository of information.  The organization is, in its own words, a &quot;network of meteorological and radiological monitoring stations, central data storage and processing systems, and public access to the data via Internet and Environmental Teller Machines (ETM's).&quot;  Find out useful information about balancing national security and energy needs with the environment and safety.  Click <a href="http://newnet.jdola.lanl.gov/newnet.html">here</a> to look at this excellent and impartial page.  Only through the Internet could such information be widely accessible by the public.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Nuclear Age Timeline.</font>  United States Department of Energy.  This site provides a general history of the developments during the fifty years of the nuclear age.  Exciting stuff!  Click <a href="http://www.em.doe.gov/timeline/">here</a> to go to this location.  You'll be glad you did!<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Nuclear Analysis and Shielding Section.</font>  Computational Physics and Engineering Division.  Oak Ridge National Laboratory.  This site is home to the agency that must &quot;develop state-of-the-art computational methods for the
modeling of radiation transport and physics phenomena.&quot;  Click <a href="http://epmnas.epm.ornl.gov/home.html">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>Nuclear Engineering 201:  Advanced Energy Systems.</font>  Department of Nuclear Engineering.  University of Illinois.  This site is the home page for the class for which this web page was created.  Find out about other types of energy sources.  Click <a href="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Office of Human Radiation Experiments.</font>  Department of Energy.  This department, established in March 1994, is to report the nature of the radiation research conducted during the Cold War using human subjects.  Click <a href="http://www.ohre.doe.gov/">here</a> to find the unfortunate truth about radiation experiments in America.<br><br> 

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Power Reactor and Nuclear Fuel Development Corporation (PNC) Home Page.</font>  From Japan, this site contains a lot of periodical information and updates about the Japanese Monju breeder reactor.  Click <a href="http://www.pnc.go.jp/indexe.html">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>Pro-Nuclear Group Fights for EBR-II.</font>  Brandon Loomis.  Post Register.  This newspaper article discusses an interesting approach by pro-nuclear activists who use the persuasive tactics often employed by environmentalists to prove their point.  Click <a href="http://www.idahonews.com/august19/inel2.htm">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Radiation and Health Physics.</font>  University of Michigan.  This site contains plenty of links and useful information about the nature of radiation and agencies examining health issues.  Click <a href="http://www.sph.umich.edu/~bbusby/">here</a> to go to this location.  This page is not radioactive.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Radiation and Life.</font>  Eric J Hall.  Professor of Radiology.  College of Physicians and Surgeons.  Columbia University, New York.  This site is a fun introduction about how radiation is all around us and affects us humans.  Click <a href="http://www.uic.com.au/ral.htm">here</a> to go to this location.  Absolutely no service provided without shoes or shirt.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>The Rad*Scanner.</font>  Meter Conversions, Inc.  Personal Nuclear Radiation Monitor.  Fear about radiation can result in profitable businesses parlaying to anxious customers.  This site contains some real information about radiation but is really intended to sell a personal radiation monitor to on-line shoppers.  Click <a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/Metercon/">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>Separating Myths From Reality: Awakening From Japan's 'Plutonium Dream.'</font>  Paul Leventhal.  President of the Nuclear Control Institute, Washington, D.C.  April 16, 1996, Aomori, Japan.  This site is a fairly lengthy dissertation mildly reproaching Japan for its supposedly misguided nuclear energy policy.  Click <a href="http://www.wideopen.igc.org/nci/sp41696a.htm">here</a> to see the text of the presentation.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>Todd's Atomic Homepage.</font>  Todd Postma.  Advanced Nuclear Engineering Computational Laboratory.  University of California at Berkeley.  This site contains many, many, many links to other nuclear power, nuclear energy, nuclear program, and nuclear issue sites subdivided into topics.  Click <a href="http://www.nuc.berkeley.edu/neutronics/todd.html">here</a> to use this useful page for navigating to tangential nuclear topics!<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission.</font>  This is the home page of the organization in charge of overseeing the construction and operation of nuclear power plants as well as mediating a lot of other nuclear issues.  Click <a href="http://www.nrc.gov/">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>The Unofficial IFR Home Page.</font>  Currently, the best or only site with significant information about the Integral Fast Reactor, this pages provides a good illustration of the concept and other intriguing information about the usefulness of the IFR.  Click <a href="http://neutrino.nuc.berkeley.edu/ifr.html">here</a> to go to this location.  You can do it.  Bela Karolyi says you can.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#FF0000>The Unofficial Trinity Site Page.</font>  This site contains a lot of information and other links to pages about Trinity Site, the infamous location of the first atomic bomb blast.  Click <a href="http://members.aol.com/JTankard/trinity/home.html">here</a> to go to this location.  Remember that, according to John Lennon, &quot;Life is what happens while you are making other plans.&quot;<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#000080>What's New (In My Opinion).</font>  Robert L. Park.  The American Physical Society.  Although outdated since it is from 1994 and indicative of only one guy's views about recent science briefs, this site is 100% devoid of termites.  Click <a href="http://aps.org/WN/wn021194.html">here</a> to go to this location.<br><br>

<img src="icons/whitebal.gif"><font color=#800080>The World of Nuclear Engineering.</font>  Aaron Levinson.  Student Chapter of the American Nuclear Society.  University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.  This site contains more nuclear engineering links and is maintined right here in the Land of Lincoln.  Click<a href="http://ne43.ne.uiuc.edu/ans/ans_links.html">here</a> to go to this location.  If you are looking for a recipe for crepes, however, you will not find it there.<br><br><br>

<center><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"><img src="icons/red_bul1.gif"></center><br><br>

<p><font color=#000000>Almost all of the links on this page were used either as sources for other sections of &quot;Fast Breeder Reactors&quot; or as links directly within various sections to more similar pages.</font><br>

