<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>Meghan K. Sullivan</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Back.jpg" TEXT="#ffffff" LINK="#FFFF00" VLINK="#C0C0C0">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ><TR>
	<TD> </TD>
	<TD><H1>Solar Car Races</H1>
	For the past 10 years, there have been several competitive solar car races to promote the idea of efficient solar powered cars.  Sunrayce is a solar car race in which over 40 North American universities and colleges compete in a nine day trek across the Midwest and Western United States.  <BR><P>

<CENTER><IMG  SRC="sunchief.jpg" WIDTH=337 HEIGHT=238 BORDER=0></CENTER><BR>

<A HREF="http://www.uiuc.edu"><STRONG>The University of Illinois</STRONG></A> entered the Sunchief in Sunrayce 95 and plans to compete in Sunrayce 97 with its new car, Photon Torpedo. These solar cars are designed and built to agree with race regulations and to exhibit maximum efficiency.  Even by the look of these racing cars, one knows that these cars are not viable for commercial use.  For instance, the driver seat, which is the one and only seat in the car, is designed so that the driver almost has to lay down to drive.  It is designed this way to decrease the drag coefficient.  In addition to being uncomfortable, the car generally does not smoothly or handle as well as common automobiles. However, the guiding principles behind the design of these solar electric cars, such as motor and photovoltaic efficiencies, are very applicable to building an effective commercial electric vehicle.  Such is the reason why companies like General Motors, who are building their own solar vehicles, are the sponsors of these university competitions.
<BR>
<P>For more information on Universities Solar Car Projects and Racescheck out these sites  <BR><BR><BR>

<P><A HREF="http://www.eastend.com.au/solar/index.html"><STRONG>The World Solar Car Challenge</STRONG></A>
<P><A HREF="http://www.crest.org/clients/nesea/atds.html"><STRONG>Tour de Sol</STRONG></A>
<P><A HREF="http://sunrace.me.uiuc.edu/competitors.html"><STRONG>Other University Solar Car Web Sites</STRONG></A> 

</table>
