<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Resource Availability</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Advanced Oil Technologies</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 16
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 Remember that only half the supposed oil in the world is located
at this point and that drilling for it becomes more expensive
and riskier every year.  What about getting more out of the reserves
we have actually located and developed?   This lecture discussion
advances in  recovery techniques and related sources.  Most of
the currently producing oil fields in the US were once thought
depleted since the &quot;natural lift&quot; and &quot;pumped&quot;
phases of their lives are over.  In conventional terms they had
run out of oil.  Secondary and now, even tertiary extraction is
economically viable.  Utilizing oil in other non-liquid forms
is more difficult and not economically viable at this point. 
Those non-liquid forms are tar sands and oil shale.  Both are
abundant but may always be too costly to develop into a significant
energy source.
<P>
