<h3><CENTER>What's All of the controversy About?</h3></CENTER>
<H4>
<P>
<P>


With the investigation of alternative fuels for energy production comes the
continued use of the more typically used fossil fuels such as oil and natural
gas.  Due to the United States growing dependence on the Middle East for oil -
we import about 40% of all of the oil consumed in the US - our country has a
continued interest in investigating and exploring domestic areas where large
oil and natural gas deposits are thought to exist.  One such area is the <A
HREF="http://www.alaskan.com/anwr">Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge</A>, also known as the ANWR.  This region is a 19 million acre
wildlife refuge, established by the Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation
Act of 1980 (ANILCA), and is located in the <A
HREF="http://www.alaskan.com/anwr/bin/whiteakmap.jpg">extreme northeast
corner</A> of Alaska.<P>
<hr>
<P>
The <A HREF="http://www.alaskan.com/anwr/bin/largemap.jpg">coastal
plain</A> of the ANWR has been identified by the U.S. Geological Survey
(USGS) and the oil and gas industry as a highly prospective site for the
development and production of a major oil field.  This conclusion is primarily
based on the fact that the Nation's largest oil field, Prudhoe Bay, lies 60
miles to the west of the ANWR coastal plain.  However, knowledge of the
subsurface geology is very limited and the prospect for oil is based on hopes
that this land is similar to the petroleum bearing terrain of its neighboring
lands in the US and Canada.[14]<P>
<hr>
<P>
However, two distinctly opposing views dominate the issue whether to use this
land for the purposes of oil production.  Both viewpoints will be presented in
the following informational pages, so that the reader can determine where his
or her interests lie and possibly act accordingly.
</h4>
<hr>
<h5>
<p><a href=back.html>Background Information</a>
<p><a href=env.html>Environmentalist's and Conservationist's Concerns</a>
<p><a href=govt.html>Government and Business Concerns</a>
<p><a href=impact.html>Impact</a>
<p><a href=alt.html>Energy Alternatives</a>
<p><a href=future.html>The Future of the ANWR</a>
