<HEAD>
<title>Nuclear History</title>
<body background="nuce.jpg" text=#000000>
<br><font size=+4><center>Nuclear History</center></font>
<br><br><br>
Here is the history of "nuclear" energy:
<br><br>

-- 1895    x-rays discovered by <A href="http://www.fh-wuerzburg.de/roentgen/index_e.html">Wilhelm Roentgen</A>
<br><br>-- 1898    Pierre and <A href="http://www2.lucidcafe.com/lucidcafe/library/95nov/curie.html">Marie Curie</A> discover the radioactive elements radium and plutonium
<br><br>-- 1905     <A href="http://www2.lucidcafe.com/lucidcafe/libr
ary/96mar/einstein.html">Albert Einstein</A> developed theory the relationship of mass and energy--(E=mc^2)
<br><br>-- 1938    Otto Hahn and Fritz Strassman demonstrated nuclear fission
<br><br>-- Sept. 1942  Manhattan Project formed to secretly build the atomic bomb
<br><br>-- Nov. 1942  <A href="http://www.lanl.gov">Los Alamos</A> selected as site for an atomic bomb laboratory and Robert Oppenheimer, a physicist was named director
<br><br>-- Dec. 1942   <A href="http://www2.lucidcafe.com/lucidcafe/lucidcafe/library/95sep/fermi.html">Enrico Fermi</A> demonstrates first nuclear chain reaction atUniversity of Chicago
<br><br>-- 1942-45   Clinton Engineer Works built in Oak Ridge, Tennessee to produce purified uranium -- renamed <A href="http://www.ornl.gov">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</A> after WWII
<br><br>-- 1943-45   <A href="http://www.hanford.gov">Hanford Site</A> built in Richland, WA to produce plutonium
<br><br>-- July 1945  U.S. exploded first atomic device at a site near Alamogordo, NM-- called the <A href="http://www.envirolink.org/issues/nuketesting/trinity/tr_test.html">Trinity Test</A>
<br><br>-- Aug. 1945  U.S. drops atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Japan
<br><br>-- July 1946  Atomic Energy Act passed, establishing the Atomic 
Energy Commission (AEC)
<br><br>-- Jan. 1950  President Truman ordered AEC to develop H-bomb 
(fusion) 
<br><br>-- Dec.1951 1st usable electricity from nuclear energy 
produced at National Reactor Testing Station
<br><br>-- Jan 1954  1st nuclear powered submarine launched
<br><br>-- July 1955 Arco, Idaho became first U.S. town to be powered by 
nuclear energy
<br><br>-- July 1957 the <A 
href="http://www.em.doe.gov/timeline/jul1957.html">Sodium 
Reactor Experiment</a> in Santa 
Susana, CA generated the first power from a civilian nuclear reactor
<br><br>-- Dec 1957 1st large-scale nuclear powerplant in the world began 
operating in Shippingport, PA
<br><br>-- 1st U.S. nuclear powerplant built entirely w/o gov't. funding; 
Dresden-1 Nuclear Power Station began operating in Illinois
<br><br>-- 1966-67  large number of orders for nuclear power reactors made 
nuclear power a commercial reality
<br><br>-- Oct. 1974 Energy Reorganization Act abolished the AEC and 
created the Energy Research and Development Administration (ERDA) and the 
Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC)
<br><br>-- April 1977 President Carter banned the recycling of used, or 
spent, nuclear fuel from commercial reactors
<br><br>-- Oct 1977  <A href="http://www.doe.gov">U.S. Department of 
Energy</a> (DOE) 
replaced the ERDA, consolidating Federal energy programs and activities
<br><br>-- Mar. 1979 <A href="http://www.uic.com.au/nip14.htm">Three Mile 
Island</a> Nuclear Powerplant suffers partial core meltdown
<br><br>-- Dec.1980 Low-Level Radioactive Waste Policy Act passed, making 
states responsible for disposal of low-level waste
<br><br>-- 1982  Shippingport nuclear powerplant, built in 1957, was retired
<br><br>-- Jan.1983  Nuclear Waste Policy Act passed, authorizing the 
development of a spent fuel and high-level nuclear waste repository
<br><br>-- Nov.1983  construction began on the Defense Waste Processing 
Facility at <A href="http://www.srs.gov">Savannah River Plant</a>, SC; 
designed to make high-level 
waste into glasslike substance, which will be stored in repositories
<br><br>-- April 1986  <A 
href="http://www.uic.com.au/nip14.htm">Chernobyl</a> 
Nuclear Reactor meltdown; in response, 
U.S. shuts down N-Reactor at Hanford, due to design similarities
<br><br>-- Dec.1987  Nuclear Waste Policy Amendments Act designated Yucca 
Mountain, Nevada as candidate for nation's first geological repository 
for high-level radioactive waste and spent nuclear fuel
<br><br>-- Nov.1989  DOE changed its focus to one of environmental cleanup
<br><br>-- 1992  DOE had decontaminated and dismantled over 90 
contaminated facilities across the country
<br><br>-- 1993-present  DOE continues to cleanup the contamination from 
the last 50 years and is also working to develop technologies needed for 
cleanup <br>
<br><br><br> This is a short synopsis of the history of nuclear 
technology, related to power and power generation.

<br><br><br><br>
<ADDRESS><A href="mailto: dpreuss@students.uiuc.edu">Comments/Suggestions</A></ADDRESS>
<br><br><br><br>
</body>
