	<TD> </TD>
	<TD><H1>Future Developments:</H1><BR><BR><BR>
The future does look promising.  The most updated record for an EV with state-of-art batteries can go as far as 450 miles on one charge.  Another vehicle just went 230 miles on one charge with batteries that are close to production and should be available at a reasonable cost.  The car is expected to sell for around $20,000.00 in volume production.  Currently, the cost of high-tech batteries is very high.  However, keep in mind that as mass volume production increase, the price of these batteries will lower.
	Undoubtedly, with the growing increase in electric vehicles, lifestyles will have to adapt to the idea of "charging up" your vehicle instead of "filling up".  You will need to plug your car into a normal 110v ac power outlet while at work, the store, or at home; and in 8-10 hours your batteries will be full again. Fast charging is still in the development stage. There are a few companies working on this, but basically it would work out something like a gas station. When your running low on your charge you would pull into the quick charge facility and in 10-20 minutes you would get charged back up. 
<BR><BR>
