<br>RESIDENTIAL USES
<br>
<hr>
<br>
<br><center><img src = "house.gif"></center>
<br>An entire house can be powered by photovoltaics.  A residential system composes of <br>three things: photovoltaic cells, a battery to store power, and an inverter that allows <br>appliances to be powered by solar electricity. <a href ="http://www.mtt.com/theSource/renewableEnergy/businesses/byP/sRP/pvM/byN/byName.html">Photovoltaic lamps</a> are also available for lighting sidewalks or driveways.
<br>

<br><img src = "pvgen.gif">
<br><img src = "batt1.gif">
<br><img src = "nwr.gif">
<br>
<br>New designs use hydrogen to store energy.  Solar hydrogen is  promising long-term <br>global energy option for the post-fossil fuel era.  In a stand-alone solar hydrogen <br>energy system, the photovoltaic array is coupled with an electrolyser to produce  <br>hydrogen which is stored to be later converted back to electricity in a fuel cell.
<br>(Solar Energy, Vol. 53 No. 3, pp.267-278, 1994
