<CENTER><H1>Advanced Coal Technologies</H1>
<BR>
Lecture-Discussion # 15
<BR>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<BR>
Professor Ruzic
<P></CENTER>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 Coal is the most abundant fossil fuel and also the &quot;dirtiest&quot;.
 Not only is it inherrently dirty by composition (ash and sulfur),
it is very difficult to burn completely.  Many techniques have
been developed since the late 1800's to burn coal.  The first
innovations were concerned more with achieving completer combustion
and reduced manual labor.  More recent innovations have focussed
on reduction of air pollution at the lowest possible cost.  Like
many of these topics, a whole course could be spent examining
coal-burning technology.  This lecture-discussion will primarily
focus on the newest advances.
<P>
<h2><a href="coal.html">Coal's Pollutants</a></h2>
<P>
<h2>History of Coal Burning</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="basic.html">Basic Boiler</a>
<li>Mechanical Stoaker
<li><a href="pulverized.html">Pulverized Coal Firing</a>
<li><a href="cyclone.html">Cyclone Furnance</a>
<P></ul>
