<head>	
<title> A General Summary of Nuclear Power, Reactors, and Radiation </Title>
</head>

<body link=#0000FF text=#000000 background="backgrnd/amorfous.jpg">

<a name="start"></a>

<h1 align=center>A General Summary of Nuclear Power,<br>Reactors, and Radiation</h1>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<p align="justify">
In order to approach the content of this page with consistent and sufficient information regarding nuclear issues, please read answers to any or all of the questions below.  Approaching a new subject without the necessary facts and background information can cause misunderstanding and confusion at best or disillusionment and dangerous misconceptions at the worst.  The intention of this accompanying web page is the familiarization of interested parties with basic nuclear terminology and popular public questions about such issues as safety concerns, viability, economics, and fuel use.
</p>

<ul>

<li>  <a href="#energy">  From where does the energy come in nuclear power? </a><br><br>

<li>  <a href="#potentl">  What potential exists for the long-term use of nuclear power relative to other fuels? </a><br><br>

<li>  <a href="#reactors">  What are the general types of nuclear reactors and reactions and what are the basic differences among them? </a><br><br>

<li>  <a href="#types">  What are the types of radiation released from either nuclear reactions or natural radioactive decay? </a><br><br>

<li>  <a href="#dosage">  What is the typical annual human dosage of radiation, and from what sources do these figures derive? </a><br><br>

<li>  <a href="#threat">Does nuclear radiation from such reactors pose a health threat to human or environmental communities? </a><br><br>

</ul>

<br>
<center><img src="breaks/colors2.gif"></center>
<br>
<br>

<a name=energy></a>
<p><img src="icons/question.gif"><b>From where does the energy come in nuclear power?</b></p>

<p>A really famous scientist by the name of Albert Einstein proposed a relationship between mass and energy during his brilliant career that most people recognize but seldom understand.  Whenever cartoons need to refer to something technical, scientific, or mathematical in nature, this equation is the preferential and stereotypical choice.  In terms of energy (E), mass (m), and the speed of light in a vacuum (c), the equation relating these three values is E = mc<sup>2</sup>.

<p>In nuclear reactions, the energy (E) comes from consuming some of the mass (m) of certain atoms such as the elements uranium or plutonium.  The nuclei of atoms of these elements split into smaller pieces through a process called <a href="glossary.html#fission">fission</a>.  The nature of atomic and nuclear bonds is such that the sum of the masses of these smaller products is less than the mass of the original uranium or plutonium atom.  Some of the mass was lost during the process.

<p>The mass that is lost does not just disappear, because such an impossible scenario would violated the law of conversation of mass-energy.  Instead, the mass is simply converted to energy by the Einstein's equation.  Since the speed of light is so large and that quantity is squared, a relatively small amount of mass can be converted into a lot of energy through nuclear fission.  In fact, on a single reaction for reaction basis, nuclear reactions provide many thousands of times more energy than chemical reactions, which involve the breaking and making of chemical bonds.  For example, burning a match in the presence of oxygen in the air is a chemical reaction.  Since the nuclear reactions provide so much more energy per reaction, the mass of fuel used by a nuclear reactor per year producing electricity is much less than the mass of coal used by a coal power plant per year generating the same amount of electricity.

<p>Another type of nuclear reaction called <a href="glossary.html#fusion">fusion</a> is nearly opposite the fission reaction.  In this case, smaller particles combine to form a larger particle, but the mass of the product is less than the sum of the constituents.  Again, the mass did not disappear but was converted to energy.  The solar energy on the Earth that arrives from the Sun is produced by fusion.  Fusion reactions occur on the Sun at such high rates as to dwarf the entire energy production throughout the world.  In contrast to fission, fusion requires much higher temperatures and pressures.  The Sun fulfills such prerequisites, but on Earth, fusion has not yet been accomplished on a significant scale.</p>

<a name=potentl></a>
<p><img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What potential exists for the long-term use of nuclear power relative to other fuels?</b></p>

<p>In terms of the available energy reserves remaining on Earth, the fuels required for nuclear power are significantly greater than all the fossil fuels.  Only renewable sources of energy, which by definition essentially last forever, have the potential for longer life, but solar and wind energy cannot be implemented on a large scale <a href="refrnc.html#1P">(1P)</a>.  If nuclear fusion can be achieved on a commercial scale, however, this energy source will also have a basically inexhaustible fuel supply, since hydrogen or water may be used as fuel.  In general, oil is expected to last about another 50 years, natural gas will last another 100 years, and coal will last another 500 years assuming moderate growth rates in usage.  In contrast, there is sufficient fissionable uranium and plutonium to power conventional fission reactors for perhaps 100 years, but enough fertile uranium-238 to power fast breeder reactors for thousands of years <a href="refrnc.html#3I">(3I)</a>.  Clearly, when fossil fuels begin to run low in the next century, nuclear power will become critical to satisfying energy needs.</p>

<a name=reactors></a>
<p><img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What are the general types of nuclear reactors and reactions and what are the basic differences among them?</b></p>

<p>Fission is the splitting of nuclei to form products of less total mass than the original nuclei.  Fusion is the combination of nuclei to form a single nucleus of less mass than the total mass of the original nuclei.  

<p>Fission requires certain radioactive fuels with long half-lives; these fuels are termed <a href="glossary.html#fissile">fissile</a> or <a href="glossary.html#fissable">fissionable</a>.  Such fissile fuels include uranium-235 and plutonium-239, which are <a href="glossary.html#isotope">isotopes</a> of uranium and plutonium.  Normally such reactions involve the emittance of radiation in the form of alpha, beta, or gamma radiation <a href="refrnc.html#7P">(7P)</a>.  Fission reactors include the light water reactor (LWR), which is used predominantly in the nuclear industry to produce electricity.  Fast and thermal breeder reactors are variations on fission reactors.  

<p>Fusion requires atoms of small atomic mass such as <a href="glossary.html#deut">deuterium</a>, an isotope of hydrogen.  The combination of two deuterium atoms, for example, forms one atom of helium.  Other possibilities for forming helium include the combination of hydrogen and tritium, a hydrogen isotope containing two <a href="glossary.html#neutron">neutrons</a>.  Fusion reactors do not yet exist on a large scale, for none have yet produced more energy than they consume.  Conditions of high pressures and temperatures must be established.  The Tokamak is a method of magnetic confinement used to concentrate the species for nuclear fusion to occur.

<p>Many people have questions about nuclear energy.  Answering more popular general questions about nuclear energy would move the scope of this main page away from fast breeder reactors.  For an excellent and straightforward, but somewhat biased, FAQ about nuclear energy, look <a href="http://www-formal.stanford.edu/jmc/progress/nuclear-faq.html">here</a> at a page maintained at Stanford University.  That page covers many more questions about nuclear power than are covered here, although remember to return to the world of fast breeder reactors on this page!</p>

<a name=types></a>
<p><img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What are the types of radiation released from either nuclear reactions or natural radioactive decay?</b></p>

<p>The three types of radiation are alpha, beta, and gamma.  Alpha radiation consists of helium nuclei, particles with a positive two charges, and is the most massive of the three types.  Beta radiation consists of high energy electrons, subatomic particles with negative one charges, and is the second most massive of the three types.  Gamma radiation can be interpreted as either a photon particle or an electromagnetic wave, the particular choice in a given case depending on what data are required.  Normally, gamma radiation is treated as a wave with an associated wavelength.  When placed on the electromagnetic spectrum, gamma waves have very high energies and frequencies and very low wavelengths.  In order of decreasing energy, the substituents of the electromagnetic spectrum include gamma waves, x-rays, ultraviolet, near ultraviolet, visible, near infrared, infrared, microwaves, and radio waves.

<p>Of particular importance in considerations of nuclear reactions and other issues is the penetrating abilities of the various radiation types.  Alpha is the least penetrating and gamma the most penetrating.  A pictorial demonstration of the substances required to stop the penetration of the three types of radiation and neutrons depicts the differences clearly:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/rad-type.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Types of Radiation">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure A.  The various types of radiation and neutrons can pass through<br>materials to different degrees.  Fast neutrons and gamma rays are<br>the hardest to stop, while the skin stops alpha particles.<a href="refrnc.html#7P"> (7P) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>In short, external alpha radiation is not of major concern, since these particles cannot penetrated beyond the skin.  Gamma radiation, on the other hand, may pass through the body, and there exists a very small chance that such radiation may cause damage to cellular material.

<p>It must be emphasized that people everywhere are bombarded by radiation from natural sources.  Approximately 15,000 gamma rays per second, most arriving from the Sun but from other interstellar sources as well, pass through each average person.  Radiation from natural sources is relatively harmless, and such natural sources cannot be avoided.  Of all cases of cancer, only a trivial portion result from radiation.  Those inhabitants of cities at higher altitudes receive more radiation exposure since the greater depth of atmosphere at lower altitudes reduces the intensity of radiation reaching the ground.  Nevertheless, barring an unlikely nuclear catastrophe, radiation for the most part should not frighten people.  In fact, radioactive materials have received heightened interest recently by helping people through disease diagnosis and treatment <a href="refrnc.html#7P">(7P)</a>.  Radiation is an unavoidable part of life.  For information pertaining to this topic, look <a href="http://www.uic.com.au/ral.htm">here</a> at a page representing the work of Eric J Hall, Professor of Radiology in the College of Physicians and Surgeons at Columbia University, New York.</p>

<a name=dosage></a>
<p><img src="icons/question.gif"><b>What is the typical annual human dosage of radiation, and from what sources do these figures derive?</b></p>

<p>In the answer to the previous question, the term &quot;natural radiation&quot; was used without proper clarification.  Natural radiation is to be differentiated from man-made radiation.  Natural radiation comes from basically terrestrial and cosmic sources, while artificial or man-made radiation comes almost exlusively from medical use, with the fallout from explosive tests and power production comprising a very small share <a href="refrnc.html#6P">(6P)</a>.

<p>The relative amounts of radiation deriving from various sources can be compared easily with use of a chart.  A millirem is simply a unit of radiation that measures the amount of exposure; the technical definition for this unit is not necessary so long as relative comparisons are used:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/sources.jpg" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Sources of Radiation">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure B.  Natural and man-made sources of radiation.  Natural sources<br>of radiation, from radon to potassium in bananas, comprise the majority<br>share of radiation for the average person.<a href="refrnc.html#1I"> (1I) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>As the chart indicates, the sources of natural radiation include radon, the largest contributor, potassium and carbon within the body, building materials like wood, stone, or brick, and cosmic rays.  Natural radiation accounts for 82% of normal annual exposure.  In terms of man-made sources of radiation, annual dosage from nuclear power corresponds to only 0.1% of annual average exposure from the natural background, indicating that the claims of those denouncing nuclear power on the grounds of great exposure to radiation are baseless <a href="refrnc.html#6P">(6P)</a>.  In conclusion, total average human exposure to radiation is about 300 millirems per year, although workers in the nuclear industry usually have higher exposure.</p>

<a name=threat></a>
<p><img src="icons/question.gif"><b>Does nuclear radiation from such reactors pose a health threat to human or environmental communities?</b></p>

<p>Basically, radiation in the immediate area surrounding a nuclear reactor is only slightly greater than normal, if it is even greater than normal.  Even if an accident occurs at a nuclear power plant, those in the United States are designed such that radiation leaks are kept to a minimum.  What happened at Chernobyl in the Soviet Union in 1986 simply cannot happen in the United States from a physical basis <a href="refrnc.html#1P">(1P)</a>!  Reactors in the United States are designed differently with more stringent safety guidelines.  During the accident at Three Mile Island in 1979, for example, the surrounding area downwind from the plant received no more than 2 millirems of radiation, which is about the dose received from just one flight in a normal passenger airliner from New York to Los Angeles.  In fact, of the total average human exposure to radiation of 300 millirems given earlier, the expected increase in radiation per year from living within one mile of a nuclear power plant is only 0.05 millirem.  This value is for light water fission reactors, the most common reactor.  The American Nuclear Society also agreed with this minor risk to the public from nuclear reactors <a href="refrnc.html#1P">(1P)</a>.

<p>The nature of fast breeder reactors, particularly the liquid metal type, necessitates significant shielding, more than in conventional light water fission reactors <a href="refrnc.html#7I">(7I)</a>.  In the United States, the only types of reactors used for commercial production of electricity are the light water fission reactors.  Therefore, installation of fast breeder reactors would reduce the risks for environmental contamination by radioactive materials even less likely.  The structures housing nuclear reactors are so strong, an airplane crashing into the containment structure would not result in the release of radioactive matter.

<p>The effects of low-level exposure to radiation do not include many health problems.  Although various interpretations of the correlation between exposure and impact exist, the probability of developing any illness from radiation is very low at normal doses <a href="refrnc.html#6P">(6P)</a>:</p>

<br>
<br>
<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<center>
<table border=4 cellpadding=4>
<tr align=center valign=middle>
<td align=center valign=middle>
<img src="images/effects.gif" align=center valign=middle
	border=1 alt="Various Models for Health Effects from Low-Level Radiation Exposure">
</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

<center>
<h5><p><b>Figure C.  Four models (a through d) have been predicted and graphed<br>to describe the relationship between an increase in low-level radiation<br>exposure and greater incidence of cancer.<a href="refrnc.html#6P"> (6P) </a>
</b></p></h5>
</center>

<center><img src="breaks/neon.gif"></center>
<br>

<p>Of the four models (a through d) in the graph, most radiation biologists follow the linear model a, while others maintain a threshold level of exposure is required, indicated by model b. Numerous difficulties exist with measuring relationships between increased illness and radiation exposure:</p>

<ul>
<li>Predicted effects are often so small that identification and clarification is difficult.
<li>A very large population, possibly involving study over several generations, is required to establish conclusive and statistically significant facts.
<li>It is difficult to distinguish increases in the rise of a particular disease or epidemic as being caused by radiation exposure.
<li>As medical diagnostic equipment becomes more sensitive, an apparently larger number of diseases attributable to such causes may be artificially noted.
</ul>

<p>Regardless of model, it must be emphasized that health effects from low-level radiation are minimal <a href="refrnc.html#6P">(6P)</a>.  Toxins in food, general diet, amount of exercise, stress, age, sun exposure, and even byproducts of fossil fuel combustion normally have greater negative impacts on an average person's health than does natural radiation.  Do you have more questions?  Consult a very extensive index page provided by the University of Michigan entitled &quot;Radiation and Health Physics&quot; by clicking <a href="http://www.sph.umich.edu/~bbusby/">here</a>.  That page contains plenty of links and useful information about the nature of radiation and information and agencies examining health issues.</p>

<br>
