<HTML>
<body BACKGROUND = "backwave.jpg"
<head><h2>Superconducting Magnetic Levitation (MAGLEV)</h2>
</head>
<body>
<p> America's cars, trucks, buses, motorcycles, aircraft, boats and railroads consume one-fourth of total U.S. energy, including two-thirds of all oil. Vehicles are also the the leading cause of urban smog and among the largest contributors to acid rain and global climate change.  Vehicles also consume more oil than the U.S. can produce, causing the need to import over $50 billion per year in foreign oil.

Superconducting Magnetic Levitation may be one of the ways to alleviate the U.S. dependence on automobiles. 
<p> Superconducting Magnetic Levitation System(MAGLEV) is the name given to mass transit vehicles that are levitated off the ground and propelled by magnetic forces.  Since the vehicles are not in contact with anything except for the air, the only friction is aerodynamic.  Thus, after an initial push, there is very little to slow the train down.  Therefore, not much energy is used for proplusion.  These types of trains have been running for a few years in Japan.  To see some of the Japanese prototypes click on <a href="http://www.rtri.or.jp/rd/maglev/maglev_E.html">Superconducting Maglev Project</a>.  This site also gives a pretty good overview of how Maglev systems work.<br><br>  
What about <a href="http://eb-p5.eb.uah.edu/maglev/chapt4.html">Maglev's National Impact?</a><br><br>
 

<a href="http://www.crest.org/efficiency/energywise_options/ch2-6.html">What is Presently Happening with Maglev in the United States?</a><br>





