<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Nuclear Physics</title>
</head>
<body background="nuce.jpg" text=#000000> 
<br><font size =+4><center><img src="atom.jpg">Nuclear Physics</center></font>
<br><br><br>
There are two ways to create nuclear energy:  FISSION and FUSION.  <br>
<br>The first is called fission. When a neutron collides with a Uranium molecule, it changes the structure of the molecule.  The molecule is now unstable and breaks into two new, lighter molecules and some leftover, highly excited neutrons.  This "split" 
releases a massive amount of energy, approximately 200MeW.  When the leftover, highly excited neutrons hit other Uranium molecules, a chain reaction can begin, and an incredible amount of energy is produced.  That is, highly useable energy, which could be
 used to produce power, and thus providing another resource for energy.<br>
The disadvantages, however, are this.  Fission produces radioactive materials and thus, "nuclear waste." 

<br><center><img src="fig43.jpg"></center> <br>

<br> Fusion, on the other hand, is a cleaner and much safer process.  In a sense, it is almost the exact opposite of fission.  Two light molecules are fused together to form a heavier molecule.  For instance, in certain conditions, the molecules Deuterium
 and Tritium will react to form Helium and a neutron.  This neutron carries 14.1 million eV of energy.  The problem, however, is that a temperature greater than 100 million degrees C must be reached for these molecules to react.  At these temperatures, al
l matter is broken down into what is called "plasma."  As you can see, this is already a problem.  Also, unlike fission, where a chain reaction can begin, in fusion it is very hard to sustain the reaction.<br>
<br> As you can see, both of these forms of nuclear energy could provide 
us with the necessary energy resources to propel us into the 21st 
century.  If the power of the atom can be harnessed, the energy crisis 
could be eliminated.  Currently, fission is what is
 being used in technology, but extensive research in fusion has made it the leading candidate to to be used in the distant future.  

<br><br><br><br>
