<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>history</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Back.jpg" TEXT="#ffffff" LINK="#FFFF00" VLINK="#C0C0C0">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 >
<TR>
	<TD> </TD>
	<TD><H1>History and Background:</H1> (Source: NESEA)<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1837</FONT> - The first electric car was built in Scotland, by Robert Davidson

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1800's</FONT> - Electric vehicles were widely produced in the 1880's when the lead acid battery was perfected. 
 
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1892</FONT> - First production electric car created a sensation when exhibited in Chicago. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1899</FONT> - Belgian-built electric racing car "La Jamais Contente" (Never Satisfied) set a world land speed record of 68 mph. 

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1902</FONT> - Record was broken by a gasoline powered car, and the gas car has retained that record. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1910</FONT> - Electric vehicle's first heyday and were a favorite of the women. They were clean, quiet and easy to start. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1913</FONT>- Twenty companies were producing 6,000 electric vehicles and trucks per year. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1930</FONT>- Introduction of the electric starter, and Ford's Model T had virtually eliminated electric vehicle companies. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1973</FONT>- Oil Embargo and a resurgence of interest in electric vehicles. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1976</FONT> - Congress passed the Electric and Hybrid Vehicle Research and Development Act over protests from Detroit, and the veto of then President Gerald Ford. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1977 </FONT>- Japan had 13,000 electrical vehicles in operation, Great Britain had 70,000 and the United States had 3,000 with projections of 25 million by the year 2000. Gas prices were then lowered and the electric car declined again. 
     
<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1980's</FONT> - Resurgence of the electric car as races such as the <A HREF="http://www.crest.org/clients/nesea/atds.html"><STRONG>Tour de Sol</STRONG></A> in Switzerland started in 1982, the <A HREF="http://www.eastend.com.au/solar/index.html"><STRONG>World Solar Challenge</STRONG></A> in Australia in 1987.

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">1990 </FONT>- The emergence of <A HREF="http://www.sunrayce.com/sunrayce/sunrayce.html"><STRONG>Sunrayce</STRONG></A>, the North American university and college solar car race across the United States. 
</TR>



</table>
</BODY>
</HTML>
