<HTML>
<BODY>
<b>
<TITLE>History and Background</TITLE>
<BODY BACKGROUND="red_rock.gif"
TEXT="#99CCFF" LINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#00FF00">
<hr>
<font size=7><center>History and Background</center></font>
<hr>
<p>
	Biomass, in it's initial state, is quite oxidized and is less energy-rich then current energy sources like coal, ethanol, and gasoline.  Energy conversion processes have to deal with complexity and varied chemical composition which depends on the biomass product used.  It's energy density can be increases by using either a thermochemical or a biochemical process.   
<p>
<font size=+1>Thermochemical process</font> 
<br>
	In a thermochemical process fuel gases such as a methane intermediate and biocrude oil can be produced.  This process uses heat energy, pressure, and catalysis to remove a certain amount of oxygen from the biomass inorder to convert it to a homogeneous product (liquid or gas).  Thermochemical process can be done in two different ways either by low-pressure fast pyrolysis or by catalytic high-pressure pyrolysis.   
In low-pressure fast pyrolysis the biomass is heated and then allowed to decompose into vaporized biocrude containg small pieces of the biomass' organic structure.  In order to eliminate any polymerization the vapor is cooled and condensed.  The end result is 70% of the energy in the biomass is converted onto biocrude.
In catalytic high-pressure pyrolysis the biomass is mixed with recycled biocrude, then it is heated at a high pressure with a reducing gas and a catalysis.  Currently the cost of producing gasoline by these methods results in the cost of $2.00 to $3.00 a gallon.
<p>
<font size=+1>Biochemical</font>
<br>
In a biochemical process converts biomass to ethanol and methane.  This process uses a lower temperature and pressure verses the thermochemical process but is found to be more sensitive to the biomass' composition.  When considering biomass such as wood and herbaceuos feedstock which contains high levels of cellulose and hemicellulose a biochemical process is utilized.  This process consist of hydrolysis with the use of strong acids, weak acids, and enzymes.  This allows the cellulose and hemicellulose to break down into component sugars which is then fermented to ethanol.   
  

<font size=4>
<br>
<p>
<dd><a href=tech.html><img src=arrow.gif>Current Technology</a>
<br>
<p>
<dd><a href=index.html><img src=return.gif>Biomass Home Page</a>
</font>

</b>
</HTML>

