<HEAD>
<title>Nuclear Reactors</title>
<body background="nuce.jpg" text=#000000>
<br><font size=+4><center>Nuclear Reactors</center></font>
<br><center><img 
src="http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/topics/light_water/images/fig91.jpg"></a></center><br>
</a></center><br>

<br> There are numerous types of nuclear reactors.  Here, I will discuss 
two relatively simple types, a pressurized water reactor and a boiling 
water reactor.  This should give you an idea as to how nuclear power is 
"Made".    

<br><br><br>Pressurized Water Reactor<br>

<br><center><img src="pwr.jpg"></center><br>
<br><br> The pressurized water reactor uses water to generate power. In 
the figure, the core inside the pressure vessel is where the fission is 
taking place.  A lot of kinetic energy, in the form of heat, exists 
here.  So, the water, which is pumped through this vessel, is heated into 
vaporization (steam).  The steam enters the steam generator, where it 
heats a different system of water into vaporization. The new set of steam 
flows down the steamline and into a turbine.  The turbine then uses the 
steam energy and pressure difference to rotate and generate power.  The 
steam exiting the turbine is then cooled into saturation (back to water), 
by the cooling water.  This water is pumped back into the steam generator 
and used to cool the first system of steam back into water.  This water 
is again pumped into the pressure vessel, and the cycle begins again. 
The containment structure is used to house the radioactive material. 
These are the basics for nuclear power generation.  <br>
<br> Pressurized water reactors were being heavily used by 1973, and the 
design 
hasn't changed much since.  These reactors can produce between 500-1000 
MWe.     



<br><br><br>Boiling Water Reactor<br>

<br><center><img src="bwr.jpg"></center><br>
<br> The boiling water reactor is very similar to the pressurized water 
reactor.  The difference is that the boiling water reactor has only one 
cycle.  Water is again heated into steam in the pressure vessel.  This 
steam is used by the turbine to generate power.  The steam exiting the 
turbine is cooled and condensed back into water, where it heads back to 
the pressure vessel.  
The boiling water reactors output is very similar to that of the 
pressurized water reactors.  

<br><br> These cycles look pretty simple and practical, so what are the 
dangers???  I am sure you have heard the term "meltdown" used in 
conjuction with reactors.  What is a meltdown???  Well, the amount of 
heat energy generated by the nuclear fuel (in the core) is so much that, 
if too little is absorbed by the water (in its transformation into steam) 
then the temperature inside the pressure vessel gets so high as to melt 
the components.  The radioactive material is then released into the 
water/steam pipes, in the containment structure, etc.  This is what is 
termed as a "meltdown".  Of course, the key is to make sure that the 
temperature inside the vessel doesn't get too high, and all reactors 
designed today are designed with control systems to prevent this from 
happening.  <br>


<br><br><br><ADDRESS><A href="mailto:  
dpreuss@students.uiuc.edu">Comments/Suggestions</A></address>
<br><br><br><br>
</body>
</html>

