<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>EMISSIONS</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="emissions.gif"><BR>
</CENTER>
<UL>
<LI><FONT SIZE=6> </FONT>The exhausts emitted by diesel engines
are primarily Nitrogen oxides (NOx) and Particulate Matter (PM).
 NOx  is produced because the engine is operated with a lean air-to-fuel
mixture.  The high compression ratio of a diesel engine creates
much higher pressures and temperatures in the combustion cylinder.
 This lean mixture and high temperatures cause the higher levels
of  NOx production.  At high engine loads, where more fuel is
injected, some of the fuel burns incompletely leading to black
smoke (PM) characteristic of a diesel engine.
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>             Tests performed at <A HREF="http://www.vw.com/" >Volkswagen</A>
, carburetor  gasoline engines are 10 to 30 times more polluting
than diesel engines as far as  CO and HC (gaseous incombustible
hydrocarbons)  emissions are concerned, and 2-3 times higher in
regard to NOx emissions.  However, diesel engines are 2 to 3 times
more polluting than gasoline as far as SO2 is concerned, and 2
to 4 times higher with regard to emission of particulate.
</UL>
<UL>
<LI>     
<UL>
<LI>               Devices which are available for the reduction
of particulate are the Ceramic Trap mufflers.
</UL>
</UL>
