<body background="stuccobac.gif">
<hr>
<br>BACKGROUND
<br>
<hr>
<br>
<br>The French physicist, Edmund Becquerel, first recorded the photovoltaic effect in <br>1839, however the technology laid relatively dormant till the 1950's when Bell <br>Telephone Laboratories made practical silicon photovoltaic cells that reached <br>sunlight-to-electricity conversion efficiencies as high as 6%.
<br>Considered strictly in terms of the energy and material resources available, the <br>potential that photovoltaics holds for energy and the environment is enormous. <br>However, the impediments to approaching that potential are large.  These include the <br>cost of photovoltaic systems, a giant energy infrastructure that resists change, a 
<br>meager photovoltaic industry that lacks financial strength and whose production <br>capacity is small, minimal government financial support for research and <br>development, and a lack of coherent national policies that would recognize the value <br>of nonpolluting technologies and that could accelerate the technology into the <br>market.  
<br> 
<br><a href ="jeremy1.html"><img src = "homeD.gif"></a>

</body>
</html>
