<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Resource Availability</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Gasifcation and Liquefaction of Coal</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 17
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 Since Coal is the most abundant fossil resource, but solid fuels
are the hardest to use, much effort has been devoted to turning
cola into burnable liquids and gasses.  In the next lecture-discussion
we will talk about combined cycle production of electricity. 
Converting the coal into another form is the first step.  This
process and technology are not new.  The German's in WW II fueled
their tanks and aircraft with liquid fuels from coal once the
oil fields in eastern Europe and Russia were lost.  The key is
to do it economically.
<P>
<h2>Gasification</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="physics.html">Physics and Chemistry</a>
<li><a href="lurgi.html">Lurgi</a>
<li><a href="economics.html">Economics</a>
</ul><P>
