<h4>
Atomization -
<dd> The process of reduction to minute particles or to a fine spray. <p>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B26-245</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B023-544</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/wascow/turbocharger.html 128.174.200.146 19970303035240 text/html 1868
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 03:49:39 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Last-modified: Thu, 24 Oct 1996 19:52:25 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 1685
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="water2.jpg" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#ffffff" LINK="#ff00ff" VLINK="#ff00ff">
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>TURBOCHARGERS<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=295><CENTER><IMG SRC="turbocharger.jpg"></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=295><CENTER><IMG SRC="turbocharger2.gif"></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>  A turbocharger increases horsepower by forcing more air
and fuel into the engine.  It does this by raising the engine's
own exhaust to drive a small fan or &quot;impeller&quot; that
pushes more into the engine's intake system.  This &quot;boosts&quot;
the pressure in the intake manifold, and allows the engine to
develop more power as needed.   At part throttle there is little
if no boost.  But as speed and throttle opening increases, boost
pressure rises and the turbo begins to make power.  The process
increases horsepower 40-60%.
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>        When a turbocharger compresses air, the air gets hot
an since hot air is less dense that cool air,  it reduces the
engine's breathing efficiency.  So, in order to cool the air and
 maximize breathing efficiency and power, the air is routed through
a small heat exchanger ( the intercooler)  to cool it down.  Most
intercoolers are air-to-air intercoolers  and since cooling makes
it more dense, power increases on the order of 10-20% compared
to a non-intercooled turbo application. 
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://cs1.cityscope.net/~jag/" >The Diesel Network</A>
</UL>
</BODY>
