<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Combined Cycle and Co-Generation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<center><h1>Combined Cycle and Co-Generation</h1>
<br>
Lecture-Discussion # 18
<br>
Nuclear Engineering 201
<br>
Professor Ruzic
<P></center>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<P>
 When we talked about energy conversion cyles, the &quot;waste
heat&quot; was lost energy exhausted to the environment.  If that
energy can be used instead for a purpose, the efficiency of the
process is greatly enhanced.  In Combined cycle, one thermodynamic
system is combined with another.  the waste heat becomes one of
the inputs.  In co-gneration, the was heat is used directly, perhaps
to heat builidings like the Abott power plant here on campus.
 The co-generated heat can even be used to convert coal into gas,
which is then burined in a different cycle --- an integrated combined
cycle co-generation gasification facility.
<P>
<h2>Combined Cycle</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="physics.html">Physics</a>
<li><a href="examples.html">Examples</a>
<li><a href="economics.html">Economics</a>
<P></ul>
<h2>Co-Generation</h2>
<P><ul> 
<li><a href="physicsb.html">Physics</a>
<li><a href="examplesb.html">Examples</a>
<li><a href="economicsb.html">Economics</a>
</ul><P>
<h2>Integrated Systems</h2>
<P><ul>
<li><a href="gasification.html">Gasification of Coal</a>
<li><a href="economicsc.html">Economics</a>
</ul><P>
