<DOCNO>WT08-B26-249</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA041-000766-B022-383</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://starfire.ne.uiuc.edu:80/ne201/96webprojects/jhauser/currenttechnology.html 128.174.200.146 19970303034702 text/html 3372
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 03:44:04 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Last-modified: Mon, 28 Oct 1996 22:18:01 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 3189
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Jeremy's Homepage</title>
</head>
<body background="stuccobac.gif">
<hr>
<br> CURRENT TECHNOLOGY
<hr>
<br>
<br> Photovoltaic cells use semiconductor technology to convert the photon energy of <br>sunlight directly into electrical energy.  Crystalline silicon solar cells presently <br>dominate the majority of commercial applications of photovoltaic power generating <br>systems. There are non-crystalline cells and other materials used besides silicon, <br>however silicon has remained strong since its introduction due to its applicability to <br>space satellites.
<br> Photovoltaic cells are semiconductors.  Under normal circumstances  a               <br> semiconductor acts like an insulator, inhibiting the flow of electrical energy.  This is <br> because they have very few electrons in order to conduct with through the crystal. <br> An external stimulus of energy must be applied in order to release electrons from the <br> valence band into the conduction band.  For transistors, this external stimulus is a <br> pulse of electric current.  In photovoltaic cells, the energy comes from the photons, <br> or light particles, in sunlight.  The electric current is born because of  the difference <br> in semiconductor materials in the cell.  This explanation is simplified by just thinking <br> of a cell as made of two materials laid on top of each other.  On the top is n-Type <br> and on the bottom is p-Type.  P-Types have a lack of  electrons and n-Types have an <br> excess of electrons.  Thus as sun shines through it forms an electric field at the   <br> junction and electrons flow from one material to the other.  The electrons are pulled <br> off to make a circuit and electricity flows.
<br> There are three types of junctions: homojunction, heterojunction, and p-i-n junction. <br> For the homojunction, the material is doped so that the p-Type has one too few   <br> valence electrons and the n-Type has one too many.  The heterojunction  is         <br> constructed by making a physical gap between the two layers.  The top layer is the <br> window material that lets the sunlight through, while the bottom layer is very      <br> absorbent.  Finally, the p-i-n utilizes an intrinsic layer  interposed between the p-Type <br> and n-Type layers.  The charge carriers are generated in the I layer and are separated <br> by the electric field set up by the p and n layers.  
<br><img src = "pn.jpg">
 <br>
<br>Crystalline silicon solar have been researched and developed to maximize their current <br>efficiency.  Such technologies are metal insulating NP junction and micro-grooved <br>passivated emitter solar cells.  There are also PERC, PERL, and PERT solar cell <br>structures and back point contact solar cells. Even more techniques are using <br>multicrystals, spherical solar cells, and concentrating the sun.  Concentration is shown <br>below.
 <br><img src = "concentrators1.gif">
<br>
<br>In depth discussion of these techniques can be read in the following journal.
<br>Energy Conversion and Management. V. 36, Apr. '95, p. 239-55
<br>
<br><a href ="jeremy1.html"><img src = "homeD.gif"></a>

</body>
</html>

