<hr>


<B><A NAME = "virtual" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">VIRTUAL REALITY: MARKETS and OPPORTUNITIES</B></A><BR>
<B>GB-175</B> Virtual reality technology promises a plethora of new
applications which may revolutions selected industry segments. This
timely BCC study details the new developments in virtual reality (VR)
technology, from passive and active VR to simulated VR and functional
equivalents. The markets are detailed for virtual reality hardware,
software, peripherals, and related equipment and interfaces.
Applications for VR discussed include instructional training, home
entertainment, CAD/CAM, chemical design, architecture, data
management and medicine. Extensive profiles of companies active in
the virtual reality field are given. Market forecasts for the next
five years are provided.
<B>Published January 1996</B>  Price: $2850.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "new" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">NEW ELECTRONIC FLAT PANEL DISPLAY TECHNOLOGIES</B></A><BR>
<B>GB-171</B> Flat panel displays in new electronic applications
represent a rapidly developing market opportunity. Currently, the
flat panel display market is dominated by consumption for laptop PCs,
but soon new HDTV, medical, industrial and telecommunications
applications will accelerate production of performance-oriented flat
panel displays. This timely BCC market study explores the
fast-changing flat panel display industry. Passive and active matrix
LCD displays, electroluminescent, and plasma panel displays are
examined. Research and development, marketing strategies, production
estimates, international efforts, and new technologies and
applications are discussed. Extensive market projections and company
profiles highlight this unique study.
<B>Published December 1994</B>  Price: $2650.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "magnetic" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">MAGNETIC/OPTO-MAGNETIC STORAGE: MEDIA AND MATERIALS</B></A><BR>
<B>GB-160</B> Published September 1992,  <B>167 pages</B> Price: $2650.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "Fiber" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">FIBER OPTIC SENSORS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-116R</B> Until recently, most fiber optic sensors could be found only at the research level or in advanced military applications. Now, however, fiber optic sensors are being used in a variety of industrial, aerospace, and military applications. This  BCC study examines the rapidly evolving market for fiber optic sensors. Fiber optic sensor technology is detailed, along with advantages and disadvantages. Types of fiber optic sensors - extrinsic, intrinsic, hybrid - are painstakingly analyzed. Companies and organizations involved in research, manufacture and sales of fiber optic sensors are profiled. Extensive market projections are provided through 1998.
Published March 1994 <B>144 pages</B> Price: $2650.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "Cables" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">FIBER OPTICS TECHNOLOGY: APPLICATIONS, CABLES AND COMPONENTS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-136</B> This BCC analysis covers all aspects of the U.S. fiber optic media/connectivity marketplace. Topics covered include industry standards and government regulations, overall industry structure, market forces influencing demand, and new technological developments. Fiber optic cables are examined by product types, detailing general purpose cables, local area networks, heavy duty applications, telecommunication cables, interbuilding super trunk cables, and multipurpose cables. Connectivity products such as laser diode pulses, connectors, passive couplers, splices, detectors, and optical switches are discussed. Market projections are provided by market, product and application.
Published December 1991 <B>147 pages</B> Price: $2350.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "Wire" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">WIRE, CABLE AND FIBER OPTICS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-070N</B> BCC report identifies the wire and cable industry segments that have grown and those that will grow in an environment affected by fiber optics. It covers the products and materials used for electronics, building installations and the internal makings of apparatus and it tabulates the present and likely future needs of the telecommunications, computers, electronics and defense industries with estimates and forecasts of materials consumption based on analysis of quantitative and qualitative trends. The study factors into its conclusions the problems and opportunities that emerge with new technologies, a competitive environment, regulatory issues, and other factors. Consideration is given to emerging technologies and new materials. Detailed market projections are provided through 1996.
Published May 1991 <B>131 pages</B> Price: $2450.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "credit" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">CREDIT and DEBIT CARDS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-132N</B> This one-of-a-kind BCC report provides a thorough analysis of the
credit and debit card industry with a quantitative account of its
current size and likely future growth in terms of volume and value
for the next five years. Major products and their applications are
described along with a discussion of driving forces. Shifts in
industry structure and trade practices are discussed for credit
cards, debit cards, ATMs, ATM networks, and POS terminals. Market
segmentation and market shares are analyzed at length for all
consortium and banks, oil companies, and retail cards and their
various programs. Channels of distribution, pricing and trade
practices, purchasing influences, successful companies and
international markets are all covered. Markets are analyzed for
application within each product category. 
<B>Published April 1995</B>Price: $2650.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "cash" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">ELECTRONIC CASH: PREPAID and VOUCHER TRANSACTION CARDS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-149</B> The transaction card is on the verge of expanding yet again, into a
totally new venue. Over the next eight years, the "coin" card will
evolve into a vital new market for an otherwise aging product line.
This in-depth and quantitative BCC study details how, when and where
prepaid/voucher cards for small purchases will enter the mainstream
U.S. payment system. Particular attention is given to the likely
impact of this new technology on a diverse array of industries,
including automated self-service vending, recreation and food
services, public transportation and telephone utilities, as well as
on small retailers. Market projections are provided through 1999. 
<B>Published July 1994  187 pages</B> Price: $2450.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "early" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">EARLY BUSINESS OPPORTUNITIES IN INTERACTIVE TELEVISION</B></a><BR>
<B>G-154</B> Interactive television services are expected to become readily available by the turn of the century. What opportunities await the savvy entrepreneurs in this soon-to-be burgeoning marketplace? This timely BCC study assesses new and potentially lucrative opportunities in regard to the development and availability of interactive television services. Types of services rendered, participants in the industry, and technology developments (network, fiber optic, co-ax, ASDL, etc.) are considered in detail. Developments in the cable industry related to interactive television are thoroughly examined. Market projections are provided by value and volume.
<B>Published January 1995</B> Price: $2650.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "electronic" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING IN THE 1990S: THE EVOLUTION BEYOND THE PRINTED PAGE</B></a><BR>
<B>G-142</B> Ten years ago, research was conducted by reading books and scrolling through microfiche - effective computer hardware and software for electronic page layout were a vision in the future. Today, however, most companies, researchers, publishing firms and editors are turning to the electronic medium for information retrieval, archival purposes, print production, and instantaneous communications. This unique BCC analysis examines the rapidly evolving electronic publishing market and the implications of new developments and requirements. Online database vendors and suppliers are detailed. Information networks and gateways are examined. CD-ROM products, trends toward multimedia, fax-PC linkage and other means of information retrieval, access, and manipulation are analyzed, with profiles provided for all major players. Market projections are given through 2000.
<B>Published April 1995</B>  Price: $2550.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "internetworking" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">INTERNETWORKING: THE KEY TO THE NATIONAL INFORMATION INFRASTRUCTURE</B></a><BR>
<B>G-153</B> The heralded "information superhighway" will be divided into local and national systems, with the true functional key being the wide-area connectivity required for voice, data and video transmission. With rapid advances in LANs and video technology, the face of internetworking will change markedly in the coming years. This in-depth BCC study addresses the rapidly changing market for internetworking technologies. New technology developments are analyzed, as is the future for wide-area internetworking. Key players in equipment manufacturers and service providers are profiled in detail. Market forecasts for all categories of equipment and services are provided through 2004.
<B>Published July 1995</B>  Price: $2650.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "future" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">FUTURE FOR THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS/ELECTRONICS SUPERHIGHWAY ERA: HIGHLIGHTING TRAFFIC PATTERNS, TRANSMISSION SYSTEMS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-150</B> New-found Federal support for an "electronic superhighway" has brought front-page headlines to new data communication applications and optical networks. Soon, information exchange will be faster and more accessible than ever before. This timely BCC study examines the creation and implications of a U.S. electronic superhighway. Existing networks, trends in service and demands, and planned network upgrades/advanced systems are discussed. New technologies such as digital broadband transmission systems, digital broadband switching, and access technologies are examined. Potential future scenarios are postulated with differing degrees of government intervention considered. Company profiles and relevant market projections through 2000 are provided. 
<B>Published September 1994, 115 pages</B> Price: $2450.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "digital" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">DIGITAL VIDEO NETWORKING</B></a><BR>
<B>G-151</B> As digital technology claims center stage, it is bringing about a revolution in regard to consumer, business and industrial electronics. Digital technology has made its impact in video networking, making it possible to transmit data, voice, graphics and full motion integrated "rich" files across local and wide area networks. This  BCC study analyzes the current and emerging trends in digital video technology, development of standards, opportunities in hardware and software development, and activities of main vendors. Emerging trends in interactive technologies, CD-ROM, video games, video-on-demand, and other business areas are considered. A comprehensive analysis of the integration of desktop computers, telephones and full motion video is provided, along with detailed profiles of companies active in this rapidly evolving industry. Market projections through 1998 are given.
<B>Published April 1994, 131 pages</B> Price: $2550.00<P>
 
<B><A NAME = "wireless" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS--UPDATE*</B></a><BR>
<B>G-131R</B> Wireless communications have experienced increasing demand as a result of new developments in PCN, LAN, PBX, and mobile satellite technology. Aside from the obvious utility and convenience of serving the mobile user, wireless technology is also becoming more economical from a provider standpoint, as the cost of maintaining a wireless network is often cheaper than running wires. This  BCC report examines the applications of wireless technologies--from satellites, microwave transmission, mobile pagers and telephones--and forecasts market size and growth for each segment. Product and technology overlap is analyzed in detail. Company profiles are provided in this strategic market analysis.
<B>Published March 1993, 245 pages</B> Price: $2250.00<P>
*Those purchasing A5G-131R will receive the original report--published 10/90--and the update addendum, which is approximately 100 pages of new and updated market data and information. If you have purchased the original report, the update addendum is available for $1600.00.<P>

<B><A NAME = "non" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">NON-U.S. WORLDWIDE TELECOMMUNICATIONS MARKETS: A DETAILED ANALYSIS</B></a><BR>
<B>G-148</B> The next five years will be a critical growth period for the worldwide telecommunications industry as developing regions in China, South America, India, and southeast Asia utilize high-grade fiber optics systems to create new telecommunications networks. At the same time, many developed countries will be upgrading their existing networks for compatibility with new information, data and video applications. <P>
This uniquely comprehensive and highly detailed BCC market study is segmented into four sections, each of which can be purchased separately: Section I: Europe (including Turkey and Russia); Section II - Africa; Section III - Latin America; and Section IV - Asia/Oceania (including Australia and New Zealand). Each section provides a detailed examination of the new technologies, applications and opportunities arising in the worldwide telecommunications industry. The changing markets for telephone and telex/telegraph equipment, transmission equipment, LANs, mobile telephones, video and broadcast equipment, fiber optic systems and cables are discussed. Information sources include a number of government databases. The entrance of cable television companies into the marketplace is examined. Market projections and company profiles are provided. Report is based upon intensive examination and analysis of key government and BCC data.<P>
<B>The full report (about 800 pages)</B> is available for $3850.00. Individual sections may be purchased separately at $1500.00 each. 
A5G-148A--Europe; A5G-148B--Africa/Middle East; A5G-148C--Latin America; A5G-148D--Asia/Oceania<P>
Published March 1994

<B><A NAME = "local" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">THE FUTURE FOR THE LOCAL TELEPHONE COMPANIES IN THE U.S.: CHANGES, COMPETITION, OUTLOOK</B></a><BR>
<B>G-146</B> As the telecommunications world changes, the role of the local telephone company remains stable....or does it? Foreign investments, cable system purchases, new revenue services, competition for commercial and residential access, and new opportunities are providing exciting opportunities for local telephone companies. This timely BCC study examines the new opportunities for local telephone companies, with mergers, wireless communications, and systems integration leading the way for a totally new look among the players. Court decisions, new technology innovations, digital communication, ISDN, fiber optic cable networks, and cellular operations are considered. Voice mail, CLASS services, project management consulting, cable communications, video communications, and terminal equipment are also analyzed, with market projections provided.
<B>Published March 1994, 161 pages</B> Price: $2450.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "delivery" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">DELIVERY ALTERNATIVES FOR RESIDENTIAL TELEVISION</B></a><BR>
<B>G-147</B> Published August 1993, <B>171 pages</B> Price: $2450.00<P>

<B><A NAME = "uninterruptible" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">UNINTERRUPTIBLE POWER SUPPLIES: CONTINUOUS DATA AND NETWORK SERVICE</B></a><BR>
<B>E-050</B> The consequences of interrupted or altered power supply
can be severe. In addition to damaged equipment which must be
replaced, lost data and communications often result in costly delays
and faulty information, translating into lost revenue and customer
dissatisfaction. This  BCC study examines the evolution of power
supply products and software into an industry that can assure
continuity of power to a single desktop computer as well as to
complex networks of telecommunications and information processing
systems. The market is segmented by products that range from battery
backups to transmission, switching and operation systems that reroute
signals around a cable break or node outage. BCC also examines the
worldwide factors affecting the growth of the power supply market.
The current status of products, materials and software is analyzed
and growth trends are predicted. Profiles of major companies are
provided. 
<B>Published February 1993, 134 pages</B> Price: $2650.00<P>

<BR><ADDRESS>
Business Communications, Inc., 25 Van Zant Street, Norwalk, CT 06855 
U.S.A.; Tel: 203/853-4266, Fax: 203/853-0348. All material 
copyrighted by BCC Inc.<P>
