<HEAD>
<TITLE>BCC Energy Magazine</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<CENTER><A HREF="bcc_order_news.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="bcc_energylogo.gif"></A><A HREF="bcc_energycover.GIF"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="bcc_energycoversmall.GIF"></A></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3>In the Two Decades Since the OPEC Oil Embargo,<BR>
the U.S. Economy Grew by 60 Percent.<BR></H3>
<H3>But Energy Consumption Increased Only 13 Percent.</H3><BODY>


<H3><I>Want to Know Why? </I></H3>

<B>Read Energy Magazine</B></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=5 WIDTH=120>

The message of the oil shocks of the 1970s was the imperative to
increase the productivity of energy. The results have been nothing
short of astonishing. And the end is nowhere in sight. Even now, with low prices of gas, oil and coal, those gains the push to conserve is continuing.<P>

That's because utilities, transportation companies, real estate
managers, manufacturers and businesses, both large and small, have
discovered that energy conservation is one of the most attainable
routes to increased profits.<P>

<CENTER><B>Energy is More Important Now Than It Ever Was</B></CENTER><P>

Since 1974, BCC has published ENERGY, an important journal of record
and an interdisciplinary magazine that reports and analyzes major
energy developments.  ENERGY subscribers rely on the invaluable and
unique compilation of energy thinking and analysis found in each
issue.<P>

The articles in ENERGY are written by experts in the field. They come from a variety of sources, such as the government (including DOE, GAO, and OTA), important industry associations (API, AGA, EPRI,
USCEA, NCA, and EEI), energy engineers, special energy interest
groups, energy companies, foreign energy ministries. Contents include original articles and papers presented at important meetings and conferences. ENERGY documents the hard facts with statistics wherever possible.<P>

Each issue of ENERGY provides important new insights into the
economics, politics and technology of energy. ENERGY regularly
covers:

<UL><LI>ENERGY ECONOMICS: OPEC, supply and demand statistics, impact of regulations.
<LI>EXPLORATION: Deep drilling, enhanced recovery, North Sea, foreign investment
<LI>RENEWABLE ENERGY: Projects; plans for wind, solar, geothermal; waste to energy; biofuels.
<LI>UTILITIES: Conservation programs, economics, rate base issues, regulations.
<LI>CONSERVATION: Building design, electric and alternative vehicles, greenhouse impact, environmental issues
<LI>REGULATORS: FERC, FEMA, DOE
<LI>DEMAND SIDE: What are consumer and industrial users doing; what are the issues?
<LI>TECHNOLOGY: Clean Coal, cogeneration, fuel cells, low head hydro.
</UL>
<P><A HREF="sample.html"><i>Sample Issue</a></i><br><p>Your subscription to ENERGY will keep you aware and informed of all
the important issues. It's all there -- covered leading energy
watchers and read by an international audience of energy analysts,
managers, researchers, and decision makers.<P>


<CENTER><B><A HREF = "bcc_order_news.html">SUBSCRIBE</A> NOW AND SAVE 20%</B></CENTER><P>

Subscription price of $250 a year. Just fill in the <A HREF = "bcc_order_news.html">order form</A> and we will begin your subscription immediately.<P>

