<h2>FOR MATERIALS</h2>

<b><a name="GB-126" href="bcc_order_report.html">GB-126 Precursors for Advanced
Materials</a></b><br>
Chemical processing of advanced materials using precursors has experienced substantial growth
worldwide. The
chemical route allows mixing of constituents at a molecular level to obtain higher purity and better
properties at lower
processing temperatures. This updated BCC report extensively reviews various precursors,
technologies, and
applications for materials such as ceramics, glass, composites, and carbon/graphite. Also
discussed are new
developments and patents, suppliers and users in the U.S. and internationally. The industries
covered include chemical,
ceramic, glass, electronic, optical, and others. Markets are identified and segmented by major
chemical and industry
types. The study also provides an in-depth analysis of the current and potential markets.<br>
Target Date:<b>December 1996</b>  Prepublication Price:<b>$3000.00</b><p>


<b><a name = "GB-192"  href="bcc_order_report.html">GB-192 Soft Magnetic
Materials</a></b><br>
Soft magnetic materials play a fundamental role in many of the electrical and electronic systems
that characterize modern society.  In the area of soft magnetic materials, ferromagnetic
amorphous alloys have provided competition to conventional materials.  However, conventional
materials have been fighting back.  This new BCC report analyzes the technology, materials (soft
ferrites, iron-silicon electrical steels, cold-rolled lamination steel, ferromagnetic amorphous alloys,
nickel-iron and iron-cobalt alloys and other materials such as solenoid-quality stainless steels and
silicon-iron alloys), new developments and recent patents, applications, intermaterial and foreign
competitions and markets.  Profiles are provided of all U.S. companies involved in soft magnetic
materials, producers of soft magnetic materials and magnets, developers and users.  Detailed
market projections are provided. <br>
Target Date: <b>December 1996</b>                           Prepublication Price: <b>$2950.00</b><P>


<STRONG> The Abrasives Industry</STRONG><br>
Ths BCC report covers abrasives materials, the mined and synthetic minerals as well as a host of manmade materials that are the basis for the abrasive industry.  Even though use of abrasives is central to manufacturing capabilities in the United States, the industry and its products are obscure due in part to the wide variety of materals used as abrasives.  Nearly every consumer product is impacted directly by the use of abrasives that clean, shape and finish components.  Manmade abrasives derived from metals, glass, waste products and numerous chemicals are the key ingredients in a vast number of processes to finish, clean or prepare stell, surfaces on bridges or ships, and other products of manmade abrasives and applications.  This BCC study is a report on the industry that produces abrasive materials, and the trends and changes in technology, environmental concerns and the marketplace that affect its future.<br>
<b><a name = "GB-191"  href="bcc_order_report.html">GB-191 Abrasive Materials: New Developments, Technologies, Markets</a></b><br>
Target Date: <b>December 1996</b>                           Prepublication Price: <b>$2950.00</b><P>
<b><a name = "GB-193" href="bcc_order_report.html">GB-193 Abrasive Industry Products: Technology Markets</a></b><br>
Target Date: <b>December 1996</b>													Prepublication Price: <b>$2950.00</b><br>

