<b><A NAME = "G-132N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">G-132N Credit & Debit Cards: What's New? Where To?</b></A><br>
This one-of-a-kind BCC report provides a thorough analysis of the credit and debit card industry with a quantitative account of its current size and likely future growth in terms of volume and value for the next five years.  Major products and their applications are described along with a discussion of driving forces. Shifts in industry structure and trade practices are discussed for credit cards, debit cards, ATMs, ATM networks, and POS terminals.  Market segmentation and market shares are analyzed at length for all consortia and banks, oil companies, and retail cards and their various programs. Channels of distribution, pricing and trade practices, purchasing influences, successful companies and international markets are all covered.  Markets are analyzed for application within each product category. <br>
 Published: <b>April 1995</b>                              291 pages                                    
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G132N.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "G-135" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">G-135 Point-of-Sale Retail Automation in the 1990's</b></a><br>
The market for retail technologies-transaction cards, POS terminals, bar-code scanners, aisle displays and automated self-service vending-will experience a doubling in sales in the next five years. This in-depth quantitatively-oriented BCC market research report details how retailers are re-evaluating the role technology will play in the 21st century, which technologies offer the greatest business opportunities and what manufacturers will face in the way of new market dynamics.  Growth forecasts by market segment are provided through 2001 based upon likely changes in market structure, competitive factors, card technology, demographics, consumer attitudes, promotional strategies, and market leadership.<br>
Published <b>October 1992</b> 226 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="G135.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>




<b><A NAME = "G-149" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">G-149 Electronic Cash: Prepaid & Voucher Transaction Cards</b></a><br>
The transaction card is on the verge of expanding yet again, into a totally new venue.  Over the next eight years, the "coin" card will evolve into a vital new market for an otherwise aging product line.  This in-depth and quantitative BCC study details how, when and where prepaid/voucher cards for small purchases will enter the mainstream U.S. payment system.  Particular attention is given to the likely impact of this new technology on a diverse array of industries, including automated self-service vending, recreation and food services, public transportation and telephone utilities, as well as on small retailers.  Market projections are provided through 1999. <br>
Published <b>July 1994</b> 187 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="G149.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "G-179" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">G-179 Electronic Banking Systems: Present Status, Future Prospects</b></a><br>
The past decade saw extremely profound changes in banking, which has resulted in placing a premium on convenience and flexibility for consumers in handling their finances.  This BCC report provides the most detailed and comprehensive multi-client study of the U.S. market for electronic banking and potential business opportunities available.  It thoroughly covers the underlying social, political, economic, and regulatory issues driving the electronic banking business, assesses new and potential products and services, and provides realistic market data and forecasts. <br>
Published <b>April 1995</b>  277 pages         
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G179.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><a name = "G-190" href="bcc_order_report.html">G-190  The Changing Retail Banking Industry Structure
</a></b>  <br>
Mergers, acquisitions and consolidations are becoming more commonplace amongst financial institutions.  Partnering arrangements and strategic alliances between financial institutions, high technology vendors and communication companies will change the dynamics of product delivery to both retail and commercial banking customers.  Traditional banking will give way more and
more to virtual banking such as increased use of unattended terminals, screen phones, telephone or remote banking, personal computers, Internet, video-conferencing, etc.  This report will examine how these changes will impact banking as we know it today through the year 2000.<br>
Published <b>April 1996</b>			110 pages          Price <b>$2950.00</b><P>
