<b><A NAME = "C-066R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-066R  Bio-Immobilization - Update</b></A><BR>
The immobilization of biomolecules has advanced to the point that it is critical to the commercialization of numerous products and processes.  Targets of immobilization include enzymes, substrates, antibodies, antigens, lectins, and other substances.  This updated and expanded BCC study examines the various immobilization methods and quantifies reagent sales.  Applications for immobilization are evaluated, along with new developments in immobilization technology.  Topics discussed include biocatalytic processes, analytical and diagnostic applications, chiral separations, and affinity purifications, to name a few.  Detailed market projections are provided, as well as in-depth company profiles of the major players active in the immobilization field. <br>
Published <b>March 1994</b>          166 pages 
Price: <b>$2850.00</b><a href="C066R.html"><i>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "C-079R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-079R  Chiral Chemical Technology</b></A><BR>
Chiral technology is already changing the drug industry and has broad implications for other markets as well.  The developments occurring in the realm of chiral technology could prove particularly significant as companies seek to introduce enantiomerically pure drugs without medical or regulatory dictates.  This unique and comprehensive BCC study examines chiral manufacturing and analysis technologies, products and companies.  Topics covered include diastereometric crystallization, asymmetric synthesis catalysts and ligands, chiral auxiliaries, analytical and preparative HPLC, enzyme-catalyzed enantiomeric synthesis, enzymatic resolution, and more. Application markets covered include drugs and intermediates, aroma and flavor compounds, and biochemicals, to name a few. Detailed projections of consumption and value are provided. <br>
Published <b>January 1995</b>     290 pages                      
Price: <b>$2950.00</b>
<a href="C079R.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-083R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-083R Dynamic Media, Sera, Reagent Market in Biotechnology</b></A><BR>
This BCC report analyzes the markets for media, sera and reagents in biotechnology.  Although these markets have grown only modestly over the last several years, each are poised for dramatic growth in the near future.   Increased market competitiveness and new research areas will create new areas of market demand.  The sera market is looked at extensively, targeting imports, exports, and new applications.  The study also investigates new developments among competitors, including new product lines, innovations, and marketing strategies. <br>
Published <b> September 1995</b>    
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="C083R.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-086" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-086  The Changing Bioreactor Business</b></A><BR> 
Hollow fiber systems, perfusion technology, thin film bioreactors, advanced microcarrier based technology, spin filters, and many other types of technologies are presented in the BCC study. Their use in mammalian cell culture, recombinant microbial applications, as well as plant cell and insect cell culture are also covered. Includes new materials under development, as well as new instrumentation, and other features. The markets for these products are analyzed for the U.S. and internationally. Market sizes and shares are presented for different kinds of bioreactors. Projections are provided up to the year 2000. The study also provides an in-depth assessment of suppliers and end-user's needs and opinions of existing bioreactors. <br>
Published <b>July 1990</b>    173 pages 
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="C086.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-088R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-088R  The Dynamic Monoclonal and Polyclonal Antibody Business</b></A><BR>
Already a business approaching $1 billion in sales, applications for antibodies are expanding rapidly in numerous directions, now that some of the major technical obstacles have been overcome.  This expansion includes both polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies.  A new study from BCC describes the nature of antibodies and their properties, illuminates the complex industry structure, identifies leaders, discusses pricing practices and influences, sheds light on purchasing practices, and details the manufacture of antibodies such as polyclonals, monoclonals, antibody fragments and conjugated antibodies.  The study provides a comprehensive analysis of antibodies in analytical, diagnostic, therapeutic, separation, and other applications.  Company profiles are included. <br>
Published <b>July 1992</b> 138 pages 
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="C088R.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-088S" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-088S  Review of Manufacturing Technologies for Antibodies</b></A><BR>
In this special companion to "The Dynamic Monoclonal and Polyclonal Antibody Business," BCC explores the specific manufacturing technologies and processes used to create antibodies utilized in medical, biotechnological and industrial applications. Included in this volume are the results from a special survey conducted by BCC on the details of this evolving market segment. Manufacturing technologies related to human-derived, polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies are examined in detail. This innovative market study is a critical reference tool for all those involved in the manufacture, supply, distribution and use of antibodies.<br>
Published <b>August 1992</b> 116 pages  
Price:  <b>$1250.00</b>
<a href="C088S.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-099" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-099  Prospects for Food Biotechnology</b></A><BR>
With regulatory barriers to the commercialization of food biotechnology lifted, biotechnology-based food products will now begin to arrive in the marketplace.  But other issues complicate the situation, including the question of public acceptance.  This new BCC report examines the issues involved in the commercialization of biotechnology-based food products and projects sales.  Technologies addressed and quantified include plant biotechnology, animal biotechnology, microbe biotechnology, enzyme technology, and transgenics.  All food applications are discussed and analyzed, including meat, poultry and seafood, fruit and vegetables, cereals and grains, herbs and spices, fermented foods and beverages, dairy products, baked goods, condiments, food colorants, food gums, fats and oils, food enzymes, and much more. Detailed market projections are provided
Published <b>May 1993</b> 268 pages  
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="C099.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-102" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-102  Plant-Derived Chemicals</b></A><BR>
Plant-derived chemicals constitute a major worldwide business, engaging organic chemists and biotechnologists alike. How much of what is produced for what, by whom? How will new manufacturing technologies affect this business? What are commercial opportunities for new plant-derived chemicals? What is and will be the impact of biotechnology and chiral technology. This BCC study covers waxes, vegetable oils, essential oils, fatty acids and derivatives, phytosterols, phospholipids, polysaccharides, gums, oligosaccharides, sugars, alkaloids, terpenes, plus many other substances derived and derivable from plants. Emphasis is on quantifying amounts and dollars as measures of new and changing directions. <br>
Published <b>June 1990</b>      178 pages 
Price:  <b>$2850.00</b> <a href="C102.html"><i>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "C-114" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-114  U.S. Chromatography Supply Business</b></A><BR>
This unique BCC study covers the market for chromatography reagents. New applications and improved methods based upon new reagents continue to be developed at a vigorous pace. The report examines the changing demand for consumables used in different areas of chromatography, including gel chromatography, HPLC, gas chromatography, affinity chromatography, thin-layer chromatography, and other types of chromatography. The leading suppliers are analyzed in regard to sales, market share in different product segments, and new product development. Solvents, resins and other products are examined. The effects of emerging analytical technologies on the demand for reagents are investigated as well. Competitive factors in the areas of marketing, technology, and new product development are considered, together with changing user needs. Market size and value projections are provided through 2000. <br>
Published <b>January 1993</b> 338 pages  
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="C114.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-117" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-117  Protein Manufacture: Changing Technologies, Applications, and Material Requirements</b></A><BR>
This BCC report on protein manufacturing technologies encompasses extraction, fermentation, cell culture, chemical synthesis and enzymatic synthesis for primary production, as well as the post-production technologies of separation, purification, biochemical and chemical modification, immobilization, formulation and protein drug delivery.  Emphasizing materials requirements, the report identifies and quantifies inorganic chemicals, organic chemicals, biochemicals and natural materials for the commercial manufacture of proteins and peptides in all application categories and markets, and the shifting directions in their use as a result of new technologies such as genetic engineering and transgenic sourcing. <br>
Published <b>April 1991</b> 313 pages    
Price:  <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="C117.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-121" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-121  Reagents for Food Testing: New Regulations and Biotechnology</b></A><BR>
As a consequence of new food labeling regulations, increasing demand for healthier and safer foods, and new technologies (including biotechnology), the market for food testing reagents is changing rapidly. Although the overall market and the shares held by the various types of food testing reagents are likely to grow, the shares held by the various types of food testing reagents are likely to change dramatically in the next several years, increasing in some applications while decreasing in others. This report examines conventional chromatography and chemical reagents, enzyme reagents, antibody-based reagents and gene probes. Specific subjects covered include meat, poultry, seafood, dairy, vegetables, fruits, grains, baked goods, candy, beverages, proteins, fats, cholesterol, carbohydrates, pesticides, antibiotics, hormones, drugs, natural versus synthetic flavors, and more. Also examined is testing for genetically engineered foods and microbes. <br>
Published <b>June 1992</b> 217 pages 
Price:  <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="C121.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-126" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-126 Biohazard Testing: Products, Applications & Issues</b></A><BR>
Over the next five years, biohazard testing in the U.S. is projected to grow at an average 2% per year to reach $750 million by 1995.  Fueling this growth will be the testing of new chemical entities, with some contributions from re-visits to old chemicals previously tested and untested.  As concerns about hazardous and toxic wastes grow and as the health effects of chemical substances come into question (occasionally even before their manufacture), biohazard testing assumes great importance to everyone in the chemical manufacturing industry. This BCC report examines the issues concerning the nature of biohazards from biological, chemical, analytical, regulatory and legal standpoints. The emerging biohazard testing business is also described by industry structure, major players and markets. The study points out new opportunities for suppliers of biohazard testing products and providers of biohazard testing services. <br>
Published <b>November 1990</b> 335 pages 
Price:  <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="C126.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-142" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-142 Investment Opportunities in China: Emphasizing Biotechnology, Drugs, Agriculture, Food & Chemicals</b></A><BR>
China is experiencing rapid industrial growth as it transforms from a centrally planned, command economy to a free market, capitalist system.  The change provides enormous opportunities for outsiders, but seizing the moment is fraught with pitfalls. This new BCC examines the intricacies of doing business with China, discussing the new policies, regulations and priorities. The study provides comprehensive listings of government agencies, companies ("factories"), and trading firms, including names of contacts. The study provides hard-to-find sales figures in major categories based on international trade estimates and direct contacts.  Data is focused upon biotechnology, drugs, agriculture, food and chemicals, while the discussions of investment climate encompass a wide range of industry sectors. <br>
Published <b>January 1995</b>   310 pages                        
Price: <b>$2500.00</b>
<a href="C142.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p> 


<b><A NAME = "C-143" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-143 Biotechnology in the 1990's: Taking Stock</b></A><BR> 
As the biotechnology industry enters a new decade, changes in product lines, players, government regulations, international competition, and technologies are drastically altering the marketplace.  This extensive BCC report examines the current and future status for interferons, interleukins, growth factors, monoclonal antibodies, among others.  New antibiotics and prospective areas of commercialization are detailed, and promising new technologies, such as recominant research, fermentation, cell culture, media development and process technology, to name a few.  International competition in the biotechnology field, primarily from the Japanese and the Europeans, will be considered.  Regulatory initiatives, the role of universities in recent product development, and joint ventures are closely analyzed in the context of the worldwide biotechnology marketplace.  The markets for biotechnological products are analyzed in regard to current sales, with projections to the year 2000. <br>
Published <b>March 1992</b>                    385 pages 
Price: <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="C143.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-144" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-144  Reagents for Biotechnology</b></A><BR>
This unique BCC report covers all the product segments of the biotechnology reagent market. This industry includes enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, peptides, amino acids, and the derivatives and conjugates of all these products. It also covers the many new and exciting novel reagents that will be introduced in the marketplace in the next several years. Major suppliers and specialty suppliers are profiled. Markets and competition are analyzed, and the growing role of international competition is discussed. Specific market projections are provided through 2000. <br>
Published<b> August 1992</b> 179 pages 
Price:  <b>$2850.00</b>
