<b><A NAME = "C-156" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-156  Labeling and Linkage Agents for Immunoassays and Gene Probes</b></A><BR>
Biotechnology-based diagnostic/analytical reagents are becoming increasingly important in clinical, food, environmental research applications.  A "hidden" side to this business, however, is the other materials required for the manufacture and supply of these reagents, aside from the polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies, antigenic units and gene probe oligonucleotides.  This new BCC study focuses on the ligands that provide the critical signaling aspect, the materials for attaching the ligands, and the auxiliary materials such as enzyme substrates, buffers and other items essential the creation of viable diagnostic reagents.  Ligands covered include radioactive and nonradioactive isotopes, fluorogens, chromophores, chemiluminescent agents, enzymes, metals, biotinylation, avidin, chloramine T, Bolton-Hunter, lactoperoxidase, to name a few.  Market size and projections through 1997 are provided. <br>
Published <b>November 1992</b>            
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="C156.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-160" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-160  Human Gene Therapy</b></A><BR>
What was once considered to be an exotic approach to only relatively rare genetic disorders has emerged as potentially the most significant advance in therapeutics since the discovery of antibiotics.  The majority of the potential of human gene therapy is to be found in cancer treatment, where it promises to be highly specific, effective and non-toxic.  This comprehensive BCC study examines the clinical applications and commercial prospects engendered by recent advances and innovations in human gene therapy.  The three primary areas of application are discussed in regard to their respective economic potential: cancer therapeutics, single gene defect correction (somatic cell gene therapy), and antiviral agents.  Considerations for employing gene therapy are detailed in each specific situation.  Market growth potential is projected by application through the end of the decade, along with in-depth company profiles. <br>
Published <b>April 1993</b>      219 pages   
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="C160.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "C-163" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-163  Biotechnology for Environmental Testing</b></A><BR>
Although often overlooked, biotechnology is having a significant impact on the environmental testing market.  With increasing emphasis on environmental issues, the testing of soil and water has taken on new importance, as has the monitoring of hazardous waste and industrial effluents.  Immunoassays and other biotechnological approaches to environmental testing are beginning to find applications in certain niches.  Moreover, in some instances, new testing approaches utilizing biotechnology are actually changing the boundaries subject to analysis.  This new BCC study examines antibody-based, enzyme-based and other new biotechnology-related testing techniques.  It describes the applications, markets, players, customers, and regulatory issues.  Future directions and opportunities are discussed and evaluated.  Market size and projections through 1997 are provided. <br>
Published <b>September 1992</b> 101 pages 
Price: <b>$1950.00</b>
<a href="C163.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-164" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-164  Immunoassays: Markets, Technologies, and Patent Survey Addendum</b></A><BR>
Immunoassays are antibody- and antigen-based diagnostic methods which promise new advances in the diagnostics industry.  Divided into two sections-markets and technology-this unique BCC market analysis covers immunoassay applications, including medical diagnostics, research, food testing, and environmental monitoring, among others.  The market section identifies and profiles industry leaders, with markets quantified from 1992 to 1997 by applications and by immunoassay method. Forecasts are provided in constant dollars and in units. The technology section is based upon a complete analysis of 727 U.S. patents issued from 1971 through 1992. This section identifies those companies that own the technology and technological leaders. Market and technological leaders are identified. <br>
Published<b> October 1992</b> 440 pages 
Price: <b>$2150.00</b>
<a href="C164.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-165" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-165  Lipids: New Technologies, Applications and Markets</b></A><BR>
Genetic engineering, enzymes and new chemical catalysts all take aim at improving the supply of lipids.  At the same time, lipids are experiencing a renaissance of interest for new applications because of their biodegradability and other properties.  This new BCC report quantifies the contributions of the new lipid technologies while delineating new and emerging applications and markets.  Included in the analysis are plant-derived oils, animal fats and oils, fatty acids, phospholipids, and waxes.   Projections are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>January 1993</b> 176 pages 
Price: <b>$2550.00</b>
<a href="C165.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-184B" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-184B  New Developments in Marine Biotechnology</b></A><BR>
Extensive work has been undertaken in recent years to investigate biomaterials present in the marine environment.  This BCC study evaluates the status of such efforts, and the potential for the resulting new and potentially lucrative commercial products.  On-going research, new extraction processes and new substances identified are covered.  In addition to new regulations affecting this field, companies active in research are detailed.  Market projections are provided. <br>
Published <b>September 1994</b>            218 pages                     
Price: <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="C184B.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "C-194" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-194 Cytokines and Growth Factors</b></A><BR>
Formulated cytokines and growth factors for therapeutic use are already a multibillion dollar worldwide business, and represent the centerpiece of biotechnology.  Much of the early "gold rush" is over, however, and today the industry is dominated by a handful of major players.  Technological innovation, though still valued, has declined in importance.  The "name of the game" now is to secure as many approved indications as possible in as many countries as possible.  This new BCC study analyzes the sales of cytokines and growth factors by products, by applications, by geographic territories, by companies and by manufacturing technologies.  Forecasts are made to the year 2000. <br> Published <b>May 1995</b>   243 pages Price: <b>$2750.00</b> <a href="C194.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><a name = "C-198" href="bcc_order_report.html">C-198  Advances & Opportunities in
DNA Testing and Gene Probes</a></b><br>
DNA-based testing methods focus upon gene probe technology.  These probes are being used to
identify a specific gene, region of a chromosome or portion of the genome.  Gene probe
technology has been used for over 30 years, but recent advances have allowed more specificity
with the creation of specific probes for specific genes.  This report covers the advances in clinical
diagnosis, forensic applications such as DNA fingerprinting, research, industrial application, food
testing, and the reference laboratory uses that have fueled this market.  Advances in gene probe
technology have directly impacted on microbiological and serological procedures.  Companies
that have emerged to conduct testing, provide reagents and to maintain DNA databases will be
profiled.<br>
Published:  <b>September 1996</b>   136 pages     Price: <b>$2800.00</b><a href="C198.html"><i> Show contents</i></a><P>


<b><a name = "C-199" href="bcc_order_report.html">C-199 Genetic Platform Technologies: Materials and Applications</b></a><br>

The revolution in genetic technology continues unabated, but already some platform technologies are maturing while new ones are emerging.  The genetic technology industry itself is undergoing significant changes, as financial constraints and business competition place new selective pressure on companies, in effect "choosing" those best adapted to survive the changed and challenged environment.  The comprehensive BCC report provides up-to-date information and analysis of interest to both the practitioners of genetic technology and the suppliers of genetic technology enabling reagents, with emphasis on the business aspects.  This study takes a hard-nosed approach to what companies are doing and why, pointing out new opportunities as well as lost causes.  A key feature of this study is its quantifying of enabling reagent sales in each of the technology platforms and market application sectors, with explained forecasts.<br>
Published <b>December 1995</b>      207 pages     Price: <b>$2950.00</b><a href="C199.html"><i> Show contents</i></a><p><br>

<b><a name = "C-202" href="bcc_order_report.html">C-202 New Development In Therapeutic
Enzyme Inhibitors and Receptor Blockers</a></b><br>

A significant fraction of biotechnology efforts seek to develop therapeutic enzyme inhibitors and
receptor blockers.  While the targets of action are biological, most of the drugs being developed
are small-molecule chemicals.  Included in this new report are HIV protease inhibitors,
mammalian metalloproteinase inhibitors, plasminogen activator inhibitors, reverse transcriptase
inhibitors, topoisomerase inhibitors, ribonucleotide reductase inhibitors, tyrosine kinase inhibitors,
HMG-CoA inhibitors, neuroreceptor blockers, growth hormone blockers, cytokine receptor
blockers, and much more.  The study illuminates the roles of chiral technology, structure-function
investigation, computer-aided drug design and the new discipline of combinatorial chemistry.
<br>

This report should be of interest and value to pharmaceutical companies and biotechnology
companies seeking to keep up with commercial developments in this field, as well as to investors
who may be overlooking  significant but under-publicized opportunities.<br>
Published <b>May 1996</b>    207 pages 	Price: <b>$2950.00</b><a href="C202.html"><i> Show contents</i></a><p><br>



<b><A NAME = "DBI94" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">DBI94  1994 Commercial Biotechnology Reviews</b></A><BR>
Keeping up with the many changes occurring in the commercial application of biotechnology is a full-time occupation, and a vital one for business planning, research planning, and marketing efforts.  BCC is proud to announce its 1994 Commercial Biotechnology Reviews, the latest in a series that keeps you informed of the important events taking place in the biotechnology industry.  It includes the headline news and the not-so-obvious events having important implications for your business, as well as analysis of sales, prospects, players and applications.  All aspects of the industry are covered: bioprocess technology, biopharmaceuticals in all the major categories, antibodies, enzymes, agriculture, food, technology transfer licensing, and finance.<br>
Published <b>February 1995</b>                       
Price: <b>$1000.00</b>
<a href="DBI94.html"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "DBE95" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">DBE95  1995 Commercial Biotechnology Review</b></A><BR>
<br>BCC is proud to announce its 1995 Commercial Biotechnology Reviews, the latest in the series that keeps you informed of the important events taking place in the biotechnology industry.  It includes the headline news and not-so-obvious events having important implications for your business, as well as analysis of sales, prospects, players and applications.  All aspects of the biotechnology industry are covered, including: bioprocess technology, biopharmaceuticals, antibodies, immune diseases, enzymes, agriculture, food, technology transfer, licensing, finance, and much more. Definitely a must for serious players in the biotechnolgy industry!
Published <b> 1996</b>                       
Price: <b>$1500.00</b>
