<b><A NAME = "C-137R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-137R Environmentally Acceptable Soldering & Cleaning Materials and Systems in Electronics</b></a><BR>
This BCC industry report thoroughly analyzes new electronic chemicals and materials for the electronics industry as they pertain to the manufacture and cleaning of semiconductors and printed circuits.  The new high purity chemicals analyzed are imaging chemicals and resists, fluxes, rosins, solder pastes, cleaners and other chemicals.  The study features in-depth analysis of the high performance requirements of products, applications, markets and marketers.  Also featured is an in-depth analysis of the impact of electronic chemicals on the environment and how environmental considerations are factors in the changing patterns of materials usage.  Case studies of the user concerns are presented along with new product descriptions and supplier profiles.  Worldwide materials markets are estimated by size, growth and usage trends with forecasts through 2000.  Critical and quantitative analyses show industry suppliers and users the path to business opportunities. <br>
Published <b> April1994</b>   251 pages     
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C137R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-145" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-145  New Surfactants for New Applications</b></a><BR>
Surfactants, which reduce the surface tension of water or other solvents, are a relatively mature but fascinating technology.  Surfactants function as soaps and detergents, dispersing agents, emulsifiers, foaming agents, and wetting agents.  They are produced from natural fats and oils; from silvichemicals such as lignin, rosin, and tall oil; and from chemical intermediates derived from coal tar and petroleum.  Much of the focus of current R&D efforts is on "green" formulas or product mixtures.  Surfactants are used in everything from herbicides and concrete additives to pharmaceuticals and foods.  Applications include rubber, plastics, textiles, civil engineering and construction, petroleum drilling muds, ore-processing agents, paper and pulp, metal, and many others.  These chemicals are attracting increasing attention in energy and environmental protection applications and are now being tried in new applications such as pollution control systems.    This new BCC report examines the technologies, markets, applications and industry players through 1997. <br> 
Published<b> April 1993</b> 378 pages 
Price: <b>$2850.00</b>
<A HREF="C145.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-148R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-148R   The Dynamic Imaging Chemicals Market in Microelectronics</b></a><BR>
In order to meet ever increasing demands of high-tech/high resolution electronics, new "high-chem" materials  being developed will change the materials mix for fine resolution devices in the coming years. This BCC report thoroughly analyzes new photoresists, developers, strippers, masks and related materials for use in microelectronics fabrication. Major imaging chemical markets for integrated circuits and printed circuits are analyzed and  market forecasts  are  provided  by  device and application.  The study examines new high-purity, high resolution advanced raw materials including polymers, solvents, photoactive compounds and additives  and their respective worldwide markets and applications.  Leading suppliers and strategic  developments are detailed. <br>
Published: <b>June 1995</b>  176 pages  Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C148R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-149" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-149 Pulp & Paper Chemicals:  Highlighting Environmental Considerations</b></a><BR>
This comprehensive BCC report examines the present and future markets for pulp and paper chemicals in the United States.   Particular attention is given to environmental considerations that are leading to large-scale changes in the pulp and paper industry, including increased recycling and significant product developments (the move to alkaline papers) and process developments (away from chlorine).  Included are pulping and bleaching chemicals (soda ash, caustic soda, sodium chlorate, chlorine, sodium sulfate, oxygen, ozone, etc.); titanium dioside and other pigments; kaolin and other fillers; wet-strength agents, dry-strength agents and other thickeners; internal sizing agents; external sizing agents (or surface sizes); retention aids, defoamers; biocides and value for these products and systems are presented along with forecasts for the 1991-1996 period.  Industry structure, R&D, international activities, and company profiles are included. <br> 
Published <b>January 1992</b> 172 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C149.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-151" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-151  Catalysts for Organic Synthesis</b></a><BR>
Issues of environmental pollution, cost-cutting in manufacture, and stereocontrol over reactions, are driving new developments in catalysts for organic chemicals synthesis. This new BCC study covers and quantifies (according to consumption and value), all catalyst types: acids, bases, metals, nonmetals, metallocenes, zeolites, free-radical initiators, phase-transfer agents, biocatalysts and the new biomimetrics. Applications covered include primary organic chemicals and early-stage intermediates, polymers, fats and oils, pharmaceuticals, pesticides, surfactants and plasticizers, photographic chemicals, fuel additives, flavor and aroma chemicals, organic dyes and pigments, biologicals, and many others. <br> 
Published  <b>March  1992</b>               197 pages 
Price:  <b>$2950.00</b>
<A HREF="C151.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-152R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-152R Ultrapure Materials for the Semiconductor Industry </b></a><BR>
The manufacture of semiconductors involves vast quantities of chemicals and water with specifications which require 
measurement of contaminants in parts per billion.  As a result of increasing production and ever more stringent 
specifications, many opportunities exist in the supply of ultrapure chemicals and water to the semiconductor industry.  
This new, comprehensive BCC report provides a qualitative and quantitative  analysis of the market for ultrapure 
chemicals and water used in cleaning, doping, thermal oxidation, chemical oxidation, deposition, metallization, and 
photolithography, including etching and stripping.  Consumption and demand for these materials are tabulated by 
volume and value. Detailed market projections are provided.  Profiles of the major players active in this evolving 
industry are given.<br>
Published: <b>November 1996</b>   166 pages   Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C152R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-153" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-153  Reprographic Chemicals and Inks:  Changing Environments</b></a><BR>
BCC examines the various inks, cleaning compounds, solvents, photographic chemicals and toners used by commercial printers and corporate publishers.  The report focuses on the growth of materials that are environmentally acceptable by today's regulatory standards.  Current status of reprographic chemicals and inks is defined, trends for growth in relation to the environment are analyzed, and projections prepared through 1996.  The regulatory atmosphere and its impact on the industry is identified  Developments in new environmentally acceptable chemicals and inks are explored.  Major worldwide manufacturers are discussed, with market shares indicated by region. <br> 
Published <b>February 1992</b> 181 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C153.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-154R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-154R  The Changing U.S. Solvents Market and the Concomitant Ancillary Solvent Substitute and Recycling Phenomena</b></a><BR>
Solvent  recovery and substitution is changing almost daily as a result of new government regulations and environmental considerations.  This timely BCC analysis examines the consumption of solvents and recovery systems, including aliphatic, cyclic and chlorinated hydrocarbons, alcohols, glycols, esters, ketones, fluorocarbons and organosulfur compounds.  Markets are quantified by major solvent and by application segment. New solvent applications and recovery systems are assessed.  Major players active in the solvent recovery and substitution industry are profiled. <br>
Published <b>December 1994</b>  108 pages    Price: <b>$2450.00</b> 
<A HREF="C154R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-161" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-161  Materials for Environmentally Acceptable Coatings, Inks, and Adhesives</b></a><BR>
With increasingly stringent regulations governing the emission of toxic pollutants, the technology and raw materials used in the formulation of environmentally acceptable coatings, inks and adhesives have been undergoing significant changes.  Raw materials have become more specialized and costly as producers strive to maintain or improve performance.  This insightful BCC report details and quantifies the relevant technological, economic, material, and corporate developments occurring in this unique industry.  Company profiles provide extensive insight into the major players.  Market projections are included through 2000. <br>
Published <b>November 1992</b>   119 pages    
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C161.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-173" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-173  Chelates and Clathrates: Markets and Opportunities</b></a><BR>
Chelates and clathrates are important materials used in a variety of chemical application areas such as water treatment, metal finishing, pulp and paper, oil fields, textiles, food and pharmaceuticals, etc.  This innovative BCC study examines the markets for chelates and clathrates, technologies/mechanisms of chemical action, and new developments in this evolving industry.  Manufacturing methods for phosphates, EDTA-type acids and salts, gluconic acids and salts, organophosphonates, citric acid and polyelectrolytes are detailed.  Environmental regulations affecting the market for chelates and clathrates are scrutinized.  Profiles of companies active in the field are provided, along with detailed market projections through 1998. <br>
Published <b>June 1993</b> 95 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C173.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-174" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-174  Cleaning Compounds: Highlighting Additives to Surfactants</b></a><BR>
A wide variety of additives are used in order to enhance the performance of surfactants in cleaning compounds.  In fact,  the detergent additive business in the U.S. is changing rapidly as a result of new formulations, additives, and technology innovations. This unique and timely BCC study identifies and examines the full range of additives for surfactants, including detergent builders, enzymes, bleaching agents, chelates, suspending agents, diluents and others.   The structure of the cleaning additives industry in the U.S. is defined and examined.  Market projections by size and value are provided through 1998. <br>
Published <b>October 1993</b>  179 pages  Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C174.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-175" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-175 Electrons are Green: Opportunities for Electrosynthesis</b></a><BR>
Applications for electrosynthesis in specialty organic and inorganic chemicals, chloralkali, and specialty products continue to grow.  Also, because electrochemical routes minimize environmental wastes and the associated costs, electrochemical synthesis is receiving renewed attention.  This extensive BCC study examines the market and technology trends in electrochemically-produced chemicals and related equipment.  Emphasis is given to chloralkali, inorganic chemicals, specialty and pharmaceutical chemicals.  Relevant markets for these chemicals are discussed, as are factors influencing the usage of electrochemical synthesis.  Key recent patents and profiles of active companies are provided in this unique BCC analysis. <br>
Published <b>July 1994</b> 125 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C175.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><a name ="C-176B"href="bcc_order_report.html">C-176B Specialty Adhesives</a></b><br>
This BCC report covers new developments, adhesive technology and end uses of specialty adhesives from consumer,
packaging, construction, transportation, electronics, dental application and tapes.  Consumption forecasts through 2000
for specialty adhesives, including hot melts, pressure-sensitive adhesives, and adhesives based on polyvinyl acetate,
epoxies, polyurethanes, anaerobics, cyanoacrylates and acrylics are also covered.  Major supply companies are
profiled.<br>
Published <b>May 1996</b> 131 pages  Price:<b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="C176B.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-178" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-178  Surface Disinfectants</b></a><BR>
Surface disinfectants serve important roles in the control and elimination of microbes from inanimate surfaces.  Issues such as the rising incidence of AIDS, tuberculosis, and food-borne diseases, as well as the problems with chlorine-based germicides, medical disinfection, and other concerns have created a situation in which dynamic change is occurring.  This new BCC study examines germicidal detergents, janitorial cleaners, machine sanitizers, hospital disinfectants, and "cold" chemical sterilants.  Relevant market projections by application and market sector are provided through 1997.  Profiles are given for companies active in this evolving marketplace. <br>
Published <b>September 1993</b> 92 pages 
Price: <b>$2250.00</b>
<A HREF="C178.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-179" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-179 Synthetic Functional Fluids and Lubricants</b></a><BR>
Synthetic functional fluids and lubricants are expected to become one of the hot industrial markets of the 1990s.  This extensive new BCC analysis covers the new lubricants required in automotive, commercial, air conditioning and refrigeration applications.  The growing acceptance of lubricants and functional fluids based on vegetable oils and other synthetic base stocks is discussed, in addition to the prospects of recycling contaminated fluids.  New EPA regulations affecting this rapidly evolving market sector are detailed.  Specific types of synthetic functional fluids and lubricants are identified, with market projections provided in regard to both volume and value.  Major market players are carefully analyzed in this unique market study. <br>
Published <b>January 1994</b> 152 pages  
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C179.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-183" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-183  Supercritical Fluids: Their Time Has Come</b></a><BR>
Using supercritical fluid processes to perform separations is a relatively new approach with significant potential for rapid growth.  Behind the recent expansion in the use of supercritical fluid technology are environmental concerns such as the need to eliminate organic solvents and the search for alternatives to incineration.  This new BCC study examines the changing market for supercritical fluid technologies.  Supercritical fluid extraction, supercritical fluid chromatography, and supercritical fluid water oxidation are covered in detail.  Market projections are provided for the next five years.  Detailed profiles are given for the major players active in this changing marketplace. <br>
Published <b>October 1994</b> 179 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C183.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-184A" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-184A  Marine Biopolymers</b></a><BR>
Marine-derived biopolymers have the potential for significant commercial opportunities in the coming years.  This insightful new BCC analysis explores recent developments in regard to marine-derived biopolymers, including hydrocolloids, gums, water soluble polymers, agar, agarose, and carrageenan, among others.  New technology developments for extraction and processing are covered. Companies engaged in related activities are profiled.  Market projections are provided by value and volume through 1998. <br>
Published  <b>August 1994</b> 159 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C184A.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-185" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-185  Lubricating Oil Additives</b></a><BR>
Additives constitute a significant portion of lubricating oils, ranging from 2% in industrial oils to about 11% in engine oils. Overall, U.S. sales of additives for lubricating oils totaled an estimated $1.6 billion in 1994.  This new BCC study examines the different additives used in lubricating oils, such as antioxidants, extreme pressure/antiwear agents, inhibitors, viscosity index improvers, detergents/dispersants, and other specialty products.  New research and product introductions are thoroughly detailed.  Additive producers and suppliers are profiled.  Market projections by value and usage are provided through the end of the decade. <br>
Published <b>September 1994</b> 138 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C185.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A> 


<b><A NAME = "C-186" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-186 Polysaccharides</b></a><BR>
Polysaccharides are used in a wide range of applications, including foods, animal feeds, petroleum products, textiles, cosmetics, adhesives and drugs, to name a few.  This unique and comprehensive BCC study examines the rapidly expanding markets for products such as cellulosics, natural gums, seaweeds, exudates, guar, xanthan, pectin, and others.  Technologies used to produce/extract these materials are detailed.  Consumption of polysaccharides is highlighted by major product and usage.  Major producers and suppliers of polysaccharides/biopolymers are profiled, with market projections by volume and value provided through 1998. <br>
Published <b>July 1994</b> 128 pages Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C186.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-192" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-192 Alternative Technologies to Regulated Solvents in Cleaning: A Growing Industry</b></a><BR>
Environmental regulations severely restricting the use of certain solvents, banning the further production of others and broadly controlling the use and application of most have resulted in a major upheaval in the use of solvents in all applications.  Amongst all of this change has emerged a huge new market.  A group of alternatives are emerging and include more environmentally friendly solvent-based cleaners, aqueous and semi-aqueous cleaners, various mechanical methods such as high pressure water as well as novel methods that employ CO2, supercritical fluids and plasma technology.  This unique and timely BCC report is a focused study of these newly formed markets and provides the reader with an accurate bearing on where the industry is heading as we move into the next millennium. <br>
Published <b>June 1994</b>   224 pages                             
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C192.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><A NAME = "C-193" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-193 Performance Fluorine Chemicals & Polymers: Future Prospects</b></a><BR>

The presence of fluorine in an inorganic or organic chemical molecule or polymer has a striking influence on its chemical and physical properties.  These influences are most often seen in high chemical stability and inertness.   However, performance fluorine-containing chemicals also find uses as chemical intermediates and products for pharmaceutical and agricultural use, as refrigerants, in fluoridation of water, in toothpaste, as etchants/dopants, and a number of other uses.  This BCC report covers a wide number of performance fluorine chemicals and polymers, with emphasis on their unique properties and markets.  Current controversies over the use of several important fluorine compounds, ranging from CFCs to electronic chemicals, are also discussed.<br>
Published <b>November 1995</b>   176 pages    Price: <b>$2750.00</b> <A HREF="C193.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><A NAME = "C-196" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-196 Oxidizing and Bleaching Agents </b></a><BR>

Use of oxidizing and bleaching agents has become increasingly significant in recent years because of their impact on the environment.  Important products in this field are estimated to be growing rapidly, while others are static or declining.  Future growth will be influenced by new technology, safety considerations, and especially by government regulations limiting the discharge of toxic wastes.  This comprehensive BCC study covers the products, markets and technologies associated with the oxidizing and bleaching agents industry. <br>
Published <b>January 1996</b> 	144 pages	Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="C196.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-200" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-200 Petrochemical and Chemical Catalysts </b></a><BR>

Catalysts and the products made with them are all around us, even though most people neither know what a catalyst is nor what functions catalysts perform.  Virtually every polymer is made with a catalytic process, as are other chemicals, from pharmaceuticals to pesticides.  This report will describe the compounds, products, and markets of catalysts that we describe as "petrochemical", that is, catalysts in petroleum refining, petrochemical processes in which the feedstocks come from crude oil or natural gas, and in chemical reactions/processes in which the feedstock materials may come from other sources.  The report will cover the products such as heterogeneous catalysts/supports and homogenous catalysts, as well as processes, technologies, and the major players that supply catalysts.<br>
Published <b>February 1996</b>	245 pages		Price: <b>$2850.00</b> 
<A HREF="C200.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><a name = "C-204" href="bcc_order_report.html">C-204 Biopesticides and Biorational Agriculture</a></b><br>
Biopesticides constitute a small but rapidly growing sector of the agchem industry.  As a group
they encompass a wide variety of products from botanical extracts, to microbial agents,
pheromones, insect growth regulators, natural predatory/parasites, and plants genetically
engineered to be pest- or herbicide resistant.  This BCC report examines the forces driving the
development of the biopesticide industry, the role of biopesticides with current crop protection
strategies, emerging products and technologies and market opportunities.  The structure of the
industry is analyzed including profiles of the major players, their activities and products.  Market
projections are provided through the year 2000.
<br>
Published: <b> September 1996 </b>    257 pages
Price: <b> $2750.00</i><A HREF="C204.html"> <I>Show contents</i><p></A><P>

<b><A NAME = "DSC95" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">1995 Stereochemical Industry Review</b></a><BR>
BCC tracked the most important developments, applications and market changes in the stereochemical industry in 1995, and has compiled the information in this report.  This study carefully and concisely brings you all the information you need to know in areas including: stereoselective synthesis, separations and analysis; catalysts and transformation agents;
technology, including patents, tech transfer; raw materials and intermediates; reaction strategies; regulations: latest developments;
markets, trends, analysis; applications: drugs, pesticides, aroma and flavor; compounds, biochemicals, liquid crystals, polymers, others; industry news: who, what, why; and research developments, among other topics.
Published: <b> September 1996 </b>    243 pages
Price: <b> $1500.00</i><A HREF="DSC95.html"> <I>Show contents</i><p></A><P>

