<A NAME="G112R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-112R Identification
Systems</b></A><BR>
Automatic Identification Systems such as bar codes and magnetic stripe cards are commonly used
in various applications such as manufacturing, access control & security, highway tolls, crime
fighting, and office automation, to name a few.  Numerous developments in technology, as well as
application, have resulted in the combining of older technologies like radio frequency and bar
coding, and the development of pattern recognition, to suit specific niche applications.  The
various Automatic ID technologies, and the industry segments that use them, are highlighted in
this comprehensive look at the industry.  This BCC study details forecast sales of equipment &
software, offers a perspective on where the industry is headed, and details of the impact of
developments in technology. <br>
Published: <b>August 1995</b>                                 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G112R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<A NAME="G126" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-126  Private Networks:  Growth
Markets & Opportunities</b></A><BR>
An estimated $9 billion was spent in 1989 for all forms of private network equipment and
services. This market is projected to grow by more than 50% over the next ten years to reach
$13.7 billion by 1999. BCC report examines the issues and considerations surrounding the PrivateTelecommunication Network market. It analyzes the strategies encountered in the PTN  market,
including user implementation and carrier plans. A full assessment is made of the influential
economic factors emanating from dedicated, virtual and hybrid networks. Consideration is given
also to Federal FT2000. The study segments and quantifies the market, assesses future growth,
and profiles the leading vendors. Segments include: services and/or media (private line, VSATs,
packet switched networks, virtual networks), equipment for dedicated networks (PBXs, T1
multiplexers, microwave, satellite, bridges for LANs), and network management products and
systems. <br>
Published <b>March 1990</b>   116 pages  Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<A HREF="G126.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G131R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-131R Wireless
Communications-Update*</b></A><BR>
Wireless communications have experienced increasing demand as a result of new developments in
PCN, LAN, PBX, and mobile satellite technology. Aside from the obvious utility and convenience
of serving the mobile user, wireless technology is also becoming more economical from a provider
standpoint, as the cost of maintaining a wireless network is often cheaper than running wires. This
new BCC report examines the applications of wireless technologies-from satellites, microwave
transmission, mobile pagers and telephones-and forecasts market size and growth for each
segment. Product and technology overlap is analyzed in detail. Company profiles are provided in
this strategic market analysis.<br>
Published <b>March 1993</b>   245 pages  Price:  <b>$2250.00</b>
<A HREF="G131R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>
*Those purchasing <b>G-131R</b> will receive the original report-Published 10/90-and the
update addendum, which is approximately 100 pages of new and updated market data and
information. If you have purchased the original report, the update addendum is available for
$1600.00. <p><br>


<A NAME="G133" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-133  Telecommunications Retail
Opportunities</b></A><BR>  
Dramatic drops in costs of equipment and long distance costs have created an environment for
new retail (accessed via "smart" telephones and home computers by residential customers)
opportunities for telephone companies, service providers and equipment manufacturers.  This
BCC report explores the growth and outlook for applications such as public telephones, voice
mail, video telephone, dial 900 and 976 services, and on-line opportunities such as pay-per-listen
business.  New ideas for provision of retail services are all reviewed, with examples of present
usage, background that supports the realization of the business opportunity, and forecasts of
services revenue and equipment sales by applications. <br>
Published <b>June 1991</b>    178 Pages Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<A HREF="G133.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G134" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-134  VSATs:  A Resurging Market
</b></A><BR>
As VSATs move from their role as replacement for leased lines to the dial-up markets, it will not
be uncommon for every franchise in town to have an antenna on the roof. This BCC
comprehensive report explores examines the three applications of VSATs (Very Small Aperture
Terminals) - one-way data, two-way data, and video.  Projections are provided for space segment
by type of transponder, VSAT economics, current and future developments of both equipment
and user implementation, international trends.  Future estimates for customer installations are
included.   With a total of 90,000 VSATs installed today, the market could reach 300,000
installations by the year 2000. <br>
Published <b>October 1991</b> 221 pages Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<A HREF="G134.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G137" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-137  Long Distance Markets,
2001</b></A><BR>
A number of changes are occurring simultaneously in the telecommunications business that will
affect the outlook for long distance carriers in the 21st century:  a move to an all-digital base for
both switched  and private line service; competition among large customers for private networks;
the rise of smaller firms buying packaged offerings and reselling long distance; the demand of new
applications such as LAN interconnections and video on-demand where  circuit speeds need to be
flexible; new software switching capabilities offered by vendors; the rise of alternate media and
carriers; and the probability of new long distance carriers entering market when BOCs have court
restraints lifted.  These and related pressures are reviewed and forecast into the next century in
this comprehensive report covering the long distance industry.  BCC has compiled a practical and
well-researched scenario for telecommunications in the future, and related those findings to the
long distance market. <br>
Published <b>May 1992</b>     176 pages  Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<A HREF="G137.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G138" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-138   Video Communications into
the 21st Century</b></A><BR>
As data transmission was to the 1970s and as facsimile transmission was to the 1980s, video
communications will be the growth telecommunications application for the 1990s.  Video is
moving from the conference room to the desktop and, consequently, to the home. Underlying this
growth will be a significant drop in cost for the digitized hardware needed for video
communications, combined with low-cost digital services offered by the telecommunication
carriers, based upon the ISDN architecture.  This extensive BCC market study examines all
aspects of video communications: conference room, desktop, and business television, including
ancillary video equipment and related carrier revenues.  Market segmentation is defined and
evaluated, and market projections by size and value are provided. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b> 173 pages Price: <b>$1950.00</b>
<A HREF="G138.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G139" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-139  Ergonomic Office Equipment,
Furniture and Supplies: Growth Markets for 1990s<BR></b></A>
Rising incidences of reported injuries resulting from the use of electronic data entry systems are
focusing increased attention on the physical aspects of the workplace.  This comprehensive BCC
report analyzes the new product developments in keyboards, mouses, workstations, monitors, and
accessory products.  The impact of repetitive strain injury (RSI), also known as cumulative
trauma disorder (CTD), is evaluated in terms of new product and services growth, as well as
prevention and treatments.   Medical and occupational statistics on claimed workstation related
eye, hand, neck and back ailments are documented with a view toward their impact on new office
equipment designs and supplies for the computing environment.  Leading suppliers of ergonomic
adjustable products and services are examined.  Corporate experiences and research training
programs are reviewed. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b> 88 pages  Price:  <b>$1750.00</b>
<A HREF="G139.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<A NAME="G142" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-142   Electronic Publishing in the
1990s: The Evolution Beyond the Printed Page</b></A><BR>
Ten years ago, research was conducted by reading books and scrolling through microfiche -
effective computer hardware and software for electronic page layout were a vision in the future.
Today, however, most companies, researchers, publishing firms and editors are turning to the
electronic medium for information retrieval, archival purposes, print production, and
instantaneous communications.  This unique BCC analysis examines the rapidly evolving
electronic publishing market and the implications of new developments and requirements.  Online
database vendors and suppliers are detailed.  Information networks and gateways are examined. 
CD-ROM products, trends toward multimedia, fax-PC linkage and other means of information
retrieval, access, and manipulation are analyzed, with profiles provided for all major players. 
Market projections are given through 2000. <br>
Published: <b>March 1995</b>  Price: <b>$2550.00</b>
<A HREF="G142.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>



<A NAME="G144" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-144   Fiber Optic Testing
Equipment</b></A><BR>
The multi-billion dollar fiber-optics market requires a significant amount of equipment to test
fibers and related components.  This new BCC study investigates the markets and applications for
the major classes of fiber-optic test equipment, including instrumentation for measuring power
and attenuation (loss), wavelength and backscatter, bandwidth and dispersion, physical parameters
of fiber and cable, and equipment for troubleshooting cables and systems.  The principal types of
test equipment evaluated in detail are power meters and sources, Optical Time Domain
Reflectometers (OTDRs), and optical test sets.  This unique study provides timely technical
economic information, profiles of the principal companies, an analysis of new technology and
research, and a clear insight into this essential sector of the fiber-optics market. <br>
Published <b>April 1993</b>        124 pages Price: <b>$2650.00</b> <A HREF="G144.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G146" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-146   The Future for the Local
Telephone Companies in the U.S.: Changes, Competition, Outlook</b></A><BR>
As the telecommunications world changes, the role of the local telephone company remains
stable....or does it?  Foreign investments, cable system purchases, new revenue services,
competition for commercial and residential access, and new opportunities are providing exciting
opportunities for local telephone companies.  This timely BCC study examines the new
opportunities for local telephone companies, with mergers, wireless communications, and systems
integration leading the way for a totally new look among the players.  Court decisions, and new
technology innovations, digital communication, ISDN, fiber optic cable networks, cellular
operations are considered.  Voice mail, CLASS services, project management consulting, cable
communications, video communications, and terminal equipment are also analyzed, with market
projections provided.<br>
Published <b>March 1994</b>   161 pages Price: </b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="G146.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G147" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-147  Delivery Alternatives for
Residential Television</b></A><BR>
Interesting and noteworthy changes are occurring in the evolving residential television market. 
This unique and comprehensive BCC report examines the implications of the major telephone
companies entering the cable television business, new information services, and the huge strides
occurring in compression and digital transmission.  The study analyzes new technologies
influencing the residential television market, including videotext, HDTV, and interactive
television.  Reasons underlying the lack of acceptance of certain technologies are also highlighted. 
All relevant alternatives for delivering television into residences are identified and detailed, with
market forecasts provided for each potential sector.  Major players are profiled. <br>
Published <b>August 1993</b>  171 pages Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="G147.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G148" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-148  Non-U.S. Worldwide
Telecommunications Markets:  A Detailed Analysis</b></A><BR>
The next five years will be a critical growth period for the worldwide telecommunications industry
as developing regions in China, South America, India, and southeast Asia utilize high-grade fiber
optics systems to create new telecommunications networks.  At the same time, many developed
countries will be upgrading their existing networks for compatibility with new information, data
and video applications.   This uniquely comprehensive and highly detailed BCC market study is
segmented into four sections, each of which can be purchased separately: Section I: Europe
(including Turkey and Russia); Section II - Africa; Section III - Latin America; and Section IV -
Asia/Oceania (including Australia and New Zealand).  Each section provides a detailed
examination of the new technologies, applications and opportunities arising in the worldwide
telecommunications industry.  The changing markets for telephone & telex/telegraph equipment,
transmission equipment, LANs, mobile telephones, video & broadcast equipment, fiber optic
systems and cables are discussed.  Information sources include a number of  government
databases.  The entrance of cable television companies into the marketplace is examined.  Market
projections and company profiles are provided. Report is based upon intensive examination and
analysis of key government and BCC data.  The full report (about 800 pages) is available for
$3850.00.  Individual sections may be purchased separately at $1500.00 each. 
GB-148A-Europe;   GB-148B-Africa/Middle East;   GB-148C-Latin America;  
GB-148D-Asia/Oceania<br>
Published <b>March1994</b>
<A HREF="G148.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G150" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-150   Future for the
Telecommunications/Electronics Superhighway Era: Highlighting Traffic Patterns, Transmission
Systems</b></A><BR>
New-found Federal support for an "electronic superhighway" has brought front-page headlines to
new data communication applications and optical networks.  Soon, information exchange will be
faster and more accessible than ever before.  This timely BCC study examines the creation and
implications of a U.S. electronic superhighway.  Existing networks, trends in service and
demands, and planned network upgrades/advanced systems are discussed.  New technologies such
as digital broadband transmission systems, digital broadband switching, and access technologies
are examined.  Potential future scenarios are postulated with differing degrees of government
intervention considered.   Company profiles and relevant market projections through 2000 are
provided. <br>
Published <b>September 1994</b> 115 pages  Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="G150.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G151" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-151   Digital Video
Networking</b></A><BR>
As digital technology claims center stage, it is bringing about a revolution in regard to consumer,
business and industrial electronics.  Digital technology has made its impact in video networking,
making it possible to transmit data, voice, graphics and full motion integrated "rich" files across
local and wide area networks.  This new BCC study analyzes the current and emerging trends in
digital video technology, development of standards, opportunities in hardware and software
development, and activities of main vendors.  Emerging trends in interactive technologies,
CD-ROM, video games, video-on-demand, and other business areas are considered.  A
comprehensive analysis of the integration of desktop computers, telephones and full motion video
is provided, along with detailed profiles of companies active in this rapidly evolving industry. 
Market projections through 1998 are given. <br>
Published <b>April 1994</b>   131 pages Price: <b>$2550.00</b>
<A HREF="G151.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G153" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-153   Internetworking: The Key to
the National Information Infrastructure</b></A><BR>
The heralded "information superhighway" will be divided into local and national systems, with the
true functional key being the wide-area connectivity required for voice, data and video
transmission.  With rapid advances in LANs and video technology, the face of internetworking
will change markedly in the coming years.  This in-depth BCC study addresses the rapidly
changing market for internetworking technologies.  New technology developments are analyzed,
as is the future for wide-area internetworking.  Key players in equipment manufacturers and
service providers are profiled in detail.  Market forecasts for all categories of equipment and
services are provided through 2004. <br>
Published: <b>July 1995</b>    162 pages  Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G153.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G154" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-154   Early Business Opportunities
in Interactive Television</b></A><BR>
Interactive television services are expected to become readily available by the turn of the century. 
What opportunities await the savvy entrepreneurs in this soon-to-be burgeoning marketplace? 
This timely BCC study assesses new and potentially lucrative opportunities in regard to the
development and availability of interactive television services.  Types of services rendered,
participants in the industry, and technology developments (network, fiber optic, co-ax, ASDL,
etc.) are considered in detail.  Developments in the cable industry related to interactive television
are thoroughly examined.  Market projections are provided by value and volume. <br>
Published <b>January 1995</B>124 pages Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G154.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G155" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-155   Data Processing
Opportunities in the Healthcare Industry</b></A><BR>
As the U.S. healthcare industry continues to experience unabated growth, numerous opportunities
will emerge for the suppliers of specialized hardware, software and services needed to handle the
huge volume of critical information and data.  And because quick access to accurate and
up-to-date information plays a major role in the quality of healthcare, state-of-the-art data
processing equipment will continue to gain importance.  This comprehensive BCC study examines
demand for equipment and services related to all aspects of data management and processing in
healthcare environments, particularly hospitals and related care facilities. Specific technology
developments designed to streamline data management while minimizing paper work are detailed. 
The utility and viability of new systems is assessed.  Market projections are provided for the next
five years. <br>
Published:<b> November 1995</b>   202 pages  Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G155.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><a name = "G-182" href="bcc_order_report.html">G-182 Personal Navigation Systems
Highlighting GPS</a></b><br>
With the availability of Geopositioning Systems (GPS) on a full-time basis, a tremendous growth
in the number of GPS terminals for both military and commercial uses, and several mobile satellite
systems waiting to be launched, all forms of personal navigation systems are set to see a
significant growth in the next 10 years.  These systems generally follow one of two forms: (1) a
self-contained navigation system that relays position to a central site, often known as positioning
or tracking systems; and (2) navigation systems that display location on some form of map for the
viewer to determine where to go next.    This BCC study explores the latest technologies of
what's to come, as well as naming the leaders in this totally new industry.<br>
Published <b>February 1996</b>  Price: <b>$2850.00</b><A HREF="G182.html"> <I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><a name = "G-183" href="bcc_order_report.html">G-183 Electronic Trading
Systems</a></b><br>
With increasing accessibility to electronic trading systems, there has been a shift in trading activity
away from the big exchanges and brokerages to "third" and "fourth" markets.  This unique BCC
study will address the growth in usage of electronic trading systems in stock, futures, bond and
currency markets, both on and off traditional exchanges.  Profiles of the major exchanges and
brokerages, along with emerging competitors are provided, including market projections through
1999.<br>
Published: <b>February 1996</b>                   
Price: <b>$2750.00</b><A HREF="G183.html"> <I>Show contents</i><p></A>



<A NAME="G185" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-185 Markets for Portable
Computing Systems Through 2000</b></A><BR>
A plethora of miniature computing and communication devices have appeared in recent years in a
market already teeming with larger, fully functional portable units, namely notebook and
subnotebook computers. The PDA, as the miniature devices are generally known as, have seen
limited success and some highly publicized failures.  This BCC report examines these past failures
and successes with an eye toward what these events mean to the market potential of these
products.  The study also explores the evolution of these devices, as well as the technological
inroads being made as vendors seek to satisfy the high expectations of a fickle marketplace which
itself is evolving.  The ever changing wireless communications environment that is so important to
perhaps most of these products is also addressed. <br>
Published: <b>August 1995</b>   130 pages Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="G185.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>



<b><a name = "G-187" href="bcc_order_report.html">G-187 OEM Automotive Safety
Electronics Systems & Technologies Report: North American Markets</a></b><br>
Driven by safety regulations, rapid innovation in sensing and other electronic technologies, and
the need by automobile companies to gain a competitive advantage, the use of safety electronics
in light vehicles has increased rapidly during the past two decades.  This unique BCC report
explores the current market and future business opportunities for OEM automotive safety
electronics in light vehicles assembled in the U.S. and Canada.  Systems and technologies covered
include; air bags and other passenger restraint systems, anti-lock braking systems (ABS),
electronic traction control, intelligent wiper controls, anti-theft systems, collision warning &
avoidance systems, and other safety electronics.  Market size and value projections are provided
for each category through 2000.  Also included is a comprehensive review of the effects of
NAFTA, the evolving automobile industry structure, the role of transplants, and technology
development joint ventures and alliances, along with their implications for OEM automotive
safety electronics suppliers.<br>
Published <b>December 1995</b>     130 pages                 
Price: <b>$2750.00</b><A HREF="G187.html">
<I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<A NAME="G188" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-188 Telecommunications Market
Opportunities in China</b></A><BR>
The Telecommunication market in mainland China has been growing steadily since the 1980's, and
even more rapidly in recent years. However, there exists a great gap between the growing
telecommunications services and the short supply.  This BCC study analyzes the Chinese
governments management system for the telecommunications market and the possibility of
reform, forecasts potential development, and discusses investment opportunities. <br>   
Published: <b>November 1995</b> 178 pages   Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="G188.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<A NAME="G189" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-189 Supplying the Virtual Home
Office: Markets for Equipment, Supplies and Services</b></A><BR>
The evolution of telecommuting and working from home has increased dramatically over the past
decade and is expected to grow rapidly through the next century.  This BCC report will explore
the demographics of the home office worker.  It will provide an in-depth analysis of trends and
forecasts of the home office environment.  Included topics are: computers, facsimile machines,
printers, networks, e-mail, software, modems, copiers.  Additional subject analyses include
telephones and telephone systems, various on-line systems, and office supplies.  Ancillary services,
such as insurance, worker's compensation, long term disability and 401k plans are discussed. 
Market and demographic projections are through the year 2000. <br>
Published:<b> December 1995</b>    112 pages   Price: <b>$2650.00</b> <A HREF="G189.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<A NAME="G195" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>G-195 High Speed Networks: Technology & Business Trends</b></A><BR>
The local area and wide area networks (LANs and WANs) of today are being overwhelmed by 
the demand for more bandwidth.  Increasing use of fiber optics, co-axial and wireless networks 
have provided some of the answers.  Other technologies, including data and video compression, 
real-time play back, and transmission systems have also helped in easing the problem.  This 
BCC report analyzes the technology trends (such as ATM, 100 VG AnyLAN, 100 Base-T, ISDN 
and PACE) and business opportunities that the high-speed networking industry offers to 
hardware and system developers.  This report will be invaluable to both technologists and 
marketing professionals involved in the Internet and high-speed networking industries.<br>
Published:<b> July 1996</b>    154 pages   Price: <b>$2950.00</b> <A HREF="G195.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<A NAME="GB170C" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>GB-170C  Trading with Mexico:
Telecommunications/Consumer Electronics</b></A><BR>
The third report covers new opportunities for U.S. manufacturers as a result of access to Mexico's
expanding telecommunications infrastructure, including cellular and fiber optic networks.
Forecasts are also provided regarding potential opportunities in the growing Mexican consumer
electronics market. <br>
Published <b>May 1994</b>     135 pages Price: <b>$1500.00</b>  
<A HREF="GB170C.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>



<A NAME="GB175" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"><b>GB-175  Virtual Reality: Markets &
Opportunities</b></A><BR> 
Virtual reality technology promises a plethora of new applications which may revolutionize
selected industry segments. This timely BCC study details the new developments in virtual reality
(VR) technology, from passive and active VR to simulated VR and functional equivalents.  The
markets are detailed for virtual reality hardware, software, peripherals, and related equipment and
interfaces.  Applications for VR discussed include instructional training, home entertainment,
CAD/CAM, chemical design, architecture, data management and medicine.  Extensive profiles of
companies active in the virtual reality field are given.  Market forecasts for the next five years are
provided. <br>
Published <b>January 1996</b> 409 pages  Price: <b>$2850.00</b>
<A HREF="GB175.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


