<TITLE>BCC Energy Reports</TITLE>

<IMG SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO"><BR>

<H4>WELCOME TO BCC ENERGY MARKET REPORTS</H4>
<BODY>
Below you will find a list and summaries of all the reports in our catalog. If you have any questions about our reports, or are interested in ordering a report, click on the title.<P>
<B>
<a href="#DOR95">	Enhanced Energy Recovery Industry Review</a><br>
<a href="#E-007U">The U.S. Energy Future:  Environmental/Social Costs Quantified</a><br>
<a href="#E-036N">Solar Thermal and Photovoltaics: World Growth Markets</a><br>
<a href="#E-054R">New Directions in Transportation Fuels: Update</a><br>
<a href="#E-059A">Bridge and Highway Maintenance: The Changing Infrastructure</a><br>
<a href="#E-059B">Bridge and Highway Maintenance: The Cement Asphalt Binder Business</a><br>
<a href="#E-059C">Bridge and Highway Maintenance:  Markets for Support Ancillary Materials</a><br>
<a href="#E-067">Non-Utility Electrical Power Generation</a><br>
<a href="#E-069">Fuel Cells</a><br>
<a href="#E-069R">Fuel Cells: On the Verge</a><br>
<a href="#E-070">Energy-Saving Devices and Equipment: Residential & Commercial</a><br>
<a href="#E-071">Reformulated Motor Gasoline</a><br>
<a href="#E-073">The Impending Electric Vehicle Market</a><br>
<a href="#E-075">Future of Electric Utilities: Impact of New Technologies</a><br>
<a href="#E-078">Commercial Use of Coal Combustion Byproducts:
Technologies and Markets</a><br>
<a href="#GB-086N">The U.S. Battery Industry: Update</a><br>
<a href="#GB-174">The U.S. Battery Charger Industry</a><br>
<a href="#GB-184">Portable Battery Powered
Products Markets</a></b><br>
<hr><P>

<b><A NAME = "DOR95" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">DOR95	Enhanced Energy Recovery Industry Review</b></a><BR>
Unlike many emerging technologies, enhanced recovery is a real business.  It is already a 
dominant factor in the total energy picture.  Optimism about enhanced recovery and the chemicals 
and technology to pursue such recovery is justified when the state-of-the-art in enhanced energy is 
compared to solar, synfuels, nuclear fission, or other alternative fuel technologies.  This review is 
a unique compilation covering breaking technology developments and the industry news of 1995.<br>
Published <b>November 1996</b>	281 pages	Price: <b>$1500.00</b>
<a href="DOR95.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-007U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-007U The U.S. Energy Future:  Environmental/Social Costs Quantified</b></a><BR>
This unique BCC report examines and analyzes the status of the U.S. energy industry by energy source. It quantitatively deals with production, capacity, technologies, government activity, the effects of conservation and provides forecasts by energy type. Furthermore, this study quantifies in detail the environmental and social costs of each different energy source-this has never been done before in a complete volume. In addition to an analysis of fossil energy, special consideration also is given to a variety of alternative energy sources such as solar, wind, waste-generated energy, shale oil, tar sands, and geothermal power. This BCC study is formulated from the input of experts in the energy field and from the vast expanse of scientific and commercial literature available. The analysis is an indispensable marketing tool for the energy analyst who must consider energy planning strategy in the context of both corporate and environmental costs. <br> 
Published <b>August 1992</b> 230 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="E007U.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-036N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-036N Solar Thermal and Photovoltaics: World Growth Markets</b></a><BR>
In the 1990s, R&D funding and industry activity has increased and solar energy again offers promise for the future.  In this timely report BCC presents a comprehensive analysis of the current solar energy markets and projects their future direction.  BCC assesses the growth potential over a six-year period from 1994 to 2000 for the worldwide status of solar thermal and photovoltaic energy together with conventional solar hot water heating.  The study focuses particularly on the kinds of equipment being used for each technology and their costs relative to more conventional sources of energy <br> 
Published <b>January 1996</b> 179 pages 
Price:  <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="E036N.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-054R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-054R New Directions in Transportation Fuels: Update</b></a><BR>
Alternative fuels will make a dent in the transport fuel market by the year 2000, displacing as much as 15% of imports. While dependence on imports is fueling the argument in favor of substitutions and alternative sources of energy, the real driving force will be the environmentalists' concern with pollution from emissions. Practically speaking, most conservation can and will occur in transportation fuel. This timely BCC report analyzes the limits and opportunities for alternative fuels for the main modes of transportation: automobiles, trucks, buses, railroads, and air. Directions, trends, markets and technologies in ethanol, methanol, compressed natural gas, hydrogen, LPG and electric vehicles are examined. Extensive data is provided, outlining current dependence on imports in the transportation industry. The impact of alternative fuels on petroleum imports and air pollution are fully discussed both qualitatively and quantitatively with projections to the year 2000.<br>
Published <b>November 1993</b> 208 pages         
Price: <b>$2550.00</b>
<a href="E054R.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-059A" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-059A Bridge and Highway Maintenance: The Changing Infrastructure</b></a><BR>
As the highway bill becomes a more important concern in the face of upcoming elections, the condition of the U.S. infrastructure of bridges and highways will come under intense scrutiny.  Part one in this exclusive three-part Bridge and Highway Maintenance series details opportunities which will arise for contractors and equipment/materials suppliers.  This BCC report examines the department of highways in every state, and details the major projects of interest.  Growth in new construction, as well as the attempts to maintain ongoing construction, are analyzed in depth.  Market value and size projections are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b>            74 pages  
Price: <b>$1300.00</b>
<a href="E059A.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-059B" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-059B  Bridge and Highway Maintenance: The Cement Asphalt Binder Business</b></a><BR>
The main materials used for bridge and highway maintenance - cement, asphalt, steel - are representative of a huge market segment devoted to U.S. roads.  Over the course of the remainder of the decade, these unique materials will become utilized in varying degrees in both new construction projects and ongoing highway/bridge maintenance programs.  The second report in the BCC Bridge and Highway Maintenance series profiles suppliers of cement, asphalt and steel, and analyzes usage trends based upon geographic area and impending highway projects. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b>          
Price: <b>$1200.00</b>
<a href="E059B.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-059C" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-059C Bridge and Highway Maintenance:  Markets for Support Ancillary Materials</b></a><BR>
In part three of the BCC Bridge and Highway Maintenance series, other materials used in the construction and maintenance of the U.S. systems of roads and bridges are discussed.  Such materials as thermosetting cements, plastic cements, concrete pipe, geotextiles, chemicals, and adhesives are detailed and analyzed.  Rust protection equipment and treatments are also examined.  Finally, other equipment, such as heavy construction machinery and other machines used in the building and maintenance of highways and bridges are discussed.  Market projections by size and value are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b>       
Price: <b>$1200.00</b>
<a href="E059C"><I> Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-067" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-067  Non-Utility Electrical Power Generation</b></a><BR>
For many years, utilities have held a virtual monopoly on power generation.  With the advent of more efficient technologies and increasing demand for a variety of power sources, non-utility owned electric power facilities are emerging successfully as the market for power continues to evolve.  This new BCC market study explores non-utility owned power generation (NUG), which now has expanded to include over 700 companies.  Regulatory issues and equipment needs for this new generation of independent power producers are examined in detail.  Geography, industry size and kW production, and industry segmentation are discussed.  Future market potential is analyzed in the midst of growing environmental concerns. <br>
Published <b>August 1993</b> 149 pages Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="E067.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-069" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-069  Fuel Cells</b></a><BR>
For years, fuel cells have proven useful for submarine, military, and aerospace applications.  In fact, as a result of global concerns regarding scarce energy sources and the environment, fuel cells may become important power sources for transportation and power generation in the next ten years.  This comprehensive BCC market study provides a detailed technology overview of fuel cells.  Companies involved in the industry are profiled.  New applications for fuel cells currently under consideration are detailed.  Market projections are provided. <br>
Published <b>December 1993</b> 155 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="E069.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "E-069R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-069R  Fuel Cells: On The Verge</b></a><BR>
This in-depth study reveals the potential growth of the fuel cell industry.  It familiarizes the reader with the background and development of fuel cells together with the classifications and their applications.  The focus is on the five main fuel cell types: alkaline, molten carbonate, phosphoric acid, solid oxide and the proton exchange membrane (for solid polymer) fuel cell.  Various applications such as space, submarine , transportation, on-site power, and utilities are examined.  This study will be of particular benefit to those involved in the fuel cell industry, those comtemplating involvements, the potential investors. <br>
Published <b>March 1996</b> 135 pages  
Price: <b>$2950.00</b>
<a href="E069R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-070" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-070 Energy-Saving Devices and Equipment: Residential & Commercial</b></a><BR>
As fossil fuels slowly become taxed at higher rates as a result of environmental awareness, energy-saving devices will make increasing fiscal sense for residential and commercial energy consumers alike.  This unique and insightful BCC study covers the evolving marketplace for energy-saving devices and equipment such as lighting (e.g., incandescent, fluorescent, high intensity), HVAC, monitoring and control systems, fans and ventilation devices, appliances, motors, and energy saving storage devices.  Cogeneration is also discussed in relation to residential and commercial uses.  Detailed market projections are provided based upon energy-saving units sold, energy and cost savings, and time required to recoup cost of the devices.  Major market players are examined. <br>
Published <b> December 1994</b>                 164 pages                   
Price: <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="E070.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-071" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-071 Reformulated Motor Gasoline</b></a><BR>
With guidelines set by the Clean Air Act of 1990 beginning to take effect, the petroleum industry is under pressure to refine reformulated gasoline (RFG) using a variety of cleaner burning additives.  This new BCC study examines new trends in gasoline production, including the effect various federal and state mandates will have on the future production of RFG.  Different industry approaches to RFG are discussed, as is stream and component hydrogenation, product blending, catalytic reformer modifications, diesel fuel production, fluid catalytic cracker (FCC) modifications and hydrotreating.  MTBE, ETBE, TAME and DIPE synthesis and process is discussed.  Markets are quantified and assessed through the end of the decade. <br>
Published <b> January 1995</b> 216 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="E071.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-073" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-073 The Impending Electric Vehicle Market</b></a><BR>
As the California electric vehicle mandate continues to spur R&D by the Big Three auto manufacturers, EVs are making front-page news. This timely new BCC study examines markets for EVs by type, size and location. Markets for batteries and other major components are detailed by type. Regulations, economics, and international developments are considered. Extensive profiles are given for players active in this changing industry. Market projections are provided for the next five years. <br>  
Published <b>January 1995</b>                 296 pages
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="E073.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "E-075" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">E-075 Future of Electric Utilities: Impact of New Technologies</b></a><BR>
This report emphasizes the role of new generating technologies over the next 10 years.  It will also discuss the developing competition between public utilities and nonutility generators (NUGs).  Emphasis is given to the traditional and non-traditional sources of future generating capacity and to the increasingly important role nonutility generators are expected to play as providers of future electric power. <br>  
Published <b>March 1996</b>                 202 pages
Price:  <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="E075.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><a name="E-078" href="bcc_order_report.html">E-078  Commercial Use of Coal
Combustion Byproducts:
Technologies and Markets</a></b><br>
Coal ash is a commercially valuable and abundant mineral resource.  This report provides an
up-to-date analysis of
technical and economic forces affecting the commercial utilization of recycled ash.  Included are
discussions of fly ash,
bottom ash, boiler ash, boiler slab, and FGD materials with a focus on current utilization
technologies, R&D, and viable
markets for the use of these materials.  Markets covered included cement/concrete, flowable fills
lightweight aggregate,
metal matrix composites, autoclaved cellular blocks, cenospheres, waste management, agricultural
and mining
applications, and more.  Includes recent patents, lists of ash marketers and technical contacts,
analysis of current state
ash utilization regulations, and more.  Both U.S. and international developments are
reported.<br>
Published: <b>July 1996</b> 178 pages    Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="E078.html"><i> Show contents</i></a><p>  


<b><A NAME = "GB-086N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GB-086N The U.S. Battery Industry: Update</b></a><BR>
This BCC report provides a complete economic and technological assessment of the electrical battery industry, highlighting major trends.  Developmental and experimental primary (throw-away) and secondary (rechargeable) batteries are evaluated with particular emphasis on emerging commercial applications.  Among those systems considered are lithium-based, sodium-sulfur, nickel-zinc, nickel-iron, nickel-hydrogen, zinc-chloride, conductive polymer, and redox cells.  Lead-acid, nickel-cadmium, and manganese dioxide-based batteries and direct solar power and fuel cells are discussed in relation to these new technologies.  Potential for developmental markets, including electric vehicles, remote and solar power storage, utility load-leveling, advanced military uses, portable appliances, computer power and memory backup, and medical implants are discussed in detail.  Predictions and development scenarios are provided through the year 2000. <br> 
Published <b>March 1994</b>      387 pages   
Price:  <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="GB084N.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GB-174" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GB-174 The U.S. Battery Charger Industry</b></a><BR>
Because batteries are critical to a vast array of components, battery chargers represent an important, yet often overlooked industry segment.  This unique BCC study presents an extensive examination and analysis of the various battery charger technologies used in consumer products, OEM batteries, automotive applications, industrial machinery and developmental systems. Industry structure and competitive aspects of the marketplace are assessed.  Profiles of companies active in the battery charger industry are provided.  Detailed market projections are given through 1998 of size and value of the battery charger industry. <br>
Published <b>October 1994</b> 181 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GB174.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><a name = "GB-184" href="bcc_order_report.html">GB-184   Portable Battery Powered
Products Markets</a></b><br>

This BCC report analyzes the U.S. market for portable battery-powered products,  including
computers, telecommunications devices, tools, toys, and scientific instruments.  As battery,
battery chargers, and microprocessor technology improves, an increasing number of electrical and
electronic products can be freed from the necessity of close proximity to an electrical outlet.  This
report identifies and analyzes trends and developments in portable product technology, including
batteries, battery chargers, motors, microprocessors, displays, and other portable interfaces. 
Applications and market sectors for portable battery-powered devices are identified and analyzed.  
Historical market value and unit shipments are provided, and used as a basis for assessing the
current market and making 5 and 10 year forecasts.  Industry practices, competitive strategies,
and channels of distribution are provided.  Company profiles and rankings are provided for
leading suppliers and OEM consumers.<br>
Published:  <b>July 1996</b>    327 pages    Price: <b>$2950.00</b><a href="GB184.html"><i> Show contents</i></a><p>


