<b><a name = "C-203" href="bcc_order_report.html">C-203 Food & Feed Enzymes:
A Global Perspective</a></b><br>
Food enzymes are traditionally used in industrialized countries for many applications, although
the use of enzymes for feed is still quite new.  This BCC study gives an overview of the technical
and economic characteristics of the most important types of food and feed enzymes, analyzes by
enzyme type and geographic region the economics of production and formulations, and shows
trends in further developments.  Application markets for each enzyme type are discussed in detail
with special reference to European, Latin American, North American, and Asian food and feed
markets.  Report reviews the industry structure and leading players.<br>
Published <b>July  1996</b>  129 pages     Price: <b>$3450.00</b>
<a href="C203.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "GA-023U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-023U The Non-Alcoholic Beverage Industry</b></a><BR>
This BCC report examines the mature U.S. beverage industry and the intense competition for market share as per capita consumption reaches a point of saturation.  The dynamic market for diet, caffeine-free, gourmet and natural juice drinks are analyzed in detail, as are new products like iced coffee, tea, juices, flavored and health-oriented waters, sports beverages and aseptically packed fruit drinks that continue to show strong growth.  Industry trends, consumption patterns, production and packaging, flavorants and additives, demographics, market shares, pricing, distribution, suppliers, franchisors and bottlers, and import export data are discussed at length.  The competitive environment in marketing non-alcoholic beverages is fully addressed with an analysis of advertising and promotional activities.  International operations are identified.  Profiles of major players are presented. <br>
Published <b>December 1991</b> 242 pages  
Price:  <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="GA023U.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-047N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-047N Mass Merchandised Healthy Foods</b></a><BR>
Preference for products made from natural ingredients with no preservatives, artificial colors or flavors, or other additives is very strong, and convenience plays an important role in the success of the product. This comprehensive BCC report covers total retail sales of "healthy" foods and beverages - both mass-marketed products and natural foods at supermarkets and health-food stores. Among the key issues considered are: how freshness and value-added concepts relate to growth in this market; impact of product positioning at supermarkets; technologies that will contribute to growth; and how the trend toward internationalization of the food industry will affect this market. <br>
Published <b>August 1991</b> 241 pages 
Price:  <b>$2350.00</b>
<a href="GA047N.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-057R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-057R Prepared Ethnic Foods: Trends & Developments</b></a><BR>
New ethnic foods are sweeping the nation in a wave of popularity perpetuated by a variety of factors, such as increased immigration, the rising number of ethnic restaurants, and consumer's desire for varied cuisine.  This unique BCC study examines the changing market for prepared ethnic foods.  Markets and demand for mainstream Italian, Mexican and Asian/Chinese products are detailed, as is consumption of newer ethnic foods originating from the Mediterranean, the Middle East, Japan, India, Thailand, Korea, Vietnam and Indonesia.  Social and market trends driving changing consumer preferences are highlighted.  Processors and suppliers active in the ethnic food industry are profiled. <br>
Published: <b>November 1994</b>  129 pages      
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="GA057R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-068R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-068R Opportunities in Aquaculture</b></a><BR>
Consumer demand for healthy alternatives to red meat with high fat content has facilitated increasing consumption of fish and shellfish.  As a result of declining stocks of some wild fish species, continuing high prices for imported fish and shellfish, growing reluctance to import with a mounting trade deficit, new technology for feeding, aeration and harvesting of fish, and a supportive regulatory climate, the continuing growth of the aquaculture industry is all but assured.  BCC examines the forces that will promote or constrain growth of freshwater and marine/saltwater aquaculture products farmed for human consumption, and describes current trends and prospects for the U.S. in the international aquaculture market.  Detailed company profiles are provided. <br>
Published <b>June 1993</b> 117 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA068R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-069" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-069 The Weight Control Industry</b></a><BR>
BCC examines market developments in products and services for weight control and reduction. Industry segments covered in this report include foods, beverages, diet aids, drugs, supplements, and weight reduction programs. The study covers the full spectrum of issues and concerns from government and medical community research and findings to consumers' interests, new ingredients and substitutes, product development, company activities, distribution channels, competition, retailing, etc. Fat-, calorie- and cholesterol-controlled products are discussed for each segment of the food industry. Market leaders, shares, sales, domestic and foreign markets are covered. Opportunities and trends are identified. <br>
Published <b>January 1990</b> 110 pages 
Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<a href="GA069.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-070" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-070 Flavors and Flavor Development for Generic and Custom/Specialty Markets</b></a><BR>
Flavors sold by flavor companies to food and beverage makers were valued at $402.5 million in 1990 and are projected to grow at a rate of 5.1% annually to reach $515.9 million in 1995. Specially designed flavors and flavor systems are an increasingly important component in the successful marketing of new packaging systems and processed foods products. These new flavors are being developed for use in the many processed food products being marketed in response to consumer demands for convenience, microwavable, nutrition, health, fast foods, variety, and a growing taste for ethnic foods and exotic flavors.  This BCC report identifies what these new flavors are, where they are being used, in what quantities, by whom, for which products, and who the suppliers are. Market sizes for the major natural and synthetic flavors are estimated in terms of value and volume for  the complete spectrum of processed foods and for each of the major application  sectors. <br>    
Published <b>January 1991</b>  120 pages 
Price:  <b>$2150.00</b>
<a href="GA070.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-072" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-072 Ingredients and Additives for the Dairy Industry</b></a><BR>
In recent years, the dairy industry has been experiencing a change in the development of its products as consumer preferences shift to items providing value-added nutritional benefits, minimal health risk, and maximum food safety.  At the same time, consumers want new products with new flavors for distinctive taste experiences.   Suppliers to dairy product makers have found it necessary to research, develop, and market ingredients and additives that enable manufacturers to deliver the desired products to consumers.  This comprehensive BCC study discusses how suppliers have responded to the demands of dairy makers as they, in turn, adapt to consumer demand.  Market strategies, players, technologies, and products are identified, analyzed and discussed. Market forecasts for existing products and new ingredients and additives provided through 1996. <br>
Published <b>August 1991</b> 146 pages  
Price: <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="GA072.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-073" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-073 New Developments in Farm Machinery</b></a><BR>
There is great demand for farm machinery in the U.S.  Over the last decade, farm machinery depreciation has far exceeded expenditures.  Now, however, high-tech machine vision, guidance systems, and controls are dramatically changing equipment designs and making present machinery stock obsolete.  This new BCC report discusses the impact of these changes and details the present domestic market for crop production and harvesting machines, with forecasts of 1995 demand.  The study examines the impact of the new technology, government regulations and other market forces on sales and industry structure.  Changes in pricing and trade practices are described, along with estimates for overseas markets for farm machinery. <br>
Published <b>November 1992</b> 193 pages  
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA073.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-074" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-074 Nutritionally Beneficial Ingredients and Additives for Processed Foods & Beverages</b></a><BR>
Are we what we eat?  Food and beverage makers have been fortifying products with vitamins and minerals for years.  But today's consumers are demanding foods that provide healthful benefits, or that reduce health risks.  Vitamins, minerals and proteins are still fortifiers, but research is directed toward identifying and extracting protective natural substances in plants as new fortifiers that can be incorporated into "designer" foods.  Another research goal is to develop replacements for fat, sugar and salt which are related to certain health disorders.  Suppliers of ingredients and additives must examine these trends and potential markets if they are to help manufacturers develop products, communicate through product labeling, and satisfy consumer demands. <br>
Published <b>December 1991</b> 227 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA074.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-076" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-076 New Convenience Foods</b></a><BR>
This unique BCC report details the growing markets for new convenience foods as changing government regulations and evolving consumer preferences shape the marketplace.  New frozen convenience foods, chilled foods, shelf-stable foods, and aseptically packaged foods are examined and analyzed.  Company profiles of the major players in the industry are provided in order to fully document the convenience food industry.  Other areas are analyzed, including snack foods, new processed meats, poultry and seafood, and new convenience dairy products.  U.S. industry structure is thoroughly detailed, with market projections provided for convenience foods by type and market segment. <br> 
Published <b>March 1992</b> 143 pages   
Price:  <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="GA076.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-078" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-078 Changing Commercial & Institutional Foodservice Industry</b></a><BR>
The expansion of foodservice sites will continue as the economy recovers and new marketing strategies are developed and implemented.  This comprehensive BCC market analysis examines the evolving commercial and institutional foodservice industry, and its prospects for growth in the midst of changing customer attitudes and demographic factors.  The study discusses competitive factors influencing foodservice facilities within each market segment.  Sales for each segment and subsegment are detailed, along with an examination of the most active companies and ownership/management arrangements.  Market projections are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>July 1992</b> 158 pages  
Price:  <b>$2350.00</b>
<a href="GA078.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-079" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-079 Food Stabilizers and Emulsifiers: New Uses, New Functions</b></a><BR>
Gums, starches and emulsifiers are increasingly required to perform new functions as food processors seek to satisfy changing consumer demands.  The traditional demands that foods must taste good and look appealing still hold, although foods now must also provide nutritional benefits, eliminate health risks via reduced fat and sugar, be made with natural ingredients, and cook equally well in both conventional and microwave ovens.  Ingredient suppliers, interested in helping food processors meet these demands, are developing ingredients with functionality and price similar to those of traditional ingredients.  This BCC report tracks recent introductions of the new ingredients used in conventional, lowfat and microwave foods, and develops market projections for each based upon industry, market and consumer influences. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b> 139 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA079.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-080" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-080 Vitamins, Minerals, and Protein/Amino Acids Used for Human and Animal Health</b></a><BR>
Both humans and animals require vitamins, minerals and proteins/amino acids for growth and good health.  Consumers are influenced by media messages linking certain nutrients (or lack thereof) with certain disorders, and they have a personal interest in buying fortified foods and dietary/nutritional supplements for themselves and their pets.  Likewise, caretakers of livestock animals have a commercial interest that animals be free of nutritional deficiencies that cause disease.  Fortified foods and supplements replace nutrients lost during food processing, storage, or poor food foraging conditions.  BCC examines the recent trends and research developments influencing each segment, and companies involved as manufacturers and packagers.  Sales estimates and projections are provided through 1997. <br>
<EM>See below for the descriptions of the two documents comprising this report.<br>  Discount for the purchase of both reports:</EM> <b>$2650.00</b>
<p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-080A" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-080A Vitamins, Minerals, and Protein/Amino Acids Used for Human Health</b></a><BR>
Humans require vitamins, minerals and proteins/amino acids for growth and good health.  Consumers are influenced by media messages linking certain nutrients (or lack thereof) with certain disorders, and they have a personal interest in buying fortified foods and dietary/nutritional supplements for themselves and their pets.  Fortified foods and supplements can all replace nutrients lost during food processing and/or storage.  BCC examines the recent trends and research developments influencing each segment, and companies involved as manufacturers and packagers.  Sales estimates and projections are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>March 1993</b> 176 pages  
Price: <b>$1500.00</b>
<a href="GA080A.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-080B" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-080B Vitamins, Minerals, and Protein/Amino Acids Used for Animal Health</b></a><BR>
Animals, of course, also require vitamins, minerals and proteins/amino acids for growth and good health.  Caretakers of livestock animals have a commercial interest that animals be free of nutritional deficiencies that cause disease.  Here, too, fortified foods and supplements replace nutrients lost during food processing, storage, as well as during poor food foraging conditions.  BCC examines the recent trends and research developments influencing each segment, and companies involved as manufacturers and packagers.  Sales estimates and projections are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>March 1993</b> 112 pages  
Price: <b>$1500.00</b>
<a href="GA080B.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-081" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-081 Light/Healthy Processed Foods & Soft Drinks: Winners & Losers</b></a><BR>
Increasing consumer awareness concerning the health risks posed by fat, cholesterol, salt, sugar, and excess calories has led to certain specialized consumer demands.  In order to help maintain good health, consumers want light and healthy foods that either reduce or eliminate these ingredients.  In response, food and beverage makers have developed healthier versions of regular products.  However, many of these new products are experiencing disappointing sales because they reportedly fall short of consumer quality expectations.  In this timely report, BCC examines the types of products - the successes and failures - and the driving forces in this segment of the mature food industry.  Sales estimates and market forecasts are provided for each product type. <br>
Published <b>October 1993</b> 175 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA081.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-082" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-082 Specialty Ingredients and Related Technologies for Lowfat and Fat-Free Applications</b></a><BR>
With health-conscious consumers demanding lowfat and fat-free foods in order to reduce health risks, food processors are looking to their suppliers for the necessary ingredients.  Suppliers have responded with new flavors, full and partial fat replacers, non-fat products, cultures, enzymes, preservatives, and other ingredients that are designed specifically to compensate for the loss of taste and texture when fat is reduced or removed.  This unique and comprehensive BCC study examines this rapidly evolving industry segment, with sales estimates and forecasts provided for specific ingredients.  New ingredients and processing technologies are thoroughly detailed. <br>   
Published <b>January 1994</b> 118 pages  
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA082.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-083" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-083 Fitness/Wellness Products: Light/Healthy Foods & Drinks, Dietary Supplements, Home Exercise Equipment</b></a><BR>
In recent years, the consumer trend has been to take responsibility for fitness and diet as a means to avoid the costly medical bills associated with failing health.  Rather than emphasizing treatment, consumers are focusing on self-care and preventative measures to ensure good health.  This timely BCC study examines the "wellness/fitness phenomenon" in the context of types of foods, supplements and home exercise equipment being marketed to meet these consumer interests.  Industry structure and driving market forces are identified and examined in detail.  Market projections are provided for each type of fitness/wellness product through 1998.  Extensive company profiles are given. <br>
Published <b>May 1994</b>                 171 pages                Price: <b>$2550.00</b>
<a href="GA083.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-085" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-085 New Niche Nutraceuticals: Nutrients, Food Substances & Food/Beverages Used As Fortifiers</b></a><BR>
Clinical studies suggest that certain natural substances can provide protective influences against major and even life-threatening disorders.  This new BCC study examines research and development occurring in regard to natural plant substances that can be extracted for use as fortifiers in foods and beverages. As one type of nutraceutical, these would be used like drugs to prevent/treat diseases.  The study examines new nutraceuticals, current and future applications, market activity, regulatory initiatives, and industry growth factors.  Market projections are provided through 1998 by volume and value. <br>
Published <b>August 1994</b> 172 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA085.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-086" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-086 Animal Feed Additives: Technologies & Markets</b></a><BR>
Additives for use in animal feeds and related products are becoming increasingly important to the general health and productivity of livestock.  This unique BCC study examines the new technologies, opportunities and markets affecting the rapidly developing animal feed additive industry.  Feed additives used for disease prevention and control, growth promotion and enhanced nutrition are covered, including anticoccidials, anthelmintics, antibiotics, hormones, amino acids, macrominerals, vitamins, and other additives.  New federal regulations and environmental considerations are assessed, as are state and federal feed labeling regulations.  Market projections are provided by additive and by livestock category. <br>
Published: <b>August 1995</b>  Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="GA086.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-087" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-087 Flavor Trends & Developments: Highlighting Beverages, Ethnic & Fat-Reduced Foods</b></a><BR>
Consumer interest in new and different flavors is reflected in the extensive marketing efforts currently underway for a variety of new beverages, ethnic foods and reduced fat foods.  This timely BCC study examines the changing market influences affecting the market for flavor additives, including health and regulatory issues, new processing technologies, and changing consumer preferences.  Industry structure is carefully examined, as are the activities and products of the leading companies.  Sales estimates are provided for various consumer and industry sectors through 1998.<br>
Published: <b>March 1995</b> 114 pages                          
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="GA087.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-088" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-088 Shelf Life Technologies for Processed Foods: New Developments and Trends</b></a><BR>
Consumers want fresh, quality processed food in their stores and homes, and processors  want food to stay fresh during transport and storage as well as extended shelf life to avoid wastage.  These demands have traditionally been met by chemical preservatives which are currently challenged by consumers as possible health risks.  Suppliers, looking for alternatives, are trying various natural preservatives, MAP/CAP packaging that could eliminate the need for any type of preservative, reformulation, and other technologies such as flavor encapsulation.  This BCC report looks at recent technological and market trends to extend shelf life, makes sales estimates and forecasts for 1999 for each technology, and describes the structure of the industry. <br>
Published:<b> August 1995</b>    160 pages       Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="GA088.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-089" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">
GA-089 Natural Food Colors: Emphasizing European Technology and Market</b></a><BR>
The international food ingredient market  is composed of many different sectors of food ingredients, some well analyzed, and some not.  One of the least transparent sectors of food ingredients are coloring agents.  Although used in food technology for a very long time, this industry has rarely been analyzed nor comprehensively documented.  This unique BCC study will review the markets for a number of natural, nature-identical and artificial coloring agents.  This report will also address the need of the whole food ingredient industry for an overview on the natural and nature-identical food color industry in Europe.  This report will interest companies and players in the color market by providing them with a comprhensvie overview on the whole business, as well as those who are considering diversification into attractive and well fitting sectors, one of which may be natural food colors.<br>
Published<b> January 1996</b>     130 pages   Price: <b>$2950.00</b>
<a href="GA089.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "GA-090" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-090 The Evolving Non-Alcoholic Beverage Industry</b></a><BR>
Non-alcoholic beverages have undergone a shift in taste in recent years due to the introduction of new types of drinks.  At one time soft drinks, juices, milk, and hot drinks were available to consumers.  Today, there are variations on each of these types of drinks, some marketed by major beverage makers and others by small, niche companies.  BCC examines how beverage makers are dealing with these changes and developing marketing strategies such as line extensions and new products, niche marketing, using fancy packages and looking at foreign markets for growth.  Further, this report covers most active companies, market leaders and the general industry environment.  Sales estimates and forecasts for each are given.
<br>
Published<b> March 1996</b>      235 pages      Price: <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="GA090.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "GA-093" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-090 The Evolving Alcoholic Beverage Industry</b></a><BR>
This BCC report examines how beverage makers are dealing with changes and developing marketing strategies such as line extensions and new products, niche marketing, using fancy packages and looking at foreign markets for growth.  Further, this report covers most active companies, market leaders and the general industry environment.  Sales estimates and forecasts for each are given.
<br>
Published<b> July 1996</b>      134 pages                           
Price: <b>$2850.00</b>
<a href="GA093.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<STRONG><EM>MONEY SAVER!! BOTH GA-090 and GA-093 for $3950.00</EM></STRONG>
<p>
<b><A NAME = "GA-094" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-094  The Western European Perspective on Protein Ingredients in Foods</b></a><BR>
This BCC report analyzes the development of the plant source, animal source  and single cell 
protein ingredients markets in human and domestic animal food stuffs in the 17 Western 
European countries through to the year 2000.  Products identified in the report include soy (flour 
and grits, protein concentrates, isolates and textured proteins, and egg-based proteins.  Annual 
sales in Western Europe amount to around $1.5 billion.  Volume usage in food sectors such as 
bakery and cereal, meat and meat products, dairy products and desserts, specialty foods and 
domestic pet foods is quantified for each of the major European countries.  Future growth is 
assessed in light of economics, technological advances, legislative controls and end-use 
requirements.  Profiles of major suppliers of protein ingredients are included.
Published <b>August  1996</b>		155 pages   Price: <b>$3000.00</b>
<a href="GA094.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "GA-096" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-096 The Global Market for Vitamins in Food, Feed, Pharma and Cosmetics</b></a><BR>
While the market for most food and feed additives shows signs of
saturation in Europe and the U.S., the market for vitamins is
still growing at above average rates especially in Asia and
Eastern Europe.  This BCC study will give an overview on the
technical and economic characteristics of all vitamins in
relation to their applications in food, feed, pharma and
cosmetics.  It also analyses the production processes,
especially when biotechnological steps are involved, and covers 
the most important formulations for vitamins.  Current and
future forecasts are given for  application rates of different
useages, along with market share estimates for each vitamin. 
Extensive analysis of price developments as well as historic
developments of market sizes for each vitamin are covered. 
Major players are profiled. 
Published: <b>November 1996</b>            Price: <b>$2950.00</b>
<br>
<a href="GA096.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


