</b>
<HR><P>
<b><A NAME = "B-101" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">B-101 The U.S. Healthcare Delivery System in the Year 2000: Opportunities for Suppliers, Goods and Services</b></a><BR>
The U.S. health care delivery system, an industry accounting for about $700 billion annually (12% of the GNP) is sharply criticized for being too costly, with many considering it "out of control." While there is little disagreement that the U.S. health care industry does in fact have to change, the course of action remains a subject of serious debate.  Even in a time when health care costs seem to rise every day, however, there exist certain lucrative market opportunities in the wake of extensive public and corporate concern.  This unique and informative BCC study examines the issues confronting the U.S. health care industry as it approaches the beginning of a new century.  The prospect of universal health care, and the implications of this policy choice on medical equipment and service suppliers is detailed.  Who will pay how much?  Is Canada a good model?  What will really work? <br>
Published <b>December 1992</b>        Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="B101.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "GA-056R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-056R Sterilization: Changing Technologies, Products & Markets</b></a><BR>
Although sterilization remains a "hidden" aspect of manufacturing, it is of vital importance in light of current concerns over nosocomial infections, AIDS, food poisoning, and other related issues.  The opportunities are present for new sterilization techniques, with technologies which may make a significant impact on the marketplace.  This comprehensive BCC study quantifies sales and service revenue, examining all types of sterilization, including heat, radiation, EtO, UV, filtration, and chemical germicides.  New sterilization technologies such as microwave, gas plasma, electron-beam, x-ray, and others are detailed.  Applications examined include drugs, biologies, medical devices, surgical supplies, foods and beverages, fermentation, biotechnology, electronics, semiconductors, health services, and other.  Detailed market projections are provided. <br>
Published <b>July 1993</b> 190 pages 
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="GA056R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-045N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-045N  Medical Diagnostic Kits & Products</b></a><BR>
This BCC report examines the market opportunities and product growth for all types of diagnostic kits, including serological/immunological, DNA probe and chemical. This study defines and reviews diagnostics in infectious diseases, metabolic disorders, genetic diseases, cancer, cell typing. In each of these areas the focus is on the specific kits used, the active companies and manufacturers, the disease itself and the results of treatment, and the users. The report also discusses marketing of medical diagnostics, namely promotion, packaging, market influences and opportunities, market research needs and services. Growth rates of kits and chemicals, future markets, technological developments that will affect commercial developments and changes in industry structure are provided and detailed. <br>
Published <b>July 1992</b> 125 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C045N.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-047N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-047N Cancer Treatment and Diagnostic Products</b></a><BR>
As the population ages, the market for products that diagnose and treat cancer increases.  At the same time, new technologies, especially those from the biotechnology industry, are being developed that are revolutionizing the cancer industry.  This updated BCC study analyzes the sales of products for cancer, as well as suggests the new directories for research and development.  Market forecasts through the year 2000 will be provided for chemotherapeutic agents, hormone therapies, biological therapies, electromedical diagnostic devices, and cancer detection test products. <br>
Target Date: <b>September 1995</b>       Prepublication Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C047N.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-050N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-050N Drug Delivery Systems: New Developments, New Technologies</b></a><BR>
Drug delivery systems are attracting increasing attention as new treatments and drugs appear on the market.  This comprehensive BCC market analysis focuses upon novel drug delivery technologies and the use of biologically-derived materials (e.g., antibodies, gene probes, enzymes).  The drug delivery product industry is examined in regard to distribution networks, the number and size of the major players, trade, pricing, purchasing decision factors, and the techniques for drugs delivery.  Particular emphasis will also be placed on the impact of drug delivery systems by specific drugs formulated by these technologies.  Market projections provided through 1998. <br>
Published <b>July 1994</b> 176 pages 
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C050N.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><a name="C-058R" href="bcc_order_report.html">C-058R The Worldwide Generic
Prescription Drug Industry</a></b><br>
Aided by fundamental industry factors such as patent expirations, therapeutic substitutions, cost
containment and pro-generic government proposals, the generic pharmaceutical industry will
double its size in dollar volume by 2000 and dominate all new prescriptions written by 2005.  This
insightful BCC study addresses the impact of generics on the pharmaceutical industry as well as
the fundamental factors that will be responsible for the success or failure of the independent
generic companies and generic subsidiaries of brand drug companies.  Statistics on current and
future market sizes, market segments, projected growth rates, patent expiration dates, product
approvals, company profitability, and leading product performers will be presented.<br>
Published <b> June 1996</b> 150 pages    Price:<b> $3150.00</b>
<A HREF="C058R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><A NAME = "C-068R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-068R  Inert Ingredients for Drugs - Update</b></a><BR>
Inert ingredients are defined as the "other" components found in  formulations that facilitate the administration of drugs.  Although hidden from the limelight, these additives are of critical importance to the formulations.  Presently, inert ingredient technology is undergoing significant change.  This new and updated BCC study examines the changing marketplace for inert ingredients in drug formulations, with emphasis on inorganic compounds, biological compounds and petrochemical compounds for all standard dosage forms (oral solids and liquids, topicals, injectables, respiratories, and suppositories).  Market projections by usage volume and value are provided through 1998, along with company profiles of the major producers of inert ingredients for drugs. <br>
Published <b>November 1993</b> 159 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C068R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>



<b><A NAME = "C-071N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-071N The Blood Industry</b>  </a><BR>
This BCC report provides a comprehensive analysis of the structure and market size of the U.S. blood collection/transfusion industry and its related areas of autologous donations, plasmapheresis/fractionation, bone marrow therapies, blood salvaging , blood substitutes, and animal transfusion.  The study defines market size and market shares, describes structure and dynamics, and profiles the major players with forecasts through 1995 for all segments.  Topics addressed include:  usage trends, regulatory controls, impact of disease on the industry, major players and their market shares and potential, current and emerging products and technologies, and opportunities for development and commercialization of new or alternative products and services. <br>
Published <b>September 1994</b> 214 pages  
Price:  <b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="C071N.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-072" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-072 New Horizons in the Pharmaceutical Industry: The Changing OTC, Ethical, Generic Balance</b></a><BR>
Comprehensive BCC report identifies the present state and forecasts the likely future direction of the pharmaceutical industry. The ethical, generic and OTC sectors are analyzed in terms of major players, nature of products, barriers to entry, innovations, growth sectors, demographics and demand, cost pressures, production, pricing, profitability, advertising, market outlets, market size and forecasts for growth. Interdependence with other health sectors; mergers, acquisitions and joint ventures; overlap among sectors; FDA, patent systems and medicare regulations; state of R&D; inter/intra-sector competition; foreign markets, the U.S. share; and the prospects for new drugs are examined. <br>
Published <b>July 1990</b>    245 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C072.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><a name="C-077R" href="bcc_order_report.html"> C-077R Markets for Advanced Wound Care Technology</b></a><br>
The adaptation of biotechnology and biomaterials science to address the requirements of wound care and healing via topical wound care products is expected to dramatically alter the marketplace.  This unique BCC industry analysis provides a comprehensive review of the developing market and newly emerging technologies in the area of advanced wound care.  The report examines the significant impact that the introdution of new technologies will have upon the structure of the wound care market.  Market projections are provided through 1999.  Analysis is segmented by wound type and technology.  Profiles of present and future companies active in this growing marketplace are provided.<br>
Published<b> April 1996</b>    242 pages   Price:<b> $2750.00</b>
<A HREF="C077R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

<b><A NAME = "C-135" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-135   New Directions in Pharma Tablet Manufacture</b></a><BR>
BCC estimates total U.S. consumption of binders and solvents for manufacture of pharmaceutical tablets for human use to reach $157.3 million by 1995 with binders representing 91.3% and solvents 8.7% of the total value.  Under pressures from new EPA regulations and constraints on costs, among other influences, the U.S. pharmaceutical industry is changing the ways it manufactures oral tablets.  And since tablets account for nearly 70% of the dosage forms made in the U.S. for human use, the changes have a significant impact.  This BCC report examines the issues of the "green" revolution, bioavailability problems, and economic pressures to identify and assess the new directions in which pharmaceutical tableting is headed.  Emphasis is placed on tablet binders and wet granulation tableting solvents with full quantifying  of materials used and their dollar sales.  The study illuminates the issues with analyses of the driving forces and their impact on pharmaceutical manufacturers and materials suppliers.  A special feature of this study is a survey of drug producers on tablet manufacturing practices, buying behavior and ratings of materials suppliers. <br>
Published <b>February 1991</b>     156 pages 
Price:  <b>$2250.00</b>
<A HREF="C135.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-139" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-139   Brain Diseases and Disorders: Diagnostic & Treatment Products</b></a><BR>
The 1990s have been declared "The Decade of the Brain," and companies are positioning themselves to take advantage of new discoveries in neuroscience.  The direct and indirect costs of CNS and mental diseases come to over $170 billion dollars in the U.S. alone, but the social consequences can barely begin to be measured.  Sales of CNS drugs in the U.S. amount to some $6 billion, despite the fact that they are often found to be inadequate in certain areas.  This BCC study discusses the technical, medical and business aspects of new commercialization opportunities and efforts, and  assesses the impact of new technologies quantitatively.  It is written for business planners and capital investors.  Topics include forefront developments in neurotransmitters, neuroreceptors, new drug discovery, computer-aided drug design, nerve cells culture, nerve regeneration, cell therapy, CNS drug delivery and the role of biotechnology.<br>
Published <b>July 1991</b> 275 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C139.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>



<b><A NAME = "C-141" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-141  Immune Diseases: New Developments in Treatment Drugs</b></a><BR>
This BCC report presents the latest advances in diagnostic and therapeutic techniques in dealing with immune diseases.  Profiled diseases include AIDS, rheumatoid arthritis, diabetes mellitus, lupus, cancer, allergies and certain infectious diseases.   Topics covered include current diagnostic and therapeutic products, recently approved products.  Potential for gene therapy and latest development in vaccines are fully assessed.  Market size estimates, market share and growth, 5-year projections and likely potential for new products are provided.  The report also examines FDA approving policy, estimates approval dates for products in clinical trials and provides status of product development programs at leading companies. <br>
Published  <b>June 1991</b>  162 Pages 
Price:  <b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="C141.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-170" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-170  Emerging Markets for Drugs & Vaccines for AIDS and Related Infections</b></a><BR>
AIDS - one of the most deadly diseases of modern history.  With estimates suggesting that the cost of treating HIV and associated infections will reach $10.4 billion by 1994, the market potential for drugs and vaccines to treat the AIDS onslaught is equally extraordinary.  This exclusive BCC study examines the major vaccines and drugs which are currently either in development or undergoing clinical trials.  New developments regarding currently available antiviral AIDS drugs - Retrovir, Videx, Zovirax and Hivid - are presented.  Drugs in various stages of FDA approval for the treatment of AIDS, ARC and HIV, suppression of CMV infection and disease, anogenital herpes simplex virus, herpes zoster and PCP are scrutinized.  Major pharmaceutical companies active in research and marketing of new AIDS and related disorder treatment drugs are profiled.  Market projections (both volume and value) are provided for all relevant drug and treatment segments. <br>  
Published <b>September 1993</b> 157 pages  
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C170.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-171" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-171  The New & Re-emerging Market for Human Vaccines</b></a><BR>
Successful vaccines for such diseases as polio, DPT, measles, smallpox, hepatitis B, meningitis, rabies and flue currently account for worldwide sales of about $1.5 billion annually.  With the concern about treatment of debilitating and often fatal diseases such as AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria rising, many pharmaceutical companies and medical labs are conducting intensive research into vaccines for these illnesses.  Clearly, the medical and financial rewards for such vaccines could be staggering.  This new and timely BCC study examines the development of new vaccines and their market potential.  Technology, research, and key developments are discussed in detail.  Companies active in this evolving marketplace are profiled.  Extensive market projections are provided. <br>
Published: <b>November 1995</b>                                    
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="C171.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-177" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-177 New Therapeutics & Diagnostics for Women's Disorders</b></a><BR></a><BR>
The medical industry is only now beginning to specifically focus on the many complex diseases which attack women.  In this unique BCC research study, new therapeutic and diagnostic treatments for women's disorders are examined in detail.  Current treatments and the role of therapeutics is examined in twenty markets where women represent either the only or the majority of the patients.  This study details the new biotechnology developments which hold promise for improved treatments and cures.  New research involving natural products (e.g., Taxol) is detailed.  Company profiles and relevant market projections through 2000 are provided. <br> 
Published <b>April1994</b> 166 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="C177.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "C-181" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-181  New Strategies for Drug Marketing</b></a><BR></a><BR>
The U.S. pharmaceutical industry is under attack by reformers on a quest to control skyrocketing healthcare costs.  In particular, drug prices have been the focus of intense debate.  In the midst of a marketplace in which increasing competition and regulation are becoming realities, pharmaceutical companies are developing various marketing strategies in order to maximize profits while sustaining growth.  Among these strategies are new marketing concepts including joint ventures, licensing, marketing alliances, mergers, acquisitions, and new pricing structures.  This new BCC study provides an extensive overview and critical analysis of the new strategic marketing programs being employed by major U.S. pharmaceutical companies.  Particular emphasis is given to the internal and external forces underlying these changing marketing strategies. <br>
Published <b>September 1994</b>                      149 pages               
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<A HREF="C181.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "GB-072R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GB-072R  Biocompatible Materials for the Human Body</b></a><BR></a><BR>
This BCC report evaluates the dynamic biocompatible materials market, focusing on the major materials now in use and the emerging trend toward advanced materials and natural products. The materials covered in detail include polymers, ceramics, metals, composites and natural materials. End-market segments analyzed include implants, tissue replacement, drug delivery systems, separation and filtration systems, biosensors, artificial organs, cosmetic and dental. Each is described in terms of materials used, market size, and market participants-ranging from materials suppliers to developers, fabricators, end-users and consumers. <br> 
Published <b>June 1990</b> 104 pages 
Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<A HREF="GB072R.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>


<b><A NAME = "GB-159" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GB-159   Intravenous Therapy Products: Technology & Markets</b></a><BR>
Infusion therapy is an important component in the overall healthcare of patients.  It includes drugs and nutritional supplements which are administered intravenously or enterally.  Important products are antibiotic and chemotherapy drugs, nutritional products and supplements for total and peripheral parenteral nutrition (TPN and PPN), blood infusion products, and enteral products.  The supplies include catheters and tubes, needles, and containers.  The materials include plastic and other chemical raw materials that are consumed in the products and devices.  This BCC study examines the overall market for infusion products, and assesses future market trends and growth in various segments.  The report examines the major players, discusses technologies, and provides market projections through 2000. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b> 164 pages 
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<A HREF="GB159.html"><I>Show contents</i><p></A>

