<HEAD><TITLE>BCC PACKAGING TECHNOLOGIES and PROCESSES</TITLE></HEAD>

<IMG SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO"><BR>

<H4>WELCOME TO BCC PACKAGING TECHNOLOGIES and PROCESSES REPORTS</H4>
<BODY>
Below you will find a list and summaries of all the reports in our
catalog. If you have any questions about our report click on the mail
option at the bottom of the document. If you are
interested in ordering a report, click on the title.<P>
<B>

<a href="#GA-067">Controlled and Modified Atmosphere Packaging (CAPs & MAPs)</a><br>
<a href="#GA-077">New Package Types/Configurations for Processed Convenience Foods</a><br>
<a href="#P-085N">What Is New in Barrier Packaging?</a><br>
<a href="#P-130">The Plastic Pouch Business:  Materials, Markets, Technologies</a><br>
<a href="#P-137">Barrier & Selective Barrier Plastic-Based Materials and Structures for Packaging</a><br>
<a href="#P-137R">Plastics for Barrier Packaging</a><br>
</B><p><HR>

<b><A NAME = "GA-067" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-067 Controlled and Modified Atmosphere Packaging (CAPs & MAPs)</b></a><BR>
Successfully developed in Western Europe, controlled and modified atmosphere packaging is now poised on the threshold of explosive growth in the U.S.  This BCC report studies the reintroduction of CAP-MAP packaging into the U.S. market, tracing its rapid growth since 1985.  It describes how this technology has been selected in response to the need for a packaging method which could provide increased freshness and  longer shelf life, as well as the possibility of central prepackaging for large scale distribution.  The study describes and quantifies the developments in packaging materials, preserving atmospheres, packaged products (raw meat, fish, processed meats, prepared foods, produce, fruits, pasta, bakery goods, etc.) and equipment used for CAP-MAP-vacuum packaging through 1996.  It also discusses the principal companies involved in spearheading this packaging revolution. <br>
Published <b>April 1991</b> 215 pages  
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<A HREF="GA067.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "GA-077" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">GA-077 New Package Types/Configurations for Processed Convenience Foods</b></a><BR>
This comprehensive BCC report details the growing markets for new convenience foods as changing government regulations and evolving consumer preferences shape the marketplace.  New frozen convenience foods, chilled foods, shelf-stable foods, and aseptically packaged foods are examined and analyzed.  Company profiles of the major players in the industry are provided in order to fully document the convenience food industry.  Other areas are analyzed, including snack foods, new processed meats, poultry and seafood, and new convenience dairy products.  U.S. industry structure is thoroughly detailed, with market projections provided for convenience foods by type and market segment. <br> 
Published <b>March 1992</b> 201 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="GA077.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "P-085N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-085N What Is New in Barrier Packaging?</b></a><BR>
The 1990 consumption of barrier polymers in the U.S. was 132 million pounds and is expected to grow at an aggregate annual rate of 7.2% per year through 1995. Opportunities for manufacturers of resins, equipment and packaging lines.  This BCC report reviews the substantial growth already experienced in barrier packaging in the recent past, and describes how future growth will be explosive due, to a large extent, to the rapid technological advances in coextruded barrier materials and packaging systems, and the improved economics which they have fostered.  While traditional food packaging materials, such as glass, metal, and paper will continue to be replaced by plastic packaging, the new coextruded composites will penetrate further into the existing markets and create new applications where low weight, design flexibility, durability, unlimited decorating potential and energy savings are at a premium.  Report discusses all these advances in resins, processing technology, options, economics and strategies used by major packagers, resin and equipment manufacturers, and food processors. <br>
Published <b>December 1990</b> 213 pages   
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P085N.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "P-130" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">P-130 The Plastic Pouch Business:  Materials, Markets, Technologies</b></a><BR>
One form of plastic packaging that has been available virtually since the dawn of the commercial plastic era is the flexible pouch. But what are the direct and indirect economic and environmental advantages of the plastic pouch today? While certain products are packaged in rigid containers, almost all food and many non-food products are packaged in small or large pouches produced from single- or multi-layer film. This comprehensive BCC study covers the materials, markets and technologies associated with the growing $6 billion plastic pouch packaging industry. It details pouch production and consumption patterns in all aspects, including the types of pouches currently available, the equipment used as substrate and barrier materials, the key applications in the primary markets, the economics of pouch production, and past/future patterns of consumption. Forecasts in sales and volume are provided with growth rates through 1996. <br>
Published <b>December 1991</b> 153 pages    
Price:  <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="P130.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b><A NAME = "P-137" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">P-137 Barrier & Selective Barrier Plastic-Based Materials and Structures for Packaging</b></a><BR>
Plastic-based barrier and selective barrier structures have grown in importance in recent years for applications in food, pharmaceutical, medical, chemical and industrial packaging. Barrier structures provide needed protection of contents, while at the same time minimizing the escape of any inside constituents. Selective barriers, on the other hand, allow easy packaging of gases and vapors, but prevent the passage of liquids. This in-depth BCC analysis examines the materials used, the applications, and market potential. Structures analyzed include flexible and rigid packaging, in both single-layered and multi-layered (coated, laminated, coextruded, and surface modified) packaging. Market projections through 1997 are provided. <br>
Published <b>February  1994</b>       167 pages   
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P137.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "P-137R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">P-137R Plastics for Barrier Packaging</b></a><BR>
This updated report covers oxygen barriers and moisture barriers, as well as others such as UV, flavor/odor, CO2, etc.  This comprehensive report assesses packaging markets by barrier resin application and technology, together with industry structure and competitive analysis as well as international aspects.  Environmental, regulatory, and public policy issues affecting the barrier packaging industry are discussed.  Major international and domestic companies are profiled.
 <br>
Published <b>May 1996</b>       269 pages   
Price: <b>$2850.00</b><a href="P137R.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


