<b> <A NAME = "C-193" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">C-193 Performance Fluorine Chemicals & Polymers</b> </a><BR>
The presence of fluorine in an inorganic or organic chemical molecule or polymer has a striking influence on its chemical and physical properties.  These influences are most often seen in high chemical stability and inertness.  However, performance fluorine-containing chemicals also find uses as chemical intermediates and products for pharmaceutical and agricultural use, as refrigerants, in fluoridation of water in toothpaste, as etchants/dopants, and a number of other uses.  This BCC report covers a wide number of performance fluorine chemicals and polymers, with emphasis on their unique properties and markets. Current controversies over use of several important fluorine compounds, ranging from CFCs to electronic chemicals, are also discussed. <br>
Published<b> October 1995</b>   176 pages         
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="C193.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b> <A NAME = "DPF95" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">The 1995 BCC Plastics Factbook</b></a><BR>
The most used plastics industry statistics are again available in the new 1995 BCC Plastics Factbook.
The 1995 edition covers resin sales, resin demand by major market and a time series of resin prices.  In addition to a 
list of about 800 major resin suppliers, compounders, additive suppliers and processors, the Factbook identifies the 
top 25 resin suppliers and major processors (by type), based on 1994 sales.  More than 375 company trademarks are 
noted, alphabetized by resin type, company, and name.  A comparison of plastics production versus competitive 
material production, over time, offers an insight into the penetration that plastics have made into traditional material 
markets.
<P>
This year, BCC has added more demand on plastics applications and specific uses, including plastics pipe, electronic 
components, plastics distribution and compounding, transparent plastics, disposables and small appliances.  These 
data are derived from recent BCC studies.
<P>
A section on international data is included, recognizing that the U.S. plastics industry is heavily supported by foreign-
based companies, and U.S. plastics companies in turn have foreign affiliations in the major trading regions.  
Traditionally, the U.S. plastics industry has been a  positive factor in the nation's balance of trade, as can be seen 
from the reported export data.<br>
Published <b>September 1995</b>		115 pages Price: <b>$275.00</b>
<a href="DPF95.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "E-057" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> E-057 Insulation Materials Markets & Applications</b> </a><BR>
This unique BCC report presents a quantitative analysis of the competition among thermal insulation materials used within the residential and non-residential construction indusetry.  It focusses on the competition within each market and assesses sales trends over the next five and ten years.  Factors that are expected to contribute to the gains of some materials and the losses of others are looked at in depth.  This analysis emphasizes relative price differentials and real and/or perceived technological advantages offered by different materials. <br>
Published <b>May 1995</b>     164 pages     Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="E057.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-027U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-027U  Plastics versus Paper & Paperboard: Update</b> </a><BR>
This BCC report assesses the historic, present and likely future of plastics penetration into markets dominated by the paper industry. Markets analyzed include wallpaper, cover and text, envelopes, labels, wrapping paper, shipping sacks, grocery bags, shopping bags, merchandise bags, containerboard, folding and milk cartons, and other food service containers, as well as waxing stock, gumming stock, and parchments. The study examines all the issues. Estimates and forecasts through 1998 are provided by type of materials and by applications with detailed analyses of trends in production and shipments. <br>
Published <b>August 1994</b>   199 pages 
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P027U.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-031X" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-031X  Fillers and Extenders for Plastics</b> </a><BR>
The market for fillers and extenders for plastics is growing as plastics processors and end-users seek enhanced cost/performance from their materials. On the one hand, the fillers used in plastics compounding help to control costs, and cost sensitivities have increased in the course of the recent recession. On the other hand, end-users want plastic materials tailored to very specific part requirements, and this has led to a re-evaluation of these fillers and extenders. This report covers the production and the consumption of mineral fillers, synthetic fillers, organic fillers, coupling agents and extenders, as well as feedstock sources, properties and pricing. Data are offered for 1992 and forecasts offered for 1997-by resin and by filler/extender. Applications addressed include those in automotive, construction, packaging, electrical/electronic equipment, furniture, appliances and housewares. <br>
Published <b>March 1994</b> 290 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="P031X.html"><I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-043X" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-043X  The Competitive Pipe Industry</b> </a><BR>
<body>Pipe of all types and sizes is critical in building, construction, chemical, energy and other industrial applications. With brighter economic trends bringing more construction, the pipe industry is expected to experience considerable change and growth.  This comprehensive BCC market analysis examines the pipe industry and the increasing use of pipe across a growing range of markets. Recent technology advances are discussed.  Volume and value projections are provided for each type of pipe and pipe material through 1998.  Players active in this competitive marketplace are profiled in detail. <br>
Published <b> March 1994</b> 238 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b> 
<a href="P043X.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-051U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-051U High Temperature Plastics: Expanding Material Options and Markets</b> </a><BR>
The range of options and the global opportunities for high heat-resistant plastic materials (thermoplastic and thermoset) are widening.  Many test programs are now ready to move to the production stage - in appliances, aircraft/aerospace, automotive, continuous processing equipment, electrical/electronic devices, industrial parts, medical parts, et al.  Following up on its 1987 report, BCC has surveyed the leading global manufacturers of these high heat-resistant resins to provide a realistic assessment of the current and likely future prospects for these materials and the new-part programs that we are likely to see in the coming decade. Specific market data is forecast through the next five years. <br>
Published <b>September 1991</b> 214 pages 
Price:  <b>$2950.00</b>
<a href="P051U.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-053N" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-053N  Rigid Non-Packaging Transparent Plastics</b> </a><BR>
Transparent plastics are used in many applications ranging from flat sheet products to parts with complex geometries or precise dimensions (e.g., optical lenses). In most of these applications they compete against glass; in others there is no clear alternative in terms of cost and/or performance. In this report, BCC quantifies and describes the opportunities for transparent plastics of the commodity/specialty type, identifies the market players (both domestic and foreign), and forecasts growth by resin and by application in the aircraft, appliances, automotive, building and construction, consumer goods, electronic equipment, industrial, medical/laboratory, optical lenses and other  industries through 1998. <br>
Published <b>July 1994</b> 166 pages     
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P053N.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-064U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-064U  Plastics in Electronic Equipment Enclosures</b> </a><BR>
 BCC has covered the topic of plastics in electronic equipment (business machine) enclosures in the past (1981 and 1986), and this report provides a comprehensive, contemporary perspective on the new economic and environmental factors affecting resin preferences and the volume of material required over the period 1992-1997. Data and insights are based upon an extensive survey of materials decision-makers at leading electronic equipment manufacturers and leading processors of these enclosure parts utilizing all types of plastics-thermoplastic and thermoset, commodity and engineering grades. Evolving trends and EMI shielding materials/methods and plastic material additives are also highlighted. Profiles are provided of the major corporate players in this diverse marketplace.  Given the competitive nature of this evolving marketplace, this study will provide potentially critical decision-making information. <br>
Published <b>October 1992</b> 215 pages 
Price:  <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="P064U.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-075U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-075U Optimization of Mechanical Properties of Thermoplastics through Alloying</b> </a><BR>
Thermoplastic alloys and blends have shown vigorous growth lately in market penetration, volumes used and new technical developments and increased need for such products by the target industries.  This detailed BCC evaluation of thermoplastic alloys and blends includes the study of alloy types and properties, their markets by application areas - such as automotive, aerospace, electronics and appliances.   The criteria used for the selection of particular blends are fully discussed.  New developments in compatibilization technology are also discussed. <br> 
Published <b> October 1991</b>          246 pages 
Price:  <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="P075U.html"> <I>Show contents</a></i><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-081A" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-081A  Opportunities for Plastics in Toys and Outdoor Playground Equipment</b> </a><BR>
Plastics have been replacing traditional materials (e.g., metals, rubber and wood) in toy manufacturing for several decades now, but the inter-material battle still goes on - not only in traditional toys such as dolls, models, play sets, board games, etc., but also in the booming business for institutional and residential outdoor playground equipment.  There is also constant intra-material competition as the suppliers and processors of commodity thermoplastics (polyethylene, polystyrene, polypropylene and PVC) vie for existing and new toy part programs.  The opportunities for plastics in toys are spread across all processing technologies - injection molding, blow molding, rotational molding, thermoforming, etc.  This report provides a comprehensive survey of toy manufacturers and custom plastics processors with significant exposure in the toy business, and it outlines the new economic, environmental and design conditions that are affecting material decision-making and growth prospects to the end of the decade. <br>
Published <b>June 1992</b> 112 pages 
Price: <b>$1750.00</b>
<a href="P081A.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-081B" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-081B Opportunities for Plastics in Household Appliances</b> </a><BR>
The end of the 1990-1991 recession is reflected in a new surge of demand for small and large appliances for residential usage.  This bodes well for the suppliers of resins (e.g., polystyrene, ABS, polyurethane, PVC, and a host of other commodity and engineering thermoplastics and thermosets) that have historically participated in this business.  This BCC report covers the continuing inter-material competition, such as plastics replacing metals, glass, etc., and intra-material competition (among the various resins) for shares of this large and newly resurgent industry. Market projections based upon value and volume are provided. <br>
Published <b>January 1993</b> 145 pages 
Price:  <b>$1750.00</b>
<a href="P081B.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-086R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-086R  Geosynthetics: New Opportunities for Geotextiles, Geomembranes, Geosynthetic Clay Linings and Geomatrices</b> </a><BR>
Geosynthetics continue to comprise a growing technology and market, with expanding applications in land reclamation, waste and hazardous waste site construction, and a variety of other construction uses.  This unique and timely BCC study examines geotextiles, geomembranes and geomatrices, explores potential market growth, developing technology trends, industry leaders, and other variables affecting this evolving marketplace.  Present and potential markets for materials are highlighted.  Abstracts for key patents are provided, in addition to characteristic applications utilizing geotextiles and related materials.<br>
Published <b>July 1993</b> 116 pages 
Price: <b>$2250.00</b>
<a href="P086R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-099R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-099R  Plastics in ESD Applications</b> </a><BR>
Along with the proliferation of microelectronics in all aspects of modern work and living patterns, there has been an increase in the risk of microelectronics component and device failure due to random static electricity hazards. As a result, a whole new industry, referred to as static control or electrostatic discharge (ESD) protection products, has emerged. Plastics play a major role in the various static control product lines-rigid containers and flexible packaging, foam cushioning, wire and cable wrap, conductive flooring, wrist straps and shoe/heel grounders, work surfacces, etc. BCC updates earlier (1987) research program in this field, identifying the major materials/methods for rendering plastics antistatic or static dissipative, identifying all the major players on the supply chain of antistatic compounds, sheet, film and products, and quantifying the volume and value of sales from 1991-1996.</b>
Published <b>January 1992</b> 245 pages 
Price: <b>$2450.00</b>
<a href="P099R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-102" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-102  Industrial Hollow Plastic Parts</b> </a><BR>
BCC study examines the wide range of hollow plastic parts-from instrument panels and fuel tanks to storage drums and toys-made by a variety of different plastics processing methods. Current and likely future consumption of commodity thermoplastics and high-performance engineering resins used in these hollow-shaped parts are tabulated by processing method and by application. In each case, price, properties and performance are discussed to lend insight to intermaterials competition.  The available technologies and the economics within the major markets are investigated, with case studies to reveal current and future trends. <br>
Published <b>January 1991</b>         129  pages 
Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<a href="P102.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-112R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-112R Degradable Plastics:  Impact on Litter & Solid Waste Disposal</b> </a><BR>
This report provides a comprehensive analysis of the present and future status of the degradable plastics industry, detailing production levels of various types of degradable plastics, the uses for these resins, the competition between producers, the technological difficulties encountered, and expected breakthroughs. It focuses on the following three areas: the photodegradability and biodegradability of synthetic polymers, and the bright future of degradable biopolymers. The report also examines the role degradable plastics are expected to play in solving our plastic waste disposal problems. With estimates suggesting 55 billion lbs. of post-consumer plastic waste to dispose of by the year 2000, the report investigates the contribution degradable plastics can make to a solution to this waste disposal problem. Market size and value projection are provided through 1997. <br>
Published <b>December 1992</b> 161 pages 
Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P112R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-120R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-120R  Polymeric Foams, A Huge Sub-Industry</b> </a><BR>
This BCC technical-market report examines polymeric foam materials and technologies. It discusses their application in comfort cushioning, thermal insulation, packaging, transportation, and a host of miscellaneous others. It covers the environmental impact and future restrictions of blowing agents used to manufacture these materials. This study provides an overview of the industry structure and the companies involved. The major players and the nature of their activities are profiled. Market estimates and forecasts are given by material and application. The study also discusses R&D, patents, international issues, economics, and other environmental concerns. <br>
Published <b> April 1994</b>    180 pages     Price:  <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P120R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b><A NAME = "P-120U" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-120U  Polymeric Foams</b> </a><BR>
Significant changes continue to occur in this major segment of the plastics production and processing industry.  This in-depth BCC report covers the most important technological, economic, political and environmental considerations in the U.S. polymeric foams industry.  Forecasts are given for markets by application as well as material types, including three classes of major commodity resins used to produce foams: polyolefins, polystyrene, and polyvinyl chloride, with focus on the largest foamed polymer group, the polyurethanes.  Also included are analysis of the industry structure, with emphasis on the major domestic producers and suppliers, trends in the industry, and the international aspects.
<br>
Published <b> June 1996</b> 233 pages      Price:  <b>$2950.00</b>
