In 1990, plastic resin sales in the U.S. totaled 61.5 billion lbs.  Over the past few years, however, the plastics industry has become embroiled in environmental controversies which threaten the very foundation of this promising business.  This new BCC study provides a comprehensive analysis of the rapidly developing plastics recycling industry, covering industrial and post-consumer collection, sorting and recycling efforts by major recyclers and by types of resins, financial considerations for plastics recycling, and technological problems associated with this industry.   Resins examined include HDPE, PS, PVC, LDPE, PET, and PP.  The role of plastics in landfills is detailed together with the legal conditions facing plastic resin manufacturers.  Material suppliers, compounders, processors, and users are identified.  Market projections for secondary plastic recycling calculated through 1996. <br> 
