<b> <A NAME = "P-141" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-141 Plastics in Durable Goods: A Qualitative Assessment of Environmental Issues</b> </a><BR>
The manufacture of durable goods in the U.S. accounts for millions of lbs. of plastics consumption annually.  However, in the wake of new environmental regulations both implemented and proposed, manufacturers of durable goods will be required to substitute and/or blend resins in a wide variety of important products.  This unique and timely BCC study examines the specific resins - which ones will be affected, and what will be the extent of these content changes?  PVC and styrenics consumption in durable goods manufacture is analyzed, as is the effect of new recycle content regulations.  Costs of handling, separating and recycling are also quantified relative to costs of the final products.  Additives such as flame retardants, antistats, UV stabilizers and other are detailed in the context of the changing durable good marketplace.  Suppliers are profiled and market projections through 2000 are provided.  European developments are explored. <br>
