<a href="P214.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-216" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-216 The Current Status of Plastic Recycling</b> </a><BR>
For years, recycling has been accepted as the best solution for the plastic solid waste management crisis.  But what is the status of recycling efforts today - how well are they actually working?  This timely BCC report provides a comprehensive overview and analysis of the trends and technologies affecting the recycling industry. Recyclers, resin companies, and recycling organizations are profiled in detail. The study reviews current markets and new Federal, state and local regulations for both durable and disposable products. Comparisons to recycling efforts in other material industries are discussed.  Market projections provided by volume and value of goods recycled through 1999. <br>
Published <b>July 1994</b>   254 pages 
Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P216.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b> <A NAME = "P-216R" HREF="bcc_order_report.html">P-216R	The Current Status of Plastics Recycling</b> </a><BR>
The plastics recycling industry has experienced incredible growth and popularity for 
more than ten years, but its continued success may be  tentative, inasmuch as it is an 
industry that was founded on, and is still supported by, political pressures and public 
concerns over environmental issues.  This BCC report examines the plastics recycling 
industry and determines whether it is an artificially driven market, destined to create a 
supply and demand imbalance, or a market-driven business, determined by cost and 
quality issues.  Major players are profiled and market projections are provided through 
the year 2000 for durable and disposable goods.  The practicality of recycled plastics 
packaging is weighed against the reliability of virgin resin packaging. The impact of 
current regulations and pending legislation is addressed.<br>
Published: <b>October 1996</b>	382 pages     Price: <b>$2950.00</b>
<a href="P216R.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

<b> <A NAME = "P-217" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-217 Plastics in Small Appliances</b> </a><BR>
Appliance makers are among the most innovative users of plastics.  This unique BCC report examines the consumption of plastics in small appliances such as leaf blowers, drills, snowblowers, trimmers, saws, hair dryers, shavers, toothbrushes, mixers, vacuums, irons and food processors, to name a few.  The study traces the consumption of thermosets, engineering and transitional materials, upgraded commodity resins, and thermoplastic elastomers, which account for a significant portion of most small appliances.  Materials substitution issues are examined, as well as impending regulatory initiatives and recycling issues.  Detailed profiles are provided of the major players active in this diverse marketplace.  Market projections by sales and material volume used are provided for the next five years. <br>
Published <b>September 1994</b>                144 pages                  
Price: <b>$2350.00</b>
<a href="P217.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>



<b> <A NAME = "P-222" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-222 Plastics in Electronic Components: A Quantitative Analysis </a><BR> </b>
Demand for plastics for use in electronic components is accelerating rapidly as consumers purchase more and more electronic devices ranging from computers to cellular telephones.  This comprehensive BCC study examines electronic technologies in which plastics are a significant design and engineering consideration, such as microchips, circuit boards, interconnects, semiconductors, capacitors, sockets, relays and coil forms.  Plastics including engineering resins, performance polymers and thermosets are examined in relation to use in these applications.  Plastics consumption and value in electronic applications is extrapolated through 1999.  Detailed company profiles are provided. <br>
Published: <b>April 1995</b>     163 pages     Price: <b>$2650.00</b>
<a href="P222.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-223" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-223 High Performance Films </a><BR> </b>
Demand for high-performance films are driven by end-use applications led by food packaging, electrical/electronics, magnetic media, photographic film, tapes/labels, etc.  This specialty niche market comprises polyesters, nylons, polycarbonates, fluoropolymers, polyimides and a host of specialty resins.  This novel BCC report will cover markets, R&D activities, trends, business opportunities, and critical factors for success.  Company profiles will be provided along with detailed market estimates and projections. <br>
Published <b>November 1995</b>                   
Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="P223.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-224" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-224 World Plastics: Opportunities </a><BR> </b>
The movement of plastics resins and fabricated products throughout the world is a multibillion dollar business involving thousnds of resin suppliers, fabricators, distributors, and machinery companies.  Economic, political and demographic changes within the past few years prompted BCC to review the dynamics of world plastics.  This study examines the production, consumption, balance of trade and key trends in each of the 40 countries investigated.  Key contacts in this competitive marketplace are profiled in detail. <br>
Published <b>May 1995</b>                       238 pages                  Price: <b>$2750.00</b>
<a href="P224.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>


<b> <A NAME = "P-2000" HREF="bcc_order_report.html"> P-2000 Opportunities for U.S. Resin Exports in the Global Plastics Market of the 1990s </a><BR> </b>
Like most processing and manufacturing industries, the plastics industry is becoming a global business with many more countries participating in the production, consumption and exports of resins.  As a result of this growing globalization and competitive factors unique to the North American economies, the trade in resins, which was an engine of growth for the whole  North American plastics business in the 1970s, became a drag on  growth in the 1980s.  What do the 1990s hold in terms of the North American plastics companies competing on their domestic markets and expanding their operations overseas?  BCC report covers the historical record of regional plastics market shares and projects trends into the future, for both commodity  resins and engineering/specialty resins of all types.<br>  
Published <b> March 1991</b> 215 pages 
Price:  <b>$1950.00</b>
<a href="P2000.html"> <I>Show contents</i></a><p>

