<P ALIGN=center>In the Two Decades Since the OPEC Oil Embargo, 

the U.S. Economy Has Grown by 60 Percent.  

But Energy Consumption Increased Only 13 Percent.</P>



<H3 ALIGN=center>How can that be? <BR>The answer is simple: 

energy conservation and increased energy efficiency. </H3>

<BODY>

The message of the oil shocks of the 1970s was the imperative to increase the

productivity of 

energy.  The results have been nothing short of  astonishing. And the end is

nowhere in sight. Even 

now, with low prices of  gas, oil and coal, those gains  and the push to

conserve is continuing.  

That's because utilities, transportation companies, real estate managers,

manufacturers and 

businesses, both large and small, have discovered that energy conservation is

one of the most 

attainable routes to increased profits.

<P>

Virtually every business can still substantially add to its profit margins and

productivity simply by 

working to reduce energy consumption and increase efficiency. Progress is

being made with new 

integrated systems, energy conservation technology and energy management

techniques.  In 

addition, new energy conservation legislation continues to be introduced. 

</BODY>

<H4 ALIGN=center>To Be Certain You Are Not 

Missing Important Opportunities,<BR>  

Read Energy Conservation News</H4>

<BODY>

<B>Energy Conservation News</B> has been an essential tool for helping companies

become more 

energy-efficient for the past 11 years.   Each month, <B>Energy Conservation News</B>

will bring you 

the latest information about:



<UL><LI>    Conservation Technology:  Cogeneration, fuel cells, energy-efficient

appliances, lighting, 

product design



<LI>    Alternative Energy: Low head hydro, geothermal, solar, electric and

hybrid vehicles



<LI>    Energy Management:  Case studies, new products, metering and monitoring,

building 

design, 

     standards, load management



<LI>    Forecasts and Analysis: State and government initiatives, energy

planning, demand 

predictions, price trends</UL>





Become a regular reader of <B>Energy Conservation News</B>. <BR>Just fill in the <A HREF="bcc_order_news.html"><I>order

form</I></A> and you will receive 12 issues for only $325.

