<H3 ALIGN=center> FROM  THE  LAPTOP TO THE MICROWAVE, 
ADVANCED DISPLAYS ARE CHANGING THE WAY WE LIVE</H3>
<BODY>
Displays are a vital part of industrial and consumer products throughout the world.  Once thought
of as 
simple indicator lights, they have become major devices in the performance of computing, medical 
imaging, and process control, and have also become a fixture in the world of entertainment. From
video to 
kitchen appliances and portable computers or even your digital wristwatch, they are now an enabling 
technology.</body><BR>
<body>
Estimates place the current annual market for flat panel displays at over $5 billion and projections
for the 
year 2000 range from $11 to $20 billion. Liquid crystal technology accounts for approximately
82% of 
this market.  Other display technologies include electroluminescence, plasma, vacuum fluorescent, light 
emitting diode and a new entrant, the field emission display. Keeping ahead in this rapidly
evolving 
technology is a challenge to investor and technologist alike.
</body>
<H4 align=center>That's Why You Should Be Reading
DISPLAY TECHNOLOGY NEWS</H4>
<body>
A major objective of flat panel displays is the replacement of the CRT with its bulky vacuum tube
and 
expensive power needs.  But the tube is not going away!  Its a $14 billion annual business and is
the 
major display used in TV and desktop computers.  Even at half the growth rate of flat panels, the
CRT 
will still be generating over $21 billion annually in 2000.  One thing is certain - the market for
displays is 
huge and will continue to expand with the growth of the information world we live in.  
</body>
What's in doubt, however, is the outcome.  

<UL><LI>  How much of the market will go to flat panels?  
<LI> Will the field emission device become the leader over the liquid crystal display?  
<LI> Will the CRT become flat enough to improve its growth rate?</UL>

<B>DISPLAY TECHNOLOGY NEWS</I> is a new newsletter that will keep you informed of
this fascinating
and lucrative battle for the market. Each month, DISPLAY TECHNOLOGY NEWS will report
on:

<UL><LI>     Cathode Ray Technology      
<LI>Electroluminescent Displays     
<LI>Display Materials              
<LI>Processing and Equipment  
<LI> New Applications     
<LI>Microtechnology 
<LI> Patents and Technology Transfer     
<LI>Patents     
<LI>Industry News   
<LI>Liquid Crystals 
<LI> LEDs  
<LI>Field Emission</UL>  

Each issue of <B>DISPLAY TECHNOLOGY NEWS</B> will keep you up to date in this fast
changing 
technology.  Don't be left in the rear areas of this battle zone.<BR>
<P>
Become a regular reader of<B> DISPLAY TECHNOLOGY NEWS<B> today.<BR> Just fill in the<A
HREF="bcc_order_news.html"><I> order form</I></A> and you will receive 12 issues for only $325.
