<H3 ALIGN=center>What Do Advanced Drug Delivery, Water Treatment, Food 

Processing, Cosmetics and Petroleum Refining Have in 

Common?

<P>

The Answer: A New Generation of

Advanced Microporous Materials.</H3>



<BODY>A new technology based on materials with carefully engineered microscopic pores is having a 

startling and lucrative impact on a wide range of industries. These designer materials can be 

made in an enormous variety of sizes and shapes and from materials as diverse as ceramics and 

metals, clays and powdered carbon.

<P>

The key is that the pore structure and size can be carefully controlled to produce very specific 

properties. They can immobilize certain chemicals, catalyze chemical reactions, release drugs 

into the bloodstream at a controlled rate, act as sensors, separate gases, decolorize wine, and 

clean up contaminated soil. Microporous materials are as important in seemingly mundane 

household products, such as baby diapers, as they are in high-tech products like advanced 

thermal insulation. They also play a role in a broad range of industrial processes, from food to 

specialty chemicals.

<P>

Already, many of these materials constitute billion dollar markets. And in this fast growing 

industry, new opportunities are arising almost daily.</BODY>



<H4 ALIGN=center>That's Why You Should Be Reading

Microporous Materials Technology News</H4>

<BODY>

An annual subscription to <B>Microporous Materials Technology News</B> will keep you up to date 

about developments in this vigorous and growing technology. Each issue explores, analyzes and 

reports on the science, technology and business of:



<UL><LI>		Sorbent polymers

<LI>		Microsponges

<LI>		Inorganic sorbents (clay, silica gel)

<LI>		Chelates

<LI>		Molecular sieves, Zeolites

<LI>		Clathrates

<LI>		Activated carbon

<LI>		Ion exchange resins</UL>



Each issue of <B>Microporous Materials Technology News</B> will bring you the latest news of 

legislative and regulatory activities, key patents, industry developments, licenses and technology 

transfer offerings. Items contain the name, address and phone number of contacts so its easy to 

act on new information.

<P>

Become a regular reader of <B>Microporous Materials Technology News</B>. <BR>Just fill in the <A HREF="bcc_order_news.html"><I>order form</I></A> and you will receive 12 issues for only $375.



