<H3 ALIGN=center>Water Is Something You Borrow.<BR> 

If You Use It, You Had Better Put It Back Clean</H3>



<BODY>

Water purity and water conservation have never been more important. Virtually every company in 

every industry is affected, from giant paper mills, food processors and utilities to the corner gas station 

and the local drive-in restaurant.  Water quality rules are becoming ever more stringent, complex and 

costly.  Companies must meet the rules enforcing the federal Clean Water Act  as well as a maze of state 

and local regulations.<BR>  

<P>

And waste is by no means the only issue.  Most industries must obtain ever-purer water for their 

processes. Some, such as semiconductor and pharmaceutical makers, require water of  almost absolute 

purity.  Most companies are finding they have to clean their water both before and after they use it.<BR>

<P>

But there is an upside. A vigorous new industry is employing new technology to cleanse process and 

potable water, clean contaminated groundwater and purify industrial waste. And many smart firms--both 

large and small--are finding that adopting advanced technology can give them an edge over less nimble 

competitors and add profits to the bottom line.  And they are finding that <B>WATER TECHNOLOGY NEWS</B> 

is an indispensable tool.<BR><P>  </BODY>



<H4 ALIGN=center>Make <B>WATER TECHNOLOGY NEWS</B>

Part of Your Company's Competitive Strategy </H4>



<BODY>There is no shortage of cost-cutting technology. Almost daily equipment and instrument makers, as well 

as industry and academic researchers announce new ways to monitor quality, remove contaminants, and 

recycle water. But finding the proper alternatives--at the right price--can be bewildering. The solution is 

<B>WATER TECHNOLOGY NEWS.</B><BR>

<P>

Each issue of <B>WATER TECHNOLOGY NEWS</B> will keep you informed of: 



<UL><LI>	 Instruments and Monitoring Devices 	

<LI>	 Testing Technology 			

<LI>	 Ultrapure Water Treatment 		

<LI>	 Membrane Processes			

<LI>	 Recycling Processes

<LI>	 Biofiltration and Chemical Treatment

<LI>	 Modeling

<LI>	 Wastewater Purification</UL>



An annual subscription to <B>WATER TECHNOLOGY NEWS</B> will also bring you the latest news of 

legislative and regulatory activities, key patents, industry developments, licenses and technology transfer 

offerings. Items contain the name, address and phone number of contacts so it;s easy to act on new 

information.<BR>

<P>

Become a regular reader of <B>WATER TECHNOLOGY NEWS</B>. <BR>Just fill in the <A HREF="bcc_order_news.html"><I>order form</I></A> and you will receive 12 issues for only $350.

