<HTML>
 
<H1 ALIGN=center>G-132R: CREDIT AND DEBIT CARDS:
                         WHAT'S NEW? WHERE TO?</H1>

<I> <H3 ALIGN=center>Gail Janowiz
                           Project Analyst</H3> </I>

<H2 ALIGN=center>INTRODUCTION</H2>


<H3>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</H3>

<P>This study focuses on integrated economic, industry, market, and
competitive viewpoints on the changing credit/debit card industry. The
industry stands today at a crossroads, where established industry players,
including the major credit card companies and the nations widespread
commercial banking sector, are being buffeted by changes brought on by
technology advances, economic shifts, and the interest and possible
encroachment by major corporate entities in other sectors. In addition, the
underlying usage sectors of payment media  the retail, service, and
government sectors  are being shaped by evolutionary forces that will in
turn affect the use of credit and debit cards. The U.S. payment system will
emerge from this evolutionary period with significant changes, and credit
and debit cards will play an even more significant role in this newly shaped
system.</P>


<H3>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</H3>

<P>This study offers a fresh look at the credit and debit card industry by
examining the underlying forces that have caused the observed evolution in
the industry over the past decade, and forecasting its future and the
resulting impact on the card economy through the year 2000. The report
takes a different viewpoint from many studies of the industry which
examined trends from the issuers viewpoint.  This study takes those
trends as the end-point, and looks at the forces that will shape the
issuers. It offers insight into the combination of industry, economic,
demographic, and technological changes that will have an impact on credit
and debit products, and how together they will reshape the industry
landscape and result in a credit/debit card industry that will look far
different by the year 2000 than it does today.</P>



<H3>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</H3>

<P>This study is positioned to offer a comprehensive overview of the
credit/debit card industry and projects its shape and size into the future.
As an overview, it focuses on the resulting effects of the various
economic and market forces shaping its future.</P>

<P>This study will be of critical interest to suppliers into the industry;
players within the various sectors in current or potential competition with
the industry (such as  checking-related institutions, and electronic
financial interchange organizations); institutions representing customers
of these industries; and industries seeking to understand their role in the
payment systems over the next six years, including information companies,
computer firms, and retail industry players.</P>

<H3>SCOPE AND FORMAT</H3>

<P>This study centers around an examination of the numerous forces shaping
the changes in the credit/debit card industry over the next decade. As a
backdrop, this report examines consumer usage of credit/debit cards,
including their role in the U.S. payment system, and the economic,
demographic, and industry perspectives forming the background for this
industry.</P>

<P>The main portion of the study focuses on the usage sectors for cards,
specifically the retail sector, service sector (including federal, state, and
municipal government) and the corporate sector. An examination of issuers
and specific credit card types offers a view of the current status and
future changes to be expected here. POS debit cards are examined
separately, drawing together the forecasts of retail, service, and
corporate usage sectors, and examining the role of the issuer and
supporting institutions. Finally, the use of credit and debit cards around
the world are presented in the International section.</P>

<H3>METHODOLOGY</H3>

<P>This study views its consumers, its industry components, and its suppliers
from an overview of how they affect each other. Each sector is analyzed
separately, and the effects of their changes on the credit and debit card
industry are discussed.</P>

<P>Industry statistics and projections in this report are, except where noted,
the result of independent analysis by BCC. They are based on a study of
the dynamics of supply and demand forces affecting the credit/debit
sector. Forecasts are not simply projections of historical trends.  Rather,
they were individually developed based on a) an understanding of the speed
of technological advancements and their acceptance by the consumer and
business sectors; b) close examination of changes in underlying consumer
needs and business structures; and c) independent evaluation of the actual
strength of the credit/debit card sectors institutions.</P>


<H3>INFORMATION SOURCES</H3>

<P>Information for this report comes from numerous sources.  These include:
interviews with major industry players, including issuers, technology
providers, and merchants; examination of economic data and interviews with
economists, market shapers, and trade associations; review of documented
history of the industry; and examination of company reports and financial
statements. Major industry experts and core industry documentation served
as a backdrop to BCCs analysis. In addition, this report sought out the
views of major players in the sectors which will affect card use,
specifically the retail, government and other service sectors.  Their views
of the evolution of their industries and payment options formed the
background for industry analysis and projections.</P>


<H3>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS INCLUDING WORK DONE BY
OTHER AUTHORS</H3

<P>This report is the latest in a line of studies on the various aspects of the
U.S. financial system and its changing technologies. Relevant recent
reports published by BCC include Electronic Cash: Prepaid and Stored Value
Transaction Cards, published June 1994 and The Smart Card, published in
January, 1991, as well as POS Retail Automation in the 1990s, published in
October, 1992.</P>


