<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-135  POINT-OF-SALE RETAIL AUTOMATION IN THE 1990s:
NEW TECHNOLOGIES AND APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-135  POINT-OF-SALE RETAIL AUTOMATION IN THE 1990s:
NEW TECHNOLOGIES AND APPLICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANCIS DUFFY</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective  of this  study is  to assess  the technological
change that  is sweeping  the U.S.  retail  world,  generating
equipment sales  of $2.7  billion annually,  based on  today's
figures.  The fact is that advances in transaction cards, bar-code scanning  technologies,  point  of  sale  (POS)  terminal
systems, electronic  point-of-purchase promotional  equipment,
and automated  self-service devices will irrevocably alter how
retailers do  business in  the 1990s,  catapulting  electronic
retail equipment  makers' sales  past the $5.4 billion mark by
1998 in the process. This BCC report identifies the structural
and market dynamics underpinning this phenomenal trend.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

* U.S  retailers collectively  are pivotal to the distribution
of  every  good  and  service  comprising  the  U.S.  domestic
economy.   It is  a venue  of unparalleled  importance and  an
economic  sphere  being  buffeted  by  recession,  demographic
change, and uncertainty.<P>

* Transaction  cards are,  today, ubiquitous:  more than  1.15
billion are  circulating in  the U.S.   The  once  serene  and
highly  profitable   credit   card   segment,   moreover,   is
experiencing  unforeseen   structural  weaknesses  and  fierce
competition.   New kinds  of card products in the meantime are
achieving wide-scale acceptance.<P>

* The  era of the POS terminal as glorified cash register-cum-
card-swipe  gimmick   is  long   gone.     Today,   relatively
inexpensive  terminals   with  powerful   microprocessors  and
extended internal  memory are  the premiere agent-of-change in
the  store   environment,  bringing  retail  management  data-
gathering  and   analysis  capabilities  that  will  radically
streamline store operations.<P>

* Bar-code  scanning equipment  is  now  reliable  enough  and
affordable  enough   to   enter   mainstream   retailing   and
revolutionize  in-store  operations  as  diverse  as  pricing,
stocking, inventory  ordering, and delivery processing as well
as to  speed customer  checkouts while  significantly lowering
retail workforce requirements.<P>

* Advanced  electronics that will eventually make self-service
retailing in  the store, the vending machine site, and the gas
station more  convenient and  profitable are  coming on-stream
and represent promising new markets for the 21st century.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study  pinpoints the  structural and  market forces  that
will shape  the coming  era of  technological  competition  in
retailing. It  examines the  impact of new technologies on the
store environment, and the dynamics of the markets evolving as
a  consequence,   with  special   emphasis   on   quantitative
projections of  demand.  It is, accordingly, an invaluable aid
to market  researchers, strategic  planners,  senior  industry
executives,  and   analysts  and  consultants  in  the  retail
technology field.<P>


<B>SCOPE, FORMAT, AND METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study  surveys   market trends  in transaction cards, POS
terminals, bar-code scanning, electronic in-store display, and
automated  self-service   retail  devices.     Each  segment's
structure,  competitive  dynamics,  and  emergent  trends  are
carefully evaluated,  and unit  shipment and sales projections
made per product category for 1992 and 1997.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Secondary material  from 200  newspaper, trade  magazine,  and
company reports  and  industry  and  government  surveys  were
collected and  analyzed for this report.  Extensive interviews
were also  conducted with  industry executives,  analysts, and
market researchers.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

This study  updates material  previously presented  in two BCC
studies:
<UL>G-113A - ATMs,  POS Terminals,  Debit Cards and Home
Banking and<BR>
G-132 Credit  and Debit  Cards:  New  Directions,
Technologies and Applications.</UL><P>



<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
