<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-149: ELECTRONIC CASH: PREPAID AND VOUCHER
TRANSACTION CARDS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-149: ELECTRONIC CASH: PREPAID AND VOUCHER
TRANSACTION CARDS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Francis Duffy
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this study is to assess the potential market for the most
popular card product in the world today, the stored value card, which has
yet to make an impact in the American market.  Specifically, this study
examines the how, the when and the where of this novel card product's
introduction in the U.S., its likely reception and how this unknown item will
evolve into a $1.6 billion industry by the turn of the century.  Also, it
examines how the stored value card fits into the smart card picture and
credit/debit card structure.<P>


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

<LI> Japan and now Europe are being inundated with prepaid cards.  The
Japanese now use and literally throw away billions of them each year.  But
why is the prepaid card virtually unknown here and what obstacles do
entrepreneurs face here to reversing this trend?  This study details the
development of prepaid card markets abroad and analyzes differences and
similarities to the American scene.<P>

<LI> What kinds of card technology will be employed in prepaid systems?  How
expensive will terminal installations be now and five years from now?  This
study profiles the card and reader technologies likely to be used, their
costs, and the market potential for each.<P>

<LI> Who in the retail sector is going to buy into the prepaid card concept and
why?  This study closely examines the potential market for prepaid card
systems by segment, whether vending providers, transit authorities,
telephone companies or banks, and makes quantitative forecasts of unit
demand and sales per segment through 1999.<P>

<LI> What American firms have ventured into the market to date and what have
their experiences been?  Which firms are positioning themselves to
dominate and how are they doing so?  This study reviews present day
American firms' prepaid card activity and pinpoints those firms already
developing competitive advantages and why this is so.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study is the most comprehensive overview to date of the last great
new card market in America -- it highlights the structural, technological,
and strategic issues facing card executives, marketing and planning
professionals and industry consultants.  It is quantitative in its
approach -- 44 tables of forecasts outline the course of the market's
development by segment and by technology.<P>


<b>SCOPE, FORMAT AND METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The report surveys market trends and industry dynamics here and abroad. 
Potential markets in the U.S. are examined in depth, and carefully arrived
at unit shipment and sales projections per product category are made.<P>


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Secondary material from over 100 published trade and company sources were
used in preparing this report, along with interviews with industry
executives, analysts and market researchers.<P>


<b>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

ATMs, POS Terminals, Debit Cards and Home Banking G-113A; Credit and Debit
Cards: New Directions, Technologies and Applications  G-132; Point-of-Sale
Retail Automation in the 1990s: New Technologies and Applications  G-135.<P>

