<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-179: ELECTRONIC BANKING SYSTEMS: PRESENT
STATUS, FUTURE PROSPECTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-179: ELECTRONIC BANKING SYSTEMS: PRESENT
STATUS, FUTURE PROSPECTS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Kevin Swift
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to provide a detailed and
comprehensive multiclient study of the U.S. market for electronic
banking and potential business opportunities.  The objectives
include a thorough coverage of the underlying social, political,
economic, and regulatory issues driving the electronic banking
business, as well as assessments of new and potential products
and services.  Another important objective is to provide
realistic market data and forecasts for these technologies.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The main reason for doing this study is that commercial banking
in the United States is undergoing significant change. 
Competition from nonbank financial services suppliers, changes on
both sides of bank balance sheets, the adoption of securitization
and derivatives  as means to manage risk, the push to develop
off-balance sheet activities (including fee-based businesses),
consolidation, and prodigious advances in information technology
are all combining to alter banking as we know it today.  This
has manifested itself in regulatory reform.   For the electronic
banking business, the most important has been the recent passage
into law of the Interstate Banking and Branching Efficiency Act
of 1994 which will allow interstate banking.   Recent directions
in the legislative and regulatory arena indicate that removal of
the barriers that have separated commercial banking and
investment banking is likely.  In addition, it is assumed that
these trends will intensify in the years to come and with the
emergence of the so-called information highway, further changes
in the electronic banking business will occur.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The electronic banking industry is not a precisely defined sector
and has not yet been assigned in any of the major economic
classification codes or activities.  Basically, the scope of the
report is limited to those retail and wholesale (or corporate)
banking services in which delivery is achieved electronically and
in which banks receive revenues.  Thus, the scope of the report
includes revenues from bank fees charged for banking transactions
conducted by customers using automated teller machines (ATMs),
point-of-sale (POS)  terminals, banking via personal computer
(PC), telephone banking, interactive television banking, smart
cards, and automated clearing house (ACH) transactions.<P> 

In addition to electronic banking services, the scope of the
report also includes coverage of sales of selected equipment,
systems, and technologies used to deliver these electronic
banking services.  Included are ATMs, POS terminals, screen-based
telephones, and interactive TV devices.  The report does not
include the cost of PCs or workstations.<P> 

The scope of this report is comprehensive, covering the present
status of and future prospects for electronic banking in the
United States.  It covers the many issues concerning the merits
and future prospects of the electronic banking business,
including banking strategies, information technologies and means
for delivering these services.<P>

It also covers in detail the sociopolitical, economic,
regulatory, and technological issues that so many regard as
critical to the industry's current state of change.  The report
provides a review of the electronic banking industry, its
structure and the many companies involved in supplying these
goods.   The competitive position of the main players in the
market and the strategic options they face are also discussed, as
well as such competitive factors as marketing, distribution, and
operations.<P> 

The value of revenues for electronic banking services reflects
the value of the unbundled fees that banks receive, if any, for
providing these services.  A complicating factor is the practice
of banks to "bundle" service charges.  Because of this bundling
of banks' products and services, extremely complex cost
structures exist and most banks do not truly understand what
their actual costs may be for a particular product or service. 
As a result, prices set by banks generally do not reflect the
actual interdependencies of cost.  Thus, banks will often vary
their fees if the customer uses other services provided by the
bank.  Many banks, for example, will waive certain fees on
services if the customer maintains sufficient funds  in a deposit
account.  In many cases, the bank fees are bundled into an
overall "bank service" fee or are adjusted based on compensating
balance.<P> 

The value of revenues for selected electronic banking systems and
products--in millions of U.S. dollars--represents the value
of the product sold to the final user of the product, whether it
be a bank (e.g., an ATM), a retailer (e.g., a POS terminal), or a
consumer (e.g., a screen-based telephone device).  As used in
this report, the term revenues is equivalent to, and used
interchangeably with, the terms purchases, demand and sales.<P>  

During the discussion of the individual market segments, 
revenues are related to indicators in the tables which are  used
for comparative purposes.  They do not imply that the indicator
used represents the sole market for that product.   All growth
rates mentioned in the tables and in the text are based on the
average annual rate of growth from 1994 through the year 2000. 
The compounding method of calculating growth rates is used. 
Because current dollar measures are used, these growth rates thus
reflect the growth in volume or real growth and the growth
including the effects of price changes and changes in product
mix.  The effects of inflation are eliminated by including unit
fee (or sales) data.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of ongoing
electronic banking developments in the United States currently
available in a multi-client format.  It provides the most
thorough and up-to-date assessment that can be found anywhere on
the subject.  The study also provides extensive quantification of
the many important facets of the market developments in the
United States for electronic banking technologies.  This, in
turn, contributes to the determination of what kind of strategic
response companies may adopt in order to compete in this dynamic
market.<P>


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Initially, a comprehensive and exhaustive search of the
literature on electronic banking was conducted.  These secondary
sources included technical journals, technical books, marketing
literature, other product/promotional literature, annual reports,
security analyst reports, and other publications.  In addition,
there were formal and informal interviews with automated teller
machine (ATM) and point-of-sales (POS) terminal producers, other
banking equipment manufacturers, computer manufacturers, software
suppliers, systems integrators, service bureaus, other
information technology suppliers, technical experts, government
officials, trade association official> <HR><H3>Transfer interrupted!</H3> 
</DOC>
