<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
G-190 THE CHANGING RETAIL BANKING INDUSTRY STRUCTURE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>G-190 THE CHANGING RETAIL BANKING INDUSTRY STRUCTURE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>TOM FRANKLIN</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVE</B><P>

The objective of this study is to assess changes which have 
occurred in the banking industry, especially with respect to 
product delivery, and ascertain what further changes will 
materialize by the year 2000.  Specifically, how will banking 
services be provided during the remainder of the 20th century and 
what in fact will our banking system look like in the year 2000?  
How will new and newer technology impact these changes and which 
companies will be at the heart of implementing the changeover 
process?  This report will identify the agents of technology 
change and what their products will contribute to the new banking 
order.  Further, the ultimate changeover will occur at the 
consumer (individual or commercial) level, wherein the consumers 
will do their banking in a different manner than in the early 
`90s.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Much has been made over the last 10 years about how banking will 
change, what new products will be brought to market, that fewer 
checks would be processed and many fewer employees would be 
required to provide banking services.  At this juncture little has 
changed.  Although ATMs have increased in number and remote 
banking in that view has been well accepted, other new delivery 
systems such as home banking, bill paying, smart cards, stored 
value cards, the use of screen phones, personal computers, etc. 
have impacted the delivery of banking services only in a modest 
way to date.<P>

However, the embracing of strategic alliances and partnering 
arrangements amongst companies heretofore considered standoffish 
has made the intrusion of these high technology product delivery 
systems on the banking scene much more likely than in the past.  
Banks, service providers and communication companies are teaming 
up to do what none of them could possibly accomplish alone.  None 
of these companies singularly possessed the resources or the time 
to bring change to the banking scene.  Turf issues have been 
forgotten and given way to identifying opportunities.<P>

Thus, we are at a point wherein exciting change will begin to 
happen and happen on a broader scale.  This report will identify 
those changes and what impact it will have on the banking system, 
the consumer and the companies involved.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study is a comprehensive overview of the much anticipated 
transition of a brick and mortar banking philosophy to the virtual 
banking forum.  It highlights the technological and strategic 
issues facing product development executives, marketing, planning 
and financial executives as well as industry consultants.<P>

It is quantitative and informative in approach with 44 tables of 
data.  In addition, there are profiles on 26 companies and groups 
deemed to be the primary agents of change over the next five 
years.<P>


<B>SCOPE, FORMAT AND METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The report surveys strategies and partner arrangements and related 
new technology which will serve to bring about dynamic changes in 
banking, both here and abroad.  Projections are made as to the 
numbers of institutions providing banking services, as well as a 
statistical analysis of the impact of new technology in these 
institutions.  This report does not cover the asset allocation 
portion of the banking industry (large loans, investments, 
mortgages, etc.)<P>

The AAGR percentage was computed on a 5-year straight line basis.  
This process involves considering the increase or decrease in 
dollars or units from 1995 to 2000.  Using 1995 as the base year, 
the percentage of increase or decrease for the 5 years was divided 
by a factor of 5.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Primary information was provided by the Federal Deposit Insurance 
Corporation, the Office of Thrift Supervision, the National Credit 
Union Administration, the National Check Cashers Association, the 
New York Stock Exchange Research Library, the American Council of 
Life Insurance and the General Accounting Office.   In addition, 
secondary material from over 50 published trade and company 
sources, as well as company annual reports were used in preparing 
this report, along with interviews with industry executives, 
analysts, and market researchers.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

This report is the latest in a series of studies on the various 
aspects of the U.S. financial system and its changing 
technologies.  Relevant reports published by BCC include Credit 
and Debit Cards:  What's New ?  Where To? published in April 1995,
Electronic Card:  Prepaid and Stored Value Transaction Cards, 
published June 1994, and The Smart Card published in January 1991, 
as well as POS Retail Automation in the `90s, published in October 
1992.<P>


