<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-053U:  BIOSENSORS AND CHEMICAL BIOSENSORS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-053U:  BIOSENSORS AND CHEMICAL BIOSENSORS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Cort Wrotnowski
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to provide a detailed study of biosensors and their 
commercial potential.  The objectives include a thorough coverage of the 
underlying technological issues of the developing tools of biosensor 
technology as well as assessments of new and potential products.  

Thus, another important objective is to provide realistic market data on the 
product areas for which the future biosensor products are expected.<P> 

The study builds on the previous editions that were published in September 
1986 and November 1989.  There have been some important changes, especially in 
the makeup of the marketplace and in the role played by different 
corporations.  Some areas of research have waned, while others have assumed 
much greater importance.  There is also a surprising amount of work that has 
only progressed a little bit.  These are pointed out as well.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The main reason for doing the study is that in the last several years there 
have been additional new product introductions, as well as a growing number of 
research papers on the subject.  Also, new communities of biosensor 
researchers seem to be emerging. 

Furthermore, there has been an increase in the number of players, as well as 
the areas they are investigating.  While many observers say that it is too 
early to predict whether or not the products currently under development will 
be commercially successful beyond the R&D market, there are indications that 
in some applications biosensors could be the only technology of choice.  

Among the claimed advantages of biosensors over other kinds of sensors are the 
specificity of the response, and, in some cases, the ability to work in very 
dirty environments.  But, there is much research still needed in order to 
improve biosensor performance in a variety of environments.<P> 


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of the report is intended to be comprehensive.  It covers the many 
issues concerning the merits and future prospects of biosensor technology.  It 
covers the different ideas about the technology itself as well as the 
applications that are under development and discussion.  It covers the 
materials science issues that so many regard as critical to the development of 
a biosensor industry.  The report provides an extensive analysis of the market 
shares of suppliers, along with sales projections that are segmented in a 
variety of ways.<P> 

The start-up firms are discussed in terms of their products, services, 
strengths and weaknesses.  The role of major corporations is considered as 
well.<P> 

The report also looks at the varieties of basic research, product development 
and commercialization that are going on in universities and government 
programs both in the U.S. and abroad.  Competitive aspects are discussed, 
including the activities of Japanese firms that are still working on getting 
involved in biosensors.<P> 

However, there are many areas that had to be given more limited coverage. 
Otherwise, the report would become unwieldy.  This is handled in the 
discussion on quasi-biosensors.  Also, efforts were made to update all 
subjects covered.  Some, though, have moved away from biosensors even though 
commercial potential still exists.  So, on the hope that readers will find 
these neglected areas of interest and value, they have been left in from the 
previous edition.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of the ongoing developments 
in biosensor technology.  It provides the most thorough and up-to-date 
assessment to be found anywhere on the subject.  No other study has as 
complete a listing of the range of applications and technologies that are 
under development or that have been suggested.<P> 

The study also provides extensive quantification of many important facets of 
the market developments for biosensors. This, in turn, contributes to 
determining what kinds of strategies firms need to adopt in order to compete 
in this still-emerging marketplace.<P> 

The eight years in which biosensor technology has been tracked through 
successive BCC editions of this report have shown both little change and much 
change.<P> 

A large portion of the total research into biosensors is still directed at 
measuring glucose.  Despite the continued market success of several such 
biosensors, university researchers and other groups seem to persist in finding 
what seems to be the ultimate glucose sensor.  This is discussed more fully in 
the technology and market chapters.<P> 

Also, there continue to be few new biosensor products on the market.  During 
the mid-80s, there were roughly six biosensor products of note on the market.  
Since then, a couple have failed and a few more have been introduced.  Now, 
there are roughly 12-18 biosensor products on the market.  Some, such as 
Medisense's Pen2 and Companion2, Pharmacia's Biacore, and Molecular Device's 
Cytosensor, have been modestly successful.  However, there has still not been 
any great blockbuster biosensor product.  It is fair to say that there are now 
more biosensor products on the market than in a comparable period five years 
ago.<P> 

The area in which there has been much change has been in research.  The 
direction and scope of biosensor research appear to make a significant shift 
around 1989-1990. Conferences such as the American Chemical Society meetings 
featured yet more sessions on biosensors, and some societies that could 
include biosensors but had not, now did so in their annual meetings.  
Researchers seemed to be specializing more on certain areas such as new kinds 
of materials, new methods of binding and stabilizing enzymes.  Biological 
materials besides enzymes seemed to get more attention.  Though it should be 
added that through the late '70s and early '80s, there were a host of 
interesting biological materials that researchers tested on different 
electrode surfaces.<P> 

Besides updating research on biosensors, this report also provides a rare 
historical perspective on how biosensor R&D has evolved since the early 1980s.  
There are many interesting phenomena and demonstrations that were tried and 
apparently forgotten.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

We first conducted an exhaustive search for the literature on biosensors and 
chemical sensors. Secondary sources included trade literature, databases, and 
various government sources.  Then, there were over 70 formal and informal 
interviews, and discussions with leading researchers, graduate students, 
government officials, presidents of start-up firms, as well as their 
associates, end users, various suppliers, analysts, venture capitalists, life 
scientists, computer scientists, engineers, and many others.  The range of 
interviews and discussions reflected the breadth and depth of biosensor 
technology in its combined use of biology and electronics.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

Many of the studies from the Biotechnology Division are related to this study 
on biosensors and chemical sensors.<P>


<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
