<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-056N: Commercial Amino Acids: Products and Technology
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-056N: Commercial Amino Acids: Products and Technology</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ANNA CRULL and NORMA CORBITT</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYSTS
<P>
<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<b>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The immediate objective of this technical/marketing study is to
update a 1991 BCC report on the commercial amino acids industry.<P> 

Further objectives seek to determine the current state of the
business, present an in-depth analysis that forecasts and tracks
significant changes in the market and identify those amino acids
with current or potential commercial significance.<P>  


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

Commercial interest in amino acids is an outgrowth of an
understanding of the many functions that these substances perform
in humans and animals.  As understanding of these functions and
the
properties of amino acids increases, resultant changes occur in
their current commercial usage and potentially expanded future
applications.  New production technology continues to make large-
scale production of these products more economical.  In turn,
availability creates newer and larger markets for these vital
substances.<P>

<b>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B><P> 
 
Amino acids gained commercial significance shortly after the turn
of the century with the discovery of the flavor-enhancing
qualities of glutamic acid and the marketing of monosodium
glutamate in Japan.  Increased knowledge of the role amino acids
play in the value of nutritional protein led to their being used
to fortify animal feeds, as well as to sustain seriously ill
patients who had to be feed with intravenous solutions.<P>  

<b>SCOPE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This technical/marketing report outlines the properties of the 20
commercial protein amino acids that are delineated in the genetic
code, their current and future uses, their production technology,
and their manufacturers.  This report focuses on three commercial
amino acid markets:  animal feed supplements, flavoring agents
for human food, and specialty uses (medical, intermediate and
research
applications).<P>  

<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Much of the information in this technical/marketing report has
been gathered through telephone conversations with key industry
players, as well as academic experts in amino acid research.  The
balance of the information comes from available trade, technical,
and government publications, an on-line data search of databases
that cover all existing literature, and an evaluation of patents
and company/research activities, including foreign work with
future applicability in the United States.<P>  

All volume of shipments and value of manufacturers' sales refer
to specific markets in the United States.  Volume and value
figures are expressed in millions of pounds (#/MM) and millions
of dollars($/MM), respectively, unless otherwise indicated.  To
make projections for the 1999 time period, the report relies on
information regarding forces affecting specific markets, expected
product introductions, and anticipated pricing.  Where precise
information was not forthcoming, a consensus was made, using a
formulation of reasonable assumptions and estimates based on a
baseline obtained from historical data.  Projections for the
1994-1999 time period are stated in 1994 constant dollars and
represent real growth.  The average annual growth rates (AAGR)
conform to the convention for significant figures.<P>  


<b>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive study provides facts, data, and insights to
senior marketing and planning executives and venture capitalists.<P>

It will assist manufacturers of products in any of the applicable
markets, as well as technical personnel involved in the research
and development of production technology for commercial amino
acids.<P>

  
<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

