<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-066R  BIO-IMMOBILIZATION: TECHNOLOGY, PRODUCTS AND MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-066R  BIO-IMMOBILIZATION: TECHNOLOGY, PRODUCTS AND MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objectives of this study are to describe immobilization
technologies, describe the applications of immobilization to
biological substances, quantify the sales and captive value of
immobilized products and measure the end results of the
application of immobilized products. The goals are to provide
business data and analysis and to identify opportunities for
new applications and markets.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

The immobilization of biomolecules contributes much to the
practical application and value of biotechnology.  At the same
time, bio-immobilization also offers significant opportunities
for the suppliers of materials needed to accomplish
immobilization.<P>

This study is unique in several ways.  It competently
describes immobilization technologies, articulating both its
benefits and its pitfalls, pointing out where it serves well
and where it may not  have merit.  It then proceeds to
quantify  immobilized products.  In contrast to other studies
which may be offered on the topic, this  study does not engage
in biotech "boosterism," but neither does it overlook the real
opportunities for immobilization.  This study provides an
objective analysis pertinent to business interests, which we
have repeatedly heard the industry wants and pleads for.<P>


<B>REPORT AUDIENCE</B><P>

We expect this report to be of interest to suppliers of
immobilization materials as well as to practitioners and
exploiters of immobilization, especially if they have business
concerns.  Those with scientific interests may also benefit
from the insights into the business point of view.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT OF STUDY</B><P>


This study describes and analyzes immobilized products and
their applications and markets.  We discuss not only the
immobilized products on the market but also ones that were
developed but not commercialized, for the failures have
lessons to teach future product development efforts. We
examine products in research development, but we give
recognition to the "great divide" that separates experimental
products and commercialized products. This study's emphasis is
on immobilized products that have made it into commerce -- and
why.<P>

As to the future, this study identifies new product
developments expected to be introduced in the next several
years. Since "The mind can conceive more than the market will
accept," this study also examines the application needs they
are projected to serve.  This study also points out market
opportunities for immobilized products that may be overlooked.<P>



<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study results from three months of devoted effort by one
individual.  Over thirty representatives in industry were
interviewed by telephone for information not generally
available in published literature.  Among these interviewees
were marketing managers, product managers, business planning
executives, presidents and technical specialists.  We also
drew on published technical and trade literature for secondary
information.  Drafts of selected, critical sections were
submitted to business people knowledgeable in their fields of
enterprise, for review, comments and suggestions to allow
revision, if necessary, prior to publication. We thank these
people.<P>

Economic analysis refers to final immobilized products (not
input immobilization materials) and to the United States only.
However, this study's technological discussions cover some
aspects of immobilization materials and this study's product
and supplier discussions include the entire world.  Sales (and
captive values) are expressed in millions of 1993 dollars.
Forecasts are made to 1998 and are expressed in constant 1993
dollars to reflect real changes without inflation, and assume
constant prices.  The average annual (compounded) growth rates
(AAGR) are derived from standard tables of net present value.<P>


All analyses and assessments are made independently, without
the bias of vested interests. Mentions of products are not
endorsements and omissions, if any, are not intentional.
Trade names are indicated in capital letters.<P>


<B>PERSONNEL FOR STUDY</B><P>


The analyst for this study is a chemist-biochemist who also
has an MBA in marketing.  After first working at the Albert
Einstein College of Medicine, where he did basic research in
protein chemistry, he then went to a major food company, where
he investigated microbial enzymes.  During this time, he also
served as a voluntary reviewer on behalf of the National
Science Foundation's funding program, concerning Research
Applied to National Needs (RANN) in connection with
immobilized enzymes.  He subsequently joined a pharmaceutical
firm, and later on came to BCC.  AT BCC, he is the Director of
Biotechnology as well as the author of numerous technical-
business studies on many topics, including enzymes, antibodies
and others.<P>

