<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-79R OPPORTUNITIES IN CHIRAL TECHNOLOGY: EMPHASIZING ENABLING
PRODUCTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-79R OPPORTUNITIES IN CHIRAL TECHNOLOGY: EMPHASIZING
ENABLING PRODUCTS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
SENIOR INDUSTRY ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

        
<B>REASONS FOR THIS STUDY </B><P>

Whenever companies mention their involvement in rational drug design, receptor-based drugs,
enzyme inhibitors, advanced compound screening and small-molecule research -- they are
generally talking about chiral drugs.  After the biological aspects, the efforts usually turn to
organic chemistry, of which chiral technology plays the major part. Chiral technology has
progressed far since its early beginnings and now  drives major developments in the
pharmaceutical industry, to the point of being considered nothing short of a revolution.<P> 

In the even broader perspective, chiral technology involves much more than drugs.  Also of
significance are applications to biochemicals, pesticides, aroma and flavor compounds, dyes and
pigments, liquid crystals, nonlinear optical materials, and polymers.<P> 

Yet, chiral technology remains somewhat of a 'hidden' subject.  Except for the technical
revelations, which have increased in number dramatically in recent years, little is being said about
the business dimension, precisely because chiral technology is shaking up old ways and because
the competitive aspects are so intense.  This study therefore seeks to shed light on a topic of
major importance, integrating both the technical and the business perspectives.<P> 

This study in fact is an update of the one we published in January 1990.  In the intervening years
much has happened: changes in the technology, changes in the industry and the business
opportunities, and changes in the regulatory and market dynamics. So much has occurred in a
short space of time that it requires a new analysis of chiral technology's current applications and
future directions.<P> 


<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS</B><P>
 
The objectives of this study are to answer the following questions:<P>

<UL>
       <LI>What is chiral technology, and why is it important?
       <LI>What are the current and potential applications of chiral technology, and not just in
       drugs but in all sectors?
       <LI>What is the market value of chiral technology's enabling products?
       <LI>What is the market value of products emerging from chiral technology's application?
       <LI>Who are the participants in chiral technology?
</UL>

The goals of this study are to provide useful, professional information, analysis and insight in both
technical and  business spheres pertaining to this subject.<P> 


<B>REPORT AUDIENCE</B><P> 

This report is intended for those already participating in chiral technology as well as those
unfamiliar with the subject and who wish to learn more.  Written from the business perspective
but with an integration of the science and technology, this report  will be found useful to suppliers
of chiral technology enabling products, to practitioners applying chiral technology for commercial
ends, and to financial investors.<P>   


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT OF STUDY</B><P>
 
All aspects of chiral technology are included in this study: enantiomeric analysis of chiral
compounds, chiral resolution for preparative purposes, and chiral synthesis. All  known
applications of chiral technology are discussed, with understandable focus on drugs since they
constitute the major category of applications.  Also covered are pesticides, aroma/flavor
compounds, biochemicals, liquid crystals, nonlinear optical materials, miscellaneous applications,
and chiral assistive materials themselves.<P> 

This study has a primary emphasis on the business aspects of chiral technology.  We are
concerned not merely with how chiral technology is being applied in the laboratory and with what
kinds of enabling products, but with where, and by which companies, chiral technology is being
applied for commercial purposes.<P>

Toward that end we stress commercial practices and prospects and 'measure' chiral technology
in terms of enabling product sales and the sales of end chemicals emergent from their application. 
We quantify sales, not for all chiral end chemicals, but for chiral end chemicals where the
racemate issue is of genuine concern.  Thus, we exclude sales of products for the manufacture
and analysis of inherently enantiomeric biological compounds.<P>

This study focuses exclusively on chiral carbon, excluding chiral nitrogen, chiral sulfur and other
types of isomerism.<P>


<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>
 
This study is not concerned with all chiral compounds, only the ones for which racemates are at
issue.  We therefore limit discussions and analysis of inherently enantiomeric natural compounds
and focus more realistically on synthetic petrochemicals and semisynthetic compounds.<P>  

To do this study, we read extensively from the technical literature.  We did an in-house computer
search of the patent literature.  We contacted companies for their corporate and product
literature. We attended conferences on  chiral technology and not only listened to the talks, but
also interviewed members of the audience in private.  We carried out telephone interviews with
scientists and with business managers to obtain answers to important questions and to get their
views on the subject.  We drew on news reports in our monthly publication, Stereochemical
Technology News. This study, however, does not simply repeat what others say about chiral
technology because we also bring objectivity and independent thought to the subject.<P>   

This study quantifies the sales value of chiral technology enabling products in the aggregate,
according to recognized categories.  Both worldwide and U.S. estimates are given.  The sales
value includes open-market sales and captive consumption valued at open market.  Figures are
expressed in constant dollars, where $1 MM equals one million dollars.  The forecast average
annual growth rate, AAGR, is derived by the compounding method from tables of net present
value.<P>  

All estimates refer to the unique products of chiral technology.  We go to lengths to exclude
enabling products of a general nature and we also exclude applications not uniquely associated
with racemates.  Thus we believe our estimates more accurately reflect the true dimension of
chiral technology than other published figures.<P>  

All analyses are made independently, without the bias of vested interests.  Mentions of companies
and products are not endorsements, and omissions of companies, products and applications, if
any, are not intentional.<P> 


<B>ANALYST CREDENTIALS</B><P>
 
The analyst for this study is a chemist and biochemist, who also has an M.B.A. degree in
marketing.  His experience includes both academe and industry. At BCC, the analyst is director
of biotechnology and healthcare and has written studies in the  areas of biotechnology,
pharmaceuticals, chemical industry and agriculture.  He authored the previous BCC study on this
subject, of which the present one is an update. The analyst additionally edits BCC's newsletter,
Stereochemical Technology News, as well as another newsletter, Applied Genetics News.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P> 

Published BCC studies, authored by the analyst or by others, that relate to the present subject,
include the following:<P>

<UL>
    <LI>C-147R:  Comprehensive Analysis of the Enzyme Industry
    <LI>C-151:  Catalysts for Synthesis
    <LI>C-056N:  Amino Acids - Products and Technology
    <LI>C-072:  New Horizons in the Pharmaceutical Industry
    <LI>C-079:  Stereoselective Chemical Technology (prior  publication of current)
</UL>



