<CENTER><H2>C-O83R THE DYNAMIC MEDIA, SERA AND REAGENT MARKET
IN BIOTECHNOLOGY</H2>
<HR><P>
<I> CORT WROTNOWSKI</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P> 

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</H3></CENTER></B>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><BR>

<P>The goal of this study is to analyze the markets for media, sera and reagent use in
biotechnology.  The study also investigates new developments among competitors, including new
product lines, innovations and marketing efforts.  The study is a comprehensive analysis of the
main segments, such as research and production, for mammalian cell culture.</P>  

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>The main reason for this study is to profile an important area of biotechnology that appears to
be poised for significant growth over the next several years.  Evidence from areas of regulation,
product development and new research suggest that demand for these products could increase
quickly.  Though there is more than considerable uncertainty associated with these product
segments, they need to be profiled and analyzed for emerging market opportunities.</P>

<P>Another reason for this study is to compare recent changes with what was covered in the first
edition since 1988.  That historical perspective also contributes to an assessment of the outlook
for these key markets in biotechnology.</P>

<P>There are many areas where unusual development could occur in the coming years. 
Advances in bone marrow transplants, tissue engineering, cellular therapy and gene therapy are
among the technologies that could add to the level of demand for media, sera and reagents over
the next several years.</P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>This study will provide information on these areas:</P>

     <P>Structure and current market size of the markets for media, sera and reagents with
forecasts through 2005</P>

     <P>Media, sera and reagent usage patterns and trends</P>

     <P>Government and regulatory controls</P>

     <P>Impact of competitive forces on the market</P>

     <P>Major players and their relative market share and market potential</P>

     <P>Current product lines and examination of newly emerging products and
technologies</P>

     <P>Opportunities for development and commercialization of new or alternative products
and services</P>

<P>Since the study provides business and technical information of a timely nature, it will prove
valuable to a variety of readers, including industry executives, managers and planners, industry
analysts and investors.</P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This study encompasses the wide range of products and services that comprise the current
U.S. marketplace for media, sera and reagents in biotechnology.  It also discusses potential new
market areas that are under development.  The study will also provide additional analysis of the
international markets.</P>

<P>The study also presents background information on how these nutrient products are used to
support different kinds of cell culture R&D.</P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>The first step was to conduct a comprehensive literature and patent search.  The literature
included technical newsletters and journals, as well as many other sources described below.  On-
line databases and government sources were consulted as well.</P>

<P>The collected information was read, studied, analyzed and otherwise compared, where
appropriate, for consistency and feasibility.  A number of different models were constructed
considering different assumptions about the likely developments that could occur in the market. 
The assumptions were based on the experience of the author, other analysts' with extensive
experience in related areas, along with market knowledge learned in interviews of managers in the
supplier companies involved in these markets.</P>  

<P>Projections were based on such estimates as the current number ofend users, funding levels,
potential end users, likely unit prices and rates of consumption.  Special cases were considered as
well where competing technologies might be involved or where other end user preferences might
become factors.  Estimates were also based on such things as demographic factors and on unit
consumption estimates for given types of applications or other appropriate measures.</P>

<P>It should be pointed out that, while many factors were considered in constructing different
models, the projections are ultimately speculative.  As a composite of the opinions and
assessments of interviewees, the author, other analysts and secondary sources, these projections
represent something of a consensus.  The relative importance of selected factors could change at
any time with new technologies and new products and thus change the direction of the market
projections.</P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>A broad range of information sources was consulted in preparing this study.  The sources
consulted included newsletters, company literature, product literature, a host of technical articles,
journals, indexes and abstracts, as well as trade magazines, books, and reference guides.  Also, a
number of different computer searches were carried out.  Exhaustive investigations of databases
by key terminology were done.</P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B>
 
<P>Among the related BCC reports are those that cover various biotherapeutic markets and
related research markets.</P>

<B>DISCLAIMER</B>

<P>The author assumes no liability for the reported information or its use.  The information
developed is intended to be as reliable as possible and of a professional nature.  The author can
assume no liability for any loss or damage as a result of any reliance on any materials or any
information developed. This is not a legal or accounting document and much of the information is
of a speculative
nature.</P>
     



