<HEAD><TITLE>C-086  THE CHANGING BIOREACTOR BUSINESS</HEAD></TITLE>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-086  THE CHANGING BIOREACTOR BUSINESS</H2>
<HR><P>

 <I>CORT WROTNOWSKI</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>



<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>The goal of this report is to provide a detailed and
comprehensive study of bioreactor technology and its more
advanced developments.  The objectives include a thorough
coverage of the underlying technological issues, related work in
materials research, the development of new products, changes in
the marketplace and the role of the suppliers.</P>

<P>Thus, another important objective is to provide updated market
data on the product areas for which the future bioreactor
products are expected.</P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>The main reason for doing the study is that there has not been
a comprehensive report on bioreactor technology and its recent
changes.  So this study fills a gap in an increasingly important
area of biotechnology.  New innovations have been introduced at
a slow but steady pace.  And, arguably these and other
developments are still looking for a place in the market. But
they can all be seen as part of the ongoing growth of the
bioreactor marketplace, as uneven as that growth has been over
the last decade.</P>

<P>Moreover, it is anticipated that there will still be
considerable growth in the market due to scale-up efforts. The
issue of scale-up has continued to feed interest in bioreactor
technology.  And there have been a number of inventive devices
introduced over the last  two years.  But end-users have
remained cautious and are still mostly waiting and watching as
the technology continues to evolve.</P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>The scope of the report is broad.  It covers the many issues
concerning the use of bioreactors in different markets.  It
covers the technology underlying many different kinds of
bioreactors, as well as the work on exploring different kinds of
materials for future bioreactors, including everything from
specialty metals and glasses to plastics and novel and
engineered materials for highly specific applications.</P>

<P>The study also looks at the related devices that have a role in
bioreactor technology.  These include areas of process control,
as well as such items as spinner and roller bottles.  Some
consideration is also given to the roles that computer
technology will have to play in areas that computer suppliers
give little attention.</P>

<P>The report discusses the prospects for suggested new uses of
bioreactors, as a function of the materials research that is
going on.  Such matters as extending capabilities and the impact
on other markets are considered.</P>

<P>The report also looks at the varieties of basic research,
product development and commercialization that are  going on in
universities and government, both in the U.S. and abroad.
Competitive aspects are discussed, including  the activities of
Japanese firms that continue to push their own bioreactor R&D.</P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B>

<P>This study provides the most complete accounting of the ongoing
developments in bioreactor technology.  It provides the most
thorough and up-date assessment to be found anywhere on the
subject.  No other study has as complete a listing of bioreactor
technologies in use, under development, or that have been
suggested.</P>


<P>The study also provides extensive quantification of many
important facets of the market developments for bioreactor
technology.  This, in turn, contributes to the determination of
the kinds of strategies firms need to adopt in order to compete
in this marketplace.</P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>We first conducted an exhaustive search of the literature on
bioreactors. Secondary sources included trade literature,
databases, and various government sources.  Then there were over
70 formal and informal interviews and discussions with leading
researchers, graduate students, government officials, presidents
of start-up firms, and  various suppliers.  The range of
interviews and discussions reflected the breadth and depth of
bioreactor technology both in design and application.</P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK</B>

<P>Many of the studies from the BCC's Biotechnology Research
Program are related to this study of bioreactors.  Among the
topics are scale-up (C-061), supply needs of biotechnology
firms (C-040R), biosensors (C-055R), and many others.</P>



