<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-088R THE DYNAMIC ANTIBODY INDUSTRY, INCLUDING POLYCLONALS AND
MONOCLONALS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-088R THE DYNAMIC ANTIBODY INDUSTRY, INCLUDING POLYCLONALS AND
MONOCLONALS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF STUDY</B><P>

The immediate  objective of this study is to update a 1989 BCC
report on  the  subject.    Further,  the  objectives  are  to
determine the  current state  of the  antibody business and to
shed light  on its  future directions.  The goal is to provide
facts, data,  and insights in the hope of assisting executive-
level managers with their business planning.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR THE STUDY</B><P>

The antibody  business has  changed much  in the  last  twenty
years, even  in the  last five.   No  longer  is  it  a  minor
enterprise, nor is it any longer focused just on polyclonal or
monoclonal antibodies.<P>

In fact,  the antibody business is today a giant industry, and
the applications  of antibodies seem capable of expanding with
no end in sight.<P>

However, resources  always have to be rationed, in these times
especially,  in  order  to  concentrate  on  the  most  likely
profitable endeavors  and to  capitalize on natural strengths.
So it is critical for those who are commercializing antibodies
to look  at the  entire scope of the antibody industry, in all
its many facets, in order to be selective.<P>


<B>REPORT'S CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

This report  does the useful job of informing about the whole
antibody industry, not just  a part  of it.  It informs about
all  applications  of  antibodies, not just a few.  Most
important of all, in an industry overdosed on hype, this study
provides the  kind of  objective and  comprehensive  data  and
analysis that  the antibody  industry has  been short of up to
now.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF STUDY</B><P>

This study covers polyclonal as well as monoclonal antibodies.
It covers medical diagnostic as well as non-medical analytical
applications, all  therapeutic  applications,  and  separation
applications.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Part of  the information for this study comes from a survey of
antibody suppliers.   The  questionnaire used  and the subject
companies  interviewed  are  detailed  in  a  companion  study
dealing with antibody manufacture.<P>

Information  not  included  in  the  survey  came  from  other
telephone discussions and fax contacts with business managers,
scientists,  and   medical  professionals.    Also  used  were
extensive readings  of the published business, scientific, and
medical literature,  and specific company reports.  Government
information and data also played a role.<P>

All sales figures refer to the United States, unless otherwise
indicated, and  are expressed  in millions  of dollars  ($MM).
The sales refer to "finished" products in their ultimate forms
and refer  to transactions  with end users.  To make forecasts
for 1997,  we relied on information regarding forces affecting
markets in  general and for antibodies in particular, expected
product  introductions,   and  anticipated   pricing.    After
estimating "theoretical" future sales based only on conceptual
market sizes,  we adjusted  with factors  to take into account
the  probabilities  of  market  approval  and  penetration  of
markets.   Forecasts are stated in constant 1992 dollars.  The
average annual  growth rate, AAGR, for 1992-1997 is derived by
the compounding method.<P>

All analyses  are made  independently,  without  the  bias  of
vested interests.   Mentions of companies and products are not
endorsements, and omissions, if any, are not intentional.<P>


<B>CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The writer  of this  study is  a  biochemist  with  immunology
experience and  experience as  an industry analyst.  He is the
author of  the previously-published BCC study on this subject,
and also  has written  many other  studies on  related topics.
The other  contributor to  the study  is an experienced market
researcher, who  also has written extensively on many relevant
industry topics.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

A companion  study to  this report addresses the Manufacturing
Technologies for Antibodies (C-088S).<P>

Published BCC  studies related  to the  subject of this report
include the following:<P>

