<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-099 PROSPECTS FOR FOOD BIOTECHNOLOGY: An Unflinching But Optimistic Analysis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-099 PROSPECTS FOR FOOD BIOTECHNOLOGY: An Unflinching But Optimistic Analysis</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Philip Rotheim</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objectives of this report are threefold:  a) to identify the key players
in the commercialization of food biotechnology; b) to identify the food
products being developed through biotechnology and determine the timeframe of
their commercial introductions; and c) to quantify in dollar terms the value
of food biotechnology and to whom.  The goal is to provide information, data,
and insights useful for strategic planning, joint ventures, and other forms of
partnership, and investment in food biotechnology.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY</B><P>

Food biotechnology offers potential benefits to farmers, processing companies,
and consumers alike, and the biotechnology revolution taking place in the
research laboratory is as significant in the food sector as it is in the
medical sector.  Yet, introduction of food products based on genetic
engineering face unique technological, regulatory, and marketing barriers that
inhibit commercial success.<P>

Now that biotechnology-based foods are about to arrive on our dinner tables,
important questions, and their answers, have new relevance to those involved
with and invested in food biotechnology, such as what are the potential sales
revenues, what are people doing to overcome the regulatory and marketing
barriers to successful commercialization, what is the technology of food
genetic engineering capable of doing and what are its current limitations,
what can biotechnology do that conventional breeding cannot, and what
biotechnology opportunities exist even without genetic engineering?<P>


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT</B><P>

This study encompasses food animals, food plants, food microbes, and food
enzymes, emphasizing genetic engineering.  This study quantitatively analyzes
the impact of biotechnology on biotechnology companies, farmers, and food
manufacturers.  This study is not only a scientific review of commercial
developments, but also a business analysis.<P>

Excluded from this study are biopesticides, frost-protecting microbes, plant
growth hormones, and conventional animal, plant, and microbe breeding.  Also
excluded from this study:  plant diagnostics, animal health products, food
testing reagents, biotreatment of food wastes, and agricultural
petrochemicals.<P>


<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>

This report has been written for the benefit of those in the established food
industry, for those in food biotechnology, for those providing support
products related to food biotechnology, and for all others interested in the
subject for business or investment purposes.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This study uses a multiplicity of resources for its information and data.
Primary sources of information are telephone interviews with business managers
and scientists in established food companies and in recently-formed food
biotechnology companies, and with government and university scientists.
Secondary sources include company annual reports and other company literature,
government statistics and other government reports, trade publications,
scientific journals, reports from relevant trade and professional
organizations, BCC's monthly newsletter, Applied Genetics News, and BCC's in-
house patent search capabilities.<P>

Forecasting sales of biotechnology-based products (to 1997) is made difficult
by current regulatory uncertainties and the organized opposition to food
biotechnology, which, if not overcome, will result in a complete absence of
sales in the U.S. market. We assume these obstacles will be surmounted and
that biotechnology-based food products will be introduced to the U.S. market
within our forecast timeframe.  We then examine technological factors which
may impede product introductions and consider marketplace competitive factors
for products most likely to be introduced in the near horizon.<P>

For our analysis, we divide biotechnology-based products into two categories:
"generative" products such as animal embryos, plant seeds, fermentation
microbes, and enzymes, which are the direct results of genetic engineering
efforts and which serve as the progenitors of food products; and "comestible"
products such as red meat, poultry, milk, eggs, plant produce, fermented
foods, and food additives and ingredients, which are the end products that
reach the dinner table.  These two product categories, generative and
comestible, receive separate sales analysis.  In both cases, sales estimates
and forecasts refer to the "immediate manufacturer" level, e.g., seed producer
rather than local seed store in the case of seeds for planting, the farm level
in the case of agricultural animal and plant produce, and the processing
company rather than supermarket in the case of fermented foods.<P>

Sales estimates and forecasts are provided with their rationales and all
assumptions are clearly stated.  Sales (or other dollar values) are stated for
the United States only, except where noted, and presented in millions of
dollars, where $1 MM is one million dollars ($1 x 106).  Forecasts are stated
in terms of constant 1992 dollars.  The average annual growth rate, AAGR, is
derived by the compounding method.<P>

All analyses are independently derived, without the bias of vested interests.
Mentions of products are not endorsements, and omissions, if any, are not
intentional.<P>


<B>PERSONNEL FOR STUDY</B><P>

The writer of this report is the director of biotechnology at BCC and a long-
time veteran in writing technical-business studies for industry and in
providing customized management consultation.  The writer also has eleven
years of experience in a major food company as both a senior and group
supervisory researcher and an advisor to management, having worked in the
areas of microbial and enzyme technology.  He is also the editor of BCC's
Applied Genetics News and the organizer of BCC's annual conference on
Commercial Biotechnology.<P>

<B>
RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

Published BCC reports relating to the present topic (written by the present
author or by others) include the following:<P>

