<HEAD><TITLE>C-102  PLANT-DERIVED CHEMICALS,/HEAD></TITLE>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-102  PLANT-DERIVED CHEMICALS</H2>

<HR><P>


<I> PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
 PROJECT ANALYST
<P>




<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


<B>OBJECTIVE AND PURPOSE OF REPORT</B>

<P>At one time, plants were the sources of most organic chemicals
people needed, and their use dates far back in history.
Plant-derived chemicals still have many important roles in many
industries for many applications. But ever since petrochemicals
arrived on the scene earlier in this century, plant-derived
chemicals have declined as synthetic duplicates, better substitutes
and unique performance petrochemical materials have come along.
What was once a "Plant Age" has become the "Age of Chemicals."</P>

<P>But today, there are forces for change hinting at a resurgence of
plant-derived chemicals and a revitalization of their business.
Concerns for natural ingredients, biodegradability and nontoxicity
are joining together in the marketplace of demand in industry after
industry, creating a new interest in plant-derived chemicals.</P>

<P>At the same time, new technologies have come along to bear on the
supplying of plant-derived chemicals, and they are shaping up to be
an area of intense technology competition. On the one hand, we have
plant biotechnology offering the prospect of improving the plant
sources of the chemicals and providing us with new and better
chemicals as well. On the other hand, however, we have advances in
stereochemical technology offering the prospect of synthetically
duplicating even more plant substances and pushing the naturally
derived materials into still further decline.</P>

<P>It is obviously a complex situation of both market and technology
forces twining together in a big stakes game. This report is
intended to shed light on the complexity, to sort out the issues
and understand the forces at work, and to predict the future in
quantitative terms.</P>

<P>To address all these concerns, we asked and sought answers to the
following questions:</P>

<P>* What are the uses of plant-derived chemicals now, especially in
nonfood, industrial applications?</P>
<P>* What are the properties and performance capabilities now
available in plant-derived chemicals and
what are the ones needed?</P>

<P>* How much of what is used where?</P>

<P>* Where are plant-derived chemicals vulnerable to replacement by
synthetic petrochemicals and where
do they still hold sway?</P>

<P>* What are the new technological and market developments affecting
the plant-derived chemicals
business now and in the future?</P>

<P>* Where could plant biotechnology and stereochemical technology
best profit in the arena of plant-
derived chemicals?</P>

<B>SCOPE & CONTENT OF REPORT</B>

<P>The report focuses on plant-derived chemicals and their performance
requirements, applications and alternative manufacturing
technologies. The intrinsic properties of plant-derived chemicals
determine their performance and, therefore, their applications and
markets, so an elucidation of the performance requirements should
help readers developing new plant substances identify
commercialization opportunities and help materials suppliers of any
kind identify gaps to be filled. This report covers food
applications but emphasizes nonfood applications in great detail.
Alternative manufacturing technologies include both conventional
and new ways to produce plant-derived chemicals, with this report
emphasizing plant biotechnology and stereochemical technology as
two new alternative manufacturing technologies.</P>

<P>Excluded from this report are any discussions of agriculture in
general, plant breeding and plant biotechnology applied to insect
resistance, disease resistance, herbicide resistance, weed
resistance, animal resistance, drought tolerance, salt tolerance,
and the marketing and manufacturing qualities of plants, except
insofar as genetic traits specifically relate to the production of
plant-derived chemicals. This report also excludes discussions of
botany, plant physiology and plant biosynthesis mechanisms. This
report also excludes plant materials used as lumber, paper,
textiles and fuel.</P>

<P>The report opens with an OVERVIEW OF THE PLANT CHEMICALS BUSINESS.
We define the plant-derived chemical products, give a brief history
of the business, classify and describe the functional uses of
plant-derived chemicals, detail the structure of the industry,
explain the international trade aspects, and illuminate the
dynamics of the plant-derived chemicals business. Anyone in the
business of supplying plant-derived chemicals, or having an
interest in them from any perspective, should find this section of
the report highly informative from a general viewpoint.</P>


<P>The section on MARKETS FOR PLANT-DERIVED CHEMICALS describes the
many uses of plant-derived chemicals, shedding light on the often
hidden world of nonfood applications. First, we discuss four major
issues driving markets for plant-derived chemicals in the future.
Then we discuss, one by one, the industries making use of the
substances. Industry after industry is showing a renewed interest
in plant-derived chemicals, and this section explains why.</P>

<P>The section on MANUFACTURING TECHNOLOGIES concisely describes the
conventional manufacture of plant-derived chemicals, and shows
where new manufacturing technologies fit in. Supercritical fluid
extraction is finding a place in the industry, but the real
excitement is the looming competition between two alternative


technologies for manufacturing plant chemicals: plant biotechnology
vs. stereochemical technology, setting biologists against the
organic chemists.</P>

<P>The section on PLANT-DERIVED CARBOHYDRATES describes in lengthy
detail all the many applications of this category of substances,
giving consumption figures and listing major suppliers. A number of
major technological developments are taking place in this field,
with enormous business stakes, and this section describes them all
and points to some perhaps missed opportunities.</P>

<P>The section on PLANT-DERIVED LIPIDS describes the many kinds of
lipids derived from plants and relates their applications in terms
of functional performance requirements. Besides the consumption
figures and lists of major suppliers, this section delves
extensively into the new technological and market developments
shaking this field.</P>

<P>The section on PLANT-DERIVED TERPENES describes the four major
subdivisions of this group of substances. Among the most high-value
plant chemicals are to be found here, and the competition between
alternative manufacturing technologies are expected to be most
intense in this arena. The section provides consumption figures,
lists major suppliers, and discusses the manufacturing
alternatives.</P>

<P>The section on ALL OTHER PLANT-DERIVED CHEMICALS, necessarily
limited because there are so many, focuses on the major "others"
and some key new categories. Innovations in the plant chemicals
business are likely to be most fertile in this field, and this
section sheds light on them.</P>

<P>Finally, the report has two append-ices: a directory of
plant-derived chemicals suppliers keyed to the products they
offer., and a directory of important trade and professional
organizations concerned with the chemicals.</P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>This study is the product of three manmonths of concentrated,
focused effort. For much of the data, information and insights, we
telephone interviewed about a hundred business executives, sales
people, product managers and scientists. For additional data and
information we read numerous articles and papers in the business
and scientific literature. Other sources of information and data
came from the U.S. Commerce Department, the International Trade
Commission, the U.S. Department of Agriculture and numerous trade
associations. We also did our own thinking and computations.</P>

<P>Although this study has some data on production, most of our data
are on consumption. We quantify the U.S. consumption of
plant-derived chemicals by both chemical type and application, and
pay special attention to nonfood, industrial applications since
most published studies on the subject look mostly at food
applications. We look at food applications too, but our emphasis is
on the harder task of illuminating nonfood consumption, with
details. Our consumption data are in pounds, on a dry basis. Our
quantification goes to great lengths to exclude nonplant sources of
materials, since too often published business studies lump animal,
microbial and petrochemical derived substances together with
plant-derived substances when the substances are chemically
identical, which unfortunately can produce a lot of confusion and
error.</P>

<P>To estimate the domestic U.S. sales and captive values of
plant-derived chemicals, we apply representative unit prices to
aggregated consumption data. The unit prices are weighted averages
for the substances in question. However, we take care to apply
prices appropriate for the applications, grades of purity and
levels of scale. In other words, we distinguish among food-grade,
pharmaceutical and cosmetic-grade and technical-grade pricing. As
far as possible, we use prices of substances as they leave the
originating producer ("manufacturer level"), usually as materials
ready for use.</P>

<P>All sales data are expressed in millions of dollars ($ MM, 106).
Forecasts are expressed in constant 1989 dollars to reflect real
changes in quantities of consumption. The average annual growth
rate, AAGR, is derived by the compounding method using standard
tables of present value.</P>

<P>All analyses are made independently and as objectively as possible.
BCC has no vested interest in any company or product mentioned in
this study, and derives no special benefit from the information
contained in it or learned during the course of its preparation.
Mentions of companies and products are not endorsements, and
omissions, if any, are not intentional.</P>


<P>The analyst for this study is a chemist and biochemist, with years
of experience in marketing and in writing market studies. Among
other subjects he has written on, the most relevant ones to this
study are on biotechnology for plant breeding, biotechnology for
agriculture, inert ingredients for drugs and stereoselective
chemical technology.</P>

<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B>

<P>We wrote this report for business managers and anyone else
concerned about the commercialization of plant-derived products and
manufacturing technologies relating to plants. Established plant
chemicals supply firms as well as newly established firms, and the
suppliers supporting both, should find this report useful and
constructive. Obviously, every reader looks for something unique to
get out of a report, but the following are some of the
possibilities:</P>


<P>* Commercial developers of new plant-derived chemicals looking for
business opportunities.</P>

<P>* Developers of new technologies looking for profit-making
applications.</P>

<P>* Strategic planners looking into new fields of endeavor.</P>

<P>* Investors and venture capital firms looking for an independent
market analysis and assessment.</P>

<P>* Anyone looking for useful business facts and figures on this
subject.</P>

<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B>

<UL>
