<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-114  THE CHROMATOGRAPHY SUPPLY BUSINESS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-114  THE CHROMATOGRAPHY SUPPLY BUSINESS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>CORT WROTNOWSKI</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The chromatography supply business has not been covered as a whole in any market study.  There are many studies on HPLC columns, detectors and pumps, but little attention has been paid to equally important consumable items, not only in HPLC but in the other areas of chromatography.  This study addresses those short-comings by providing in-depth analysis of the markets, products and suppliers for these important
areas.<P>

There is a need for an analysis that shows how different types of chromatography are
used in conjunction with each other.  Also, there have been some important advances
in product innovation, and other areas of technology are changing as new capabilities
are developed and introduced to the marketplace.  It has also been found that there
are a number of new niche markets for some products based on different kinds of
chromatography.<P>


<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The basic objective of this study is to provide an overview of the different
chromatography supply markets.  How big are they?  How many end-users are there
for the different types of chromatography?  What are the important products and
technologies? These are some of the questions that need to be asked.<P>

Since this market has not been covered before, we discuss the basic principles
underlying the different technologies, along with the products that are on the market,
and the companies selling these products.  This also includes looking at the markets
for these products, and how those markets are likely to change.<P>

The chromatography supply market is a complex array of products.  Any one could be
a special study in itself given the variety of applications and capabilities that are
available to end-users.  Some areas have been large, growing, commercial markets for
the last 20 years, and others have remained small niche markets.  In general, interest
has been increasingly driven by the need to find ways to either improve performance
with commonly studied compounds or else to come up with a practical way to study,
chromatographically, the properties of new compounds.<P>

The complexity of this area is compounded by the variety of purposes to which
chromatography may be put.  The most basic uses are to isolate a compound for
further analysis, and to monitor production processes to make sure contaminants stay
below specified levels.  The various kinds of chromatography may also be used to pre-
treat fluids, make commercial-scale quantities of pure compounds, and clean up waste
streams.  So, at its most basic, the objective of this study is to assess all these
different areas and determine their likely future directions.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This is the first study ever that looks at the chromatography supply business as a
whole market.  Among its contributions are the identification of areas of decline, as
well as areas of significant growth.  It also contributes by gathering much of the
information on new products in chromatography.  This gives a sense of how the
overall field has changed in the last several years.  Still another contribution is that
this study provides data on different market segments that are either hardly covered
or not covered at all.  Thus, this study is probably the only source for many of the
estimates about consumption of various products.<P>

Also, chromatography technology cuts across a number of application areas, and, as
such, continues to hold much promise for the growth of future markets.  The fact that
many types of chromatography continue to find new uses highlights the fact that this
area still has much potential to be developed and improved.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study evaluates technologies and markets as they relate to the chromatography
supply business.  The ways in which types of gas chromatography and liquid
chromatography are conducted is explained.  The current and projected sales for many
different types of products are considered as well.<P>

But it should also be pointed out that this study limits its coverage to five product
segments:  Columns, adsorbents, solvents, other chemicals and membranes.  The materials involved, such as various resins and gels used for adsorbents, the various product forms such as columns, coils and disks, along with the many different chemistries employed, serve as a starting point for considering the many different types of chromatography that are used for different purposes.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The first step was to conduct a comprehensive literature and patent search.  The
literature included technical newsletters and journals, as well as many other sources
described below.<P>

The collected information was read, studied, analyzed and otherwise compared, where
appropriate, for consistency and feasibility.  A number of different models were
constructed considering different assumptions about the likely developments that
could occur in the market.  The assumptions were based on the experience of the
author, other analysts with extensive experience in related areas, along with market
knowledge learned in interviews of managers in the supplier companies involved in
these markets.<P>

Projections were based on such estimates as the current number of end-users, funding
levels, potential end-users, likely unit prices and rates of consumption.  Special cases
were considered as well where competing technologies might be involved or where
other end-user preferences might become factors.  Estimates were also based on such
things as demographic factors and on square-foot-of-use for given types of
applications.<P>

It should be pointed out that while many factors were considered in constructing
different models, the projections are ultimately speculative.  As a composite of the
opinions and assessments of interviewees, the author, other analysts, and secondary
sources, these projections represent something of a consensus.  All recognized that the
relative importance of selected factors could change at any time with new technologies
and new products, and thus change the direction of the market projections.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

A broad range of information sources was consulted in preparing this study.  The
sources consulted included newsletters, company literature, product literature, a host
of technical articles, journals, indexes, abstracts, as well as trade magazines, books,
and reference guides.  Also, a number of different computer searchers were carried
out.  Exhaustive investigations of databases by key terminology were done.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

Among the related BCC reports are those that cover membranes, chromatography,
aspects of biotechnology, and the pharmaceutical industry, including medical
diagnostics.<P>

Some of the reports include:
<UL> C-073 Separation systems for Commercial Biotechnology<BR>
C-062 High Tech Gas Separations<BR> 
P-041U Membrane Separations Markets and
Technologies, and<BR> 
C-046R Membrane Microfiltration:  Materials and Markets</UL><P>

